<HEADLINE>
MIGHTY DUCKS NOTEBOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Suspended Anaheim Mighty Ducks defenseman
Ruslan Salei said he tried to contact Dallas' Mike Modano through
the National Hockey Players Association, but said he didn't get a
response.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt bad when it happened, I felt sorry for him,'' said
Salei, who was suspended 10 games for pushing Modano into the
boards in last Saturday's game in Dallas. ``I just wanted him to
hear it from my mouth. I wasn't trying to hurt anybody, I felt real
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Salei explained he probably could get Modano's number on his
own, but doesn't want to force the issue if the Dallas center
doesn't want to talk to him.
</P>
<P>
   Salei's character has taken a lot of hits this week. Dallas
coach Ken Hitchcock has called him ``a stupid player'' and Brett
Hull said his passport should be taken away. But the Anaheim
defenseman said it's nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already got this bad reputation,'' he said when asked if
was concerned about his image. ``But I can't be concerned about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Salei, however, did admit he is concerned about losing his
aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I'll be all right,'' he said. ``The first couple of
practices (after the suspension) I was afraid to touch anybody . .
. I was backing off.
</P>
<P>
   With all of the talk of revenge it was Modano who had a press
release posted in the Dallas dressing room Thursday asking his
teammates to keep their cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm calling on my teammates to set an example for all
players,'' Modano said. ``I'm looking forward to getting back on
the ice and playing as soon as possible, but not to getting even.
More importantly, I don't want anyone getting even on my behalf.
Somewhere along the road, players have lost respect for one another
and the sport, and that is unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   The tone of the message was dramatically different than the
anger the Stars displayed after Modano and Darryl Sydor were
injured last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two wrongs don't make a right and we know that,'' Dallas
defenseman Richard Matvichuk told a Dallas newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   But the bad feelings certainly aren't going to go away as Stars
defenseman Shawn Chambers made perfectly clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't have to be this game,'' Chambers said. ``We're
going to play them four more times. You never forget things like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Speaking of things teams and fans never forget, Gary Suter
will likely face Paul Kariya on Monday for the first time since he
cross-checked the Mighty Ducks' captain in February 1998 while a
member of the Chicago Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya missed the remainder of the '97-98 season with
post-concussion syndrome. Suter, now with San Jose, missed the
entire '98-99 season due to a shoulder injury and staph infection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
