<SLUG> BC-ANIMAL-HAVEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'SHOOGY'S EMERGENCY ANIMAL RESCUE IS A TWO-PERSON LABOR OF LOVE _
AND ENDLESS WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. JOSEPH, Mo. _ Every dog at M'Shoogy's Emergency Animal
Rescue has a name. All 583 of them. And Lisa Silverglat knows
almost every one.
</P>
<P>
   She hurries down the gravel path to the feed barn. It's after 4
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know when I'm late,'' she says, walking quickly past the
cacophony. ``I try to be on time for them. After what they've been
through, it's the least I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   She hoists a 50-pound bag of dog food from the mountain of bags
towering to the ceiling. With her right hand, she slices one bag
with a knife. Her left hand tilts the bag. Brown nuggets rain into
a 5-gallon bucket.
</P>
<P>
   One filled. Twenty-three more to go.
</P>
<P>
   M'Shoogy's, which is just outside St. Joseph, is a no-kill haven
where animals live out their lives, without a time limit, even if
no one adopts them.
</P>
<P>
   Silverglat, 42, and her husband, Gary Silverglat, 58, the
owners, discovered years ago that a rescued animal that got a home
became a friend for life.
</P>
<P>
   So they gave the animals theirs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986 they opened their home, their land and their wallets to
helping thousands of animals society had thrown away or cast off.
Here are pets that humans discarded as easily as dumped trash.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their work in adopting out more than 26,000 animals in
13 years, and making sure that all adopted animals are spayed or
neutered, new animals keep arriving.
</P>
<P>
   And more work needs to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lisa and I can't do any more by ourselves,'' said Gary. ``We
need help. We have ideas, ideas that could work, but we need people
to help us.''
</P>
<P>
   It's exhausting work. The Silverglats begin feeding animals at 8
a.m., break near noon, start again at 4 p.m. and finish four hours
later. They do this seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 13 years since they have taken a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   This is a job few people would choose to do. Not even avowed
animal-loving volunteers stay with them long. Feeding, watering,
deworming and disinfecting is too hard. Too demanding.
</P>
<P>
   At times, even dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't try to pet Scarface. He tried to get Gary once,'' warned
Lisa, who knows these animals' temperament.
</P>
<P>
   Scarface is kept in a pen with 26 other dogs. A 50-pound black
chow with curly fur, he stands aloof. He's the dominant dog of this
pack. When he eyes visitors, his face seems to beg for an
``atta-boy'' pat.
</P>
<P>
   Until he turns his head.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of an eye on the other side, there's an angry red gash.
Underneath his furry cheek, his bone is concaved, pock-marked. He
has no floppy left ear, just a round nub.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone tried to blow him away with a shot gun,'' said Lisa
swishing water into his bowl. ``He was a bloody pulp when we got
him. I didn't think he was going to make it. He's one of the only
dogs here who hasn't forgiven humans.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of the animals at M'Shoogy's Emergency Animal Rescue do
turn the other cheek and often become great pets, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about how many animals are walking around now because
of us, and it makes me happy,'' Lisa said. ``There are literally
thousands. I have a whole file cabinet full of dogs and cats
adopted out. But some days, all this seems too much.''
A spiritual occupation
</P>
<P>
   M'Shoogy's is a 20-acre haven with 150 dog runs, several barns,
a two-story stone building, another building for adoptions, several
pastures, ponds and an atrium housing 40 cats.
</P>
<P>
   The Silverglats named their no-kill shelter M'Shoogy's because
the word is a Yiddish variation meaning ``crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the daily feedings and waterings don't make you crazy,
listening to 600 dogs bark at once will,'' Lisa said.
</P>
<P>
   The Silverglats' no-kill facility was a cutting-edge idea 13
years ago. Today no-kill operations are sweeping the country, said
Merritt Clifton, editor of Animal People in Clinton, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``M'Shoogy's is well-known among animal people,'' he said. ``I
know people who have traveled there to see how they do it. The
Silverglats set their shelter up without any help from anyone. It's
a model for how a no-kill operation should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the largest no-kill facility outside of Utah and
Texas. No one else compares to what they're doing. It's also
extraordinary that they're doing it themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Other no-kill shelters in the United States include the late
Cleveland Amory's Black Beauty Ranch in Texas and a shelter called
Best Friends in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``But neither one of those places rescues animals themselves.
Gary and Lisa do,'' Clifton said. ``Their kind of lifestyle
commitment is very much like monks and nuns, bordering on a
spiritual occupation.''
</P>
<P>
   Witnessing the traumas of animals has made the Silverglats
intolerant of lukewarm help from others. They acknowledge that they
are zealots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain why we do this,'' Lisa said. ``Even the
meanest, rottenest, whatever dog that no one else can get near will
still come over to me. I don't know why or how, but we connect with
them. We just love animals, and they love us back. I guess we're
obsessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Their ``spiritual occupation'' includes donning yellow plastic
gloves in the morning and picking up by hand all dog feces,
checking it for worms and blood.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, just providing animals the basics _ a clean living
area, healthy food and fresh water _ are chores that cannot be done
mindlessly. The Silverglats have only one employee.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of running M'Shoogy's is also a never-ceasing problem.
</P>
<P>
   Rescues often mean hundreds of dollars in veterinarian bills,
adding to the thousands of dollars in bills for spaying and
neutering. And the monthly food bill is about $5,100.
</P>
<P>
   The money to run the shelter comes from their own pockets, with
neither Silverglat taking a salary.
</P>
<P>
   Gary said he had made a fortune from retail stores in the 1960s,
``but our money is not unlimited.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry we'll run out. It's tough. We need people. Helping
hands from people who care about animals, too.''
Beyond words
</P>
<P>
   Every animal at the shelter represents an instance of the
Silverglats' devotion. Devotion that bewilders even the
Silverglats.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Gary cares so much because of an illness he had at age
16. After he almost died that year, he said, all of life became
sacred to him.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps he cares so much about animals because he knows what
it's like to be persecuted, he said. Silverglat is Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm sure about is that I can't stand for anything to
needlessly suffer,'' he said. ``When you're an ethnic person and
you're raised in a hostile environment, you get a second sense for
these things. Whether it's kids or animals I can't stand to see
injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa shares Gary's love of animals but not his enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Some days the endless chores of feeding, watering, deworming,
disinfecting and caring get to her. Sometimes, it's too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday I started sobbing, because, well, I have to do it
all over again,'' she said. ``It shouldn't be this hard to do
something so good. But it is.''
</P>
<P>
   On those days when she dreams of never filling another dog dish,
she makes a point to visit some of her furry friends.
</P>
<P>
   There's Scarface, wagging his tail and watching her with his one
good eye.
</P>
<P>
   There's Duke, a golden retriever mix who once had three broken
legs but now walks well.
</P>
<P>
   One-Eyed Willy squints out from his cage and purrs at Lisa. A
gray tabby, he lost his eye and his tail when a car ran over him
and he was left for dead.
</P>
<P>
   There's also Wee-Wee. Lisa always cuddles him a little extra.
</P>
<P>
   As a 1-year-old, he was thrown from a car on Interstate 29. His
beagle body caught on the car's side, tumbled beneath its wheels
and was crushed.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't die.
</P>
<P>
   An anonymous truckdriver witnessed the horror. He stopped and
scooped up the quivering puppy, delivering his broken body to
M'Shoogy's.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa stayed up with the dog all night, making sure he had water.
Giving him medicine. Things she does often with injured animals.
</P>
<P>
   Today, although Wee-Wee walks oddly, and urinates with every
step, he's one of M'Shoogy's extra special dogs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``See how he grins,'' she said, scratching his ears.
</P>
<P>
   His muzzle curls around his teeth, he begins to pant and, sure
enough, it flits slowly into...a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at them, I know this is worth it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The dogs are quiet now, all 583 of them. Lisa smiles, looking
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about animals that goes beyond words into a
deeper level of understanding. They've taught that to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
