<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS DEFEAT DIAMONDBACKS, EVEN WITHOUT PIAZZA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like migraine sufferers scrambling for aspirin, the
Mets needed some soothing on Friday night, and fast. They had spent
the hours preceding game three of the division series trying to
function with simultaneous headaches from Mike Piazza's
inflammatory reaction to a cortisone injection and Bobby
Valentine's inflammatory words in a magazine profile.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza was out of the game because his left thumb was stiff and
swollen from an adverse reaction to a cortisone shot he received
Thursday to alleviate pain from a sprained joint at the top of his
thumb. And Valentine was sharing a dugout with players he had said
were not professional and not really intelligent.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. The New York Mets, behind some clutch hitting by John
Olerud and a six-run sixth-inning splurge, calmed their on- and
off-field nerves with a 9-2 pasting of the Arizona Diamondbacks
that put the Mets one victory from the National League Championship
Series.
</P>
<P>
   With Al Leiter on the mound, the Mets could close out the
division series on Saturday, just eight days after their improbable
resurgence from an earlier, now nearly forgotten headache, began.
</P>
<P>
   After a somnolent loss to the Diamondbacks in Arizona in Game 2,
in which the Mets managed one paltry run, the Mets could smile
again _ at least until they opened a copy of Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who Valentine said was only 50-50 for Friday, is usually
at the core of the Mets' powerful offense, but he has been slowed
in this series, perhaps by the ailing thumb, which has bothered him
for at least a week, Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   After game two, Piazza had mentioned how banged up he was _ he
had planned to spend the day with ice all over him _ although he
did not specifically mention the thumb and, indeed, his impact on
this series had been negligible, since he is only 2 for 9 with four
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   So, when Benny Agbayani, who usually plays when a left-hander
starts against the Mets, went to bat as the cleanup hitter in
Piazza's absence Friday night, the Mets might have been giving up
plenty in intimidation, but not much in postseason numbers.
Agbayani led off the third inning and slapped a single to right
field off Arizona left-hander Omar Daal. Robin Ventura walked, but
he was taken out on a double-play ball by Shawon Dunston.
</P>
<P>
   With Agbayani on third, Todd Pratt _ Piazza's rarely used backup
_ drew a walk. Then Rey Ordonez got his third hit of the series, a
single to right that scored Agbayani to give the Mets a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets added to the lead in the third inning when, with one
out, Edgardo Alfonzo hit a full-count pitch for a double that
curled toward the left field line. Olerud's single to left scored
him and Olerud went to second on the throw from Luis Gonzalez,
which had no chance of getting Alfonzo at home.
</P>
<P>
   Agbayani singled to put runners on first and third _ at that
point he had as many hits in this game as Piazza has in the series
_ and Ventura's roller to first base scored Olerud to give the Mets
a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Mets starter Rick Reed, who pitched a complete game three-hitter
in his start against the Pittsburgh Pirates last Saturday as part
of the Mets' winning streak that got them into the playoffs, rolled
through the first four innings, but Arizona got to him in the fifth
when he threw two bad pitches. Kelly Stinnett led off with a double
that Dunston, playing center field, broke badly on. Turner Ward,
pinch-hitting for Daal, smacked a curveball for a home run into the
right field bullpen to close the lead to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   But compared with what the Mets were dealing with, two runs was
pretty harmless. What's a narrow lead when your superstar is
sitting on the bench with the thumb on his catching hand in a
splint and your manager has called five of your teammates losers?
</P>
<P>
   A loss to Arizona, a second-year expansion team that won 100
games this season, would have been understandable under the
circumstances. But it also would have provoked questions about how
critical Piazza's health was to the team's chances to advance and
how much the firestorm surrounding Valentine had distracted his
players.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets made all such concerns moot with a six-run sixth
inning, which, appropriately began with a Pratt walk. Bobby Bonilla
was mentioned by name in the Valentine story _ it said Valentine
was worried about the influence Bonilla had on the team _ and
before the game, Bonilla said he was ``disappointed'' that his
manager would say such things. Presumably neither Bonilla nor
Valentine was disappointed when Bonilla drew a walk in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Rickey Henderson, who had three hits, hit a bloop single to
right field that scored Pratt and a misplay by right fielder Tony
Womack allowed Bonilla to go to third. After Alfonzo walked to load
the bases, and Arizona brought in reliever Dan Plesac, Olerud
smashed a grounder past first base that scored Bonilla and
Henderson. Roger Cedeno, who had pinch-hit for Agbayani in the
fifth inning, singled to score Alfonzo.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored two more runs in that inning. It was padding for
their lead, but it served as a bandage for the throbbing in
Piazza's hand and the nasty sting of Valentine's words.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
