<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-KILLING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS TOWN STRUGGLES WITH DEATHS OF THREE CHILDREN AND MURDER
CHARGES AGAINST THEIR FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN L. PETTERSON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINDSBORG, Kan. _ Three stuffed animals, surrounded by small
bouquets of fresh flowers, rest peacefully on the front steps of
the bungalow at the corner of South Main and Union streets.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be no one to play with Owl, Piglet and Winnie the
Pooh, and no one to enjoy the colorful flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The three children who lived in the bright teal home with the
white trim are dead, and their father, Christopher E. Jones, is
accused of murder.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to first-degree murder charges in the deaths of the
children _ Sarah, 2, Joshua, 5, and Christopher, 7 _ he also faces
an aggravated battery charge involving injuries to his wife, Cathy
Jones. She was hurt Wednesday night about 10:30 p.m., shortly
before she ran to a neighbor's home, screaming, ``He is after me.''
</P>
<P>
   By Friday afternoon she was in fair condition in Lindsborg
Community Hospital, her parents at her bedside.
</P>
<P>
   Her 47-year-old husband was locked in the nearby McPherson
County Jail. Bond was set at $3.5 million. Arraignment will be
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Funerals for the children will be Tuesday at 10:30 a.m. at
Trinity United Methodist Church, across the street from the family
home.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity is the same church where Christopher and Cathy Jones
were married 10 years ago, and where the family that everyone
thought was ``perfect'' attended Sunday services.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, Christopher Jones had stood in a church service
and told the congregation that he was thankful Cathy was his wife
and that he thought he was the luckiest man in the world.
</P>
<P>
   They joined the neighborhood church only two weeks ago,
transferring their membership from the United Methodist Church in
Waterville, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This community is in shock, because they can't understand how
a family that looked so good together, how this could happen,''
said David Smith, pastor at Trinity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came as a complete surprise to Cathy,'' said Smith, who
visited her at the hospital earlier Friday. ``It came out of
nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The family had moved back to Lindsborg about six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Jones had once lived here, earning a degree in music
education at Bethany College, the Lutheran-affiliated liberal arts
school at the north end of the town of 3,372.
</P>
<P>
   Before this year the family lived in Winslow, Maine, where
Christopher Jones, who holds a doctorate in forensic science, was
director of Young Laboratories, a private lab, according to
published reports. The parent company later was acquired by
Binax//NEL, and the laboratory in Winslow no longer operates.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Marcoux, an assistant librarian at the Winslow Public
Library, remembers helping Christopher Jones with research journals
for his work, and she remembers him helping the children with
books. All the family members were regular visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' Marcoux said Friday. ``They were lovely
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcoux said ``rumors are a dime a dozen'' in town since the
homicides were reported, and she sharply criticized an anonymous
description in the local newspaper that characterized Jones as
lazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not have called him lazy at all,'' she said. ``He was
a very brainy man.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones had no police record in Winslow, according to a police
clerk.
</P>
<P>
   This year, after Jones lost his job in Maine, the family moved
to Lindsborg, where he hoped to start his own business. They moved
into the former home of Cathy Jones' grandmother, Ruby Mayden, who
died in December.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks ago Cathy Jones got a job as an office assistant for
the Lindsborg Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Things were not going so well with Christopher's plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he had a dream of going into some kind of private
business in Lindsborg,'' Smith said. ``As he pursued avenues of
approach, he felt like doors were not opening and he was a little
despondent about it.''
</P>
<P>
   If there were problems, however, neighbors did not know about
them.
</P>
<P>
   They saw Christopher as a stay-at-home husband who doted on his
children, often taking them for walks along the tree-lined streets.
He worked hard to keep his lawn in shape.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, 91-year-old Martin Ringstrom, a retired
Lutheran pastor, was watching TV in his living room Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   He thought he heard a siren. ``The thought crossed my mind: I
hope it's nothing serious.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not know how serious it was until the next morning when
he saw the house surrounded by police cars.
</P>
<P>
   Ringstrom also said Christopher Jones had been unable to find
employment and that could have weighed on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had probably been building up for some time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The killings left Lindsborg residents in disbelief, particularly
since children were the victims.
</P>
<P>
   At Soderstrom Elementary School, where Christopher was in the
second grade and Joshua in kindergarten, students and faculty were
devastated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of shock and sadness about the kids. They were
characterized by the teachers and principal as `friendly kids,
happy kids,' '' said the school district's superintendent, Marlin
Berry.
</P>
<P>
   The district's crisis intervention team was called to the
school, where members met with teachers and pupils Thursday and
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In Winslow, too, counselors were at the elementary school
7-year-old Christopher once attended.
</P>
<P>
   Marcoux on Friday remembered a 7-year-old who was ``very
bright'' and would announce his presence by proudly saying, ``I'm
Christopher George Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish Cathy all the best _ I can't imagine,'' Marcoux said.
``She's lost her children, and she's lost her husband, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
