<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-VALENTINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENTINE'S TIMING MIGHT NEED WORK, IT SEEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS) 
(mk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bobby Valentine was a championship ballroom dancer as
a teen-ager, but his sense of timing could not have been worse this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine was the subject of a profile in Sports Illustrated in
which, among other things, he was quoted as saying that his
pitching coach, Dave Wallace, then a member of the front office,
was involved in the decision to dismiss Valentine's hitting coach
and close friend Tom Robson.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of the players on the expanded September roster, he
was quoted as saying, ``You're not dealing with real professionals
in the clubhouse'' and ``you're not dealing with real intelligent
guys for the most part'' in explaining why he was concerned about
``five guys in there right now who basically are losers, who are
seeing if they can recruit'' malcontents.
</P>
<P>
   The article also said that Valentine's wife, Mary, had
encouraged him to resign and that those closest to him would be
surprised if he returned as Mets manager next season.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said Friday that there were several inaccuracies in
the article. Among others, he said that his wife had never wanted
him to quit and that he didn't know who would be surprised if he
returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife has always been the push behind me to continue to do
my best,'' Valentine said. ``I've always said I'd be back unless we
didn't win the wild card.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine also said the statements attributed to him about
Wallace were inaccurate. ``He didn't have anything to do with the
firing of the hitting coach and I never said he did. Either I said
it inaccurately or he reported it inaccurately. I think he reported
it inaccurately.''
</P>
<P>
   But did he say it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt it,'' Valentine responded.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine did not deny his remarks about his players, which he
made while they held a players-only meeting in Philadelphia during
the team's recent seven-game losing streak. The article said
Valentine was particularly concerned about the influence of Bobby
Bonilla on the rest of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an overall comment I made,'' Valentine said, referring
to his remarks about the players' intelligence. ``I said, `We're
not rocket scientists.' I think I was talking in general. The
question was, `Are you worried about someone having undue
influence?' Of course. That was an expanded roster. That wasn't the
team with us all year. It was people I didn't know very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, who did not seem upset about the article, said he
spoke to general manager Steve Phillips about it. Phillips seemed
irritated by it, although he said he would not try to smooth things
over between the manager and his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of timing issues this year,'' Phillips said.
``The timing is not good. It's something Bobby will have to handle
within the confines of the clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the players, most of them had either not heard about the
article or had not read it. ``I don't care,'' Rickey Henderson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla had a different opinion about the man he has feuded with
throughout the season. ``I'm extremely disappointed,'' he said.
``It's not so much the timing, I'm just disappointed he would say
some things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla, asked about the statement that the players aren't
intelligent, responded, ``I knew I should have finished that
scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   Those Excitable Fans
</P>
<P>
   As the Mets warmed up before their first postseason game at Shea
Stadium in 11 years, the fans seemed more excited than the players
did, at least on the outside. Even if Mike Piazza would not be in
the lineup, there were dozens of fans clad in his jersey, shouting
encouragement to the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be one of the few guys in the locker room to know what
this atmosphere is going to be like,'' said John Franco, who grew
up a Mets fan and was sitting in the stands during the Mets' last
playoff series, against the Los Angeles Dodgers in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Franco, who played for the Reds at the time, went to the game
with a friend but did not stick around for the outcome. They
departed when Mike Scioscia hit a two-run home run in the ninth
inning off Dwight Gooden to send the game into extra innings. The
Mets lost in 12, creating a 2-2 tie in the series, which the Mets
lost in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in Cincinnati in 1988, I came to the playoff game
against the Dodgers, the game Scioscia hit the homer off of Doc,''
Franco recalled. ``When he hit it, we got up and left. My buddy was
sick to his stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night the crowd was loud, beginning with the pregame
introductions, and loyal nearly to a fault, but still booing a
hometown target, Bobby Bonilla, and cheering the former Met Bernard
Gilkey.
</P>
<P>
   Al Leiter, Saturday's scheduled starting pitcher, who also grew
up nearby as a Mets fan, added: ``I expect it to be crazy and
obviously very supportive for us. We felt it even during the Braves
series in the regular season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
