<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1530 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-PRESS-NYT &LR;      10-09 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-PRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE OFFICIAL BLAMES NEWS COVERAGE FOR MURDER INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The city's deputy police commissioner who oversees
crime-fighting strategies contends that negative news coverage has
so intimidated police officers that they are reluctant to patrol
aggressively, and that their reluctance is why murders are
increasing.
</P>
<P>
   While Police Commissioner Howard Safir has said in the past year
that negative coverage has hurt the effectiveness of police, none
of his statements has been as strong as the ones made on Thursday
by Edward Norris, the deputy commissioner for operations, who
blamed news coverage for the murder increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not stopping people and being as assertive as we
were,'' Norris said. He blamed news coverage that questions the
official version of events for intimidating and demoralizing police
officers. ``That is why we are seeing the street shootings we had
not seen for years,'' Norris said, speaking at a seminar at the
John Jay College of Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Homicides are up 10 percent so far this year, compared with the
same period last year. Other police officials have said in recent
months, however, that murders linked to domestic violence are
pushing the crime increase, and that is something that police
officers, demoralized or not, can do little to prevent. Those
officials are now saying that street crimes are contributing to the
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Davitt, a spokesman for the Brooklyn district attorney,
Charles Hynes, whose office has established a task force to study
the homicide rise in that borough, said the increase in murders
appears to be caused by a rise in both domestic violence and street
shootings. ``We feel that people who may have hesitated to carry a
gun in prior years seem to have lost that hesitation,'' Davitt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Norris, the police official in charge of the office that advises
Safir on anti-crime strategies and coordinates the program that
holds commanders responsible for crime in their precincts and
boroughs, was specifically critical of coverage in The New York
Times. He did not cite specific articles.
</P>
<P>
   He said that coverage ``particularly in The Times, has led
people to believe that we are a brutal, horrible agency that is
stopping crime by stomping on people's rights.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that anyone skeptical of his conclusion ask police
officers ``if they want to be the next guy to get involved in one
of these incidents where the shooting is questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   The result, Norris said, is that ``instead of doing what we
should do, and see how the facts weigh out in court, as we used to
do, and we should do in this society _ and everyone else gets that
privilege _ every time a police officer gets involved in something
he is convicted in the media the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Norris' comments came four days after Safir attacked The Times
for an article that found sharp differences between the
commissioner's initial account of the September shooting by police
of a hammer-wielding mentally ill man in Brooklyn, and the findings
of investigators preparing the case for a Brooklyn grand jury. The
investigators believe the man was not striking a sergeant with his
hammer or even in physical contact with police when he was shot.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lelyveld, the executive editor of The Times, said Friday
that it was unfair for Norris to blame news coverage for the rise
in murders. ``We weren't given credit for lowering the murder rate
when we were writing about the Giuliani administration's
innovations,'' Lelyveld said. ``I don't think that it is fair to
blame us when we begin writing about some of the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the deputy commissioner got carried away with
himself,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials, including Safir, have complained for months
about news coverage that they say is causing officers to become
more timid. Safir has said that the criticism of police has
intensified since the killing in February of Amadou Diallo, an
unarmed West African immigrant, who was shot 19 times by four
Street Crime Unit officers in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Norris said that arrests that would take guns off
the street were down because of news coverage. He said arrests have
dropped to 286,651 so far this year, compared with 311,578 at this
point last year, an 8 percent decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming feeling on patrol, and you know this as well
as anybody else, stop-and-frisk arrests are down,'' Norris added.
</P>
<P>
   The Street Crime Unit, which makes up about one percent of the
force, in previous years made 20 percent of the gun-possession
arrests. Norris said those numbers were down, although specific
numbers were not available Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The unit's stop-and-frisk policies have been a source of
contention among leaders in predominantly minority communities who
say officers would stop people for no reason. After the Diallo
killing, Safir placed the Street Crime Unit officers in uniform. He
is now allowing some to return to plain clothes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 0008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
