A1532 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NY-PARK-NYT &LR;      10-09 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-PARK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE VIEW FROM CITY HALL PARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Oct. 9:
</P>
<P>
   New York's City Hall Park sparkled on its opening day with new
plantings and the old Jacob Wrey Mould fountain dragged back from
Crotona Park in the Bronx and restored. The renovation paid
attention to historical details, returning the public space south
of City Hall to its original geometry, with fixtures such as the
fountain lights and the park's new fence modeled on the originals.
But the restoration does not change the fact that the new park is
utterly cut off from City Hall by chains and guards.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has imposed tight
restrictions on the use of the steps and plaza in front of City
Hall for public rallies and demonstrations. Now the public is
prevented from walking from the park to those areas in front of
City Hall. City Council Speaker Peter Vallone boycotted the park
dedication ceremony because, he says, Giuliani should have
increased public access to City Hall after the park construction
was finished.
</P>
<P>
   For years the City Hall steps and plaza have provided public
spaces for those who wished to address city policies. Giuliani
argues that security requires him to tightly control use of those
public areas.
</P>
<P>
   His policies, however, seem designed to control some groups but
not others. The rules restrict groups seeking to hold rallies in
front of City Hall to 50 people. Yet the policy allows
city-approved or -sponsored events to be exempt from that rule,
thus giving the government the final say over who must abide by the
numerical limits.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor allowed more than 5,000 people to gather to celebrate
the Yankees' 1998 World Series victory in the same spot where other
groups that do not have the mayor's support are limited to 50
participants.
</P>
<P>
   A case challenging the constitutionality of this policy is now
in federal district court before Judge Harold Baer. The court has
already rejected an earlier policy that limited demonstrations to
25 people. No one would argue with measures that are carefully
designed to meet real security threats. But the First Amendment
grants the highest level of protection to political speech in
public places. It puts the burden on government to show that any
limits placed on such speech are narrowly tailored to address
significant government concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The administration will have to show in court how greatly
restricting the use of the space around City Hall meets those
criteria. It must also demonstrate that exemptions are applied
fairly to all groups. City Hall Park does not now feel as if it is
part of City Hall. But it does give the public a nice place to view
their seat of government from afar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 0014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991009.0008 </DOCNO>
