<HEADLINE>
CONSTRUCTION SEES RIVETING SURGE IN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- An uptick in highway and heavy construction plus
a surge of projects in Southern California helped boost
construction activity across California 13.4 percent during the
first eight months of this year, an industry tracker said on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The growth to $33 billion in construction is being driven in
part by a 21.7 percent increase in residential activity, a pace
that will likely result in about 144,000 new units being built this
year, said Burbank-based Construction Industry Research Board. The
residential construction includes single-family homes, condominiums
and apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the residential growth came in the seven county Southern
California region, with San Diego leading the way in total units,
said Ben Bartolotto, the research board's director.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County also turned in a robust performance as
builders pulled permits for 8,875 units, up 27.9 percent on an
annual basis, during the year's first eight months.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clarita Valley led the way in Los Angeles County with
1,145 units, an annual increase of 57 percent, Bartolotto said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is definitely a lot of work going on right now, though
I'm not sure how long it will last,'' he said. ``It's an old story.
This region took longer to recover, and in recent months there are
indications that (activity) is slowing.''
</P>
<P>
   While Southern California is leading the surge in residential
construction across the state, the pace is still not brisk enough
to satisfy demand for new housing.
</P>
<P>
   The California Department of Finance housing forecast for 1999
matches that of the research boards. Bottom line: Construction
increases are good news but not good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing, to be honest with you,'' said Ted Gibson,
the finance department's chief economist. ``The state was building
a quarter of a million units a year in the second half of the 1980s
and we are just a long way from there now.''
</P>
<P>
   The local numbers reflect Gibson's dismay.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clarita is expected to finish the year with about 2,600
new housing units. But that is far below the 6,750 units built
there in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   That means homes are going to be more expensive in the future.
For example, the median price in some Northern California
communities is now about $400,000, he noted, because of a tight
market.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, nonresidential building is up 7.4 percent and highway
and heavy construction is up 2 percent during the first eight
months of the year on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's report marked only the second time this year that this
sector has been in the plus column for month-to-month and
year-to-date comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   A big reason is the influx of new federal funding due to a new
federal act that is expected to generate $800 million for a variety
of projects during the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   The research board is forecasting the heavy construction sector
to bring in $7.6 billion in 1999, up 2.3 percent from 1998. This
will be the first positive gain in this sector since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 0022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991009.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1544 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-HMOS-BOS &LR;      10-09 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-HMOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGED CARE MISHMASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bill that passed the US House this week to protect patients
in managed care plans contained so much junk that it must have been
designed by the House leadership not to become law. Still, hidden
in the bill are provisions that, if stripped out and passed
separately, would provide sound protection for patients without
disrupting the tax code or providing disguised subsidies for
medical activities Congress should not regulate.
</P>
<P>
   A managed care bill ought to feature:
</P>
<P>
   --Requirements for internal and external review of health plan
decisions that patients or physicians consider unwise. Doctors must
be free to advise their patients honestly without fear of
retribution.
</P>
<P>
   --A provision that a patient can be treated in any hospital
emergency room in a medical crisis, even if the hospital is not
part of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   --A provision that a patient should have access to specialist
care if he or she has a serious medical condition that warrants
such treatment and a mandate that if a plan drops a physician from
its network, an ill patient would not be forced to seek a new
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   All of these are in the House bill _ and, unfortunately, much
more, including the most controversial provision, which would allow
patients to sue plans for malpractice. The House bill would bar a
patient from seeking punitive damages if the plan could prove it
relied on an independent review board in making a decision on
coverage. This is a sensible exception that ought to encourage
plans to arrange for impartial and quick-acting external reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of the bill, however, made a mistake when they mandated
that managed care plans pay the ``routine costs'' of clinical
trials for critically ill patients. These costs are far from
routine if they involve expensive hospitalization. Also, this bill
is no place to impose federal regulation on an extremely complex
subject. The matter of how much society ought to pay _ through
direct government subsidy or insurance premiums _ for what is
essentially scientific experimentation is one that deserves lengthy
scrutiny and a separate piece of legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of the bill dip their toes into another complex issue
as well: the extent to which plans should use ``formularies,'' or
preferred lists of drugs, instead of allowing doctors to prescribe
whatever they believe is necessary. The bill mandates that health
plans make exceptions to the formularies when medically necessary,
an elusive standard that would mean more work for the independent
review board.
</P>
<P>
   By itself this section, though unnecessary, would do no harm.
Its great weakness is that it does not address the urgent issue of
how plans can be expected to pay the high costs of drugs when
pharmaceutical firms are free to advertise their latest inventions
to consumers and when companies refuse to accept any government
role in setting prices.
</P>
<P>
   The managed care bill could easily have been trimmed into a
sound piece of legislation if not for a gambit by members of the
the House Republican leadership. Under the guise of reducing the
number of people without medical insurance, they added several
changes in the tax code that would benefit wealthier individuals
and companies with medical interests. They know that President
Clinton will veto the bill if it ever reaches his desk. The
House-Senate conference committee should spare him the task by
excising the tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   The most costly of them is a tax reduction for health insurance
premiums paid by people who do not have company-subsidized health
insurance. This makes some sense, since companies are allowed to
deduct their enormous premium costs from their tax bills. But the
proposal has nothing to do with managed care improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Because most of the uninsured do not make much money and cannot
afford insurance premiums even with a tax reduction, the proposal
would do little to provide them with health coverage. Most of the
people taking the deduction would be affluent enough to afford
insurance without the need of a tax break. A plan proposed by
presidential candidate Bill Bradley to offer direct premium
subsidies to low-income workers would do much more to reduce the
number of uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Republicans' add-ons, the bill will probably not
pass this year. But managed care remains a vexing issue for many
Americans. The elements of a sound bill are within reach if
Congress has the will to pass one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
