A1547 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-AID-BOS &LR;      10-09 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-AID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IMPOVERISHED FOREIGN AID BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the furor that surrounds the debate on foreign aid each
year, it is easy to forget that it represents just 1 percent of all
federal spending. The Republican-controlled Congress, wanting to
slash foreign aid even further, sent President Clinton a shamefully
inadequate spending plan this week that mocks US claims to be a
power for good in the world. The president would be well justified
in vetoing the plan and sending Congress back to the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   An isolationist strain is running strong through Congress and
much of the public. But an examination of the programs cut by
Congress in the foreign operations budget highlights their
importance. For example, the proposed budget would eliminate 100
percent of the funds to implement the Wye River accords, which are
still the best hope for peace in the Middle East. It would slash
funding nearly in half for peacekeeping commitments in Kosovo,
Bosnia, and Croatia. Itwould cut by 21 percent funding for
counterterrorism programs and efforts to curb the proliferation of
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   This does not even begin to count the ``humanitarian'' side of
foreign spending. The proposal sent to Clinton would slash
international disaster aid, the Peace Corps, AIDS prevention,
family planning programs, and environmental initiatives on matters
ranging from global warming to safe drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   With this budget Congress also dismisses out of hand the debt
forgiveness plan agreed upon at a June meeting of the Group of
Seven industrialized nations in Cologne. The budget would underfund
by over 90 percent the effort to relieve the international debt
that is crippling poor nations and destabilizing their governments.
The G7 relief plan is a historic opportunity to restructure foreign
aid to poor countries, specifying that funds be used for health,
education, and poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomacy is not just about the niceties of protocol. It is
essential to the national interest and the national defense. In an
interdependent world, such efforts must be advanced, not strangled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
