r s BC-BBA-CLEMENS-TEX     10-09 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLEMENS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS MIGHT HAVE PROFITED FROM LOSING CLEMENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The debate continues over ``The Big Picture
vs. The Big Pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' failure to acquire right-hander Roger Clemens in
February might be the best trade general manager Doug Melvin never
made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's best in the long run that we didn't make it,''
Melvin said. ``It might have been OK in the short run, but you can
get into a lot of trouble making short-term decisions. Who knows,
though? He might have performed better down here.''
</P>
<P>
   The defending World Series champion New York Yankees will send
the five-time Cy Young Award recipient to the mound tonight at The
Ballpark in Arlington for Game 3 of the best-of-five Division
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens could be the person who paints the finishing touches on
the Yankees' second consecutive three-game postseason sweep of the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario drips with irony considering the Rangers came
within a bang-bang play at first of acquiring Clemens from the
Toronto Blue Jays for center fielder Ruben Mateo and right-handers
Esteban Loaiza and Jonathan Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers turned their attention toward Clemens after failing
to lure left-hander Randy Johnson to Arlington, despite offering a
four-year contract worth $51 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, he was certainly one of the two premier starting
pitchers that Doug and I talked at length about trying to interest
in coming here,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   It might be best for the Rangers that their bid failed.
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   The slide. Clemens went 41-13 with a 2.33 earned-run average en
route to Cy Young Awards Nos. 4 and 5 during his final two seasons
with the Blue Jays, but the former University of Texas standout
slipped to 14-10 with a 4.60 ERA this season.
</P>
<P>
   The top two members of the Rangers' rotation _ right-handers
Aaron Sele (18-9, 4.79) and Rick Helling (13-11, 4.84) _ had
similar seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more surprised than anybody else when he doesn't do
well,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``The reason I feel he will
do well _ and I've always felt that way _ is what he's brought to
the table all these years. You win five Cy Youngs. Understand you
don't forget that. You don't fall off the end of the earth that
quickly after winning one last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palmeiro Factor. The Rangers ``might not be in the
postseason today'' without designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro,
Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro hit .324 with 47 home runs and 148 runs batted in and
likely will merit serious consideration for the AL Most Valuable
Player Award. It would have been difficult for the Rangers' payroll
to support the salaries of Palmeiro, who signed a five-year
contract worth $45 million, and the remaining $16.1 million owed
Clemens for the 1999 and 2000 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether that would have happened,'' Melvin said.
``I might have had to do something else to make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Money plus talent: The Rangers also would have been forced to
part with Mateo, whom the organization views as a future All-Star
waiting to blossom, for a 37-year-old pitcher who can demand a
trade this winter after being dealt during the midst of a multiyear
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Melvin favored acquiring Clemens at the time
``even though it might not have been the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't say, `No,' to it,'' Melvin said. ``Toronto said,
`No,' to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays accepted the Yankees' offer of left-handers David
Wells and Graeme Lloyd and second baseman Homer Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing about being the GM is that you've got to look at
the big picture,'' Melvin said. ``You've got to look at the long
term and the short term and balance one against the other.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
