<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COUNTDOWN100-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANES CAN'T STOP FLUTIE'S MAGICAL PASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When 36-year-old Gerard Phelan is introduced to people the
introductions usually conclude this way, ``That's the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 23, 1984, ``the guy'' was a rain-soaked Boston College
receiver standing on a tattered Miami 48-yard line with six seconds
remaining as BC trailed the defending national champion Miami
Hurricanes, 45-41.
</P>
<P>
   While the Hurricanes celebrated their apparent victory, Phelan's
roommate, quarterback Doug Flutie, called flood-tip for the game's
final play. Eight-point-three seconds later, Phelan would attain
college football immortality and become ``the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day when Flutie passed for 472 yards and three touchdowns
and virtually assured himself of the Heisman Trophy, this game _
and arguably his career _ is defined by these final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Against a Hurricanes defense that included future NFL stars
Jerome Brown, Daniel Stubbs, Kevin Fagan, Winston Moss and Bennie
Blades, Flutie was flushed from the pocket by Brown as time ran out
and uncorked a pass from his own 36.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly don't think they thought Doug could throw the ball
that far,'' BC coach Jack Bicknell said.
</P>
<P>
   All the while Phelan and Miami defensive backs Darrel
Fullington, Tolbert Bain and Ken Calhoun back-peddled near the goal
line before the Miami trio jumped simultaneously for the ball at
the 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a brown ball against a black night, it's raining, there's
a sea of bodies in front of me and for a second I couldn't see
it,'' said Phelan, who caught 11 passes for 226 yards and two
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   They shielded Phelan from the ball until it came down into his
body. Suddenly, Phelan _ and the ball _ were in the end zone with
no time remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't tip it which made it harder because that ball was
really coming hard,'' Phelan said. ``It hit me below the face mask
and I grabbed it as it rolled down my chest.''
</P>
<P>
   His catch gave No. 10 BC a that-didn't-just-happen 47-45 victory
over the No. 12 Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Phelan is a sales representative living in Boston with
three children of his own, including 8-year-old and 6-year-old sons
who know their dad's famous catch and have friends who run that
play in backyard games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a special memory for me,'' Phelan said. ``It would have
been awful had I dropped it and I turned into a Buckner-esque
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Phelan was immediately mobbed by BC teammates while the
Hurricanes were surrounded by disbelieving stares and broken
hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it doesn't take away that sick feeling, but they have
nothing to be ashamed of because they gave it all they had,''
first-year coach Jimmy Johnson said. ``It's just a shame that the
final score wasn't a few seconds earlier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
