A1550 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-MAGIC-BOS &LR;      10-09 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MAGIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNSOUND SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   People want to believe in magic, and they often find it in
misinterpreted science. The supposed ``Mozart effect'' has pregnant
women standing close to stereo speakers so their babies can hear
music that will make them smarter.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the original research made no claims about
general intelligence or about infants, in the womb or in the crib.
The 1993 University of Wisconsin study merely found that adults
answering spatial relationship questions on an IQ test had a
temporary boost in their scores after listening to 10 minutes of a
Mozart piano concerto.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting, yes, and worth further exploration, but not a
prelude for the baby music madness that has spawned an industry of
CD and videotape sales and even prompted some states to send new
mothers home from the hospital with free samples of classical
music.
</P>
<P>
   Like all science, the University of Wisconsin report was the
beginning of a journey that more research will advance, either by
disproving or corroborating all or part of the original findings.
Harvard psychologist Christopher Chabris has done studies showing
that Mozart has a minimal impact on test scores, while physicist
Gordon Shaw at the University of California-Irvine has data that
support the Wisconsin paper.
</P>
<P>
   For now they're both right. But an impatient public, eager for
absolutes, does not take the time to digest complexities. People
want quick fixes and believe that the miracles of science _ which
can replace human organs, change genetic destiny, and make babies
in test tubes _ must surely have the formula to enhance brain
power.
</P>
<P>
   Well-meaning parents treat their children like pots of stew,
dropping in what the experts have supposedly shown to be the
ingredients for greatness. People tinker with themselves on the
basis of such informational fragments, gulping down vitamins,
embracing the latest herb craze, or overexercising because of a new
study with ``the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is no one answer, and there is no magic. In science,
as in daily living, success depends on an open mind and common
sense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 0055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
