<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AUTUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FIRST AUTUMN FIRE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Oct. 9:
</P>
<P>
   One day last spring, the fire in the kitchen woodstove went out
and was never relit. I didn't record the date, because some endings
are lost in a crowd of beginnings, passing unnoticed until months
later, when the oversight seems almost melancholy. So I note here
the first fire of the new season: Monday, October 4, thermometer
lodged in the mid-40s, a chill in the bones of the house, rain
falling hard through dwindling yellow hickory leaves.
</P>
<P>
   When the kindling caught the first dry log _ a length of honey
locust _ in its flames, the stove called all the dogs. They
sprawled across the warm tiles, mouths agape. Not a half-hour had
ticked away, and there we were, back on the night before the fire
went out for the last time last spring.
</P>
<P>
   A kind of accounting has been going on here for the past few
weeks, how many pounds of honey gathered, how many bales of hay
laid up in the barn-loft, how many cords of wood stacked and under
cover. This is such an ancestral satisfaction _ the antithesis of
the city's constant abundance _ that it feels almost embarrassing
to acknowledge it, the sign of the hayseed. But even here, where
farms are few now, a sense of harvest clings to the rural landscape
like the sudden mist that forms in the mornings when the mercury
first rises. The manure pile, steaming in the cool drizzle, looks
like simple wealth, and so do the hickory nuts that crack beneath
my feet as I walk to the barn and the milkweed pods that crowd
against the fenceline, ready to burst. There is a fine crop of
horsehair coming in on the mares and the gelding. It will go to
make bird nests in spring.
</P>
<P>
   In April, what you see are your own intentions. In October you
see their unexpected wreck and fulfillment. All summer, potato
vines spread across a corner of the garden. But when I lifted a
plant, hoping to rob new potatoes, I saw that the vines, every one,
had rotted right at the soil. Meanwhile, two peach trees _ planted
vainly, I thought, by previous owners _ blossomed heavily and set
fruit. When September came, the peaches turned as red as the
Virginia creeper is turning now. I finally picked one, just to
savor my doubts. But it was the very promise of a peach. A garden
is so full of cheap sermons.
</P>
<P>
   _ VERLYN KLINKENBORG
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991009.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1553 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-INDONESIANS     10-09 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-INDONESIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNWELCOME STUDENTS IN VERMONT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, October 10, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Norwich University, a private military college in Vermont,
should end its training program for students from the Indonesian
Army and its infamous special forces unit known as Kopassus.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, after a UN-supervised referendum in which the East
Timorese voted overwhelmingly for independence, the world watched
in horror as so-called militias formed and directed by the
Indonesian Army, in particular by officers from Kopassus, murdered
defenseless civilians, among them priests and nuns. They put whole
villages to the torch and displaced almost the entire population of
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton reacted by suspending all military cooperation
with Indonesia. This was the least Washington could do to
dissociate Americans from the murders, rapes, and arson supervised
by an Indonesian officer class that had benefited from joint
training and exercises with the US military.
</P>
<P>
   But the Norwich program, which amounts to an evasion of the
administration's ban on military cooperation with Indonesia, has
not been curtailed. In a letter last week to Defense Secretary
William Cohen, two Democratic members of Congress, Representative
James McGovern of Massachusetts and Senator Tom Harkin of Iowa,
wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``We were deeply disturbed to read in the Oct. 4, 1999, Boston
Globe about Indonesian Army recruits being trained at Norwich
University in Vermont at a time when President Clinton has declared
all US relations with the Indonesian military have been effectively
suspended. . . . We believe this training of Indonesian military
recruits who openly identify themselves as part of Kopassus is in
direct violation of congressional prohitions on US military
assistance and training of military committing human rights
abuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, McGovern and Harkin asked Cohen to ``investigate and
identify all members of the Indonesian military, including
recruits, who are studying in the United States'' and have them
returned to Indonesia. The presence of such students at Norwich
University defiles that institution, Vermont, and the cause of
human rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
