<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYSTEM WORKS FOR KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; WASHINGTON, D.C. _ The Kings arrived here during rush hour
Friday afternoon, which was fine because they were in no hurry.
Practice was canceled. The Washington Capitals, tonight's opponent,
were in Buffalo playing the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   And after four games in six days, they were able to savor all
the elements of Thursday night's 5-2 victory over Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings scored four power-play goals, three by Luc Robitaille,
who leads the league with six goals. Last season their power-play
efficiency was 13.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Their record is 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   But more important, they were able to put the new system of
coach Andy Murray back in place after Wednesday's brutal loss to
the Florida Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   When the Kings came out flat in the first 10 minutes against
Tampa Bay, a few players started to wonder about the carryover
effect of Wednesday's game. The Kings had a 2-1 lead with less than
two minutes to play before allowing three goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have lost this game (vs. Tampa Bay) last year,''
captain Rob Blake said. ``It would have taken awhile to recover.''
</P>
<P>
   But Murray has a plan to break with the past. In a lengthy
meeting before Thursday's game, he stressed the players' need to
remain accountable to the team. He also singled out several
players, including Blake, for their poor play against the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Then he turned it over to his assistants, Dave Tippett and Mark
Hardy, to put the pieces back together.
</P>
<P>
   Tippett, who runs the club's power-play drills in practice, had
success earlier in the week working on faceoffs with first-line
center Jozef Stumpel. Stumpel is not a strong defensive player, but
he won three faceoffs in the final 20.3 seconds during Monday's
victory over St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good-cop, bad-cop thing and I have no problem with
that,'' Murray said. ``I think our meeting was very constructive. I
am a demanding coach but not a demeaning coach. I expect a lot, but
I am not going to tear into a player just to do it. You have to
bring the positives out of a negative situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray said part of Thursday's power-play success was timing. In
the first few games, the Kings often went on the man advantage when
their top line was well into its shift and unable to return right
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like we couldn't get them on the ice until 30
seconds had passed,'' Murray said. ``In this game, we had them
fresh at the start.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
