<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGIOUS-ICON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAITHFUL JAM CHURCH TO SEE ICON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ROBERT MONROE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nearly 2,000 people came to Our Lady of the Valley
Catholic Church on Friday night, jamming the pews, the choir loft,
the aisles and even the altar to get close to a traveling image of
Our Lady of Guadalupe that has been blessed by the Pope.
</P>
<P>
   They wept and shuddered, and prayed fervently to the beloved
Mexican icon, whose digital image has been drawing large crowds at
Los Angeles churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big deal,'' said Eduardo Chavez, the 23-year-old driver
who has been transporting the framed image from church to church in
the back of his Chevy pickup truck. ``One, it's the only one in the
United States; two, we have the largest population of Mexicans
outside of Mexico City in Los Angeles; and three, it's been blessed
by the Pope.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Macias and her mother Graciela held each other and cried
as several men unloaded the image from the truck. Graciela said she
prayed to the image when her 19-year-old daughter was a baby
needing surgery. After Graciela's promise to visit Our Lady of
Guadalupe, doctors told her Nancy no longer needed surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard she was coming here, I said now is the time to
bring her,'' said Graciela Macias, 53, gesturing to Nancy.
</P>
<P>
   Our Lady of Guadalupe, who Catholics believe appeared to a
Mexican man and left behind her image on his cloak as a sign, has
come to take on not only religious significance but is also an
emblem of Mexican culture, many said. Victor Villalba, vice
president of public relations for the Pueblo Corporation sponsoring
the tour, said the icon has elicited veneration from more than just
Mexican-Americans on its tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has been very eye-opening to me personally is that she
means a lot to a lot of people from a lot of ethnicities,''
Villalba said.
</P>
<P>
   At Our Lady of the Valley, the image was carried into the
church, preceded by a Mexican flag, accompanied by dancers in Aztec
dress and serenaded by mariachis. But Manny Singson, wearing the
traditional Filipino dress shirt known as a barong, said Our Lady
of Guadalupe has appeal beyond Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their culture is the same as our culture,'' Singson said.
</P>
<P>
   The original icon is a poncho worn by a Mexican campesino to
whom the Virgin Mary appeared in 1531, believers say. The woman in
Juan Diego's vision asked him to pick roses to convince a skeptical
bishop to erect a cathedral at Tepeyac in Mexico City. He did and
wrapped them in the poncho. He took the roses back to the bishop,
but underneath the poncho, they had been transformed into the
image.
</P>
<P>
   The original cloak remains visible at the Basilica of Tepeyac,
but even a reproduction draws crowds at every church it's been
taken to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same image,'' said Singson. ``It's the faith here
that we're talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   The image will remain at Our Lady of the Valley until Sunday,
when it moves to St. Patrick's Church in North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez said that as he drives the image to its display sites, he
has seen other drivers on the freeway keep pace with him to look at
it in the back of his truck before speeding off.
</P>
<P>
   In his rear-view mirror, he has seen them cross themselves in
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
