<HEADLINE>
DESPITE LOSS, D-BACK FANS
 STILL HOPEFUL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 By LES POLK 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  NEW YORK _ The Diamond-back ers'
section behind home plate was lost for a while in the din as the
Mets broke open Game 3.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the few, the proud, the Arizona fans who came to Shea
Stadium for Friday (Oct. 8) night's playoff game plan to be back in
force, with Diamondbacks rattles in tow, today (Oct. 9) for Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, they said they're proud of their team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done a great job,'' said Jeanne Miller, catcher Damian
Mill er's wife.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first playoff game in 11 years at the crusty old ball
yard, and a raucous crowd saw the Mets run away with it, 9-2, to
take a 2-1 lead in the National League division series.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the rough outing, the Arizona fans were having a nice
time in the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more tame than we thought it would be,'' said Erica
Mantei, wife of reliever Matt Mantei. ``It's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her husband had never let her come to New York before
because he hates the place.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' group was cau tioned against wearing flashy
Dia mondbacks gear and even told to keep the noisemakers at home,
Jeanne Miller said. Yet they encoun tered little trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really been very easy here,'' Miller said. ``It's my
first time in New York, too.''
</P>
<P>
   One brave soul in the Diamondbacks cheering section wore his
D-Backs black visiting road cap.
</P>
<P>
   Most were incognito in your basic New York black leather.
</P>
<P>
   Others included an 83-year-old grandmother, two New York cops
from Queens, a Brooklyn man and his son, and three busloads with
the Diamondbacks' official traveling party.
</P>
<P>
   They gave Turner Ward a standing ovation after his pinch-hit
two-run brought the Diamondbacks within one run of the Mets, 3-2,
in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't even give up after the Mets put up six runs in the
sixth inning on four hits and two walks, setting off a jubilant
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK; we're going to take it home and win,'' said Donna
Riley, whose husband, Roger, is in charge of travel for the team.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, even some of the cops keeping an eye on the
Diamondbacks section were high-fiving and celebrat ing an apparent
Mets win.
</P>
<P>
   The official party had a police escort to Shea from their
midtown Manhat tan hotel and praised their treatment everywhere in
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has been so nice and considerate,'' said Dee
Robbins, who works on team travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were more afraid of people jumping in front of the bus on
the street'' than of Mets fans, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Davis, 83, traveled all the way from New Mexico for the
game. Her grandson, Dave, is the team's assist ant trainer.
</P>
<P>
   She flew from El Paso to Baltimore, where she met her daughter,
Punkie Garretson, from Johnstown, Pa. The two of them then rode an
Amtrak train to New York.
</P>
<P>
   They took the subway to the ball park, and were having blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said they couldn't lose if I would come all this way,''
Davis said. ``They better win.''
</P>
<P>
   Garretson went to Opening Day at Bank One Ballpark last year and
travels to see the team when they're on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting,'' she said. ``They've come so far.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Ryan and Eddie Trentin, the New York cops, got their
tickets because Pete's dad chauffeurs Dia mondbacks boss Jerry
Colangelo around New York.
</P>
<P>
   They'd like to see an Arizona-New York Yankees World Series, not
a Subway Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate the Mets with a passion,'' Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   He smiled: ``I hope nobody tries to kill us.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cardinale proudly wore his Diamondbacks cap outside the
park on Casey Stengel Plaza, waiting to pick up his tickets with
his son, Billy Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinale, whose father, Phil, played for the Brooklyn Dodgers,
has friends affiliated with the Diamond backs and he's a fan.
</P>
<P>
   He's also a Yankees fan, and can't stand the Mets, adding that
he figured the Diamondbacks would clobber the Mets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
