<HEADLINE>
STILL-ACHING KNEE HAS PALMEIRO CONCERNED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rafael Palmeiro is concerned about his
injured right knee to the point that he is planning to seek an
additional medical opinion after the season.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro said he doesn't believe more surgery will be needed,
but he is concerned because the knee hurt worse than expected in
the cold weather of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just need to get on a rehabilitation program and rebuild my
leg muscles,'' Palmeiro said. ``It definitely bothered me much more
than I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro originally injured the knee while working out in the
off-season and underwent arthoscopic surgery on Feb. 10 to repair
torn cartilage. He re-injured the knee in spring training and had a
second operation on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I worried about the long-term effects?'' Palmeiro said.
``You have to be when you have a surgery like that. But I'll tell
you what, if I was told my knee wasn't going to get any better, I
could still go out and play defense. I'll be out there playing for
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm much more worried about after I get done. Will I be
limping? But I don't think it will be a problem playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro started 129 games at designated hitter and 28 games at
first base this season. Despite the problems, he has had his best
season offensively, hitting .324 with 47 home runs and 148 runs
batted in. Manager Johnny Oates was hoping to use Palmeiro at first
base in New York, but the pain in his knee prevented that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't let that get in the way of what I was trying to do,''
Palmeiro said. ``I played with some pain, but I still played every
day. I just need to build up the leg muscles. For some reason, I
just wasn't able to do that this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
