A1561 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     10-09 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
RANGERS STILL IN SEARCH OF `BIG BREAK' (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ They're on baseball's version of Death Row,
their last meal is in the microwave but instead of gloom and doom
the Rangers seem downright giddy just to have someone else picking
up the dinner check.
</P>
<P>
   They may be taking this lemons into lemonade theory a little too
far.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers didn't act like players about to play their last
baseball game of the century as they gathered yesterday at The
Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   They laughed and chattered around the batting cage, like
baseball players always do. They swung the bat, took groundballs,
stopped for interviews when asked.
</P>
<P>
   For a team just one game away from extinction in the first round
of the American League Division Series _ and perhaps a complete
makeover as an organization _ the Rangers were remarkably at ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have anything to hide from,'' hitting coach Rudy
Jaramillo said, shivering from a fever brought on by the flu-bug
that just won't loosen its grip on the team. ``I still have a lot
of confidence in these guys. They can turn it around like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaramillo snapped his fingers for emphasis. If only it was that
easy. If only the Rangers could snap their fingers and start over,
make those two games in New York disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it has come down to this: Roger Clemens vs. Esteban
Loaiza.
</P>
<P>
   In Vegas, the oddsmakers are laughing their heads off.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, once upon a time the Rangers regularly did more than hold
their own against Clemens. But it wasn't October and he wasn't
wearing a Yankees uniform.
</P>
<P>
   The ramifications of failure this time could be wide-reaching
and painful.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, before the Rangers lost 3-1 in Game 2, owner Tom
Hicks said that another early exit from the playoffs would of
necessity bring about an off-season evaluation of the franchise's
overall baseball philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would guess that would include personnel,'' said second
baseman Mark McLemore, who is in the last year of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   I would guess so, too.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore, third baseman Todd Zeile, center fielder Tom Goodwin
and pitcher Aaron Sele are the Rangers' most prominent potential
free agents. Another collapse against the Yankees almost certainly
will make Hicks and general manager Doug Melvin more inclined to
shake up the team with off-season changes.
</P>
<P>
   Long term, it could even have an effect on how they approach
negotiations with Juan Gonzalez on a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to be happy just going to the playoffs every
year,'' Hicks stressed. ``Our goal is to win the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   That road, the Rangers have discovered to their dismay, almost
always runs through New York, where the Big Apple seems to be
permanently lodged in their throats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressing,'' said Rafael Palmeiro, going through this with the
Rangers for the first time. ``I see guys pressing a lot and
thinking too much about the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we can overcome this. We just need one big break.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything has blanketed the Rangers' clubhouse even more
thoroughly than the flu bug, it's The Big Break Theory.
</P>
<P>
   One break, one big hit, one time. Just something to get them
started.
</P>
<P>
   It smacks perilously of a team grasping for straws.
</P>
<P>
   ``One big hit to get us going,'' first baseman Lee Stevens said.
``That's what we need. I've still got a good feeling about this. I
think we can make a run.''
</P>
<P>
   Before they can make a run, they have to score more than one. In
this October or last, they have yet to prove they can do that.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge ahead is daunting. First, beat Clemens, no easy
challenge in and of itself. Then beat David Cone here tomorrow in
Game 4. Then go back to New York and win Game 5 Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   If you say it all fast enough, it's like bad-tasting medicine.
You might actually be able to choke most of it down before the
gag-reflex kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' best glimmer of hope yesterday may have actually
come from Yankees manager Joe Torre, who keeps insisting his team
will be taking nothing for granted tonight in Game 3, though why
they wouldn't is beyond me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced that in a short series, it takes very little to
turn it around for the other team,'' Torre said. ``If takes just
one game and the momentum shifts.''
</P>
<P>
   One game tonight. That's all the Rangers can think about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't win three at once,'' manager Johnny Oates cautioned.
``We have to take it one step, one day, at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   On the field, McLemore paused a moment to think about tomorrow.
Would there be another game to play?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want \Rtoday\S to be the last time I wear this
uniform,'' McLemore said. ``I don't want this to end, not like
this. Not this soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can come back. We can still win.''
</P>
<P>
   Mac always knows the right things to say. I'm just not sure,
though, that even he really believes it any more. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 0138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991009.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1562 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX     10-09 0257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODSON, MCIVER HURTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL, JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said the decisions on
whether injured strong safety Darren Woodson (sprained ankle) and
right guard Everett McIver (strained hamstring) will play against
the Philadelphia Eagles tomorrow won't be made until right around
game time.
</P>
<P>
   Woodson, who was injured in Thursday's practice, did not
practice yesterday. While Gailey remained cautious about his
status, Woodson maintained that he would be ready for the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to play,'' said Woodson, the team's leading tackler
with 26 stops, including 18 unassisted. ``It's not that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   If Woodson can't go, backup free safety Izell Reese will start
at strong safety alongside free safety George Teague. Reserve
safety Singor Mobley would play in the nickel defense.
</P>
<P>
   McIver, who missed Sunday's game against the Arizona Cardinals,
practiced yesterday and looks to be ready to play. Gailey said the
Cowboys will play it safe and evaluate McIver's situation in
pre-game warmups. Gailey said McIver will likely be in uniform, but
the decision will be whether he's ready to start.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Myslinski will start at right guard if McIver can't go.
</P>
<P>
   What is certain is that cornerback Kevin Smith, who has been
sidelined since training camp with a bulging disk, and right tackle
Erik Williams, who missed the Cardinals game with a strained
quadriceps, will start against the Eagles. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
