<HEADER>
A1585 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     10-09 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STADIUM WILL BRING IN NFL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's NFL-loathing edition of The Sporting Muse:
</P>
<P>
   If anyone out there still cares about bringing a NFL team to Los
Angeles, and I'm not sure anyone does, I know how to make it
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Just build a stadium.
</P>
<P>
   That is a daunting task under normal conditions, of course.
Carolina funded the construction of its NFL stadium through PSL
(private seat license) sales, and PSLs are part of virtually every
modern stadium blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   But if Ed Roski, Eli Broad and the Coliseum Commission were to
proceed on renovation of the Coliseum on their own, an idea they've
said they're willing to do, I believe a line of transient NFL
owners would show up at their door.
</P>
<P>
   The disadvantage would be the huge upfront financial stake Roski
and Broad would have to make. But with a good working relationship
with the commission and a stadium design that made it more than
just a football stadium, it might be a better deal than owning a
team outright.
</P>
<P>
   The clout Roski and Broad have in the business community could
probably secure commitments for luxury suites and select club seats
before a team even lands here.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than envisioning a stadium with frosted glass touches, as
included in one of Michael Ovitz's plans, envision a stadium that
would be adaptable for soccer, concerts and Olympic track and
field. (We're due to bid on one of those again, and I can't think
of a better person, other than Peter Ueberroth, to run it than
Roski.)
</P>
<P>
   As part of their investment, Roski and Broad would receive a
share of PSL revenue, naming rights, Super Bowl income and minority
ownership in the team once an NFL owner lands here.
</P>
<P>
   They would be hailed as heroes who put the interests of the city
before their own.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, they could possibly pick the owner and team they
want. Imagine how wonderful it would be to see Roski and Broad tell
Al Davis and Bill Bidwill that they need not apply, that they
prefer to be partners with the (49ers') DeBartolo family. ...
</P>
<P>
   Count me among those who believe the league's statement that it
has no plans to expand beyond 32 is written in pencil. They'll
continue to expand as long as it makes financial sense and they can
use it as a wedge in TV negotiations. ...
</P>
<P>
   NFL inflation at work: It was just ten years ago that Jerry
Jones bought the Dallas Cowboys for $180 million and business
people said he was out of mind to pay so much. ...
</P>
<P>
   One bright spot in the NFL's decision to go to Houston is that
St. Louis won't share in the $23 million-a-team booty. As part of
its agreement to move, the Rams forfeit all expansion revenue for
ten years unless a team returns to L.A. ...
</P>
<P>
   The entire state of California has sort of become the NFL's
messy cesspool. There's no team in L.A., Al Davis is trying to get
out of his lease in Oakland, San Francisco's deal for a new stadium
is on the rocks and has already cost it a Super Bowl, and the city
of San Diego has to buy unused tickets as part of its very bad deal
with the Chargers. ...
</P>
<P>
   Famous last words, by new NFL owner Robert McNair: ``I'm just a
sportsman.'' Well, he was until Wednesday. I don't know what he is
today, but the last time I saw someone get taken down this hard, I
was watching ``Oz'' on HBO. ...
</P>
<P>
   Famous last words Part II, laughingly uttered by Paul Tagliabue
on Wednesday after taking Houston's $700 million: ``The one thing
that was clear, we were not just making a decision based upon a
price.'' The man is funnier than a Friar's Roast. ...
</P>
<P>
   Realignment into two conferences of four divisions is coming in
the NFL once Houston kicks off. NFC changes would be minimal, like
Arizona moving to the West and Seattle likely moving over from the
AFC. But there will be some in-fighting among AFC teams. It would
be logical to have a AFC South featuring Houston, Tennessee,
Jacksonville and Miami, but the Dolphins would fight to stay in the
NFC East with their longtime rivals (Jets, Pats, Bills).
</P>
<P>
   A quick look at the most sensible realignment, with geography
important but many rivalries kept intact:
</P>
<P>
   NFC: East - Dallas, New York Giants, Philadelphia, Washington;
Central - Chicago, Detroit, Green Bay, Minnesota; West - Arizona,
St. Louis, San Francisco, Seattle; South - Atlanta, Carolina, New
Orleans, Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   AFC: East - Baltimore, Buffalo, New England, New York Jets;
Central - Cincinnati, Cleveland, Indianapolis, Pittsburgh; West -
Denver, Kansas City, Oakland, San Diego; South - Houston,
Jacksonville, Miami, Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Is Denver dead? Well, the Broncos are 0-4, and their next four
games are against Oakland, Green Bay, New England and Minnesota.
This would make the Broncos the Florida Marlins of football. ...
</P>
<P>
   Famous last words, baseball division, made in April from
just-exiled Dodgers president Bob Graziano: ``The year of turmoil
(in 1998) was necessary to get where we are today. I think we're
through with all of the changes.'' Obviously, someone wasn't. ...
</P>
<P>
   I would love to see Ramon Martinez pitch back to his pre-injury
form with the Dodgers against the Indians today, and give his
brother a chance to come back and win Game 4. I'd love it even more
if I could sit with Tommy Lasorda and Fred Claire while it happens.
...
</P>
<P>
   I'd love to see the Indians win the World Series, but I can't
support any team unable to play a game in less than four hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 0148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
