A1587 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FORD-AUTOTALKS-1STLD-     10-09 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-AUTOTALKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS CONTINUE ON FORD MOTOR CONTRACT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS third graf with some workers walking off the job) 
(ATTN: Mo., Kan., Minn)  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ Negotiators for the United Automobile Workers
union and Ford Motor Co. continued their talks over a new labor
contract past a midnight Friday deadline .
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the union told Ford that it would end the
current contract at 11:59 p.m. on Friday and would call a strike if
no agreement had been reached by then on a contract covering
101,000 unionized workers.
</P>
<P>
   Around midnight, about 1,100 workers who build Ford Explorers at
a St. Louis factory walked off the job along with about 2,300 in
Kansas City who build pickups and sedans, about 900 workers in St.
Paul, Minn., who build Ranger pickups and about 1,400 in Flat Rock,
Mich., who build Mercury Cougars, said Jim Vella, a Ford spokesman.
At a handful of other plants, he said, workers left their jobs but
were urged to return to work by the national union.
 &UR;  &LR; The company and the union are struggling to reconcile Ford's plans
to spin off its giant auto parts unit, Visteon Automotive Systems,
to shareholders. After all, nearly a quarter of Ford's unionized
workers toil in Visteon factories, and they fear that their jobs
and pensions will be less secure in the long run if Visteon becomes
an independent company.
</P>
<P>
   The continuation of the talks suggested that both sides were
eager to reach an agreement without a strike. Local union officials
at Ford's factories waited to hear from the union whether to
strike. Wall Street analysts said that any long shutdown would
quickly result in big losses, particularly because Ford is already
having trouble meeting demand for its high-profit pickup trucks and
sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't build them fast enough,'' said Scott F. Merlis, a
managing director and head of the automotive practice at
Wasserstein Perella Securities Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Both DaimlerChrysler AG and General Motors Corp. have already
reached agreements with the union on new, four-year labor contracts
that call for annual raises of 3 percent on top of increases that
nearly compensate for inflation. In addition, workers get a $1,350
signing bonus and sweetened pension benefits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 0206EDT &QL; 
