<HEADER>
A1589 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG     10-09 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS EARN PEACEFUL VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It was a rare victory for the Anaheim Mighty
Ducks over the Dallas Stars, but perhaps the biggest winner Friday
night was the NHL, which is trying to promote the skills of its
players, not grudge matches.
</P>
<P>
   With all the elements in place for a war on ice, it was instead
the skill of Ducks goalie Guy Hebert that was the highlight in
Anaheim's 3-0 victory over Dallas in front of 17,174 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert stopped 37 shots en route to his 23rd career shutout and
the first in franchise history over the Stars as the Ducks (1-2)
finally got into the win column. It was just Anaheim's fifth
victory in the team's past 26 games against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge win for us,'' said Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg,
``with all we've gone through this week. We took a lot of criticism
and we took it together.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg said he was relieved to have the game completed and
said, ``It was a hockey game and I think the league should be proud
of the two teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest thing to an incident came in the second period when
Dallas defenseman Richard Mativchuk cross-checked Paul Kariya into
the Stars' net. No penalty was called.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas winger Mike Keane said he wasn't surprised the game was
played the way it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played hard and physical,'' he said. ``Sometimes, the hype
is bigger than the game. It (revenge) was something we weren't
going to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hurt Paul Kariya or Teemu Selanne . . . that's not what
the NHL is all about. I think an eye-for-an-eye is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks were outshot 37-21, but Hebert was difference. Hebert
was much different than he was when he was pulled in Tuesday's 4-0
loss at Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows why we think he's one of the best goalies in the
league,'' Hartsburg said. ``He rebounded and gave us the chance to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   After going 133 minutes, 18 seconds without scoring, the Ducks
got their first goal in a most unlikely manner.
</P>
<P>
   The normally disciplined Stars gave up an outnumbered attack
when Hebert shoved a long rebound toward Ted Drury. Anaheim's
fourth-line winger carried the puck down the left wing and left a
drop pass for Kevin Haller who, with the help of a screen by
newcomer Ladislav Kohn, beat Ed Belfour on the glove side at 13:18
of of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Haller, who missed all of training camp because of knee surgery,
had only one goal last season. Hebert picked up his fourth career
assist on the play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 0306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
