<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 08:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1591 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-INDIANS-NAME-BOS &LR;      10-09 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-NAME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENOBSCOT MAY HAVE BEEN MAN BEHIND CLEVELAND NICKNAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It's the stuff of legend: how Louis Francis Sockalexis,
Penobscot Indian, mighty outfield warrior, might have inspired the
Cleveland baseball club to call its team ``the Indians'' in his
honor.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball buffs say the Maine native had an arm like a cannon,
ran so fast he was dubbed ``deerfoot of the diamond,'' and belted
the ball farther than anyone could fathom. New York Giants manager
John McGraw described Sockalexis as ``the greatest natural talent I
have even seen.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as his Boston-area descendants watched the Indians take on
the Red Sox, they recall a man who was far more complex than the
cartoon mascot of myth, who led a painful life and suffered an
early death. He drank heavily after arriving in the major leagues
in the 1890s and played parts of only three seasons before fading
from the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had never had a drink before, and then one night after a
victory some team members carried him into a bar and gave him his
first taste of alcohol,'' said Ann Padovano, a Sockalexis
descendant who lives in Stoughton, Mass. ``He was never the same
after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Other aspects of the Sockalexis legend are colored with doubt.
Indeed, despite the Indians' claim that Sockalexis was the
inspiration for the team name, some historians aren't sure. Recent
research shows the club also was called the Indians to encourage
team members to follow the example of the Boston Braves, who had
come from behind to win the World Series in 1914.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Cleveland's team had been dubbed ``The Forest
Cities,'' ``The Spiders,'' ``The Blues,'' ``The Broncos'' and,
beginning in 1903, ``The Naps'' _ in honor of their stellar second
baseman, Nap Lajoie. But after Lajoie was traded to Philadelphia in
1914, the Napless Naps needed a new name.
</P>
<P>
   When a group of local sportswriters suggested calling the team
``the Indians,'' club officials adopted the idea ``to remind the
players of the record of the Boston Braves,'' says Ellen
Staurowsky, associate professor of sport sciences at Ithaca
College, who spent months researching the topic.
</P>
<P>
   She cites a drawing that appeared on the front of the sports
section of the Cleveland Plain Dealer on Jan. 16, 1915, the day the
new name was announced. Over the caption, ``They're Indians,''
stands a tall Indian with a long bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the nature of the name has anything to do with pennant
chances,'' the cartoonist writes, ``they should cop the flag _ for
instance, look at the Boston `Braves.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, a similar notice appeared on the newspaper's
front page. It said team members would wear an Indian head on their
uniforms to remind them ``of what the Braves did last year, jumping
from last place to first.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Cleveland team was at the bottom of the
American League standings.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence in Cleveland newspapers of the time that
the team was called Indians in tribute to Sockalexis, Staurowsky
says. The name was ``just a marketing ploy,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But others say the Native American slugger surely must have been
on the minds of the team's management.
</P>
<P>
   Sockalexis died in 1913, and in his brief career he fascinated
fans from Cleveland and beyond, who thronged to ballfields wherever
he played.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps the name wasn't picked to honor him exactly, but it
was in his memory,'' says Luke Salisbury, a Chelsea, Mass. author
who has written extensively about Sockalexis.
</P>
<P>
   No one denies that, for a time, Sockalexis was one of the most
extraordinary athletes anybody had ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1871 on the Penobscot reservation on Indian Island,
Maine, he was well-known in local baseball leagues even as a boy.
At Holy Cross in Worcester, Mass., where he attended college in
1895 and '96, he batted .436 and .444 during his two seasons, stole
6 bases in one game, and stunned audiences with his arm. Two
Harvard professors, who measured Sockalexis's throwing ability,
said he could toss a ball more than 400 feet, accurately.
</P>
<P>
   In 1897, he transferred to Notre Dame but left after just 30
days to join the Cleveland ballclub, then called ``The Spiders''
because many of the players were unusually skinny. But at 6 feet
tall, 190 pounds, Sockalexis had a powerful physique.
</P>
<P>
   He was not the first Native American to play major league ball;
that distinction belonged to James Madison Toy, who played for the
Cleveland Forest Cities in 1886. But Toy never received much
national attention. Sockalexis created a sensation.
</P>
<P>
   On his first time at bat in New York's Polo Grounds, Sockalexis
socked a home run off Amos Rusie, the ``Hoosier Thunderbolt.'' On
another occasion, he made a game-winning play when, standing deep
in right field, he threw out a runner at home plate. Fans were
fascinated by him.
</P>
<P>
   But after just three months with the Spiders, the supernova that
was Sockalexis all but vanished. Accounts differ about the cause of
his downfall.
</P>
<P>
   Padovano, whose mother was Sockalexis's great-great niece, says
it happened after teammates introduced him to alcohol by serving
him whiskey to celebrate a big win.
</P>
<P>
   But Salisbury argues that Sockalexis had been drinking long
before then. He was suspended from Notre Dame for a barroom
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Sockalexis broke an ankle while jumping from the second-floor
window of a Pittsburgh brothel in July 1897, Salisbury says. The
combination of his drinking and his injury did him in. The ankle
improved, but Sockalexis never bounced back.
</P>
<P>
   He played in 66 of about 150 games in 1897. In 1898, he appeared
in just 20 games, and in only 11 in 1899. Team manager Pat Tebeau
offered him $10,000 to stop drinking, but he could not do it.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Sockalexis's abilities fade was ``like seeing smoke
waft away from a Maine campfire,'' Tebeau reportedly said.
</P>
<P>
   Sockalexis drifted off, living on the streets and in the woods.
He tried unsuccessfully to play for minor league teams, and worked
briefly for a ferry company and as a lumberjack. But the glory was
gone.
</P>
<P>
   Sockalexis died on Christmas Eve in 1913, at a logging camp in
Maine. He was just 42. News accounts reported that, crumpled in a
pocket of his shirt, colleagues found clippings of his heroics in
the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Today a flat stone with two crossed baseball bats marks
Sockalexis's grave in a small cemetery on Indian Island.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his fall, his descendants are still proud of him and
pleased that, for whatever reason, the Cleveland Indians may have
named the team to honor him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel excited about that part of my heritage,''
said Angelo Quieto, 53, another Sockalexis relative, who lives in
Naples, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``But just think of what might have been.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
