<HEADER>
A1594 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-09 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SLOUCHING TOWARD NASHVILLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Al Gore began stressing his Tennessee roots,
running for president in the South in 1987, a top official for a
rival campaign was dismissive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore just hasn't captured their imagination,'' said Donna
Brazile, then the national field director for Richard Gephardt.
``You don't hear Southern party chairmen going around saying,
`Gore, Gore, Gore!'''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Gore is back stressing his Tennessee roots, with a new
campaign headquarters in Nashville and a new campaign manager:
Donna Brazile.
</P>
<P>
   The cautious Gore's choice of the incautious Brazile is strange,
and like so many of the vice president's moves, it has caused a lot
of people to shake their heads and say, ``Why is he doing that?''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1988, after Michael Dukakis had run a campaign that
broke creative new ground in flatlining, his deputy field director,
Ms. Brazile, got desperate. She goaded reporters to check out
unsubstantiated rumors about George Bush's personal life, noting
that ``the American people have every right to know if Barbara Bush
will share that bed with him in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   She was forced to resign, and had to apologize for her loose
talk. Perhaps it seems quaint now, but at the time, her remarks
were seen as taking politics to a new tabloid low.
</P>
<P>
   So it's an odd twist that she will be directing the campaign
against George W. Bush, who vividly defended his father against the
same gossip Ms. Brazile was peddling with the line: ``The answer to
the big A question is N-O.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Ms. Brazile is not widely viewed as a dazzling
strategist, her appointment has struck some as pandering to women,
a constituency Gore is losing to Bush, and to African-Americans, a
constituency he fears he's losing to Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   With an accentuated twang, Gore rhapsodizes about starting
fresh, far from the Gucci Gulch of lobbyists on K Street: ``Home is
not only a place, it's an idea ... Home is where we learn our
values.''
</P>
<P>
   But he isn't trading ``K Street for the aisles of K Mart,'' as
he so clunkily puts it. He's simply packing up all those same old
Washington Democratic insiders and the mercenary values of K Street
and moving them South. Instead of ``Nashville,'' this movie should
be entitled ``Hackville.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is smart. He's been in politics his whole life. He's
skilled at policy-making.
</P>
<P>
   And yet he can't seem to get it right. He's behaving in a
weirdly incompetent manner. At this early stage in the game, his
campaign is already a matter of damage control. Even his friends
find the tinniness of his electoral ear mysterious.
</P>
<P>
   He has just reshuffled the high command of his campaign, and
people have grown so dismayed with his decision-making that they
are now saying the candidate himself is the problem.
</P>
<P>
   He does not seem to inspire extreme loyalty in his troops, some
of whom are already protecting their own legacies by leaking memos
purporting to show that the candidate neglected the repeated
counsel of his pollster and other advisers to engage Bradley months
ago, before he gained so much ground.
</P>
<P>
   Gore cherishes his reputation for decency. But as he scrambles
away from Bill Clinton's baggage, he adds new advisers with
baggage, and his old advisers pile on more baggage. This campaign
needs nothing so much as a porter.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Coelho, the campaign chairman, helped usher in the modern
era of fund-raising as ideology. He had to resign his seat as a
House Democratic leader in 1989, under the cloud of scandal
involving a $100,000 junk bond investment. Now he's embroiled in a
new mini-scandal.
</P>
<P>
   State Department auditors criticized his management skills at a
World Exposition in Portugal last year. In a job where he had
ambassadorial status, Coelho had trouble raising money for the U.S.
pavilion, though he spent lavishly on an $18,000-a-month furnished
apartment and hired his niece at a fat salary.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's clumsiness has been so startling that even those close to
him are beginning to psychoanalyze his ambition. Does he really
want it, they wonder, or is he in the race just because daddy
always wanted it?
</P>
<P>
   It's a bad sign when a man who is already in the White House
runs for president and people ask: Why is he doing that?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 0919EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
