<DOCNO> NYT19991009.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     10-09 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: YANKS SET A TONE AMONG THEMSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Yankee welcome wagon is not always as
overt as Chuck Knoblauch's and Derek Jeter's donning full catcher's
regalia to greet Roger Clemens in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   That was their jovial way of telling the Rocket, ``Hey, bud, no
hard feelings'' for the way he had sent them sprawling a time or
two when he was a member of the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the salutation is more subtle. The Yankees go about
their business, and the new players pick up on it. The result is an
almost seamless sense of entitlement evident on this ball club in
the first two victories in Yankee Stadium. Saturday night Clemens,
the new boy in the rotation, tries to sweep the Rangers in the
division series.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to maintain dynasties in these days of free agencies,
but the Yankees currently have a dynasty of attitude, a dynasty of
technique.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is a salty old dog who has been battling the Yankees
since he came to the majors. They have been even more impressive
since he walked in the door and was twitted by Jeter and Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I have been around so many guys that just beat
themselves up and are hard on themselves as far as their game is
concerned,'' Clemens said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see guys giving away too many at-bats,'' he added.
``When they do, you don't have to look any further than the dugout
or water cooler and listen. Something is being torn up. They're
getting it out so they can maybe concentrate on their next
at-bat.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is just the owner. No, just kidding. George
Steinbrenner has not been the constant goading presence he once
was, but newcomers notice that he does set a certain tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are never satisfied,'' said Jason Grimsley, the
pitcher who had a good season but is not on the roster for this
series. ``It starts at the top with an owner who wants to win and a
manager who wants to win. I mean, every owner wants to win, but
ours shows everybody he wants it.''
</P>
<P>
   The tone also comes from Joe Torre, who does not deliver
lectures to new Yankees, or hand them organizational notebooks on
any Yankee Way of Playing Winning Baseball. Torre just keeps track
of everybody with a nod or a glare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe works out every day,'' said Allen Watson, who played for
Torre in St. Louis and was thrilled to be reunited this summer.
``He had cancer this spring, and he runs and lifts weights and
everybody sees him. He doesn't yell or deprecate his players. He's
the same as he was in St. Louis, but he just didn't have the
firepower there.''
</P>
<P>
   The incentive to win is not quite as primal as the Yankee
mentality back in the late '50s when a Hank Bauer or a Moose
Skowron would sidle up to a rookie on opening day and growl,
``Don't mess with my World Series check, kid.'' The Series checks
are proportionately smaller these days. It's more about getting it
right, really right.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no rah-rah,'' Watson said. ``They expect to win. It's
a real quiet team. They have great fundamentals. The bunting. Not
making mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley, who has also been around, said: ``You notice it the
second you walk into the clubhouse in spring training. These guys
are not thinking about playing .500 or winning the division or
winning the American League. All they're thinking about is winning
the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley expected to go to Columbus out of spring training, but
found that the Yankees, with their two World Series rings, treated
him as an equal.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as you do the job, you've got the same look they do,''
Grimsley said. ``Everybody's professional. You watch Coney go to
the mound. You watch Jeter go to the plate. Their attitude is, `OK,
guys, this is it.'''
</P>
<P>
   With all the stars in the clubhouse, Grimsley said, it is normal
to see David Cone enjoy being teased by a rookie like D'Angelo
Jimenez, as he was in the last weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't see that on other teams,'' Grimsley said.
</P>
<P>
   As a new Yankee, Grimsley was asked who impressed him most. He
started to name names: ``Watching Jeter and Bernie, the way Mariano
goes about his business. The consistency. Roger works harder than
anybody I've ever seen. Pettitte's right with him. Girardi. Nobody
studies the game more than he does. Nobody here is a follower.
There are 25 leaders here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyritz has watched this attitude develop. As a yappy
part-time starter, he made gigantic contributions to big victories
in 1995 and 1996, and then was sent away _ ``but everybody felt I
was still part of the ball club,'' he said. He came back this
season, and discovered the Yankees had matured to another level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the major leagues has ability,'' Leyritz said.
``It's the mentality that makes a difference. When I was here the
first time, if you lost a game, guys worried maybe you'd lose three
or four. Now they get upset if they lose one game.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz watched the team play badly on the last weekend of the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just laughed,'' Leyritz said. ``I'm not saying you can just
flick a switch, but these guys knew how to get ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there is one thing different about the Yankees that he
did not understand from a distance, Leyritz said, ``I think of what
Derek Jeter was when I left,'' meaning a poised and talented rookie
in 1996. ``Now Derek has superstar status but he never changed. It
hasn't gotten to him. He works as hard as anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz stops short of calling Jeter a leader of the team. On
the Yankees, that is a communal job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
