 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(th) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Oct. 10:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-JEWISH-PRIEST (Lublin, Poland) _ Past the ditches where
thousands were executed by the Nazis, the crematory described as
having ``a daily yield of about 1,000 bodies,'' and the gas chamber
being visited by a group of Israeli schoolchildren, the priest
walks in silence. His name is Romuald-Jakub Weksler-Waszkinel. He
is a priest and a teacher at Lublin's Catholic University. He is
also _ as he discovered late in life _ a Jew. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   TEST-BAN-TREATY (Washington) _ In debating the historic treaty
that would ban all underground nuclear testing, the Senate is
reliving one of the most divisive arguments of the Cold War: Do
international arms control treaties enhance or imperil America's
nuclear deterrent? By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   TEST-BAN-ASSESS _ A mystery unfolded last year when India, on
May 13, announced that it had set off a pair of nuclear blasts. The
global network of seismometers recorded no faint rumbles emanating
from India's underground test site in its northwestern desert. Had
India faked the explosive tests? Were they flops? Or had small
blasts eluded the eavesdroppers? These questions have a strong
bearing on the bruising battle in Washington over whether the
Senate should ratify the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty. By William
J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-MASKHADOV (Grozny, Russia) _ The Chechen leader, Aslan
Maskhadov, a former colonel in the Soviet Army, is a restrained,
gray-haired man. A profile. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-NEWSPAPER (Tehran, Iran) _ Undaunted by the closure of its
three preceding newspapers, all of which rocketed to the highest
circulation in Iran, a group pressing for a more democratic and
tolerant form of Islamic rule has opened a fourth daily. By John F.
Burns.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-GOLD (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ For days, the miners
listened to the crackle of good news from their battered radios and
prayed that the soaring price of gold would save them. But the
banner headlines that have thrilled government officials,
economists and mining executives were not enough to stop the
layoffs. By Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ Vicente Fox Quesada, a
brash-talking National Action Party presidential candidate with a
bold swagger, thinks he can build the frustration among Mexican
voters into a runaway victory for the opposition next year. But
Fox's campaign for the top job faces a debilitating problem: He
does not have the unqualified support of his own party. By Julia
Preston.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN-HEALTH (Moscow) _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin
was taken to the Central Clinical Hospital on Saturday morning
suffering from what his press secretary described as the flu
accompanied by a high fever. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   EAST-TIMOR-U.S. (Dili, East Timor) _ The Americans are in East
Timor. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ Indonesia, which invaded East
Timor in 1975 and yielded the shattered territory to foreign troops
three weeks ago, is organizing a commission to investigate reports
of atrocities committed by militia groups and the Indonesian army.
The question hanging in the air is: How can a country that annexed
and brutally subjugated its neighbor for nearly a quarter-century
investigate its own behavior and bring those responsible to
justice? By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS-CREATIONISM _ Scientific lessons about the origins of
life have long been challenged in public schools, but some Bible
literalists are now adding the reigning theory about the origin of
the universe to their list of targets. Nearly overlooked in the
furor over the Kansas Board of Education's decision in August to
remove evolution from its education standards was a decision to
delete from its standards a description of the Big Bang theory of
cosmic origins. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   WIS-WELFARE _ Wisconsin, of all places, suddenly has the jitters
about cutting families off welfare. Since 1996, the state's
famously tough work rules have swept more than 57,000 families from
the rolls and turned a war on welfare into a social experiment
commanding international attention. But Wisconsin is now grappling
with the ultimate symbol of the new welfare age: time limits. By
Jason DeParle.
</P>
<P>
   IRS-TAX-DELINQUENTS _ Understaffed and caught in a set of mixed
signals from Congress, the Internal Revenue Service for more than a
year has been letting many big tax delinquents go without paying
huge tax bills. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   ELVIS-AUCTION (Las Vegas) _ The mystery train that carried
Andrea Bauer to the MGM Grand Hotel this weekend started in her
family's living room when she was just a girl, back in the 1950s.
Sometimes when her father, a devoted Perry Como fan, left the
house, her mother would quickly switch to a record by that new
singer, the twitchy kid from Tupelo. ``Elvis Presley would sing and
my mother and I would dance and dance and dance,'' Ms. Bauer said.
So, four decades later, she came to Las Vegas to get herself a
little piece of Graceland. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   S.C.-GAMBLING-VOTE (Rock Hill, S.C.) _ It has been more than 50
years since any state banned an existing form of gambling, but a
drive around the border roads of York County helps explain why
South Carolina is poised to do just that. Video poker is
everywhere. On Nov. 2, voters will have a choice to either ban the
machines beginning next summer or regulate them more closely. By
David Forestone.
</P>
<P>
   WIS-BURGLARY (Rhinelander, Wis.) _ In the deepest, most tranquil
lands of Wisconsin, where people could retreat for a few days and
forget about urban woes, burglars have been clearing out vacation
homes with the efficiency of a moving company. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   FIDDLER-APPRENTICE (Nicut, W.Va.) _ The mountain-hollow art of
old-time Appalachian fiddling, long withering under the pressures
of youthful emigration and homogenized broadcast entertainment, is
hanging on by a few well-bowed strings here in a backwoods
master-apprentice program. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   CREW-SINGLE-MOTHERS (South Hadley, Mass.) _ Their oars splashed
and slipped a little more often than the other rowers' did. Their
shoulders didn't lean as far back on each stroke. But the crew
members from the Holyoke Care Center, competing in their first
regatta, had the biggest cheering section of any team on the
Connecticut River. As Anne Teschner, their mentor, said, the care
center's crew was the only team of ``single mothers out there.''
</P>
<P>
   PATAKI-HUNGARIANS _ When a group called the Hungarian-American
Chamber of Commerce of New York and New Jersey paid for two trips
by Gov. George Pataki to Hungary a few years ago, it was based in
suburban New Jersey and listed its official address as its
president's home. These days, the group has more distinctive
quarters: a small office on the 63rd floor of One World Trade
Center. By Clifford J. Levy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-BUSH-DELAY (Washington) _ There are a couple of leading
theories about the relationship between the two Texas Republicans
who may soon be running the country: A) That the party's
presidential front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush, and House Majority
Whip Tom DeLay are closer than we know. B) That these two guys from
opposite sides of the tracks have little to nothing in common. By
Melinda Henneberger and Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS _ Short items on politics from around the
nation. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN _ On the Gore campaign. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN _ On arms control. By Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
