<DOCNO> NYT19991009.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      10-09 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   IT'S TIME FOR THE STEELERS TO ACT ON STEWART'S FUNK
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Giants did with Dave Brown, and the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers did with Trent Dilfer, and the Oakland Raiders did with
Jeff George, it is time for the Pittsburgh Steelers to stop fooling
themselves, and take a long, hard look at their quarterback,
Kordell Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   It is time because after three years as a starter, Stewart has
not shown the instincts, or the accuracy, to be at least an average
quarterback in the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Because he is perhaps one of the nicest people in the game, it
is hard not to root for Stewart. And despite his troubles, the
Steelers have stuck by their man, mainly because this past off
season they invested $27 million in him. But he has been a disaster
at the position.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the team was stunned after Stewart threw three
interceptions in a 17-3 loss at home to the Jacksonville Jaguars.
As usual, Stewart displayed poor mechanics, and at times he was
fooled by schemes the Seahawks used to confuse him.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart has thrown only one touchdown pass in his last eight
games. His quarterback rating is 57.6. Pittsburgh's offense is
ranked 18th over all and 24th in passing. The team is in a funk
that it has not seen in years. Still, Coach Bill Cowher said the
problems were not all about Stewart, and became angry at any such
suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I thought it was just one person, I'd make a change,''
Cowher said. ``It has nothing to do with what a guy makes, it has
nothing to do with who a guy is. The fact I haven't made a change
ought to indicate it's not just one person.''
</P>
<P>
   There is definitely some truth to that. The starting running
back, Jerome Bettis, has been hobbled with injuries, and the
Steelers have lost a number of key offensive players to free
agency. But Stewart still does not grasp the position.
</P>
<P>
   When Pittsburgh plays host to the Buffalo Bills Sunday, Stewart
should look across the field and watch Doug Flutie, who is 10-4 as
a Bills starter over the last two seasons. The two are basically
the same, in that both are good athletes. But they differ in that
Flutie has been able to absorb the intricacies of the NFL football
since arriving from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh's quarterback guru, Kevin Gilbride, the team's
offensive coordinator, is working on Stewart's mechanics and mental
well-being. Against Seattle, Stewart was benched for the third time
in his last seven starts. Stewart is young, at 26, and has plenty
of time to turn his career around. He can take solace in that the
Jets' Vinny Testaverde was once considered a mistake-prone player
but took his team to the conference title last season.
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart had better change things quickly because it is only
a matter of time before Cowher, despite his affinity for Stewart,
turns to Mike Tomczak, the backup quarterback. Maybe for the rest
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   DEVALUING WARRICK
</P>
<P>
   When Peter Warrick, the Florida State star, was charged last
week with grand theft in a clothing scheme at a Tallahassee, Fla.,
department store, his mistake may have cost him more than the
Heisman Trophy. It may have cost him millions of dollars when he
turns professional.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL general managers and scouts salivate when they think of
Warrick, an explosive offensive player who comes along once every
five years or so. He has the capability of changing a game the way
Randy Moss does.
</P>
<P>
   Personnel men from six teams said before the arrest that Warrick
would be drafted from as high as first over all to a low of fifth.
But after the arrest, they said, Warrick could go as low as 10th.
There is a major monetary difference in a player being drafted in
the top 5 or being picked 10th.
</P>
<P>
   How big a difference? Last year, Ricky Williams, the 1998
Heisman Trophy winner from Texas, was chosen fifth in the first
round by the New Orleans Saints and earned $8.8 million in signing
bonus money. At the 10th spot, the Baltimore Ravens selected Chris
McAlister, the Arizona defensive back. His signing bonus was $3.75
million.
</P>
<P>
   If the initial feelings of a small group of team executives are
true, and Warrick's shopping spree causes him to drop from fifth to
10th, that will be a difference of at least $5.05 million. And that
drop in value does not include the possible loss of off-the-field
endorsements once Warrick turns professional.
</P>
<P>
   Those same general managers said it was not Warrick's alleged
crime itself that bothered them. After all, teams have drafted in
the first round woman-beaters, car thieves and drug abusers. But
what NFL teams hate is a player who knows so much is at risk _ in
Warrick's case, the Heisman, a national championship and his future
_ and tosses those things away over something so petty.
</P>
<P>
   What also bothers general managers is Warrick's lack of at least
public remorse. They want to hear him say, ``I'm sorry, I made a
mistake, and it won't happen again.'' Instead, Warrick was quoted
as saying, ``It's not like I killed the president.''
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   THE YEAR OF RECEIVERS
</P>
<P>
   So far this season, there has been a quiet offensive explosion
the NFL has not seen in years.
</P>
<P>
   While the quarterback play may be down, there is a great crop of
young wide receivers such as Terry Glenn of the New England
Patriots, Marvin Harrison of the Indianapolis Colts, Keyshawn
Johnson of the Jets, Kevin Dyson of the Tennessee Titans, Michael
Westbrook of the Washington Redskins, and, of course, Randy Moss of
the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first four weeks of the season, there have been 43
games in which a receiver caught passes for 100 yards or more,
tying 1989 for the highest total for a season's first four weeks
since the 1970 merger between the American Football league and the
National Football League. And there have been 17 games in which
quarterbacks threw for 300 yards or more in the first weeks, the
most since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   While the quarterback play has been average at best, a number of
receivers are having career years. One is Harrison, who is tall,
bulky, and quick, and who like Moss last season has constantly beat
double-team coverage. In three games (the Colts have had a bye),
Harrison has 28 receptions for 422 yards and 6 touchdowns. Those 6
touchdown catches in 3 games are the best since Seattle's Daryl
Turner had 6 in his first 3 games in 1985. And Harrison's 422
receiving yards are the most since Jerry Rice opened with 449 in 3
games in the 1989 season.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   One of the best defensive minds in the league is someone few
have heard: Ted Cottrell of the Buffalo Bills. The Bills' defense
allows just 261 yards a game, third best in the American Football
Conference. Soon Cottrell's name will be talked about as a
head-coaching candidate. ... Charley Casserly, the former
Washington Redskins' general manager, who is still a consultant for
the team, is attempting to become the general manager for the
expansion franchise awarded to Houston last week. ... Jake Plummer,
the Arizona Cardinals' quarterback, has told teammates that the
loss to free agency of Lomas Brown, the veteran tackle, has hurt
the offense more than people realize. Plummer rarely worried about
protection on Brown's side when he was there. That may account for
why Plummer immediately starts scrambling when he gets to his
second read, and it is not open.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
