<HEADLINE>
NBA NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNICKS SEEK TO RETAIN UNITY DESPITE SPREWELL ABSENCE
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston went to Charleston, S.C., last week to ready
himself for the coming season. But he also allowed himself some
time to remember the surreal events of last season, how the
fractured Knicks came together when it mattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, it taught us a lesson,'' Houston said as he
finished a training camp practice at the College of Charleston.
``It just goes to show you, after all the other things that
happened, in this league you should just care about winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``What separates you is winning. Honestly, there have been a lot
of players in this league who weren't necessarily great players.
But because they won, they were considered great. I hope we take
that from last season.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston and some of his healthy and committed teammates
excluded, the Knicks are not off to a rousing start. As they exited
their one-week training camp Saturday, they had important injuries,
were in desperate need of a legitimate center and were dealing with
the irresponsibility of Latrell Sprewell, who was AWOL for the
week.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, while he was with the Utah Jazz, Scott Layden
vetoed a trade for Rony Seikaly because the enigmatic center would
not show up in Salt Lake City for his physical. Layden's attitude
and that of the franchise was: if you don't want us, we don't want
you.
</P>
<P>
   Now Layden, who was hired as the Knicks' general manager in
August, has to negotiate a contract extension for a player who
failed to call his bosses to tell them where he was for the past
week. Noted for his firm, no-nonsense approach, Layden must be
seething.
</P>
<P>
   The new general manager also has to negotiate through the
executive suite politics of Madison Square Garden, which are far
from stable. Months after Ernie Grunfeld and Jeff Van Gundy could
not get along, ending in Grunfeld's being sacrificed, a residue of
bitterness remains.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, Ed Tapscott, the Knicks' assistant general
manager, placed a call to the SuperSonics. He casually inquired
about the All-Star point guard Gary Payton, who at one juncture
last season had expressed unhappiness about being in Seattle. Van
Gundy also made a call on the Knicks' behalf, to the Sonics
assistant Dwayne Casey _ a call that greatly concerned Tapscott.
</P>
<P>
   Tapscott was less worried about Van Gundy's going over his head
than about the Knicks' tipping their hand by showing too much
interest to make any kind of deal for Payton. The Sonics were not
genuinely interested in moving Payton, so all discussions ceased.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Tapscott approached Dave Checketts, the Garden's
president, and essentially told him that people have to be on the
same page in the Knicks organization, so that the front office will
not splinter as it did a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts felt it already had, especially in view of Tapscott's
close ties to the departed Grunfeld. It was one of the main reasons
he did not elevate Tapscott to the general manager's job, though
Tapscott had been acting as the g.m. for much of the summer.
Tapscott is still under contract with the Knicks, but it won't be
long until they buy him out or he finds a more permanent situation
to employ his talents.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Layden, who must be wondering why he left Utah for this
mess. Losing Salt Lake City's quality of life _ not to mention the
pleasure of dealing with All-Stars who are also professional and
committed to the cause _ can't be worth $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond all the board-room intrigue that comes with working for a
multinational conglomerate instead of one, maverick owner, this is
what Layden surveyed last week during Knicks training camp:
</P>
<P>
   _ Patrick Ewing on a running machine, his 37-year-old body
trying to overcome tendinitis in his left Achilles, no real
timetable for his return.
</P>
<P>
   _ The utter lack of a bona fide center; Chris Dudley is still
rehabilitating a knee injury and 7-foot-2 Frederic Weis, the
Knicks' first-round draft pick, is a slow-moving, European project
who may not play in the N.B.A. for another two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ And finally, a barrage of questions about Sprewell's
whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Injury. Calamity. And the unpredictability of Sprewell. The
Knicks keep going like this and they'll be back in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   SHAQ BIGGER ... BUT IS HE BETTER?
</P>
<P>
   It sounds unfathomable, but there is actually more of Shaquille
O'Neal to go around. The Diesel _ the Daddy or Shaq Fu, if you
prefer _ came into training camp weighing 340 pounds, up 10 pounds
from his playing weight of last season.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal does not look flabby, and in fact the Superman tattoo on
his biceps actually stretched from all the weight-lifting. But
coming into camp that heavy was not a good way to endear himself to
Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal paid a visit to Jackson at his home in Montana after
Jackson accepted the Lakers coaching job; O'Neal was giving a rap
concert in Montana at the time. After initial pleasantries, Jackson
essentially told O'Neal he wanted him to come to camp lighter, that
he felt O'Neal was not getting up and down the court as quickly as
he once did.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson gave O'Neal an ideal weight for reporting to training
camp, a number Jackson would not disclose but believed to be near
300 pounds. O'Neal was listed as 303 pounds his rookie year in
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if O'Neal met his goal, Jackson said, ``No, he didn't. But
I'm not unhappy about it. I think he's in condition, that's the
major goal. The guy is in condition, so he can get up and down the
court.''
</P>
<P>
   Said O'Neal: ``The more I lift weights, the higher the number is
going to be. I'm not really concerned about numbers. I'll bust any
big man's butt, no matter what I weigh. And you can underline it,
put two periods behind it and tell them I said it.'' He added that
he wants to increase his strength to ward off brutes in the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to disagree with Shaq about those types of
things, because he gets fouled harder than anyone in the game,''
Jackson said. ``People take him down. But all the other parameters
going into it - getting up and down the court, the idea that he's
had a knee that was injured, he's had the stomach injury, all those
things - are better served if there is less weight.''
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   NOT THE SPREE P.J. KNEW
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell's failure to report to training camp last week
stunned P.J. Carlesimo, of all people. The Golden State coach, who
was choked by Sprewell nearly two years ago during a practice,
said, ``I don't ever remember him being late.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely never missed a practice,'' Carlesimo added. ``I
remember the first training camp, he hadn't been around all summer
and the first time I saw him was five minutes before the first
meeting, but that was fine. I don't ever remember him missing
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he finally got in touch with the Knicks, Sprewell was
said to be driving cross country _ from Oakland, Calif., to his
hometown of Milwaukee, and finally to New York. The Knicks should
not have counted on him for training camp, given some of Sprewell's
misadventures on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Once, while with the Warriors, Sprewell got lost driving to San
Jose - only one of California's largest and well-marked cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I was way off when I saw a mileage sign for Los
Angeles,'' he said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
