<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DON'T BLAME (OR CREDIT) THE BALL, SAYS MAJOR LEAGUE BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   Conspiracy theorists won't buy it, but Major League Baseball has
conducted tests that show the baseball was not the reason baseballs
flew out of and all over ball parks in record numbers again this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Major league players, led once again by Mark McGwire and Sammy
Sosa, hit a record 5,528 home runs, and teams, led by Cleveland's
awesome Indians, scored a record 24,691 runs. The National League
set so many hitting records its computer may have to run overtime
to compile them all before next season.
</P>
<P>
   As a direct result of, as well as being a major contributor to,
the NL's enhanced offense, the Colorado Rockies became only the
third NL team in this century to have an earned run average
starting with a 6.
</P>
<P>
   But don't blame it on the ball, said Sandy Alderson, executive
vice president for baseball operations in the commissioner's
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the documentation I have and studies that have been
done as recently as the last few months, there doesn't appear to be
any difference in the ball with the ball of 10-15 years ago,''
Alderson said. ``I know people like to point to the baseball as one
of the reasons for these changes, but as far as we can tell,
there's been no change in the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The testing, Alderson related, was done in conjunction with the
decision to use professionals in the Pan Am games and the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make sure the Mizuno ball had similar
characteristics to the Rawlings ball,'' he explained. ``We did
another set of tests on Rawlings balls and those were the
conclusions. Other than the test data being faulty or the tests
themselves not being appropriate, there's no apparent change.''
</P>
<P>
   Some suspicious souls have suggested that the balls have been
wound tighter, but Alderson rejected that contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's wound tighter, it would be smaller or heavier and
those things aren't happening,'' he said. ``The size of the ball,
the weight of the ball, the basic construction materials of the
ball _ taking all those things into account and doing tests for
coefficient restitution, the liveliness of the ball is essentially
the same. There's no statistical difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Numbers associated with the ball are different, though. In
virtually the same number of games as the 1998 seasons, the two
leagues hit a total of 5,528 home runs, a 9.2 percent increase over
the previous record of 5,064 that were hit last year. Runs rose 6
percent, from a record 23,297 last year (9.58 a game) to 24,691
this season (10.17).
</P>
<P>
   The American League, for some reason, fell short of its record
totals in various hitting categories, but the NL went wild. Its
teams and players broke league records not only for most home runs
and runs but also for hits, total bases, extra-base hits, singles
and doubles. (Why not triples? Probably because Lance Johnson was
hurt much of the season.)
</P>
<P>
   The league also had its highest ERA, 4.56, while its pitchers
threw its fewest shutouts (93, down from a record 98 in 1987) for a
162-game schedule. Its pitchers would have tied the record for
fewest complete games (127 in 1996) had Al Leiter not pitched nine
innings for the Mets last Monday in their wild-card playoff victory
over Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing to understand,'' Alderson said, ``is
nobody is directing the game in the direction of offense. But at
the same time, we do have to keep our eye on it and make sure
regardless of what factors have led to more offense that the fans
and the players and the clubs are comfortable with where the game
is and the direction it's taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Alderson said the subject is one that officials will discuss in
the next few weeks, though not because individuals or groups have
complained about the increase in offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably needs to be looked at objectively,'' Alderson
said. ``Once we get the post-season behind us, there's an
opportunity to do that. I don't want to suggest there's anyone in
baseball who has raised it as a serious concern. Obviously it's a
fact and the important thing to understand is where we are and make
objective decisions as to what that means for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing perception in baseball is that fans like high
scoring and tons of home runs. The only group that would dispute
that stance is pitchers, but the players union would be hard
pressed to take up their cause because a majority of union members
are hitters.
</P>
<P>
   If officials should decide some greater balance, for pitchers'
sake, is needed _ and that's highly unlikely to happen this
off-season _ the most likely change would be in the strike zone, as
in going back to the rule book strike zone, basically from the
hollow of the knee to basically the uniform shirt letters.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem with that idea is that Alderson tried this
season to get umpires to raise their strike zone to a top level of
two inches above the waist, and they didn't really comply. The
drastically shrunken strike zone is considered one of the major
culprits in the proliferation of home runs and runs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   HOMER-HAPPY
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, with an increase in the number of home runs
that were hit came an increase in the number of players who reached
the higher echelons of home-run hitting. The National League went
from 26 to 34 in the number of players who hit 25 or more, the
American from 27 to 30. The AL had the biggest increase in any one
level, with 14 players slugging 30 to 40 compared with 6 last year.
</P>
<P>
   However, four of those 14 players finished in that group because
they tumbled from the next one up, having hit 40 or more last year.
Albert Belle plunged from 49 to 37, Jose Canseco 46 to 34, Mo
Vaughn 40 to 33 and Juan Gonzalez 45 to 39. Maintaining their
status on the 40 plus plateau were Rafael Palmiero, Manny Ramirez,
Alex Rodriguez and the ALleader, Ken Griffey Jr., though he fell
from 56 to 48.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa retained their
membership in the over 60 club, and no one joined them. But just as
remarkably, Jay Bell of Arizona hit a home run on the last day of
the regular season, enabling him to finish one ahead of Albert
Belle, 38 to 37.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   THE DIAMONDBACKS' POOR RELATIVES
</P>
<P>
   In their first season, the Arizona Diamondbacks and the Tampa
Bay Devil Rays finished in last place in their respective
divisions. Arizona won two more games than Tampa Bay. One year
later, the Devil Rays again finished last, gaining four more
victories than last year, but the Diamondbacks finished first with
35 more victories than they had in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a question, Larry Rothschild, the Tampa Bay
manager, said, ``No, I don't have time to be envious. I'm
concentrating on what we're doing here. Would I like to be in the
playoff hunt? Yes. But that makes me envious of every team that's
in that situation, so it's not just Arizona. That's where we want
to get to. That's what the game is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams, Rothschild said, have taken different routes. ``I
think it would bother me if I were a team that had been in
existence a long time and they were able to do that,'' he said.
``We started at the same time, but obviously the plans were
completely different.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothschild, who served as pitching coach of the expansion
Florida Marlins when they won the 1997 World Series, applauded the
Diamondbacks for what they've achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks because you spent the money you're going to
win,'' he said. ``That's not the case and it's been proven over and
over. It gives you a chance, but you still have to assimilate those
players together. You have to make sure you got the right players.
That's not an easy thing to do. I give them credit.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Diamondbacks' poor relatives, the Marlins' manager
said he could never gain a true sense of how good they could be
because they suffered a string of devastating injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it tough to evaluate where we really are because we
didn't see this team together virtually the whole year,'' he said.
``By the same token we've seen a lot of guys play here so we can
evaluate where we are a lot easier. I think that's going to be
important for us. It's time for us to start weeding out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothschild estimated that if the players he had expected to be
the regulars had all remained healthy, the Devil Rays could have
won between 75 and 81 games. ``All year we'd get something going,''
he said, ``then we'd lose two or three guys. There'd be a setback
and then we'd have to regroup and come back.''
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   BOBBY VALENTINE'S TUTOR
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine recently recalled an educational experience he
enjoyed in his early days of managing with the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in Texas, we had Paul Richards there,'' the Mets
manager related, referring to a legendary baseball figure. ``He was
a back room advisor. About every couple or three weeks, I'd invite
him to lunch. I'd go to his office and say what do you think, we
had first and second, the eighth and ninth hitters coming up and I
went to the bunt. What do you think. We pitched out on 1-1, the
count went to 2-1, the pitcher got behind in the count and wound up
walking him. What do you think. They were just wonderful walls to
bounce off. It wasn't so much second-guessing as education because
I had never managed before. It was a refreshing thing to do with
someone who knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence or not, Richards is second on the list (1,837 games)
and Valentine third (1,704) of managers who have managed the most
games without finishing first. True, Valentine has reached the
playoffs this year, but his didn't finish first. In the days of
Richards and Jimmy Dykes (2,962 games), they didn't have the
benefit of the wild card.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
