<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1678 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-MASKHADOV-NY     10-09 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-MASKHADOV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECHNYA'S CHIEF, UNDER FIRE, TAKES A FIGHTING STAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia _ The Chechen leader, Aslan Maskhadov, a former
colonel in the Soviet Army, is a restrained, gray-haired man.
Dressed in camouflage uniform, sitting on a sofa, he issues firm
orders to his men in a low voice in the Chechens' urgent, hiccuping
language.
</P>
<P>
   The man who is confronting Russia in Chechnya this time is a
pale shadow of Dzokhar Dudayev, the former Soviet Air Force general
who took the republic into war in 1994. Where General Dudayev, who
perished toward the end of Chechnya's war with Russia in 1996, was
famous for his flamboyance and explosive rhetoric, Maskhadov is
known more for his straightforwardness and reason. He has always
been seen as politically moderate and as someone who could
negotiate with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in an interview last week, he seemed to drop his usual
conciliatory talk. As Russia has gradually pushed into Chechnya,
and bombed its towns and villages in the name of flushing out or
destroying Islamic militants, Maskhadov has shown himself ready to
fight.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that the end was near for Russian power in the
Caucasus _ a power derived from Russia's traditional role as broker
or military bulwark of the various Caucasian peoples, locked in
centuries-old quarrels among themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, important events are happening in the Caucasus.'' he
declared. ``The West is already here,'' he added, referring to the
presence of Western investment and aid in Azerbaijan and Georgia,
which lie just south of this small mountainous republic. ``Russia
will soon go from all the Caucasus.''
</P>
<P>
   While deploring the involvement of Chechens in fighting in the
neighboring Russian republic of Dagestan in August and September,
he described the underlying cause as a ``nationalist liberation
movement,'' motivated by broad disagreements with the Russian
government.
</P>
<P>
   He also refused to denounce the two most wanted men in Russia,
the prominent Chechen field commander Shamil Basayev and the Arab
fighter known as Khattab. Russia has accused them of leading the
incursions into Dagestan this summer, and implied that they were
behind a series of explosions that killed some 300 people.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov is seen, even in Moscow, as a man with whom Russia
could have negotiated. Indeed, the Kremlin did so for a time. He
was elected president after the war in January 1997 by an
overwhelming 65 percent of the vote, in elections judged free and
fair by foreign observers of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin of Russia even sent him congratulations
in what was seen as a peace offering, effectively a fresh start
after the 1994-96 war that humiliated the once-mighty Russian
military and ended with the status of Chechnya, formally a Russian
republic, frozen in its current limbo until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Twice after the Chechen election, Yeltsin and Maskhadov met in
Moscow, and Yeltsin vowed on television that he would always get
together personally with the Chechen leader to resolve any future
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Now, although the Chechen leader has offered talks, Moscow has
ruled them out. Yeltsin, whose grip on Kremlin power is firm but
increasingly overshadowed by the knowledge that his era will end
after presidential elections next summer, seems to have forgotten
his pledge.
</P>
<P>
   To push Maskhadov into a fight may, however, be shortsighted. He
has proved himself a hard man when his back is to the wall. He is
legendary among Chechens for his stand in Grozny's besieged
Presidential Palace in the winter of 1994, when he hung on for
weeks commanding the resistance as Russian tank shells were
blasting the building from 500 yards away.
</P>
<P>
   He is also prepared to go on the offensive. As Chechen chief of
staff, he masterminded the rebels' seizure of Grozny in August
1996, when several thousand Chechen fighters swooped on the city in
a coordinated assault and trapped some 12,000 Russian troops there.
The operation brought the Russian Army to a standstill and forced
an end to the war.
</P>
<P>
   After three years of what he sees as fruitless efforts at
cooperation with Russia, and now facing another war, Maskhadov has
hardened his line. ``I should have said to Russia that this is all
a waste of time,'' he said, looking back on the agreements he
signed with them.
</P>
<P>
   ''Russia was always looking for some way to weaken us, with some
sort of provocation or sabotage,'' he said. ``They have been the
bosses here for a hundred years and they have their own people
here.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Russia apparently feels that Maskhadov has been
unable to deliver on any of the promises he might have held out for
the Kremlin. Certainly, in the view of Russia, the Chechen leader
cannot control the fighters it blames for the incursions into
Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's rejection of Maskhadov's overtures is pushing him
closer to die-hard commanders who will never give up their
ambitions for independence or their armed resistance to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   He has alienated many of them over the last few years with his
attempts to cultivate warm relations with Russia. Aslanbek
Izmailov, one of his senior commanders and the deputy chairman of
his cabinet of ministers, criticizes him harshly for that policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was absolutely not right from the beginning to try to be
friendly with Russia,'' Izmailov said. ``He hoped Russia would
recognize our independence. Maybe now he has realized a bit how
wrong that was, but not totally.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little tangible evidence that Moscow was ever serious
about helping Maskhadov. The city of Grozny remains in ruins, as
does much of the republic's industry. He has barely won a penny of
promised compensation for his people from the Russian government,
let alone any sort of long-term aid for development or
reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government's frustration is that Maskhadov is weak.
He has been unable to bring under control many of the powerful
field commanders, who have become virtual warlords in their own
areas, or dilute their demand for independence. Nor has he been
able to prevent the wave of kidnappings that has alienated local
people seized for ransom and driven foreign investment,
international aid organizations and all but the most intrepid
outsiders from Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov has always called for full independence for Chechnya
because, he says, the people do not want to be ruled by Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chechens do not want to be subjects of the Russian
Federation, and so the Chechen people need to build joint relations
in a civilized way with a normal government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov has also been blamed for not moving against the
Wahhabis, members of a conservative Arab Islamic sect who are seen
as major troublemakers by many ordinary Chechens and who are blamed
for catapulting Chechnya into this new war. Maskhadov has refrained
from a complete crackdown because he says it would start a civil
war in Chechnya, which he says is what Russia wants.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's latest offensive has ended the internal divisions for
the moment and brought his opponents in Chechnya around the
president again. But Maskhadov is also sounding tougher than ever
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will protect our land and Russia, if it comes in to occupy
it, will be annihilated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
