<HEADER>
A1680 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-IRAN-NEWSPAPER-700&AMP;AD     10-09 1419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-NEWSPAPER-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN REFORMERS, SILENCED 3 TIMES, START ANOTHER PAPER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran Undaunted by the closure of its three preceding
newspapers, all of which rocketed to the highest circulation in
Iran, a group pressing for a more democratic and tolerant form of
Islamic rule has opened a fourth daily. Once again, the reformers
are challenging the conservative clerics who would have the country
remain the bristling, anti-Western, inward-looking creation of
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's 1979 revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The first edition announced itself on Thursday with a banner
headline proclaiming ``Comeback'' and a robust editorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when the world is approaching the third millennium,
Islamic people, including Iranians, have to ask themselves what our
attitude toward this new age is going to be,'' the paper said. It
added, ``The answer is that ease of access to information of all
kinds is one standard by which we can differentiate between
countries that have established civil societies and those that have
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamidreza Jalaeipour, 41, a financial backer, editor and
columnist for each of the three closed papers and for the new one,
is something of a veteran of the cat-and-mouse game of publishing
bold newspapers in a society in which reformers and conservatives
are locked in a struggle for Iran's future, and the conservatives
control the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, a judge ordered the closure ``forever'' of the
third of a string of reformist newspapers that Jalaeipour and his
colleagues have published _ and been forced to close _ in the last
16 months. In that most recent ruling, the judge declared that the
daily, Neshat, had insulted Islam with articles chronicling the
conservatives' hard-knuckle tactics.
</P>
<P>
   So Jalaeipour and his colleagues delved into the stock of
publishing licenses they took out as a precaution two years ago,
when the election of a reformist president, Mohammad Khatami,
emboldened Iranians looking for relief from 20 years of Islamic
authoritarianism.
</P>
<P>
   Their new paper, Asr-e Azadegan, looks like nothing so much as a
clone of its three purged predecessors. Despite the euphoria at the
new paper over being back on the streets, the
conservative-controlled Parliament signaled that it intended to
strike back, this time with a bill that would broaden the already
broad powers of the press court to close publications.
</P>
<P>
   Reformers plan to boycott Parliament to deny the conservatives a
quorum, but the outcome is likely to await a parliamentary election
in February in which the two sides will vie for a majority,
particularly for the votes of young people in a country where
two-thirds of the 69 million people are under 30.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the 100 editors, reporters and production
specialists at Asr-e Azadegan are hoping they can outlast Neshat,
the longest-surviving of the paper's predecessor, which published
149 editions before it was closed. Along with the closure of
Jaameeh and Tous, Neshat's forerunners, the closures have left the
paper's backers with a $200,000 debt _ a heavy burden in a country
where newspapers sell for the equivalent of 6 cents and the average
monthly salary is less than $50.
</P>
<P>
   There are worries, too, about the eventual fate of Latif Safari,
Neshat's publisher, who held the paper's publishing license. After
an eight-hour trial last month, the 28-year-old judge, Said
Mortazavi, sentenced Safari to 30 months in jail and banned him
from journalism for five years, but left him free pending appeal, a
process that could take months or even years.
</P>
<P>
   In his haste to see Neshat shut down, Judge Mortazavi even
refused to adjourn the court hearing for the noontime prayers,
usually imperative among Islamic stalwarts.
</P>
<P>
   Among the reformers, the closure of Neshat, and new threats that
were made against Asr-e Azadegan even before its first edition,
have been viewed as part of a wider attempt to use the courts to
stifle change.
</P>
<P>
   Mashallah Shamsolvaezin, the editor of Neshat and now of Asr-e
Azadegan, has written an open letter to Khatami appealing for him
to be bolder in defending the reforms. ``Everyone understands that
what happened to Neshat was because of the complex political
situation in the country,'' he said. ``The clash between the
different forces has slammed the brakes on the entire process of
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Iranians think the country could still go one way or the
other _ toward a more open and democratic society that would enable
Iran to rejoin a world it has largely shunned since the shah's
overthrow in 1979, or back to the rigidity of the past.
</P>
<P>
   If the odds swing back and forth, it is partly because so much
of the struggle within the clerical establishment _ between those
backing Khatami, a middle-ranking cleric himself, and hard-liners
who see Khatami as an apostate _ takes place beyond public view.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the man who heads the clerical establishment,
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, stunned the country with a speech praising
Khatami as a pious man who has been working ``for the rebirth of
Islam.'' The speech was all the more striking for being delivered
at the shrine of Ayatollah Khomeini, his predecessor as Iran's
``supreme leader'' and the man who more than any other fashioned
the Iran now criticized by the reformers.
</P>
<P>
   Khamenei may have decided that the high-ranking clergy must
accommodate Khatami's reforms, which envisage a continuing
``guardianship'' role for the top ayatollahs, or risk losing power
altogether as popular impatience with the conservatives builds.
</P>
<P>
   Others note that much that has been done to frustrate change,
and particularly to thwart the ``liberal'' intellectual class
represented by the reformist newspapers, has been done by the
powerful state apparatus that Khamenei ultimately controls.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, reformers were chilled by the slayings of five
leading reformers, three of them writers. Within weeks, an inquiry
established by Khatami forced the powerful intelligence ministry to
admit that the killers belonged to a secret death squad operating
within the ministry, supposedly without knowledge or approval of
their superiors. One man accused of being a leader was later said
to have committed suicide in a Tehran jail, but three others have
still to be brought to trial.
</P>
<P>
   While there have been no new killings, reformers say that in the
wider struggle, Khamenei has generally aligned himself with the
hard-liners, particularly on the issue of press freedom. Last year,
he described reformist papers as ``the crawling cultural advance of
the enemy.'' And Gen. Rahim Safavi, the commander of the
Revolutionary Guards, said, ``Heads need to be rolled, tongues need
to be cut, and pens need to be broken.''
</P>
<P>
   In this climate, the reformist newspapers operate in a
minefield.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jaameeh, the first of the four papers put out by Jalaeipour and
his colleagues, was closed after five months for ``publishing
lies,'' among them its report of General Safavi's remarks about
cracking down on intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
   Tous, Jaameeh's successor, lasted two months before it was
closed for ``endangering national security,'' apparently with its
criticism of Iran's threats of war after the Taliban movement in
Afghanistan killed nine Iranians, including eight diplomats, in the
Afghan city of Mazar-i-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
   Zan, a reformist paper edited by Faezeh Hashemi, daughter of Ali
Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani, the previous president, was closed in
April after it published parts of a new year's message from Farah
Diba, the exiled wife of the deposed shah.
</P>
<P>
   Salam, founded by Mohammed Moussavi, a middle-level cleric who
is a close ally of Khatami, was banned in July for ``attempting to
create turmoil and instability'' after it published what it said
was a handwritten letter from the man accused of leading the
intelligence ministry death squad.
</P>
<P>
   Salam's closure prompted student demonstrations at the
University of Tehran in July that escalated into the worst rioting
since the shah's overthrow.
</P>
<P>
   Neshat, the most recent newspaper closed, hastened its demise
with its reporting of the rioting. The paper was found guilty of
inciting the students and insulting the national police commander.
The main charge, insulting Islam, stemmed from an article that
suggested that the death penalty and other harsh punishments in
Iran's criminal code were un-Islamic.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
