<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-SEX-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POST-MONICA SKITTISHNESS: SEX, POLITICS AND THE OPEN DOOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. _ Gary Bauer ordered a glass door for his office
at his presidential campaign headquarters here last week. There was
nothing wrong with the old wooden one _ except that two former
aides have said they left because Bauer frequently closed it to
meet one-on-one with his female deputy campaign chief.
</P>
<P>
   So, Bauer quipped, better a glass door than a glass ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   There were titters after the conservative former head of the
Family Research Council called a news conference to deny rumors
almost no one had heard _ about improprieties no one seems to
believe occurred.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not a particularly funny episode for Bauer, who seems
to have suffered with his base on the Christian right after the two
former aides, men who are now working for his Republican rival
Steve Forbes, came forward to say they quit because Bauer had been
willfully oblivious to appearances. The 27-year-old woman who was
the subject of the rumors certainly isn't laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Other politicians and their consultants said that, especially
after the Monica Lewinsky scandal, the incident was sadly
unsurprising in a world of terrified male principals, not to
mention the female aides who would be penalized if they had only
limited access to the boss.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer's reaction to the criticism seemed to speak to a general
skittishness in the post-Monica moment in U.S. politics. And while
the long-term impact on professional women in a still mostly-male
arena is unclear, the state of play for men and women at work on
campaigns is certainly a live issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks again, Bill and Monica,'' said Republican consultant
Alex Castellanos, who added that while he does see a
much-heightened sensitivity to appearances, he does not advise
candidates to safeguard appearances at the expense of female staff.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic consultant Joe Trippi left Clinton out of it, but
otherwise agreed. ``It's crazy that it's gotten to this point,'' he
said. ``It's probably the one and only time I agree with Gary
Bauer.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of conservatives felt Bauer should have been more
cautious, and should have stopped meeting privately with his female
aide after their strategy sessions caused talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was wrong, especially after he was warned'' by his former
aides that long closed-door meetings didn't look right, said Cathie
Adams, head of the Texas Eagle Forum, a conservative women's group.
``That should not be part of what a man of integrity does. You've
got to have true friends around you, who will confront you if there
could even be a perception of misbehavior. Maybe it doesn't mean no
closed-door meetings, but not hour after hour with someone half
your age.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Black, who was a political adviser to presidents Ronald
Reagan and George Bush, said Bauer should expect to be held to a
particularly high standard because ``many Christians believe that
to avoid temptation, men and women just shouldn't be alone when one
is married.''
</P>
<P>
   But that view ``seems sexist to me,'' Bauer said in an interview
_ one-on-one, with the door open _ in his headquarters, where his
wife, Carol, has an office across the hall, and his 22-year-old
daughter, Elyse, a campaign aide, is just down the corridor.
</P>
<P>
   He said the whole brouhaha over private meetings was hard for
him to comprehend. ``I'm not this debonair guy,'' he said. ``And I
don't understand how we can set a standard that says young
professional women can never rise to a point with a male boss that
they're able to give confidential advice. My daughter said, `Dad,
if that's the standard, I just wasted four years of college.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, feminist standard-bearer?
</P>
<P>
   He gave a wounded smile. ``I'm not the Neanderthal I've been
made out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   And he is not, apparently, the only politician wondering about
how to preserve his own reputation without damaging the careers of
female aides. On Capitol Hill, several members said the fact that a
female congressional staff member had been named in Newt Gingrich's
divorce proceedings had further complicated matters.
</P>
<P>
   One House Democrat said that in September, when Sen. Max Baucus,
D-Mont., was accused of, and denied, sexually harassing a female
aide he had let go, ``Every one of us looked at that and said,
`There but for the grace of God go I.' Even if you're not doing
anything wrong, you know you could be accused of anything at any
time.''
</P>
<P>
   This man, who like others said he was afraid to be named even
talking about the issue, said he had himself been warned by
supporters not to let a woman drive for him during his last
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was cautioned to be careful of appearances,'' he said, but
decided to ignore the advice. But he added: ``I know several
members who feel they have to keep the door open when they meet
with female staff. And the question is whether that diminishes the
effectiveness of top female staff.''
</P>
<P>
   No member, of course, admitted to compromising female employees
in that way. Rep. Steve Largent, R-Okla., whose spokesman had been
quoted by The Washington Post as saying he would not meet alone
with women, said via a spokesman that he in fact has ``no hard and
fast rule, but tries to use common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   But several members did say they knew others who had concluded
that private meetings with women were just too risky.
</P>
<P>
   With more women in powerful positions, do female principals have
to be equally careful? Nah, said several consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elizabeth Dole has been traveling with young male aides
throughout the course of this campaign, and it's never been a
problem,'' said Linda DiVall, who is Mrs. Dole's pollster. ``Though
some of them do have to carry her purse.''
</P>
<P>
   As more than one political adviser pointed out, State Department
spokesman James Rubin has been all over the world with Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, presumably without scandalizing anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Black, the former Reagan and Bush adviser, said he, for one,
would tell women candidates to be just as careful as their male
counterparts _ and has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran Paula Hawkins' Senate campaign and I gave her that same
advice, not to travel alone with male aides,'' he said, referring
to a Florida Republican. ``There's a little more attention on it
now, but this is not totally new.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Susan Estrich, a University of Southern California law professor
who ran Michael Dukakis' Democratic presidential campaign in 1988,
said that men's fear of career-stopping sexual allegations was
acute in the world of politics _ ``a weird world of married men and
single women'' _ but also quite common in the business world. And
in part, she says, that's a result of the laws that were supposed
to protect women from sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men are reluctant to go on business trips with women,'' said
Ms. Estrich, who teaches a course in gender discrimination. ``At
the end of a hard day, a man can have a beer and watch the game in
his room with another man, and that's OK, but with a woman, it's
not.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that as a result, professional women were often left
without the mentors that are crucial to most successful careers.
``It's pretty hard to be mentored by somebody who doesn't want to
be alone with you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And she finds that yes, Monica Lewinsky, and even Ally McBeal,
the mini-skirted TV lawyer, have made men at work still more
nervous. ``The message to guys is, if you see a 24-year-old woman,
particularly one who's a little bit sexy, beware.''
</P>
<P>
   The immediate outlook for young women in politics does seem
circumscribed. ``If I were running a campaign today, even I
wouldn't assign a 25-year-old woman to travel with the candidate,''
Ms. Estrich said. ``I wouldn't want to encourage people to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   But Melissa McClard, the passionately conservative 27-year-old
Bauer aide whose closed-door meetings and campaign trips with her
candidate did become an issue, said she has drawn precisely the
opposite conclusion from her recent educational experience. And
what she feels she's learned the hard way is that you can't let the
whisperers have their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has undermined my confidence in the workplace and other
people's confidence in me, because now women are mistrusted in the
workplace,'' she said. ``In the wake of everything that's happened
in the last year, the presumption is that, when the door closes,
there is something else going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'll be honest, this has changed things in my job. Whether
it's conscious or subconscious, it's always in the back of your
mind and it's hard to keep a focus and not allow anger to take
over. You don't want to overcompensate, but you have to be
tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   After disapproval over her access to Bauer first registered, she
said, ``I went through a phase where I did not wear skirts to the
office and I did not wear makeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then one day somebody said, `Maybe you should pull your hair
back in a bun.' At that point, I didn't know if they were kidding
or not. But when that comment was made, I finally realized that
what others say is not as important as how you feel when you sit
down all alone, and you know who you are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
