<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1692 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-ELVIS-AUCTION-960(2TA     10-09 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELVIS-AUCTION-960(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURES OF ELVIS ARE SOLD AT AUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Nev., Tenn., Ill.)  (lb) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The mystery train that carried Andrea Bauer to the
MGM Grand Hotel this weekend started in her family's living room
when she was a girl, in the 1950s. Sometimes when her father, a
devoted Perry Como fan, left the house, her mother would quickly
switch to a record by that new singer, the twitchy kid from Tupelo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elvis Presley would sing, and my mother and I would dance and
dance and dance,'' Ms. Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   So, four decades later, she came to Las Vegas to get herself a
little piece of Graceland.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis Presley Enterprises, the group that manages Graceland _
Presley's former home _ and other Elvis-related properties,
including the trove of archives from a man who seems to have thrown
away nothing (do you still have your 1960 Texaco credit card?),
decided it was time to put some of its treasures on the auction
block.
</P>
<P>
   For three days this weekend, each one devoted to memorabilia
from a decade of Elvis' performing life _ beginning with the 1950s
on Friday and ending with the 1970s on Sunday _ collectors,
obsessives and ordinary fans from all over the world could walk
away with a piece of Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands came to see the auction preview exhibits that went on
display Sept. 28, said Arlan Ettinger, president of Guernsey's
auction house in New York, which is handling the auction.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we opened the doors, there was already a line, and there
was not a time during all of those days that it was not crowded,''
Ettinger said. ``We have handled a lot of big auctions, including
the baseball auction that had Mark McGwire's record home-run ball
and an auction of John F. Kennedy items, but we have never seen
anything like this. I had to triple the size of my staff.''
</P>
<P>
   The cavernous, chandeliered auction hall at the MGM Grand was
humming Friday afternoon when the lights dimmed and ``Also Sprach
Zarathustra,'' better known as the theme from ``2001: A Space
Odyssey'' blared over the loudspeakers. It was the music Elvis
always played to announce his arrival on the stage in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the lights came up and it was Ettinger at the
microphone. ``I guess you were hoping it would be someone else,''
he said. ``I guess I was, too.''
</P>
<P>
   It was just the kind of oddball scene you might expect _
tourists from Iowa seated next to serious collectors whispering
into cell phones, several Elvis impersonators working the crowd
(including one guy who, frankly, save for his pompadour and
gleaming jewelry, looked a bit more like Broderick Crawford), and
dozens of people of all shapes, ages and sizes in Elvis T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bauer fidgeted excitedly in her seat near the back of the
room, grimacing as she lost out on the bidding for a couple of
items. Finally, she hit pay dirt, forcefully raising her auction
paddle into the air until, for $950, she became the owner of a 1956
note from Steve Allen to Col. Tom Parker, Elvis' legendary manager,
thanking him ``for sending the wonderful saddle for Stevie.'' Elvis
had appeared on Allen's show in July 1956, singing ``Hound Dog'' to
an actual hound dog that sat nervously beside him.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bauer, who flew in from Carol Stream, Ill., to attend the
auction with her 17-year-old son, did not care whether anyone else
thought the note was worth the money. She came to Las Vegas for
this and she wanted to take something away with her. Her mother got
her started collecting Elvis memorabilia, and she already has some
concert tickets, a pocket watch and other items.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was a big Steve Allen fan and I'm a big Elvis fan,
so it feels right,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For decades most of this Elvis arcana was out of sight and in
the care of archivists. Then, said Jack Soden, the chief executive
officer of Elvis Presley Enterprises, the idea of the auction came
in a flash one afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   An arm of the group, the Elvis Presley Charitable Foundation,
had been working for decades on a variety of projects in Memphis,
Tenn., and had gradually become more and more impressed with the
work being done by the Memphis Inter-Faith Alliance to get homeless
families off the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were drawn to the program because of the role public
housing played in Elvis' life,'' Soden said. ``When his family
moved to Memphis from Tupelo, they had to live in public housing,
and he never forgot that period of poverty in his childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance had built ``villages'' of transitional housing for
homeless families that had particularly impressed Soden and the
others. So they came up with the idea of auctioning the memorabilia
to pay for the construction and maintenance of Presley Village, a
new housing development near downtown Memphis, to be managed by the
Inter-Faith Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   They asked Lisa Marie Presley, the singer's daughter and heir,
if she liked the plan (``It's her stuff,'' Soden said), and she
said yes.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much the three-day auction brings in _ sales have
been projected to reach $2 million, but Soden and Ettinger say
nobody really knows _ the Presley Foundation will give $1.5 million
for Presley Village, which will have 12 units. That is enough to
break ground in about a month, have the first homeless family move
in next year and maintain the place for many years.
</P>
<P>
   If the auction makes more than $1.5 million, the excess will be
pumped into the Presley Foundation until it has what its managers
believe is a sufficient cash reserve. If there is any money left,
it will go into expanding and upgrading the Presley archives and
exhibits at Graceland, Soden said.
</P>
<P>
   He was keen to assure people that none of the items put up for
auction had been on exhibit at Graceland. ``This auction does not
diminish the Graceland experience,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Those who came looking for something to sneer at (as a great man
once said, don't be cruel) found a rich banquet for their
patronizing scorn _ furry pillows, furry chairs, a leopard-skin
beanbag chair (also furry), coats with lime-green lapels, black fur
collars and red-leather pocket flaps, a 9-foot-long love seat
shaped like a banana, several sparkling jumpsuits in neon shades of
green and red and gold, a table whose legs were statues of nude
mermaids, holding a lamp that looked like a Mardi Gras float, and
on and on.
</P>
<P>
   There were also enough trivial financial documents among the
objects _ hotel bills, canceled checks, performance contracts,
plane tickets, car-repair invoices _ that it seemed all someone
would need was Elvis' W-2 to be able to do his taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet these were not the overwhelming impressions left by the
auction's assemblage of objects. Instead, what you saw, peeking
from amid the relics, were the little flashes of humanity, through
the eyes of a bewildered country boy from Tupelo who walked a very,
very strange American road from poverty to pop-cultural deity,
perhaps getting a little loopy in the process.
</P>
<P>
   There was Elvis' sixth-grade report card from Tupelo Junior High
School in 1947. He was particularly strong in music and spelling,
weak in geography and arithmetic, scored higher and higher in the
``citizenship ratings'' of reliability, cooperation, industry and
courtesy, and was absent only a handful of days.
</P>
<P>
   There was also the receipt from the Fountainbleau Hotel in 1960,
with Presley's precise and demanding breakfast order, including
eggs fried hard (``yolks broken'' is underlined), bacon crisp,
sliced tomato, hash brown potatoes, toast (``well buttered'' is
also underlined), coffee and milk.
</P>
<P>
   And there was a hand-scrawled note found in Parker's desk that
reads: ``Hello Colonel, I used your phone. Hope you don't mind.
Respectfully, E.P.''
</P>
<P>
   One imagines Parker saving it so he would remember to bill Elvis
for the call.
</P>
<P>
   All through the auction, bits of Elvis' life disappeared with
the nod of the auctioneer's head into the lives of strangers. His
first piano went for $90,000. The report card fetched $8,000. His
1956 white Lincoln Continental Mark II went for $250,000 to an
anonymous bidder on the phone. His draft card drew $22,500. Elvis'
set of keys to Graceland went for $23,000.
</P>
<P>
   The keys to Graceland!
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Johnson, the director of the Association for Retarded
Children in Knoxville, Tenn., said she did not know exactly why she
had wanted those keys, but she got them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain why,'' she said. ``I came with a list of five
or six items I might bid on, and they were one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   For reasons they cannot explain, some people just want to see
Graceland.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Johnson seemed a little shocked that her purchase of the
keys prompted television cameramen to follow her out of the auction
room and down the hotel corridor, past the celebrity-chef
restaurants and toward the casino and the palm-lined Strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose I'll just put them in my underwear drawer, where
they'll be safe,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had no plans to display the keys and no desire to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'll take them home and tell my friends I've got
them,'' she said. ``Or maybe I'll go on over to Graceland and see
if they changed the locks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
