<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1695 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-AUSTRIA-NAZIS-REVIEW-     10-09 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-NAZIS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIENNA, RIGHTWARD: SOMETHING'S AFOOT IN AUSTRIA, BUT IT ISN'T
GOOSE-STEPPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ Wedged inside a crowd in the central square
here, listening to a politician harangue the throng while 200
student demonstrators behind you scream ``Nazis, raus! Nazis,
raus!'' at him, it's important to quell those waves of memory and
remind yourself: You don't speak German, stupid. Forget all those
black-and-white films you watched as a kid. This isn't ``Triumph of
the Will'' even if you're getting the guttural aural cues. It was
your father who was in on the Normandy landing; you only caught the
flick.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders often think they spot Nazism on the march in
German-speaking countries. It's a conditioned reflex, the same way
African newspapers love to run big pictures of tiny Ku Klux Klan
rallies, leaving the impression that every third American is a
Klansman.
</P>
<P>
   One American TV report on the 27 percent showing by Joerg
Haider's right-wing Freedom Party in voting here last week worked
in old clips of goose-stepping soldiers and a fulminating Hitler.
An Israeli headline said: ``One Out of Every Four Austrians Chose a
Neo-Nazi Chancellor.''
</P>
<P>
   That offended even Austrians who detest Haider (whose party tied
for second and is highly unlikely to become chancellor).
</P>
<P>
   In fact, my translator said, the speaker was criticizing the gap
between the pay of Austrian bank presidents and working stiffs.
It's true that when Haider complains about ``Uberfremdung,'' or
over-foreignization, even Austrians say the word has a certain
``Deutschland Uber Alles'' ring to it. But the overtly racial
element of Nazism is lacking. It's similar to the sentiment
expressed in Ross Perot's ``giant sucking sound'' from south of the
border _ nativist populism.
</P>
<P>
   Even here, it isn't necessarily racial. An Egyptian taxi driver,
Hassan Ramy, told me he was a Haider voter. What about his
anti-immigrant feelings? I asked. He's against the ones who don't
have papers, he answered.
</P>
<P>
   True, Austria was long criticized for failing to deal with its
Nazi past; for years, while Germany apologized, it portrayed itself
as Germany's first victim. And Haider has made what a Jewish leader
in his party called ``a couple of stupid remarks that are
constantly quoted.''
</P>
<P>
   In one, he retorted in the heat of debate that the Third Reich
had a sounder employment policy than the today's governing Social
Democrats, and in another he told a veterans' reunion that included
some Waffen SS soldiers that they were ``decent people who stuck to
their belief through the strongest headwinds.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither at the Vienna gathering I attended nor at a noisy
beer-tent rally in Haider's home area, near the Slovenian and
Italian borders, did his supporters harp on race. ``Sixty percent
of the people here, I think, are protest votes,'' said Hans
Hechenleitner, 53, explaining that people felt the ruling Social
Democratic-conservative coalition in Vienna left them feeling
powerless. ``There's not racism, except maybe among some of the
uneducated ones, and you have also this difference in the U.S., is
it not so?''
</P>
<P>
   I asked Hechenleitner about something Haider has said in Vienna,
complaining about the ``extremist'' tag: ``People say I'll declare
war on Slovenia if I'm elected. But that's not true. In my area, we
have good relations with the Italians and Slovenians.''
</P>
<P>
   The reaction suggested Haider had gone a bit bleeding heart in
pandering to the urbane Viennese. Hechenleitner and his friend,
Horst Assam, 62, looked at each other. Hechenleitner finally spoke,
betraying the Austrian mistrust of outsiders: ``No, you can't say
we  &UR; like &LR;  them. But we work together.''
</P>
<P>
   There is definitely something creepy about Haider's xenophobia
and how many Austrians it appeals to. Austria is in the middle of
Europe and has been overrun by a lot of peoples _ and Austrians
themselves are often eager to enumerate their diverse ethnic
backgrounds for you. But there's something in at least 27 percent
of the country that wants to shut the door, and it lives even in
the breasts of Egypto-Austrian cabbies. Andreas Rudas, a senior
tactitian for the Social Democratic Party, called it ``the omnibus
effect,'' as in, ``Once I'm on the bus, I want the doors to close
so it doesn't get crowded.''
</P>
<P>
   What liberal leaders find disturbing is less Haider's rhetoric
on race than his oratory on crime _ which, by extension, whips up
fear of foreigners. Prodded by his claims that it is coddling drug
dealers, the government launched a series of drug raids. ``But the
subtext becomes anti-black, anti-Nigerian,'' said Georg
Hoffman-Ostenhof, a political columnist for the weekly Profil, even
though the black population is minuscule.
</P>
<P>
   With 4 percent unemployment, health care for all and a
negligible murder rate here, it's a mystery why a lot of Austrians
are convinced that their tiny nation is a hotbed of crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``What drug dealers?'' my translator, who weighs about 100
pounds and feels safe bicycling anywhere in Vienna at night, asked
Horst Thaler, a 66-year-old in a Tyrolean jacket at a rally for
Haidar's party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look in the Karlsplatz,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a subway station a few blocks away, so we did. By Times
Square standards, it's an Alpine village. By Austrian standards,
it's littered, and there were several unwashed guys begging for
``Zigaretten.''
</P>
<P>
   On election night, coming home from watching the late returns, I
passed the Karlsplatz again. The beggar who approached me was, I
presume, Austrian; he was polite and completely bilingual.
</P>
<P>
   Then a music event nearby let out, and a crowd came surging
toward the tram. They climbed on, loud and obnoxious, practically
shouting at each other. They were from North Carolina and
California, they were in black tie and had hearing aids. They were
ticked: They didn't know the opera in Vienna begins at 6, and they
had missed the whole first act.
</P>
<P>
   Uberfremdung.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
