<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1713 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-REPUBS-BUSH-DELAY-985     10-09 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-BUSH-DELAY-985(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POLITICAL PUZZLE OF 2 TEXANS:   BUSH AND DELAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Mo.)  (mk) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER and FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There are a couple of leading theories about the
relationship between the Texas Republicans who may soon be running
the country:
</P>
<P>
   A.) That the party's presidential front-runner, Gov. George W.
Bush, and the House majority whip, Tom DeLay, R-Texas, are closer
than we know, ideological kindred spirits who like to play good
cop/bad cop but then share the double-secret conservative handshake
when nobody is looking.
</P>
<P>
   B.) That these two guys from opposite sides of the tracks have
little to nothing in common and if Bush was elected president,
would enjoy roughly as easy a relationship with DeLay as the
governor's father did with Newt Gingrich, the firebrand who later
became speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Those close to both men suggest yet another possibility: that
while they are not unfriendly and are at least somewhat
like-minded, they are also similarly tough and competitive _ enough
so to be willing to win at the other's expense, if need be. And
smart enough to recognize, too, that they need each other, at least
for now.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks, Bush certainly seemed to go out of his
way to poke DeLay and all House Republicans in the eye a couple of
times. First, he accused them of trying to ``balance their budget
on the backs of the poor.'' Then, in a speech on education, he
portrayed his party as fixated on affluence _``focused on the
national economy, to the exclusion of all else.'' But aides to Bush
insist that his later remarks, which had been written before the
first flap occurred, were not intended to cut congressional
Republicans a second time, and seemed harsher in light of the
earlier criticism.
</P>
<P>
   After initially lashing out that the governor ``does not know
how Congress works,'' DeLay is said to be over his pique (or
facsimile of pique, in the alternative view). DeLay, who is
commonly viewed as the real power in the House, volunteers that he
and the governor have ``never had dinner. We aren't social
friends.'' But his comments do advance the theory that the two are
ideologically much closer than their stylistic differences might
suggest. And, of course, no one in the Bush campaign has ever
hinted that their candidate is anything other than a credentialed
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure there's a whole lot of difference between us,''
DeLay said in a recent interview, before Bush's unflattering
remarks. ``I'm not sure there's a dime's worth of difference
between us, philosophically. I don't know of any moderate Texas
Republicans, if you really want to know. It's conservative and more
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   In his quest to put a friendlier face on the Republican Party,
Bush has more reason to put some distance between himself and the
majority leader, Rep. Dick Armey, another fellow Texan, and DeLay,
also known as ``the Hammer,'' whom Democrats are trying to make
Bush's de facto running mate. (``Just remember B-A-D,'' said Chris
Lehane, a spokesman for Vice President Al Gore. ``Bush-Armey-DeLay:
Bad policy, bad politics, bad for America.'')
</P>
<P>
   One Republican strategist said that because Bush would be
jettisoning the House Republicans' confrontational style, the
members of Congress hurrying to board the Bush bandwagon seemed to
be catching on only belatedly to the fact that their instant
affection for the governor might not be reciprocal. Most House
Republicans rushing to support him ``never calculated that it was
an act of self-immolation,'' the strategist said, adding that most
were still ``as oblivious to what this means for them over the next
two to four years as a 6-year-old is to the workings of a jet
engine.''
</P>
<P>
   But not so DeLay, who seems both reconciled to the fact that
some distancing is probably inevitable and willing to return the
favor and speak out against the governor, if necessary. ``Bush has
to do what he has to do to win his presidency,'' he said at the end
of last week. After making the critical remarks about fellow
Republicans in last week's education speech, one adviser to the
governor said that Bush had acknowledged that House leaders knew
the score, saying, ``Those guys understand.''
</P>
<P>
   And the governor, in turn, understands that he needs
congressional support _ 152 House members have endorsed him so far,
along with 25 senators _ and so must keep DeLay at least relatively
happy. ``For House Republicans, DeLay is the most important figure,
and within the campaign there's a recognition that we need to be
working with him,'' the Bush adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   Many in Congress have already pitched in with fund-raisers back
home, and will help to turn out the Republican vote in their
districts, where many of them are quite popular. If Bush is
elected, a working relationship with House Republicans would
certainly make life easier, even if they fail to hold on to their
majority. But it is also generally understood that if he has to
sacrifice the House to get elected, he will.
</P>
<P>
   Relations do not seem to have been permanently chilled by the
recent criticism. Aides to the two men socialize, and the
governor's official liaison on the Hill, Rep. Roy Blunt, R-Mo., who
says he talks to the governor's staff nearly every day, is also
DeLay's chief deputy whip.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Bush formally announced his candidacy, he and some
House Republicans had begun meeting informally to discuss an agenda
for 2000. Bush needed their early support, and House Republicans
needed a strong presidential candidate, one with the potential to
help them preserve their slim majority despite some pretty iffy
poll ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly,'' Blunt said recently, ``a lot of our members
endorsed him before they met him,'' but have only become more
enthusiastic as they have gotten to know him, he added. When asked
to name Bush's closest friends on Capitol Hill, he thought for a
while and said, ``I think he and Tom DeLay are friends'' _ again,
not golfing buddies, but political allies with an understanding.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In background, bearing and basic style, the two men are
obviously worlds apart: Bush is an Ivy League-educated former owner
of a professional baseball team who was born into a political
dynasty _ a sunny, big-picture guy's guy who likes to get along and
seemed to enjoy governing Texas alongside his good friend, the late
Democratic Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, on the other hand, is the son of an alcoholic wildcatter,
a man DeLay describes as ``like something straight out of
`Giant.''' The House whip is a former pest exterminator who made
his own way, got into politics to cut red tape and became a
true-believing, i-dotting and t-crossing, fight-to-the-finish
conservative, the ultimate partisan, and proud of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush does the forest, DeLay does the trees,'' said Ed
Gillespie, a Republican strategist, with a laugh. ``Bush is
passive-aggressive, DeLay is aggressive-aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, by all accounts, seems to regard DeLay with a respect
exactly commensurate with the power he wields in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   They first met in 1980, ``when I was first starting,'' DeLay
remembers, ``and his daddy was running with Ronald Reagan.'' Their
first encounter was at a fund-raiser in Houston, where DeLay said
the younger Bush made an impression. ``He was, what's the word I
want? Passionate is too feminine, but he was gung-ho for his daddy.
He was kind of oil field trash _ that's an endearing term, by the
way. And when I first met him he was trying to find himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, ``He's certainly smoothed over the edges. Probably
the best thing that ever happened to him was getting involved with
the Texas Rangers, because he focused and learned from that.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, when President Bush abandoned his no-new-taxes pledge,
DeLay was front and center among House Republicans who opposed him.
And the younger Bush did not enlist DeLay into his gubernatorial
campaign against the incumbent governor, Ann Richards, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   But DeLay does seem to get along better with the governor than
he ever did with President Bush, referring to the younger Bush as a
fellow Christian and ``much more of a people person'' than his
father. Typically, he likes to position himself as the benefactor,
rather than the supplicant, in the relationship. ``When he needs
something, he calls, and we try to take care of him,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   But even if in truth the balance of power is probably in Bush's
favor, DeLay does have the power to hurt the governor, and those
who know Bush say that means he will try to keep him as close as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   As one Bush supporter who knows them both put it, ``They're
different guys, but at the end of the day, they're both just a
couple of pols. And I can see them now, on the Truman balcony with
their boots up, trading war stories.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
