<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Goes on Offensive In a Foray Into Canada
</P>
<P>
   The sun was shining, he was among friends, and soon the
president was on a roll, improvising jokes as he worked his way
through a speech inaugurating the new U.S. Embassy in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Blithely unaware of the Canadian government's defensiveness over
its high tax rates, Bill Clinton cracked that his host, Prime
Minister Jean Chretien, ``says that if I come one more time I have
to start paying taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Clinton, who undoubtedly has been briefed on the national
aspiration of many French-speaking Quebeckers, described a family
trip he made a decade ago to Montreal as a trip to ``France.''
White House stenographers corrected the transcript to read
``Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the blooper that catapulted a routine trip to the top
of Friday evening's BBC television news. He improvised a folksy
image to illustrate his efforts to ``help the people in the land of
my forebears in Northern Ireland get over 600 years of religious
fights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And every time they make an agreement to do it, they're like a
couple of drunks walking out of the bar for the last time,'' he
said of the zigzag peace process between Protestants and Catholics
in Northern Ireland. ``When they get to the swinging door, they
turn around and go back in, and say, I just can't quite get
there.'' Clinton later apologized for what he called an
inappropriate metaphor.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES BROOKE
</P>
<P>
   Wanted, Whoever He Is &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some wanted posters of the future may have no photographs, no
names, only strands of DNA, if a Wisconsin prosecutor's charge
against an unknown suspect is upheld. And the notion of a time
limit for filing criminal charges may go the way of the powdered
wig.
</P>
<P>
   Someone committed three rapes in Milwaukee in 1993. But with the
state's six-year time limit for filing charges about to run out in
one case, police have no idea who the rapist is. So to put a foot
in the door, the prosecutor has filed charges of rape and
kidnapping against ``John Doe, unknown male with matching
deoxyribonucleic acid profile.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You can change your name, but you can't change your genetic
code,'' said the prosecutor, Norman Gahn.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say the case will be challenged, but is not
frivolous. ''We are at the beginning of an era where law
enforcement has to go back and look at old unsolved cases,'' said
Barry Scheck, a law professor and member of the Commission for the
Future of DNA Evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I assure you,'' he said, ``you are going to find thousands
of serial murderers and serial rapists.''
</P>
<P>
   A series of numbers that describes the Milwaukee suspect's
genetic code were uploaded by modem to the FBI's national databank
of DNA Each month, they will be compared with 200,000 profiles from
convicted offenders and crime scene evidence submitted by police
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL DEDMAN
</P>
<P>
   A Presidential Visit To the Teamsters
</P>
<P>
   For decades, U.S. presidents have shied away from meeting with
leaders of the International Brotherhood of Teamsters because of
that union's malodorous past. But President Clinton cast such
caution aside by attending a dinner honoring James P. Hoffa, the
union's new president and the son of its most famous leader. Union
officials say Clinton spoke at the dinner in the hope of persuading
the teamsters to endorse Vice President Al Gore. White House
officials say the president appeared at the dinner because the
teamsters union is such a large, important organization. These
officials also noted that thanks to a 10-year federal cleanup, the
union is far less corrupt than it used to be. _ By STEVEN
GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Interest Rates Hold  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan is in a tough spot.
Traditional economic models say the economy is so strong that there
is a danger of inflation, but in the real world inflation is almost
non-existent. So Greenspan held interest rates steady, but hedged
his bets by hinting that the Fed could push rates up as soon as
next month. Even the hint was enough to give Wall Street a case of
the jitters.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD W. STEVENSON
</P>
<P>
   A Blueprint for East Timor
</P>
<P>
   United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan laid out his
blueprint for the new nation of East Timor _ Timor Loro S'ai in
Tetum, the local language. The two-to-three year project promises
to be the biggest operation the United Nations has had to mount
since rebuilding Cambodia in 1992 and 1993. With a U.N.
peacekeeping force assuming responsibility for defense, the
organization will be expected to take over East Timor's gutted
towns and depopulated civil administration and organize everything
from garbage collection to a new legal system. Putting the troops
in place could take a few months, but Annan made it plain that
civilian administrators should move into the dangerous political
vacuum much sooner. The Security Council is likely to give the
go-ahead in the next week or two.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARBARA CROSSETTE
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   India's Hindu Party Gains A Solid Victory
</P>
<P>
   When election returns were counted in India, the Hindu
nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party emerged in a commanding
position, able to lead a centrist coalition of 24 parties that
offered hope that India would now have a durable government, rather
than the shaky one that the party had been leading. The big loser
was the once-dominant Congress Party, which had hoped to return to
power but suffered a humiliating defeat instead.
</P>
<P>
   3 Indicted in Money Case  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury indicted three key figures in the
investigation of about $7 billion in suspect funds that moved
through the Bank of New York over the last three years. The three
Russian emigres named _ former Bank of New York executive Lucy
Edwards; her husband, Peter Berlin, and a business associate,
Aleksey Volkov _ are charged with running an illegal wire transfer
business, but investigators indicated last week that further
indictments are on the way. The investigation is examining whether
the enormous money transfers involved money laundering, the process
of washing ``dirty'' money through a series of bank accounts until
it looks ``clean.'' Investigators say that is hard to prove and
federal investigators still haven't uncovered proof of it at the
Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN
</P>
<P>
   New Life for the F-22
</P>
<P>
   Congress will allow the Air Force's $70 billion F-22 fighter jet
to proceed to the assembly line, but only if it can pass stringent
flight tests. The House and Senate struck a deal under which the
F-22, projected to be the most expensive fighter jet ever built at
$200 million a plane, will receive $2.5 billion in research and
development money this year but none for procurement until it pass
a series of hurdles and milestones.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TIM WEINER
</P>
<P>
   Return of the Iron Lady
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Conservatives, smarting from their loss to Labor two
years ago, have been in need of steeling. So they sent for the Iron
Lady. Former Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher went to their annual
party conference in Blackpool and moved effortlessly to the center
stage she had occupied until being ousted from office by Tory
rivals in 1990. She may have been too outspoken for the
Conservatives then, but not now. Modern-day Tories want to hear
about British pride and the dangers of encroaching Continentals,
and Baroness Thatcher obliged. ``We are quite the best country in
Europe,'' she said. ``In my lifetime, all the problems have come
from mainland Europe, and all the solutions have come from the
English-speaking nations across the world.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By WARREN HOGE
</P>
<P>
   Nixon Speaks. Again.
</P>
<P>
   President Richard M. Nixon's use of anti-Semitic remarks are
fairly well known because of the use of his secret taping system.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when a new batch of those tapes was released by the
National Archives, it was jarring to hear him telling aides that
every member of the communist conspiracy was Jewish except for
Whittaker Chambers and Alger Hiss, and he harbored the suspicion
that Hiss might have been half Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Hiss' son, Tony, when told of Nixon's notion, said:
``Unfortunately, it's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not over. The National Archives is to release more X-rated
Nixon tapes in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   _ By IRVIN MOLOTSKY
</P>
<P>
   A Step Back For Genetic Engineering
</P>
<P>
   Monsanto Co., the biggest name in agricultural biotechnology,
pledged not to market a controversial product that does not yet
exist: seed genetically altered to produce infertile crops. Such
seed would put a stop to farmers saving seed from their harvest for
replanting the next year, giving biotech companies a better shot at
selling them new seed annually. Monsanto does not currently control
the rights to the technology and some scientists say it will never
work outside of the laboratory, but it has already become so
infamous that Monsanto decided to repudiate it. Biotechnology
critics, referring to it as ``Terminator genes'' or ``suicide
seeds,'' have been using it as a potent symbol for everything they
oppose in agribusiness.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARNABY J. FEDER
</P>
<P>
   Train Crash in Britain
</P>
<P>
   Britain's worst train wreck in decades provoked soul-searching
about safety measures on the national railroad system since it was
sold to private investors three years ago. The debate raised the
question of whether national assets like the railroads should be
shielded from raw market forces and run by the state. The police
said more than 70 people were believed to have died in the crash
between two trains in West London on Tuesday, and scores more were
unaccounted for. _ By ALAN COWELL
</P>
</TEXT>
