u i BC-YUGO-COMMUNISTS-REVIE     10-09 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-COMMUNISTS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE NEW YUGOSLAVIA, A FAMILIAR DEAD HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Communism may have died 10 years ago in
Eastern Europe, but it lives on, after a fashion, in Yugoslavia _
both in patterns of power and habits of mind. The failure of
political and social transformation helps explain why efforts to
oust President Slobodan Milosevic are faltering.
</P>
<P>
   While ``reform communists'' are back running Poland, for
example, they are a younger generation, humbled and educated by
periods out of power, during which more liberal reformers bungled
government in their own peculiar ways.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout the republics of the former Yugoslavia, with the
exception of Montenegro and Slovenia, the same leaders continue to
rule as did 10 years ago in the name of the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Montenegro, which is Serbia's last sister republic in
Yugoslavia, the Western-backed leader, Milo Djukanovic, runs his
tiny republic (population 650,000) with all the old habits of
cronyism and patronage. Slovenia is the only former Yugoslav
republic that might be considered democratic.
</P>
<P>
   One obvious reason for this durability of the old leaders and
their style of rule was the nature of Titoism _ a softer brand of
Communism that rejected Stalinism and the higher authority of
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Standing proudly, even contemptuously, outside the Soviet bloc,
with a better living standard, a freer press and easy access to the
Western world for ordinary citizens, the old Yugoslavia became a
model for Soviet reformers like Mikhail Gorbachev. And Belgrade was
also insulated from the crisis of Soviet-bloc communism that led to
its collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The flexibility of Yugoslav communism, with its commitment to
private agriculture and some private business and employment in
service industries, allowed the system to bend rather than snap. In
Yugoslavia, there was less repression aimed at ordinary citizens
and more freedom of expression, especially after Tito died in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   A higher standard of living meant that the state and its
companies could afford to provide decent social benefits for longer
_ benefits, like good pensions and free education, that people
still fear losing now, even when Belgrade no longer has the money
to pay them on time, and they have become virtual, rather than
real.
</P>
<P>
   The force of the state and its instruments of repression were
used more thoroughly to keep the multi-ethnic Yugoslavia together
and to tamp down national expression _ especially resentment felt
by Serbs at the economic and political sacrifices they were called
on to make for the idea of a federal state.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure for change swept through Yugoslavia after Tito's death,
but it took the form of national and ethnic ``liberation'' and
conflict rather than political and economic transformation, said
Ivo Viskovic, a political science professor at Belgrade University.
</P>
<P>
   New freedoms of expression were used for nationalist ends, even
by the Serbian intellectual elite. By 1987, the Serbian Academy of
Science had published an infamous memorandum complaining of Serbian
humiliation and mistreatment in Yugoslavia _ a harbinger of
Milosevic's own manipulation of nationalist passions, on which he
built his power.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia has been different from the rest of Eastern Europe
for a long time, Viskovic said. ``People didn't suffer so much as
in other countries, and the standard of living was pretty high. So
people didn't feel such a need for a dramatic change of the
system.'' The Serbs, Bosnians, Croats and Slovenes ``tried to free
themselves from the others, instead of from the system of economics
and power,'' he said. ``Led by their political and intellectual
elites, people chose to go to war instead of changing the system.''
</P>
<P>
   While Milosevic renamed the party, he has never recanted or
disowned any part of the ideology. Yet he is an authoritarian
coalition-maker, not a dictator, and this is a multiparty state
with the possibility of change through elections.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, given the basic tenets of communism as it was
practiced _ social ownership of the means of production and a
single-party state _ the Yugoslav version doesn't really qualify,
says Ljiljana Smajlovic, an independent journalist originally from
Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Smajlovic said, ``this place is more like the old
Yugoslavia than any of the other broken states.
</P>
<P>
   ``People cling to what is left, a little frozen in time.'' she
said. ``They still put their confidence in the army and the
education system. They no longer have salaries, but 40 percent of
people are afraid of privatization. They hold to the notion of
socialized medicine and of job security when there is none. They
have lost the reality of social security but they are convinced
they are clinging on to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mental habits persist in part because of Western-imposed
isolation, and in part because many of Serbia's best, youngest and
brightest _ up to 350,000 people _ have emigrated in the last 10
years. In many ways, the West's quarantine of Milosevic has only
strengthened the curtain of ignorance behind which, like some odd
Wizard of Oz, he continues to rule.
</P>
<P>
   Now people are so poor and desperate here that they have lost
the sense that change is possible, Viskovic said. ``It's much
riskier to be for change now than 10 years ago,'' he said. ``To
lose your job now is a life tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   He described the case of a student who took his doctorate and
taught as a professor in a Smederevo high school, then was fired
six years ago for criticizing the local authorities and has nowhere
to turn for redress. ``People simply feel that if they are in
conflict with the regime they will lose,'' Viskovic said.
</P>
<P>
   Such fears, explicit in polling data, have reduced people's
willingness to demonstrate. The regime has fostered such fears,
with cameras filming rallies, sudden investigations by the
financial police and ordinary police visiting homes to check
documents.
</P>
<P>
   In a large recent poll of Serbian attitudes, nearly two-thirds
of respondents were unhappy with the regime. But some 70 percent
were afraid to participate in demonstrations compared to only 40
percent in 1996, when Belgrade saw 88 days of pro-democracy
protests. Today, 90 percent fear a decline in living standards, and
nearly as many fear new inflation and the loss of jobs. Some 80
percent fear civil war and 70 percent hunger.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia's larger problem of authoritarianism is reflected
throughout the former Yugoslavia, except for Slovenia, Viskovic
said. ``This is not just an inheritance of communism or Titoism but
of our history.'' Except for some 10 years in Serbia before World
War I, he noted, there has been no experience of democracy in the
Balkans in modern times.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need is not a new leader,'' he said, but a new
generation and a more modern political ideology, where politicians
solve problems through pragmatism and cooperation and not simply
fealty and force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
