<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-GOLD-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BLEAK HOUR FOR SOUTH AFRICA MINERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ For days, the miners listened to
the crackle of good news from their battered radios and prayed that
the soaring price of gold would save them. But the banner headlines
that have thrilled government officials, economists and mining
executives were not enough to stop the layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 1, 2,895 miners lost their jobs at the Western Areas
gold mine, which in recent months has suffered from poor
productivity and slumping prices. And last week, even though gold
prices surged to their highest levels in nearly two years, the men
who built a living burrowing underground found themselves
unemployed and out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hoped the gold price would minimize layoffs, but it
didn't,'' said Welcome Mzunjani, 31, who supported a wife and two
daughters on his $230 monthly paycheck. ``Now I will have to battle
to make ends meet.''
</P>
<P>
   These are heady days for South Africa, the world's leading
producer of gold. The metal dipped to a 20-year low of $255.75 an
ounce in early July but is flying again. On Friday the price closed
at $323 an ounce in London.
</P>
<P>
   If it holds at this level, economists say, annual export
earnings will increase by about $762 million to $5.1 billion, which
would provide a desperately needed lift for the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
   But even optimists acknowledge that the gains will not stop the
labor force from shrinking. Since 1989, the number of gold miners
has dropped to about 180,000 from about 514,000. A strong gold
price will slow the pace of decline, economists say, but layoffs
will probably continue as mines become more efficient, ore deposits
are depleted and the country continues to reduce its reliance on
gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big boost to the economy, but it doesn't mean that
retrenchments are going to cease,'' said Roger Baxter, chief
economist for the Chamber of Mines. ``You're still going to have
retrenchments, but the rate of decline in employment numbers will
slow.''
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Manuel, the finance minister, also cautioned against
over-optimism, telling local reporters that while higher prices
would save some jobs, ``there will always be difficulties,
especially given the fact that a number of mines are as marginal as
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month the East Rand Proprietary Mine, the country's oldest
operating mine, closed down, leaving 5,000 workers jobless. Another
4,000 miners have lost their jobs since July, when the gold price
plummeted and several other companies laid off workers, union
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to halt the layoffs at Western Areas, the National Union
of Mineworkers went to court, seeking an injunction. But on Tuesday
the judge ruled in favor of the mining company, which is jointly
owned by Western Areas Ltd. and the Canadian-based Placer Dome. The
company argued successfully that it could not keep the workers,
because it had lost about $4.5 million in the quarter that ended in
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``A week, even two weeks is too soon to be able to say this is a
stable, sustainable price,'' said Patrick Evans, a spokesman for
Placer Dome, of the current gold price. ``We had to bring the
business back onto a profitable footing.''
</P>
<P>
   The company allocated $2 million to help jobless men find work
in their villages in Swaziland, Lesotho and South Africa, and hoped
that 70 percent would be self-sufficient in two years, Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   But union officials complained that the company cares more about
its bottom line than the livelihood of its workers. Referring to
the Canadian owners, George Molebatsi, a spokesman for the National
Union of Mineworkers, said: ``They came to make money in this
country. That's the bottom line. The issue of job creation doesn't
mean anything to them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The laborers are typically men in their 30s and 40s with little
education, few skills and little hope of finding work in a country
where unemployment has reached nearly 40 percent. At Western Areas,
the average miner has spent about 10 years digging for gold.
</P>
<P>
   Now they sit restlessly outside their concrete-block hostels,
waiting for their final medical exams and severance pay and
watching enviously as the 5,000 remaining employees put on hard
hats and overalls, rubber slickers and rubber boots, and descend
into the deep.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Shongwe, 35, said he might try planting corn in Swaziland,
his country. Simon Gumedze, 24, said he would take up computers, if
he could find the money to pay for a course. Palita Tyobsile, 34,
said he would take a job, any job.
</P>
<P>
   But all three said they expected to struggle for months without
work. Gumedze said it took him a year and a half to get the job at
Western Areas; for months he waited hours every day at the mine's
hiring depot, until they finally called his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would have 10 years working here,'' said Gumedze,
a father of two who has spent two and a half years at Western
Areas. ``But my chances to be in the mine is past. Now I'm thinking
about my future, how I will support my family, how we will
survive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
