<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN IN HOSPITAL, REPORTEDLY WITH FLU 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CHECHNYA-MASKHADOV) 
(mk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin of Russia was taken to the
Central Clinical Hospital on Saturday morning suffering from what
his press secretary described as the flu accompanied by a high
fever.
</P>
<P>
   Dmitri Yakushkin, the Kremlin press secretary, said that
Yeltsin, 68, had not felt well Friday but refused to go into the
hospital until Saturday. Yakushkin said the president would stay in
the hospital for at least two days.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, now less than a year away from finishing his second
four-year term in office, has been repeatedly plagued by poor
health.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 he underwent multiple bypass heart surgery, and he has
also suffered from acute back pain, several bouts of pneumonia and,
earlier this year, a bleeding ulcer, for which he was hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   These ailments have complicated a fitful work schedule. Yeltsin
has sometimes stayed out of public view for weeks at a time. In
recent weeks, as Russian troops moved into the breakaway region of
Chechnya, Yeltsin has again kept a low profile, although Kremlin
aides have reported that he was holding regular meetings with top
government officials up through the end of last week.
</P>
<P>
   However, he has not made any public appearances for more than a
week. In the early phase of the 1994-96 Russian war against
Chechnya, Yeltsin also remained out of sight, as he underwent what
Kremlin aides said was an operation on his nose.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Yakushkin suggested that the president might soon be
ready for a vacation. ``Undoubtedly, it is very hard to work in
such a rhythm, taking into account his age and other factors,''
Yakushkin was quoted as saying. On Saturday, Yakushkin said the flu
would not prevent Yeltsin from watching a televised soccer match
Saturday night between Russia and Ukraine, fierce rivals in the
playoffs for the European championship in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   With presidential elections scheduled for next June, Yeltsin and
his political advisers have been waging a behind-the scenes
struggle to take control over his succession. Last August, Yeltsin
designated Prime Minister Vladimir Putin _ his fourth prime
minister in the last year and half _ as his preferred heir, and in
the same televised address last August, he said he intended to
become Russia's first leader to hand over power in a democratic
transition.
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, the Kremlin has denied recurring rumors that
Yeltsin may choose to resign early because of poor health, and in
accordance with the Russian constitution, hand over power to his
prime minister, Putin. In that event, presidential elections would
have be held within three months of the handover.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Yakushkin rejected as ``nonsense'' reports that
Yeltsin was going to Germany for heart surgery later this month.
</P>
<P>
   But with Russian troops now reportedly moving deeper into
Chechnya, fighting a low-intensity war that at the moment holds out
little or no prospect for a political solution, Yeltsin's physical
and political weakness have again become an issue. In an interview
with The New York Times last month, Yegor Stroyev, chairman of the
Russian Parliament's upper house, caused a political stir by saying
it would be better for both the country and the president if
Yeltsin voluntarily left his job before the end of his term.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
