<HEADER>
A1775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WIS-BURGLARY-ART-575&AMP;     10-09 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIS-BURGLARY-ART-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEFTS PLAGUE WISCONSIN'S NORTH WOODS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RHINELANDER, Wis. _ Wheeling the car down the sloped pathway
through a forest of soaring oak and pine trees, John Sobolewski
glimpsed his beloved old cedar cabin, and noticed the door had been
left open.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed it on the wind, or his own forgetfulness. In 30 years
of weekend trips to his cabin in the pristine north woods of
Wisconsin, Sobolewski had never once had trouble with thieves.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, he left the doors unlocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I walked in, I realized burglars had gotten in,''
said Sobolewski, 65, who quickly discovered that intruders had
stolen his hunting guns, his binoculars and other valuables. ``I
couldn't believe it. You never had to worry about anything in the
woods, except, you know, for the squirrels and raccoons getting
into the garage and chewing up the boat cushions.''
</P>
<P>
   In the deepest, most tranquil lands of Wisconsin, where people
could retreat for a few days and forget about urban woes, burglars
have been clearing out vacation homes with the efficiency of a
moving company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become epidemic up here in the last few years,'' said
Michael Roberts, a sheriff's investigator in Price County. ``It's a
sign of the times, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Price County has seen more than 100 burglaries this year, at
least double the rate of five years ago, Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   It is the sort of crime that happened so rarely 15 or 20 years
ago that it scarcely registered on the police radar screen. ``Back
in the '80s, when we saw some tracks leading to a cabin in the
winter, we just figured, oh somebody on a snowmobile is stopping
by,'' said Joe Fath, the chief deputy of the Vilas County Sheriff's
Department. ``
</P>
<P>
   In some recent cases, burglars have cleaned out cabins so
thoroughly that they even pulled up the carpet and took the
toothbrushes and deodorant.
</P>
<P>
   Police say the wooded privacy that draws vacationers also suits
the working conditions of burglars, and the thefts are made easier
still because the homeowners generally come around only on
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The burglars also know that vacation cabins in these affluent
times tend to be stocked with expensive furniture and artwork, said
Fath.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the typical old shacks anymore,'' he said.
``Nowadays, people build a $200,000 home and call it a cabin.
They've got stereos, hot tubs, all the comforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Detective Jim Wood, of the Oneida County Sheriff's Department
here, said some thieves specialize in guns, while others are
looking for deer antlers. Some people will buy the black market
deer antlers, he said, so they can hang them on their walls and
boast of their hunting prowess. He said the antlers had also become
popular as artwork and lanterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you haven't seen them, they're really pretty neat,'' he
said of both.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the thieves were becoming especially busy during
this time of year, as many of the owners had said goodbye to Lake
Tomahawk and Crescent Lake, among the hundreds of freshwater bodies
in the woods, and gone back to the screech and bustle of Chicago
and Milwaukee until next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these burglars are going to work right now,'' said
Fath. ``And people won't know what hit them until they come back in
the spring.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing popularity of snowmobiling, with trails plowed by
the county highway departments, has also made it easier for thieves
to reach their targets, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It's not the old north woods like it used to be,'' he said
sadly, noting that break-ins in the north woods were as scarce as
nightclubs when he joined the force in the '80s. ``A lot of people
up here still act like it's the old way, leaving everything open.
They think you don't have to worry, since you're hundreds of miles
from a city, where all the bad things supposedly happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Fath said he tells them otherwise. ``If you compared crime to
population,'' he said, ``it's not so different here than it is for
them back in Milwaukee.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobolewski, a retired chain company worker who lives near
Chicago, acknowledged that he was being naive. He said he never
imagined people could be up to trouble in a place that seemed so
peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   But that has changed. A few weeks ago, he had sturdy locks put
on the doors of his cabin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there's problems all over anymore,'' Sobolewski said.
``I hear they've even got gangs in little towns in Wisconsin now,
for heaven sakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobolewski, the son of Polish immigrants, said the vacationers
in the north woods used to be mostly working people, like himself.
One of his neighbors was a brewery worker. Others were tradesmen.
Fishing was a passion they all shared.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, the north woods have become more popular
among younger people who drive sport utility vehicles and pack a
computer in their travel bags. Some of them do not even fish.
</P>
<P>
   As he has for years, Sobolewski still likes to walk down from
his cottage to the banks of the Wisconsin River, cast a line out
into the deep, still waters, and wait for the perch to bite.
</P>
<P>
   On the day he discovered the burglary in September, he brought
along his 10-year-old great-grandnephew, Daniel. It was going to be
a special day for the young man and his uncle. Sobolewski, who does
not have children of his own, was going to show Daniel how the red
squirrels in the north woods bring pine cones into the garage and
fill open pails, stocking up food for the harsh Wisconsin winter.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, he needed to call the sheriff's department and
make a report.
</P>
<P>
   Going back to the cabin has not been the same for Sobolewski for
the past two years, since his wife, Charlotte, died.
</P>
<P>
   ``She could really fish,'' he said, growing quiet for a moment.
``We did everything together _ walk, bike, garden. Oh, we had
fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
