<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HISPANICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS SENATE HOLDING UP HISPANIC JUDGESHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BILL DEDMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ President Clinton told a national Hispanic group
Saturday that the U.S. Senate was a black hole of delay, unwilling
to vote for his Hispanic nominees for federal judgeships but afraid
to vote against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I don't know about you, but if I took three and a half
years to make a decision, you wouldn't think I was a very good
president,'' Clinton said. ``How many times has somebody been on
you because you took three and a half hours?''
</P>
<P>
   The president was warmly received Saturday morning at the annual
conference of the U.S. Hispanic Leadership Institute, a nonpartisan
organization that promotes voter registration and training of
Hispanic officials. He gave credit to the Clinton-Gore
administration for the growing economy, particularly this week's
economic information showing that household incomes of Hispanics
are growing faster than those of other Americans. But he devoted
much of his address to the judicial nominees.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was not an isolated incident last week when the
Senate rejected his nominee for the federal bench in Missouri after
the seat sat empty for two years. The Senate on Tuesday voted 54-45
against the nominee, Justice Ronnie White, who is black.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have said they have approved hundreds of Clinton
nominees, including two on the day that White was rejected. They
said the Missourian had an extremely pro-criminal record in hearing
appeals in death penalty cases. The president criticized White's
rejection as ``a disgraceful act of partisan politics.''
</P>
<P>
   And while many Republicans said they were not aware of White's
race when they voted against him, in its reaction to the vote the
White House emphasized what it called unfair treatment of minority
nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton continued that theme Saturday, turning the focus on
Hispanic judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just disappear somewhere in the dark recesses of the
calendar of the Senate,'' Clinton said. ``Why? Well, they don't
want to vote him down because they hope that you will vote with
them in the next election, but they don't want to vote for him.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Senate was dragging its feet on the nominations of
Richard Paez of California, the first Mexican-American to serve on
the federal bench in Los Angeles, to serve on the 9th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals ; Marsha Berzon, an appellate lawyer, also in the
9th Circuit; Judge Julio Fuentes in the 3rd Circuit; Enrique Moreno
in the 5th Circuit; and Judge Ronald Guzman for the Northern
District of Illinois.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
