u l BC-FASHION-FIANDACA10-CO     10-09 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-FIANDACA10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fiandaca's fall line offers youthful style and old-fashioned
attention to detail
 &HT;    By Robert Janjigian
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Flattery can get you everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Fiandaca presented 79 distinctive day and evening
ensembles for autumn and winter 1999/2000 at his petite
second-floor salon along Boston's Newbury Street.
</P>
<P>
   It was a warm evening and 79 is a large number of looks to take
in at one sitting, but the Fiandaca flair came across, as did a new
direction that will undoubtedly have women from Palm Beach, Fla.,
to Portland, Ore., clamoring for a chance to add some Fiandacas to
their fall and winter wardrobes.
</P>
<P>
   There was a flurry of ordering on the minute the last model,
dressed in an ivory silk satin bridal-style gown, left the
spotlight. Fiandaca's agenda the following day was filled to the
brim with appointments and fittings.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston- and New York-based designer, who spends a large
portion of the Palm Beach season working out of his Via Mizner
shop, has a large number of loyalists, among them Jane Dudley and
Emily DiMaggio. In the crowd at the Boston showing were several
stylish Palm Beach locals, including Diane Tosi, Denise Swan, Jerre
and Cheryl Gowdy, Carol Henderson, Mickey Lee, Heather Hill, Ruth
Shapiro and Phyllis Rappaport. They and many others come to
Fiandaca for the old-fashioned attention he pays to making
almost-custom, couture-level clothes for them.
</P>
<P>
   Fiandaca, at a point in his career when he could probably rest
on his laurels, is consciously making a slightly younger design
statement. He acknowledged this by suggesting daring, baring
features in some outfits, but didn't forget about those who don't
want to show too much skin, adding boleros, stoles and jackets to
give women the option of covering up in a finished way. The
strategy of producing a collection that appeals to everybody, from
20-somethings to 80-somethings, worked very well.
</P>
<P>
   Several young things, so to speak, invited to preview Fiandaca's
fall collection, could be heard murmuring their approval during the
show.
</P>
<P>
   For the fall and with a eye on the big new year ahead, Fiandaca
touched all the stylistic bases. Some might view that as taking the
safe route, addressing a variety of tastes to appeal to a wider
range of buyers, but Fiandaca's creative concerns didn't seem muted
or hesitant about making a statement. He mixed it up in an apt
manner.
</P>
<P>
   Bright brocade suits would make a handsome addition to a woman's
closeted repertoire. While reminiscent of Fortuny, Issey Miyake and
Mary McFadden (certainly not bad company to keep), Fiandaca's
pleated velvet pieces were a triumph. Steel gray mattelasse and
chiffon pieces came off as rich and pretty instead of bland (as
this tone can come off in the hands of less-reputable stylists).
Mixed prints were eye-catching and contemporary. Retro peasant
passages, in the New Bohemian vein, were deftly inserted. Both
goddess-style and beaded gowns would make a splash.
</P>
<P>
   Looks reminiscent of the jet-set era were also on hand, with one
charmeuse halter gown worn with a cream lace cover-up. It was just
so Claudine Longet, it made you want to rethink those layered-look
crocheted vests everybody wore at one point in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   There were only a few missteps. A ruffled purple-velvet gown
looked like something a bridesmaid would lament. The dresses that
offered unnatural geometric necklines and a graphic sensibility
were not quite up to snuff. But, overall, there was something for
everyone, age be damned.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Janjigian writes for The Palm Beach Daily News, Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
