<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Oct. 10, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A plume of tropical moisture will precede a cold front moving
swiftly across the northern tier of the nation. The corridor of
humid air will stretch from the mouth of the Mississippi River to
the northern Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, more than 2 inches of rain fell on Paducah, Ky., a
daily record. More heavy rain is expected Sunday in the central and
southern Appalachians as high pressure east of the Carolinas
circulates additional moisture into this region from the Atlantic
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Very mild air will cover the East as morning readings average
well above seasonal levels due to thick clouds and winds from the
south. Florida will be bright and rather hot with isolated
thundershowers in the southern sections.
</P>
<P>
   Fog will be slow to dissipate in the middle Mississippi and
western Tennessee valleys. Cooler, dry air will push into the upper
Midwest on blustery breezes from the northwest, which will gust
over 30 mph.
</P>
<P>
   An elongated high pressure system will promote very pleasant
conditions for most of the western half of the nation. The
clockwise circulation will direct dry, warm air from the interior
west to the Pacific Coast. Temperatures will rise to near record
values in parts of California.
</P>
<P>
   The jet stream will flow along the border states from Washington
to Michigan. Streamers of moisture above 10,000 feet will interrupt
the otherwise tranquil, bright weather in this region. Sunday night
will be cooler in the northern Plains and upper Great Lakes. The
Southwest will be sunny and hot, though a few high clouds will
arrive later on.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: AUTUMN FROST
</P>
<P>
   While mild air has returned to the Northeast this weekend, a
frost occurred in much of the region earlier in the week. The date
of the first frost can differ by weeks within 100 miles. There are
significant delays in frost in major cities as opposed to the
suburbs, in coastal communities compared to inland areas, and in
hilly terrain vs. nearby valleys. In the mountains of northwestern
Pennsylvania, there is a 70 percent chance of a freeze by October
1. Yet, not far away along the shores of the relatively warm Lake
Erie, wine makers can enjoy frost-free weather into early November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
