u a BC-CREW-SINGLE-MOTHERS-N     10-09 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREW-SINGLE-MOTHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROWING CREW OF YOUNG MOTHERS IS RACING FOR CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH HADLEY, Mass. _ Their oars splashed and slipped a little
more often than the other rowers' did. Their shoulders didn't lean
as far back on each stroke. But the crew members from the Holyoke
Care Center, competing in their first regatta, had the biggest
cheering section of any team on the Connecticut River.
</P>
<P>
   The four-person scull was easy to spot. As Anne Teschner, their
mentor, said, the care center's crew was the only team of ``single
mothers out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Out there, or maybe on a rowing team anywhere. In recent years,
rowing has been praised as an alternative sport for inner-city
children, a way to impart fresh air, exercise and discipline. Ms.
Teschner, executive director of the center, decided to see whether
rowing could do the same for young mothers on public aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than sitting at home or being a couch potato,''
said Marilyn Cruz, 20, who passed a high school equivalency exam
this summer with the center's help and is taking classes at a
community college. Ms. Cruz, a ninth-grade dropout and mother of a
1-year-old, plans to use her crew connections to apply to Mount
Holyoke's program for students with children.
</P>
<P>
   The two dozen women who volunteered for the program practiced
two afternoons a week, an hour and a half at a time, for two
eight-week sessions over the summer. Mount Holyoke College offered
its boat house, boats and coaches to train. The care center
provided a rowing machine for off-water practice, along with day
care for the rowers' children.
</P>
<P>
   Tessa Spillane, the coach who worked closest with them, said the
mothers _ and sometimes mothers-to-be _ learned faster than some of
her other novices, who practice daily. At the Mount Holyoke
Invitational, the oldest women's regatta in the country, the care
center team competed against Amherst, Middlebury, Regis, Simmons,
Smith and other colleges known not only for their academic programs
but their rowing prowess.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Spillane's biggest challenge in training was that only about
half the women spoke English. About 95 percent of the care center
clientele is Puerto Rican. Ms. Spillane relied on the bilingual
team members to translate.
</P>
<P>
   Cary Perez, 19, taught her colleagues how to put an oar in the
water properly. ``I don't know the word for oar,'' she admitted.
``I call it a `stick' _ `palillo.'''
</P>
<P>
   The translators became the leaders of the group. ``These four in
particular are quite feisty,'' Ms. Spillane said of Ms. Cruz, Ms.
Perez, Vicky Ortiz, 18, and Desiree Velez, 17. Although all the
trainees could have participated in the regatta, only this small
group wanted to compete.
</P>
<P>
   This was their first time hearing the cow bells and the Mount
Holyoke cheer that accompany a launch: ``We drink acid, we eat
rocks!''
</P>
<P>
   The care center is located in downtown Holyoke, where blighted
patches contrast with the stately brick buildings of Mount Holyoke
College just across the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emphasis has never been on going fast, but on showing them
that they could do something new,'' said Jeanne Friedman, Mount
Holyoke's head crew coach. ``The hope is that the self-confidence
would carry over to other parts of their lives. They are living in
parts of the city which are not beautiful, and this gets them on
the river. It's a stone's throw from where they live, but most of
them have never been on it.''
</P>
<P>
   On shore, Ms. Perez's daughter, 2-year-old Keysha, watched the
race from the arms of her father, Lioneo Alsina, 20. At first Ms.
Perez ``was complaining that her muscles were sore,'' said Alsina,
who shares an apartment with her. But the comments are more
positive now. ``She said she's getting very good at it,'' he
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part for Ms. Perez and the other high school
dropouts has not been the discipline _ showing up on time for
practices and learning the skills _ but ``carrying the boat,'' Ms.
Perez said. ``It's real heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   As for who won, well, it turned out the care center crew rowed
the only four-person boat in the novice class that day. But the
team's 11 minutes 32 seconds would have been respectable time, even
if there had been competition, Ms. Teschner assured them.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ortiz scoffed. ``11:32? We should have done nine minutes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
