<DOCNO> NYT19991009.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1795 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TOBACCO-KY10-COX     10-09 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-KY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tobacco farms' last gasp?
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAINT LICK, Ky. _ Henry West is finished with his back-breaking,
brow-drenching burley tobacco harvest. In boots and Wrangler
bluejeans, he spent the hottest parts of summer weaving leaves of
burley through 4-foot-long wooden tobacco sticks to dry. Family and
hired hands hung thousands of them from barn rafters so leaves
would cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm up from daylight to dark-thirty,'' the 55-year-old former
accountant said, repeating a refrain of tobacco farmers across the
South. In a few weeks, tobacco auctions will start in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   But growers worry the sun's about to set on their way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Baked by a summerlong drought, some Kentucky fields produced
just half their typical yield. But the real heat, the farmers say,
comes from legal setbacks for Big Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Already bleeding from a $206 billion settlement with 46 states
that had pressed or threatened lawsuits, the top tobacco companies
recently were hit with a lawsuit brought by the U.S. Justice
Department. It seeks to recover hundreds of billions of federal
health care dollars spent to treat illnesses blamed on smoking.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, experts predict cigarette prices will keep climbing
and excise taxes will continue escalating, further diminishing
domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
   That means Kentucky farmers will need to grow less tobacco.
Their toil has made Kentucky the state most economically reliant on
tobacco and helped generate the country's highest smoking rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see themselves under enormous attack, and there's a lot
of pessimism,'' said Hampton Henton, director of Kentucky's Farm
Service Agency, which administers price support programs. ``A
banker might ask, `How much longer are you going to be raising this
stuff? Are you going to sell any land for development? What are you
going to do next?'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to keep your head down and keep on truckin' when
you're asked the same questions all the time.'' Cigarette companies
say they'll buy just 618 million pounds of burley and flue-cured
tobacco this year _ the smallest amount this decade. Also expected
to push down demand is the decision by cigarette makers to increase
wholesale prices _ five times last year, including 45 cents a pack
in November, the largest boost ever.
</P>
<P>
   The continued decline in demand for tobacco could quite
literally change the agricultural landscape in some Southern
states.
</P>
<P>
   There has been talk about cigarette companies contracting
directly with growers, allowing farmers to sell their quotas or
eliminating the tobacco program and its price supports. If direct
contracts take the place of auctions, cigarette makers may find an
economy of scale by turning to larger operations at the expense of
small family farms.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, production may shift to flatter land in the
eastern part of the state, where large farms aren't limited by the
Appalachian Mountains. Similarly in Kentucky, the rugged land in
the central and eastern parts of the state ultimately may yield to
friendlier landscape to the west.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to farm in central Kentucky and make a decent
living, you've got to farm tobacco,'' said Donald Mitchell, who
grows about 53 acres just outside Lexington.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of these changes is last year's legal settlement
between 46 state attorneys general and Big Tobacco _ and the threat
of still more litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The national settlement, which some experts said might be
undermined by the federal lawsuit, came after legal challenges in
four states that resulted in separate settlements totaling about
$40 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris Inc. _ the nation's largest tobacco company and
maker of Marlboro, Virginia Slims, Basic and Cambridge _ noted in
its annual report that it faces 500 domestic smoking suits from
individuals as of March 1. There were 185 at the end of 1996.
International sales are growing, but so are foreign lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The company recorded total pretax charges of $4.6 billion for
1998 and 1997 to accrue for its share of the tobacco settlement.
The annual report warned investors ``it is possible that the
company's business ... could be materially affected by an
unfavorable outcome or settlement of certain pending litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken it's toll,'' West said. ``It makes you wonder how
important tobacco will be in the future.'' Southern farmers from
Georgia
</P>
<P>
   to Virginia grow more than 90 percent of the nation's tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   From 1992 to 1997, the number of U.S. tobacco farms fell 27
percent. In 1954, there were 512,000 domestic tobacco farms. Today,
there are only 90,000 _ half of them in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina, which grows flue-cured tobacco on many
commercial farms, produces more leaf than any other state _ 320,000
acres, or nearly 38 percent of the U.S. total.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky depends on tobacco even more. On average, tobacco has
accounted for nearly half the state's crop values, producing nearly
$825 million annually. ``You're probably going to see a 20
(percent) to 25 percent long-term decline in demand due to the
settlement,'' predicted Will Snell, a tobacco expert at the
University of Kentucky. ``Tobacco will remain a viable enterprise
in the state but for a lot fewer people.'' For generations, picking
burley by hand has been embedded in Kentucky culture. Henry West
grows 15 acres in low spots between rocky hills an hour south of
Lexington, just like his father and grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Burley doesn't lend itself to the mechanization that has helped
make the harvest easier in North Carolina. Almost anybody who farms
here grows at least a small tobacco patch, squeezing dollars out of
backyard plots the same way suburban teen-agers turn to
baby-sitting or cutting the neighbor's grass. Thousands of farmers
tend 5-acre fields on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by a federal program that dictates how much tobacco a
farmer can grow and guarantees a minimum price at auction, Kentucky
burley can fetch up to $4,000 an acre.
</P>
<P>
   ``No crop generates the money per acre that tobacco does,'' West
said. ``Tobacco is the only cash crop I grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the health settlement, Big Tobacco set aside $5.15
billion to compensate growers in 13 states. The trust fund will be
financed by contributions over 12 years by Philip Morris, R.J.
Reynolds Tobacco Co., Lorillard Tobacco Co. and Brown &AMP; Williamson
Tobacco Corp. West is one of six farmers on a state board that
decides how Kentucky will parse its $1.5 billion. Outside of
tobacco, there aren't many farming options in Kentucky. There's
little flatland for livestock feed. The state lacks huge produce
processing plants. West and his neighbors have tried growing
tomatoes, cucumbers, green beans. But the payoff paled compared
with the subsidized value of tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we had tomatoes, everybody had tomatoes,'' West said. In
Garrard County where West farms, bluebells grow on the shoulders of
winding country roads. Cattle and horses graze. Land speculators,
usually developers aching for the chance to build 100-home
subdivisions, snatch up available farm land. West stores most of
his tobacco in a charcoal-colored barn his father built in the
1930s. He sowed seeds in March into square Styrofoam containers
that float in water. Two months later, West spent a week
transplanting the seeds in tilled ground the color of cinnamon.
</P>
<P>
   In August and September, West, his two grown daughters, son,
wife and about 10 hired hands picked burley. Through slots in
wooden sticks, they weaved tobacco leaves, then loaded them on
wagons and hoisted the leaves into curing barns.
</P>
<P>
   The rafters will be emptied this month and next for auctions
that open just before Thanksgiving. The leaves will be tied off in
100-pound bales. Tips from the plant will command the highest
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard life,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   He hired a tenant farmer five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking to slow down a little bit,'' West said. ``I
wanted to play a little golf. There's more to life than standing in
a tobacco patch.''
</P>
<P>
   None of his children has an interest in tobacco farming, and the
family tradition may end with him _ an exit quickened by the
political unpopularity of tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't smoke and I don't chew,'' West said. ``There's not a
reasonable American that doesn't understand that there's some
problems with smoking. But as long as it's legal, it's a pure
economic situation with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Manuel writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 1427EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991009.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-PITT-STADIUM-NYT &LR;      10-09 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PITT-STADIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITT STADIUM, AT 74, IS PUT ON THE AUCTION BLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MIKE ROSENWALD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ With 42 seconds left in the 1982 Sugar Bowl game,
Susan Coyne and her husband sat nervously in the Superdome in New
Orleans as Pittsburgh, their beloved alma mater, trailed Georgia by
3 points. They had driven 23 hours and 1,100 miles from Pittsburgh
and did not want to return home disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers had a fourth-and-5 on Georgia's 33-yard line, and
Coach Jackie Sherrill forsook the tying field goal and went for the
victory. Quarterback Dan Marino passed to tight end John Brown over
the middle, and he marched into the end zone for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Coyne has cherished the memory over the years, and she has
thought about it often lately, especially since the university
recently decided to demolish 74-year-old Pitt Stadium. While
forging ahead with plans to share a stadium with the Steelers, the
university is giving fans such as Coyne the chance to savor
football history by auctioning off memorabilia from the stadium,
which will face the wrecking ball in December.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of holding in-person auctions and sales, as has been
done for many stadiums before demolition, the university has set up
a Web site much like other popular online auctions for people to
buy and bid on a variety of relics, ranging from bricks to
locker-room carpet to ticket windows and even the giant scoreboard.
It is believed to be the first such sale of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``After it was decided that Pitt Stadium was coming down, we
knew right away that people would want mementos,'' said Steve
Pederson, the athletic director. ``And we did get flooded with
people who wanted things. This made a lot of sense. The Internet is
a great way to communicate with large numbers of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyne heard about the Web site (www.pittstadium.com), and on it
she came across a painted wooden sign depicting the Panthers'
participation in the 1982 Sugar Bowl. Each item up for bidding has
a picture and a list of previous bids. She saw the high bid was
$150.
</P>
<P>
   Coyne, who lives in Washington, Pa., south of Pittsburgh,
registered with the site and put up a bid for $200. A few days
later, the site e-mailed her, as it does with anyone who is outbid,
and told her she had lost her position as high bidder. She raised
her bid to $300.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the things to bid on, this was the item that was most
special to my husband and I,'' said Coyne, who also bid on another
sign from the 1976 Sugar Bowl. ``It would be nice to have. But
we'll have to wait and see. I keep thinking that I'm going to have
to up my bid. I check every day. So far, so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitt, which also has an abridged paper catalog of items, has
received about 60 bids since the site went up in August, according
to Brian Cavanaugh, the director of licensing and merchandising.
There are 500 registered users to the site, which also accounts for
between 40 and 50 sales transactions a day for less coveted and
abundant mementos such as bricks, bottles of dirt, bathroom sinks,
railings and small pieces of turf.
</P>
<P>
   The associate athletic director Jim Earle is overseeing the
project, and said that officials from other old stadiums told him
similar auctions had earned more than $1 million from nostalgic
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a goal we've set, but we're extremely pleased with
how things are going,'' Earle said. ``The bids have been slower
than sales, but once the season moves forward and we get closer to
the demolition I think we'll see things heat up. It's obvious that
we have made a great piece of history available to a lot of fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Pederson and Earle are curious to see what people will covet.
</P>
<P>
   There is the large window covered with a painted Panther above
Gate A. It is original to the stadium. Bidding opens on it for
$10,000. The opening bid for the entire north end zone turf is
$7,000. A program stand opens at $300.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular item so far has been a sign that lists all of
Pitt's national championships. Bidding opened at $75 and 13 bids
later it was up to $350.
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there is the main scoreboard, which takes
up a good deal of the north end of the stadium. It's only four
years old. Bidding opens at $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a chance someone might want it,'' Pederson
said, only half joking. ``You'd have to have the right place for
it, though.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
