<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Calif., Utah, R.I.)  (mk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Colorado, nominees for governor do not get to choose their
running mates. Rather, at the same time each party holds a primary
to choose its candidate for governor, it holds a separate primary
to pick its candidate for lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   Which means that come November, when the nominees must run as a
pair on the same ticket, everything is not always buddy-buddy.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does a victory on Election Day necessarily improve
relations.
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, relations could hardly be worse between Gov. Bill
Owens and Lt. Gov. Joe Rogers, the first Republican team (if team
is the right word) to be in charge of running Colorado in 24 years.
Since the moment last year when they were first thrown together on
the same ticket, they have hardly spoken _ except to snipe and
spat, much to the embarrassment of fellow Republicans and the
chuckling delight of Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The governor contends that the lieutenant governor is an inept
public official and last week asked the state controller to
investigate his use of state funds for gifts, meals and
long-distance phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   The lieutenant governor, the state's highest-ranking black
office holder, says the governor is too authoritarian about budget
matters, assumes powers he does not legally have and is insensitive
to the needs of others, especially the state's blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Both men talk of the need to get together and thrash things out
_ but continue to thrash each other.
</P>
<P>
   One of their first public breaks occurred early in the 1998
campaign when Owens backed out of a debate with the Democratic
candidate, Gail Schoettler, and infuriated Rogers by ordering him
to fill in. The debate never took place.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the two men tangled when the governor called a summit on
youth violence after the shootings at Columbine High School and
scheduled it to take place during the week when Colorado blacks
traditionally commemorate the freeing of American slaves. Rogers
said the governor was being insensitive and owed the black
community an apology. Owens refused.
</P>
<P>
   Still later, the two men tangled when Colorado's secretary of
state, Vikki Buckley, died and Rogers tried to postpone a task
force meeting on child welfare so he could assist the Buckley
family with funeral arrangements. The governor ordered the meeting
to be held as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the two men have feuded over whether the governor
can order the lieutenant governor's employees to undergo the same
criminal background checks he requires for his own staff.
</P>
<P>
   The governor insists he can. And when a Rogers employee refused
to submit to a check, he held up her pay.
</P>
<P>
   She filed suit _ with the lieutenant governor's blessings.
</P>
<P>
   Which led the governor to raise still another question about the
lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   Why, he asked last week, did the state police decide not to
ticket a Rogers aide they caught driving 103 mph in a state car _
with Rogers riding in the passenger seat?
</P>
<P>
   Strictly a state police decision, Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   Whereupon the governor took it upon himself to suspend the aide
for a week without pay.
</P>
<P>
   Of Gay Marriages, Religion and Speech
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has one of the nation's largest and most
politically active gay and lesbian communities. So no issue is
hotter in that city at the moment than a statewide initiative to be
voted on in 2000 that would bar the state from recognizing gay or
lesbian marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Gay men and lesbians all over the country are looking to San
Francisco's gay men and lesbians to lead the fight to defeat the
initiative, figuring that a victory in the nation's biggest state
would give a huge lift to efforts to beat back similar restrictive
measures elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of traditional marriage also see the California vote
as crucial to their struggle and likewise are girding for the fight
and looking for a signal victory. Among the most outspoken of them
are members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, the
Mormons.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some gay and lesbian leaders say Mormon support for the
California initiative is so outspoken and organized that it goes
well beyond what is permitted by federal laws regulating political
activity by tax-exempt organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders disagree. They insist that church members are
doing no more than exercising their constitutional right of free
speech as they urge passage of the measure that, in effect, would
define marriage in California as strictly a one-man, one-woman
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, last week the city's board of supervisors
went along with the wishes of gay and lesbian leaders and, on a
unanimous vote, passed a resolution calling on the IRS to look into
whether the church was violating federal laws that forbid churches
to engage in ``substantial lobbying or political activity.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the resolution, sponsored by Supervisor Mark Leno,
who is gay, some church members have told city officials that the
church has set quotas for church members' donations to the
initiative cause.
</P>
<P>
   One of the nation's most prominent Mormons, Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-
Utah, happened to be in San Francisco pushing his quest for the
Republican presidential nomination when the resolution was passed.
</P>
<P>
   He called the board's action ``idiotic, bigoted and
prejudiced.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It flies in the face of free-speech rights almost as much as
anything I've ever seen,'' he said. ``If that type of philosophy
became the norm, that almost means nobody affiliated with any
religion would have a right to talk freely.''
</P>
<P>
   A Pre-Emptive Strike Pays Off in the Polls
</P>
<P>
   Remember Mayor Lincoln Chafee of Warwick, R.I., a Republican who
is running to replace his father, John Chafee, in the U.S. Senate?
</P>
<P>
   Early on in his campaign, before anyone had even bothered to
ask, he confessed that in his younger days he smoked some pot and
snorted a bit of cocaine. The way he figured it, by coming clean up
front, he could ``inoculate'' himself against any embarrassing
questions that might come at him down the road and, at the same
time, garner a few extra votes for being honest and forthright.
</P>
<P>
   It appears he has.
</P>
<P>
   A new Brown University poll puts the mayor in a dead heat with
the leading Democratic candidate, Rep. Bob Weygand, who represents
the 2nd Congressional District in western Rhode Island. Weygand led
by eight points in a June poll.
</P>
<P>
   The new poll also has Chafee a couple of points ahead of the
independent candidate in the contest, former Attorney General
Arlene Violet. She led him by a couple of points in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``People appreciate a politician who is straight-shooting on
tough issues _ as long as the bad behavior was in your past,'' says
the director of the poll, Darrell West.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
