<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-FLEURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEURY CAN PASS, TOO, IN THE STYLE OF GRETSKY 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By   JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Theo Fleury is primarily known as a goal scorer. But
Friday night at Madison Square Garden, Fleury showed just how well
he can pass the puck, too.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury was so effective in the Rangers' 3-1 victory over the
Carolina Hurricanes _ their first triumph of the season _ that
Rangers Coach John Muckler had to restrain himself from comparing
Fleury to Wayne Gretzky, indisputably the greatest passer in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theo really sees the ice,'' Muckler said. ``He's really a
super passer. He did that in Calgary when he was playing against
Edmonton. Those little short passes he makes under pressure, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Muckler was speaking after Fleury had scored his first goal in a
Rangers' uniform. And that came after Fleury had set up the first
two scores with beautiful feeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people probably don't know how good he passes the
puck,'' said center Petr Nedved, who figures to reap the benefits
of Fleury's passes all season.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury is a prolific scorer, but he is definitely not
one-dimensional.
</P>
<P>
   He scored 40 goals last season. The diminutive 5-foot-6 right
wing has scored 40 or more goals four times in his career, which is
entering its 12th year. In 810 National Hockey League games, Fleury
has 375 goals.
</P>
<P>
   But he also has 482 assists.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Fleury can pass the puck, too. It's just that
his passing ability is usually overshadowed by his scoring touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sometimes that's been the case,'' said Fleury, who
often was Calgary's only true scoring threat in his later years
with the Flames. ``But I'm playing with two shooters now, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Friday, however, those two shooters _ Nedved and Adam
Graves _had not scored a point. Friday night, the line broke out.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury (a goal and two assists), Nedved (three assists) and
Graves (power-play goal plus an assist) combined for 8 points.
Nedved and Graves were good. Fleury was great.
</P>
<P>
   You could almost hear Rangers President Neil Smith heave a sigh
of relief.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, this was the Fleury that Smith spent $28
million for over the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury admitted late Friday night he had been putting pressure
on himself to produce. Perhaps that was one reason he did not tally
a point in the Rangers' first three games. It also could have been
a reason why the Rangers went 0 for their first 15 on the power
play, while scoring a goal a game over their first three outings,
until they exploded for three goals (including one on the power
play) on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   And Fleury had a hand in each.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theo took a lot of pressure off himself playing the game he
played,'' Muckler said. ``He was outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleury was artistic, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a world-class player and a world-class talent,'' Graves
said. ``Those are things you can't teach. He can do basically
everything. When you're playing with him, you just try to give him
the puck and go to the net.''
</P>
<P>
   And Fleury will usually find you, if he doesn't find the net
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does everything,'' Rangers Captain Brian Leetch said.
``That's the type of player he is. He's been one of the top five,
six or seven forwards in the league for a long time. And he
competes hard, too. He's got the elite skills.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Fleury was buoyant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I told you guys,'' Fleury said late Friday night. ``It
was just a matter of time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
