<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991009.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1804 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSHRECORD10-COX     10-09 2398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSHRECORD10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Supporters say Bush's record rosy; critics
 &HT;    find many gaps
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ George W. Bush's critics like to say he has a habit
of jumping in front of a parade as it nears the reviewing stand.
</P>
<P>
   His friends say he is a natural consensus builder, unusually
adept at giving people what they want.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, supporters and detractors agree that the Texas
governor has not been a trailblazer, but rather a cautious steward
who has picked his fights carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is only now beginning to lay out specific proposals for
what he would do as president. Last week, for the second straight
week, Bush spiced his campaign speeches with criticism of
Republicans in Congress for lacking compassion. The tactic has
puzzled some Republicans since so many members of Congress support
his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   But the candidate's willingness, even eagerness, to separate
himself from other leaders of his party should be no surprise. It
illustrates the way he has governed Texas for the last five years.
Bush has generally avoided pitched battles with the
Democratic-controlled Texas Senate, sometimes parting ways with his
own party. He also has found ways to salvage public relations
victories from legislative defeats, most notably on a failed tax
plan in 1997, and made the most of changes that were under way
before he took office, particularly in the areas of education and
criminal justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has shown remarkable shrewdness for a political newcomer,''
said Elspeth Rostow, former dean of the Lyndon B. Johnson School of
Public Affairs at the University of Texas. ``It hasn't yielded any
tremendous policy breakthroughs. It's more that he has taken
advantage of things already under way.'' Things like the booming
Texas economy, the billions of dollars in state budget surplus,
decreasing crime and an improving educational performance.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's supporters look at this rosy picture and conclude he is
doing something right.
</P>
<P>
   His critics look at the same set of facts and lament that, even
in flush economic times, Texas remains on the bottom rung in many
measures of education, the quality of its environment and he
availability of health care for children. They see in Bush's tenure
as governor a bushel of missed opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   But a Texas governor's ability to act on such opportunities is
restricted because the office lacks many of the formal powers that
are given to governors in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Responsibility for the state's budget, for example, rests
primarily with the Legislature. Bush also has no appointed Cabinet
and does not name judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's technically a weak governor system, which means the
governor has to pull strings to get things done,'' Rostow said.
``That includes extending his right hand in fellowship to the
Democratic side.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has tended to sketch broad themes _ changing welfare,
improving education, limiting awards in civil lawsuits, overhauling
the juvenile justice system _ while leaving the details to others.
Here's a look at Bush's record on a number of key issues that are
likely to arise in his campaign for president:
</P>
<P>
   TAXES
</P>
<P>
   In campaign speeches, Bush claims credit for the two largest tax
cuts in Texas history _ nearly $3 billion worththat he says he
``fought for and signed.''
</P>
<P>
   Reggie James, director of the Southwest Regional Consumers
Union, said the reductions provided ``illusory benefits for the
masses.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, anti-tax groups complain that a $1 billion property tax
cut in 1997 was all but eliminated when local authorities increased
property appraisals and tax rates in response. A recent study found
a similar trend after this year's tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The critics say that the tax cut disappeared, and maybe taxes
went up for some people,'' said Jim Oliver, Bush's former budget
adviser. ``But without him, they would have been even higher.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's cuts included more property tax relief, some sales
tax reductions and a research and development credit for business.
</P>
<P>
   His boldest legislative proposal was killed by his own party. In
1997 he pushed a measure to shift the financing of public schools
away from local property taxes. That would have lowered property
taxes, but the state sales tax would have risen. Doctors, lawyers,
architects, consultants and other service providers would have
faced a new business tax.
</P>
<P>
   Republican opposition killed the plan, and lawmakers gave the
governor the $1 billion property tax cut instead. James credits
Bush for raising the right question in 1997: Was the allocation of
state taxes fair?
</P>
<P>
   But he faults Bush for taking a politically tepid stand this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to have surpluses forever,'' James said, ``and
he passed up the chance to set up a rainy day fund or to do
something about what we know will drive costs in future years _ our
aging population and our increasing school population.''
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION
</P>
<P>
   Scores on standardized tests for elementary school students have
taken a leap forward during Bush's administration. This is
especially true of African-American and Hispanic children.
</P>
<P>
   Bush backed tougher standards in math, English and science in
1995, his first legislative session. Demonstrating bipartisan
appeal, he signed the bill in a Democratic lawmaker's district.
</P>
<P>
   The governor this year signed a Democratic-backed $3,000 pay
raise for public school teachers and won approval of a plan to end
so-called social promotion, the practice of advancing
schoolchildren to the next grade regardless of their performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves credit for signing (the salary increase). He could
have vetoed it,'' said John Cole, president of the Texas Federation
of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Texas' public schools are among the worst. They ranked
46th in SAT scores in 1999; and dropout rates, while in decline the
past 10 years, are still distressingly high among minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Cole and others point out that Bush also is taking credit for
educational reformsdevised under his predecessors, including
setting academic standards and establishing regular testing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also supports vouchers, which would give public money to
parents to pay for their children's private education.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush could not persuade the Legislature to go along with his
proposal this year. ``I said, `Let's try it in Texas. Let's just
see if it works,''' the governor said. ``I tried to tie it to an
accountability system.''
</P>
<P>
   While the opposition was mainly Democrats, social conservatives
objected to some provisions of the voucher proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagle Forum, a conservative family group, opposed what it
considers onerous state requirements, including the testing of
voucher recipients.
</P>
<P>
   ``His bill would have taken away the freedoms of a private
school,'' said Cathie Adams, director of the Eagle Forum in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   CRIME
</P>
<P>
   Death penalty opponents and some civil libertarians cringe when
they talk about Bush's record, which includes lowering the age at
which children may be tried as adults and sending an increasing
number of convicts to their deaths. The governor also vetoed a
bill, passed without dissent by Texas lawmakers, that would have
guaranteed a lawyer for indigent defendants within 20 days of their
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   When the Texas Senate passed legislation to bar the execution of
mentally retarded prisoners, Bush announced his opposition and said
juries should retain that decision-making authority. The bill died
in the state House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's law and order approach has been extremely popular, and he
has signed 100 death warrants. Explaining his support for the death
penalty, Bush invokes compassionate conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support the death penalty because I think it prevents people
from killing people,'' he said recently in Georgia. ``That's
compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Harrington, executive director of the Texas Civil Rights
Project, said the governor has done nothing to ensure the death
penalty is administered fairly.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the whole issue of DNA testing, what you need is time _
and he doesn't give anybody time at all,'' Harrington said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I review every case,'' Bush countered. ``I always ask if there
are any outstanding appeals. I always ask if the courts have vetted
all the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   He has commuted one death sentence (when the evidence suggested
the convicted killer was in another state), and he allowed Karla
Faye Tucker, a pickax murderer who became an evangelical Christian
in prison, to die, despite the protests of Christian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The crime rate has dropped during his administration, although
not as quickly as the national crime rate. More prisoners are in
Texas prison facilities, and the governor has claimed a share of
the credit.
</P>
<P>
   But the rate of crime fell more steeply in Texas during the
administration of Democrat Ann Richards, whom Bush defeated in
1994. The bulk of new prison construction had begun and criminal
penalties for many violent crimes had been strengthened before Bush
took office.
</P>
<P>
   The parole rate also dropped sharply under Richards.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS
</P>
<P>
   The recent killings in a Texas church refocused attention on
Bush's opposition to most gun control measures. (Bush has more
recently endorsed a national instant background check for sales at
gun shows.)
</P>
<P>
   He signed a bill, over objections of many Texas police chiefs,
allowing Texans with permits to carry concealed weapons. ``I don't
imagine that any governor could have gone against the Legislature
on concealed weapons,'' Rostow said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he outlawed lawsuits by local governments against gun
manufacturers _ although no Texas municipality was known to be
considering such a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION
</P>
<P>
   Bush comes under attack from both sides on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   He incurred the wrath of anti-abortion leaders this year when he
declared that abortion would not be a litmus test in his choice for
vice presidential running mate or judgeships.
</P>
<P>
   Along with most other Republican presidential candidates, he has
sought to play down the abortion issue.
</P>
<P>
   But the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League
has tried to remind voters in key primary states that Bush has a
long record of opposing abortion rights, noting 16 measures he has
signed as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, he signed a bill requiring that parents be
notified before minor children have abortions. The bill also
requires a 48-hour waiting period for young women.
</P>
<P>
   But the Eagle Forum's Adams said Bush ``has been very quiet'' on
abortion. ``He should be saying, `I am going to defend innocent
life,''' she said. ``Everything short of that is appeasement.''
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRONMENT
</P>
<P>
   Texas' industries emit more toxic pollutants than those of any
other state. The state's pollution has worsened through the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   But on a recent campaign trip in New Hampshire, Bush proclaimed,
``I'm for clean air and clean water and have a record in Texas to
prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many environmental activists are skeptical, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a poor record,'' said Tom Smith, director of
the Texas chapter of Public Citizen. ``He had the opportunity to
hit a home run in environmental protection, and instead he got to
first base.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush signed two bills into law this year dealing with emissions
from utilities and other industrial plants that were exempted from
the state's anti-pollution laws.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than force the companies that own older facilities to
reduce their emissions, Bush supported a voluntary program.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hammond, chairman of the Texas Association of Business and
Chambers of Commerce, praised Bush for achieving a balance between
``a clean environment, which we all want, and jobs. If it had been
more draconian, Texas definitely would have lost jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   But Smith said the proposal that became law essentially was
written by industry. Worse, he and other environmentalists say,
Bush let several years pass before taking any action.
</P>
<P>
   The other measure Bush signed, adopted as part of a law that
deregulates electric utilities, requires older electric plants to
cut emissions by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush also had been for voluntary compliance and accepted the
tougher language only after House Democrats insisted on it.
</P>
<P>
   CIVIL RIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   Bush never took a position on a hate crimes bill spawned by the
case of James Byrd Jr., a black Texan dragged to his death behind a
pickup truck in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The bill never made it out of the Legislature, sparing Bush from
having to make a decision on a sensitive issue just before he began
his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He signed a bill guaranteeing admission into a state college or
university for the top 10 percent of high school graduates from
every Texas school, regardless of race or ethnicity. Supporters of
minority preferences devised the plan in response to challenges to
affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   On one matter, even Bush's critics credit him with standing
tall: ``When a lot of Republicans were engaging in immigrant
bashing, I was really proud of George Bush when he stood up and
said, `That's not how we play the game,''' said James of the
Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH CARE
</P>
<P>
   Texas' managed care reform of 1997 is serving as a model for
bipartisan legislation under consideration in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides touted that recently when President Clinton mocked
Bush's ``compassionate conservatism'' as being light on compassion
and heavy on conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush didn't support a major reform _ allowing Texans to sue
HMOs. He allowed it to become law without his signature, having
vetoed a managed care bill two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   There have been just a handful of lawsuits so far, said Kim
Ross, a lobbyist with the Texas Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he was in the position where he had supported tort reform,
so he felt he couldn't sign a bill that created a new class of
lawsuits,'' Ross said. ``To his credit, he allowed it to become law
and said he would be watching.''
</P>
<P>
   On children's health care, lawmakers decided Bush was too stingy
when he proposed an insurance plan that set eligibility at a
maximum of 150 percent of the poverty line. Critics said his plan
would have ignored 200,000 children. Legislators set the limit at
200 percent of the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
