<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1806 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ALA-LOTTERY10-COX     10-09 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALA-LOTTERY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alabama vote on lotter will test slipping Christian clout
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Christian clout in Alabama ain't what it used
to be.
</P>
<P>
   Evangelical Gov. Fob James was ousted 11 months ago, a bill that
would have expanded Sunday alcohol sales snuck through the
Legislature this year, and, after a decade of waiting, voters
finally will get a chance to approve a state lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we've lost a great deal with the Legislature this time
from a church perspective or a religious perspective. If we hadn't,
this wouldn't even be on the ballot,'' said Joe Bob Mizzell,
director of Christian ethics for the Alabama Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   For the state's Christian soldiers, the next battle is Tuesday.
The fight is over Amendment 1, a proposed change to Alabama's 1901
constitution. If approved, the referendum would authorize a
Georgia-style education lottery that would pay for HOPE
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   The largest Christian group in the state, the Alabama Baptist
Convention, claims 3,100 churches and 1.1 million members. With
help from other denominations, the socially conservative Baptist
group has helped closed the gap on lottery advocates.
</P>
<P>
   One poll puts lottery support at just 51 percent after years of
riding support at higher rates. Another poll puts support at 54
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But just like in 1992 _ when Georgia churches narrowed the lead
of lottery supporters _ the surge may be too little, too late. As
in Georgia, where Christian conservatives failed to elect
Republican Guy Millner over Democrat Roy Barnes as governor last
year, Alabama's religious right is behind in rallying votes for
lottery opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be an indication of Alabama's movement to more of a
secular state,'' said William Stewart, a political scientist at the
University of Alabama. ``People aren't taking the lead from their
Protestant church leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving around Tuscaloosa, Stewart sees church marquee after
marquee deriding the lottery. But gone are the days, he said, when
Alabama preachers would make pronouncements and the flock would
follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of Baptists on the rolls, but they're not
taking their cues from the religious leaders,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery opponents claim momentum on the strength of a University
of South Alabama poll taken in September that shows 51 percent of
likely voters favor the amendment. In August, the same poll showed
61 percent favored the measure. But pollster Keith Nicholls said
support actually may be higher because opponents are framing
gambling as immoral.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be more of a social desirability issue than a
political issue,'' Nicholls said. ``You may favor the lottery, but
you're not going to tell that to someone on the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition of Alabama had planned to distribute
thousands of anti-lottery voters guides this weekend. But rather
than subject itself to a state law that requires groups spending
more than $1,000 on an election to disclose contributors, the
Christian Coalition backed off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks in the churches know where we stand,'' said John Giles,
president of the Alabama Christian Coalition and a former candidate
for lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Don Siegelman, the Democrat who ousted James in November,
ran almost exclusively on the issue of creating a state lottery
modeled after the Georgia lottery. Since 1993, Alabama residents
have spent more than $400 million on Georgia's lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama has one of the country's lowest tax burdens and one of
the most underfunded school systems. The state is surrounded by
lotteries in Georgia, Florida and Louisiana along with casinos in
Mississippi and New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Siegelman projects a state lottery would churn out $150 million
a year for college scholarships, a pre-kindergarten program and
school computers. As in Georgia, HOPE scholarships would pay for
tuition at state schools.
</P>
<P>
   The majority-black electorate in Birmingham could help pass the
lottery the same way it swept Siegelman into office. In November,
nine of every 10 black voters cast ballots for Siegelman.
</P>
<P>
   Though black politicians aggressively are backing the lottery,
the black clergy opposes the amendment, Mizzell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fearful that a lot of ministers are not talking about it
or their congregation is not listening to them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like easy money to raise revenue for issues they care
about,'' said Phillip Cook, a Duke University economist whose
lottery research was incorporated into the National Gambling Impact
Study Commission report, which urged curbs on gaming. ``Some people
are reluctant to raise taxes unless the lottery option has been
explored.''
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire started the nation's first lottery in 1964. Today,
37 states and the District of Columbia operate lotteries.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, South Carolina voters get their chance at a lottery
referendum. State legislatures in North Carolina and Tennessee have
debated the issue and are watching the Alabama vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly believe there's enough revenue to go around,''
said David Gale, executive director of the North American
Association of State and Provincial Lotteries. ``You can see that
in areas where there are adjoining states with lotteries.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Northeast, 11 contiguous states operate profitable games.
</P>
<P>
   In the South from Texas to Virginia, money still gushes into
lotteries _ but slower than before. Over the past six years, sales
have flattened or declined in five of six Southern lotteries. Only
Georgia's ticket sales have increased every year since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a social cost, say Alabama ministers, who will be
pushing an anti-lottery message from their pulpits this weekend.
Poor people will gamble their food money. An already regressive tax
system in the state will get even worse.
</P>
<P>
   Even the socially moderate United Methodist Church has joined
the anti-lottery crusade. Rev. Bill Morgan, the district
superintendent who supervises 50 of North Alabama's largest
churches, said there are those in his congregations who will vote
for the lottery ``knowing it's not a good thing'' socially but
perhaps the only way to raise cash for higher education.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a historical reluctance to raise taxes for anything,''
he said. ``Methodists who vote for it will be saying it's the
lesser of two evils.''
</P>
<P>
   But only 15 percent of state voters consider the lottery immoral
or sinful, which works against religious-based opponents, said
Gerald Johnson, pollster for the Alabama Education Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly is an uphill struggle to oppose the education
lottery in Alabama,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
