<HEADLINE>
SIR NIGEL BROACKES, 65, BRITISH ENTREPRENEUR AND DEVELOPER 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Sir Nigel Broackes, a real estate developer who
controlled the Ritz Hotel in London as chairman of Trafalgar House
and was one of Britain's most successful young entrepreneurs during
the 1960s and '70s, died Sept. 28. He was 65 and lived in
Oxfordshire.
</P>
<P>
   His relatives described the cause of death only as a short
illness.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 24, Broackes, the son of a Russian lawyer who died
when Nigel was 8, became the managing director of Trafalgar House,
a small holding company that at the time had little more than an
assortment of investment properties.
</P>
<P>
   But Broackes, depicted in the company's prospectus as ``almost
29'' when Trafalgar House first sold shares of the company to the
public in 1963, had grand ambitions. In short order, he managed to
acquire several construction and engineering companies, giving him
a reputation as a shrewd businessman and spirited entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, Broackes brought in Victor Mathews, who would later
become instrumental in turning Trafalgar House into a well-known
diversified conglomerate. By age 35, Broackes had become the
chairman of Trafalgar House and with the advice of Mathews began
acquiring some of Britain's most prized properties. In 1975,
Broackes bought the Ritz Hotel in central London for 2.7 million
pounds. He also bought the Cunard shipping fleet, giving him
control of the QE2.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, Broackes made a bid for the troubled Beaverbrook
Newspaper group, which owned some of Britain's most well-read
newspapers: The Daily Express, The Sunday Express and The Evening
Standard.
</P>
<P>
   The move to buy the newspaper company was the brainchild of
Mathews, who became chief executive of Trafalgar House and was 14
years older than Broackes. While Mathews was instrumental in the
company's growth, the relationship between Broackes and Mathews
soon became strained.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Broackes published an autobiography in 1981 with
critical references to Mathews, the newspaper interests were spun
off and Mathews left Trafalgar House to head them.
</P>
<P>
   However, his departure also signaled the beginning of a downturn
for Trafalgar House. Broackes made an unsuccessful and embarrassing
hostile takeover bid for Peninsular &AMP; Oriental Steam Navigation
Co., the British cruise-line operator.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Broackes became the chairman of London Docklands
Development Corp. redeveloping the Docklands area, which had become
run-down after the docks were closed. He then gave up active
management of Trafalgar House.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Broackes returned to Trafalgar House, but the company
had already lost focus and had begun a steady decline. By 1992 the
company reported pretax losses of 30.3 million pounds. Toward the
end of the 1980s the company had been embarrassed by reports of
eccentric accounting practices. Broackes was forced into early
retirement in 1992 when Hong Kong Land bought 15 percent of
Trafalgar House as part of a reorganization of the management.
Trafalgar House has subsequently been acquired by Kvaerner.
</P>
<P>
   Broackes was knighted in 1984 for his work redeveloping the
Docklands.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Joyce, died in 1993. He is survived by two sons,
Justin and Simon, and a daughter, Vicky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
