<HEADER>
A1808 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-GETEVEN-GIULIANI-N     10-09 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GETEVEN-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMON PERCEPTION: THE MAYOR WILL GET YOU FOR THAT
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 BY BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before New York's major cultural institutions came
out against Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's attack on the Brooklyn Museum
of Art, museum directors fretted that the mayor would get angry at
them and then he would get even.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor tends to take those who disagree with him as enemies
to be punished,'' Martin McLaughlin, a lobbyist for the cultural
institutions, wrote in an e-mail circulated among museum directors.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, New Yorkers traveling by subway last weekend to the
Brooklyn Museum to see ``Sensation,'' the exhibition that is the
object of Giuliani's ire, believed they were targets of mayoral
punishment. They complained that train service was suspended as
part of a City Hall plot to torpedo the exhibition. Subway repairs,
however, had been scheduled for months by the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority, which the mayor does not directly
control.
</P>
<P>
   Paranoia over the Brooklyn Museum is a reminder that after
nearly six years in office, Giuliani's reputation for retribution
has grown to near-mythic proportions, triggering tremulous
hand-wringing among those who contemplate crossing him and
convincing many New Yorkers that he is out to get them, even when
he is not.
</P>
<P>
   Is this any way to run a city? Does Giuliani possess a tactical
genius that finally makes America's largest city governable or does
he suffer from a tragic flaw that may one day bring him down?
</P>
<P>
   The mayor would not comment last week on these questions, but he
has said in the past that he ``does not really care'' whether New
Yorkers like him, so long as they perceive that the city is
becoming a better place to live.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many people whose livelihoods depend on City Hall say they
are growing weary of the mayor's get-even act, even as they concede
that New York is safer, cleaner and more livable than it was before
Giuliani was elected. These grumblers, who, out of fear, demand
anonymity, include builders, directors of nonprofit agencies and
business leaders of nearly every stripe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intimidation is his full-time operating style,'' said a
prominent businessman who says he likes the mayor and raises money
for him, but is afraid to be even mildly critical of him in public.
</P>
<P>
   The self-appointed spokesman for this cowed and cowering camp is
former Mayor Ed Koch, a Democrat who says he twice voted for
Giuliani, a Republican, but has since come to regard the mayor as a
bully.
</P>
<P>
   Koch feels so strongly about what he calls the mayor's
``despotic'' qualities that this year he wrote a book, ``Giuliani,
Nasty Man,'' to explain his contention that the mayor's penchant
for ``disemboweling'' his opponents is approaching the point of
``Greek tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His nastiness is causing his self-destruction,'' Koch said.
</P>
<P>
   By most measures, though, the mayor is not self-destructing.
Polls over the past several years have found that Giuliani's
aggressive style is a key to his political appeal. Although a
recent poll in the Daily News said most New Yorkers did not support
Giuliani's threats to cut city funds for the Brooklyn Museum, the
mayor generally remains popular, and his political advisers have
said that his position on the museum is good politics because it
shows resolve.
</P>
<P>
   In his presumed campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton for the
U.S. Senate, his advisers have said, Giuliani's tough leadership
skills will be a central part of his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the merits of his governing style, specialists in New
York City history generally agree that Giuliani has outdone all his
recent predecessors when it comes to striking fear into the hearts
of those who do business with City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   No other New York mayor since World War II has ``terrified'' so
many New Yorkers in so many walks of life, said Mike Wallace, a
professor of history at John Jay College and co-author of
``Gotham'' (Oxford University Press, 1999), a Pulitzer
Prize-winning history of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``He casts his net so broadly,'' Wallace said. ``I don't think
it is fair to characterize it as personal vindictiveness. What he
is doing is very interesting from a historical point of view.
Machiavelli said it is better for a leader to be feared than loved.
I think he intends for people to be scared because he thinks that
this is one way to achieve the social order that is beneficial for
the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back over 60 years of New York mayors, Wallace said that
Fiorello La Guardia, whom Giuliani has often called his role model,
was probably the only individual who could fairly be described as a
``holy terror.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But La Guardia tended to punish only people inside his
administration,'' Wallace said. ``He kept score as most politicians
do, but nothing on the order of Mr. Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
