<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1809 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-GETEVEN-GIULIANI-2     10-09 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GETEVEN-GIULIANI-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: ... Mr. Giuliani.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wallace said that Koch also was known to hold political grudges,
but not to the extent of ``casting a pall of concern'' across the
city, which, he said, Giuliani has done.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Calvin O. Butts III, pastor of Abyssinian Baptist
Church and a leader in Harlem, said he is ``one of those who have
crossed the mayor and suffered the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Early last year, Butts called Giuliani a ``racist'' whose
policies were moving the city toward ``a fascist state.'' The
minister has since retreated from those remarks and made peace with
the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say the minister's words infuriated Giuliani and
triggered 18 months of City Hall delays at a commercial development
on 125th Street, which is being built, in part, by Butts'
Abyssinian Development Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was instant, naked retaliation,'' said a state official
familiar with the project. ``Without question, it is the way City
Hall works.''
</P>
<P>
   The city has said it delayed the project out of concern for
smaller retailers in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``People of good will in many businesses and agencies are afraid
to speak their mind,'' Butts said. ``That is not the kind of
climate in which people should have to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Fear of Giuliani's bite is so pervasive that in many cases he
doesn't even have to bark to keep his critics silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a self-fulfilling prophecy at work here,'' said
Raymond D. Horton, a professor at Columbia University Business
School and the former president of the Citizen's Budget Commission,
an independent watchdog agency that, under Horton's watch,
infuriated the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   In apparent retaliation for years of criticism, the mayor's
office tried in 1997 to undermine Horton's agency by urging
investment bankers not to buy tickets for a fund-raising dinner
that accounted for nearly a third of the commission's annual
budget. Instead of caving in to pressure, Horton said, he chose to
fight back.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our case, it turned out to be a public relations disaster
for the mayor,'' Horton said. ``We wound up with more donations,
rather than less, and the mayor came out looking like a
troglodyte.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, most people opt for silent tolerance rather than public
confrontation with the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the city's cultural institutions, many of which
are in city-owned buildings or depend on city money for daily
operations, several museum directors said privately that they took
so long to criticize the mayor because they were afraid he would
punish them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can feel the fear and intimidation that is out there
because this is an administration that engages in retribution
constantly,'' said Councilman Stephen DiBrienza, a Brooklyn
Democrat who last year sponsored a homeless shelter bill that the
mayor did not like. In retaliation, Giuliani threatened to _ but
ultimately did not _ put a homeless shelter in DiBrienza's
district.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the mayor's most ardent supporters, business leaders who
say that his achievements in reducing crime and cleaning up the
city are historically significant, are often just as afraid of him
as his harshest critics.
</P>
<P>
   One businessman said developers were afraid to speak ill of the
mayor, even privately, for fear that word would get back to him.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the director of a private nonprofit agency that
depends on the city said that she and dozens of her peers have
concluded that the only way to protect the poor people they serve
is to never say anything in public that the mayor might not like.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shortage of evidence, however, that the mayor's
fear-inducing manner continues to produce results.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, for example, Giuliani used threats to force the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority to adopt a plan to spend $645
million to build a subway link to La Guardia Airport. The mayor
threatened to hold up approval of the entire 5-year capital plan
for the transit authority in the New York region unless the subway
extension was included, said Jeff Zupan, a transportation analyst
for the Regional Plan Authority, a nonprofit planning group.
</P>
<P>
   ``By being insistent, he has gotten his way,'' Zupan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
