<SLUG> BC-FBN-REALIGNMENT10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL realignment will result in both winners and losers
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After more than 18 months of debate, the NFL announced
this week that professional football would return to Houston. NFL
owners also passed a resolution to realign the league into eight
divisions of four teams each, when the Houston team begins play in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next year-and-a-half, NFL owners will be jockeying for
position, hoping to stay in their current divisions to maintain
long-standing rivalries and sellouts. Houston will play in the AFC,
which means that one existing AFC team will be forced to move to
the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be in for a big fight on realignment,'' said
Buffalo's Ralph Wilson, an original American Football League owner.
``Agreeing on realignment might be tougher than deciding to expand
to Houston or Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   The realignment plan will be completed by May 2001. The NFL
still will be split into an AFC and an NFC, and 12 teams still will
make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely scenario has each team playing 16 games _ six in
its own division, four against other teams from its conference,
four from one division in the other conference and two wild-card
games.
</P>
<P>
   Realignment won't get done without a long, nasty battle. Here's
an early look at the possible winners and losers:
</P>
<P>
   WINNERS
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh Steelers: Team president Dan Rooney says he has been
assured by the NFL that rival Cleveland will remain in the
Steelers' division. Cincinnati and Baltimore also could join
Pittsburgh in the AFC Central, which would be the league's weakest
division this season. The Steelers also will go from five division
opponents to three, leaving more room for variety in its schedule.
   Atlanta Falcons: The Falcons' only true rivalry has been with
the Saints. One proposal has Tampa Bay and Carolina joining Atlanta
and New Orleans in a new division. The teams' close proximity to
each other would create some interesting matchups, and the Falcons
wouldn't have to play San Franciso two games per season. Atlanta
has lost 23 of its past 30 regular-season games against the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay Buccaneers: By joining a new division, Tampa Bay would
leave the rugged NFC Central. The Bucs haven't won in Green Bay
since 1989, and they would avoid those frigid trips to Lambeau
Field and Chicago's Soldier Field.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Seahawks: The Seahawks will have a new stadium in 2002
and possibly a new NFL address. Seattle is the popular pick to
switch conferences, as it doesn't have a natural rival in the AFC
West. The Seahawks could join the NFC West, and a Seattle/San
Franciso series would be an intriguing rivalry. Seahawks coach Mike
Holmgren loves to beat the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   LOSERS
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis Rams: The NFL wasn't happy in 1995 when the Rams left
Los Angeles, the nation's second-largest television market. As
punishment, the Rams didn't receive their cuts from the past two
franchise fees, which owners usually share equally. St. Louis lost
$17 million when Cleveland joined the league and $23 million when
Houston was awarded a team. Another condition in the Rams' move to
St. Louis was that the team would have no vote in future
realignment. Now, the NFL can put the Rams in any division, but St.
Louis probably will stay in the NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Cardinals: The Cardinals probably are headed to the NFC
West, with San Francisco, St. Louis and possibly Seattle, which
would be the one franchise switching conferences. Arizona owner
Bill Bidwell doesn't want to leave the NFC East and lose a
guaranteed sellout for the Dallas game each year. It might take
millions of dollars to persuade him to switch, but Bidwell doesn't
have much leverage after he pulled his team out of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
