u s BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-NYT &LR;      10-09 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAYOFF OVER, ISLES WILL LEARN ABOUT THEMSELVES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eight days between games in the National Hockey League can be
either good or bad. The Islanders will find out Sunday whether they
benefited or were harmed by that long a layoff when they play their
home opener against the Colorado Avalanche at Nassau Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The layoff between the first and second games on their
regular-season schedule provided the Islanders with plenty of time
to fix the things they got wrong in a 4-2 loss to the Tampa Bay
Lightning last Saturday. Practice they did, skating through drills,
working on the power play and learning new systems for two hours
each day.
</P>
<P>
   But, as some players complained, the layoff was just enough time
for the team to lose any momentum it may have had entering the
season. They are not in the regular-season groove they should be in
for the season's second week, and the butterflies that should have
vanished by now will be fluttering in full force on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We waited three weeks for the season to start,'' Islanders
Coach Butch Goring said after practice on Friday. ``Now we've
played one game and we've had to wait again. It's felt like an
eternity.''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran defenseman Rich Pilon said: ``We're very anxious to
play a game. It was good to get some more practice, but now it's
time to get in a groove, get into the normal rhythm of the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some coaches, who may change their lines as often as
every shift during the early part of the season, Goring seems
satisfied with the forward lines and defensive pairings he
assembled during camp. Even after losing the season opener, he has
kept those combinations through the days of practice.
</P>
<P>
   So, when the Islanders take the ice Sunday, the forward lines
should look like this, from left to right: Brad Isbister, Mats
Lindgren and Mariusz Czerkawski; Mark Lawrence, Tim Connolly, Gino
Odjick; Jorgen Jonsson, Claude Lapointe, Olli Jokinen; Mike Watt,
Tony Hrkac, Chris Ferraro. Steve Webb is the extra forward.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive pairings will be: Kenny Jonsson and Zdeno Chara;
Jamie Heward and Jamie Rivers; Rich Pilon and Eric Brewer. A
rookie, Mathieu Biron, is the extra.
</P>
<P>
   If that lineup does not sound formidable, it isn't. The
Islanders played hard against the Lightning, but made mistakes and
paid dearly for them.
</P>
<P>
   Because the season's first game was against the lowly Lightning,
the worst team in the league the past two years, Goring said it was
hard to for him to determine how good or bad his Islanders would
be. The first-year coach said he would have a better idea after
Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
