<SLUG> BC-FBN-DITKA10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Test of mettle for Iron Mike
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ When Mike Ditka was named coach of the New Orleans
Saints more than two years ago, he expected to revive a franchise
that had endured three consecutive losing seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But after two 6-10 finishes, Iron Mike's eminence has been
reduced to tin foil. And the Big Easy's still an easy win in the
NFL for most teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have thought we'd won the Super Bowl my first year if
you'd asked me,'' Ditka said. ``But what I think and what we do are
two different things.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditka, who guided the Chicago Bears to a victory in Super Bowl
XX in 1985, left coaching for five years after the 1992 season. He
was finally persuaded out of the television booth in 1997,
replacing Jim Mora in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   In his first season with the Saints, Ditka doubled the team's
win total from the previous season. In August 1998, he was rewarded
with a five-year contract extension through the 2002 season, but
few NFL observers believe he'll last that long.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those same observers second-guessed Ditka in April after
he made one of the biggest gambles in NFL history. The Saints
traded eight draft picks _ all six this year and two in 2000 _ to
the Washington Redskins for the fifth choice overall. New Orleans
selected Heisman Trophy-winning running back Ricky Williams of
Texas, who became the first one-man draft class in history.
</P>
<P>
   But Ditka believes Williams, the NCAA's all-time leading rusher,
might be what was missing from the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Ditka already has a gritty leader in quarterback Billy Joe
Hobert, and there's more speed at receiver after he traded for
Eddie Kennison. The offensive line has been solidified with
free-agent signee Wally Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints finished fourth in the NFL in total defense in 1997,
before falling to 26th last season. This year, free-agent signees
Ashley Ambrose and Willie Clay have upgraded the secondary, which
ranked last a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing star defensive end Joe Johnson to a season-ending
knee injury in the preseason, the Saints still have one of the
league's most aggressive units.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had our share of struggles, that's for sure,'' Ditka
said, ``but nobody is throwing in the towel. We're not giving up.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ditka isn't giving up his sideline tirades, either.
Offensive coordinator Danny Abramowicz will move from the sideline
to the press box today against the Falcons. Ditka didn't like
Abramowicz's play-calling in last week's 14-10 loss at Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike probably calls five plays every game,'' Abramowicz said.
``And we yell at each other like crazy. Yeah, he yelled at me. But
if people think this is the first time, they're crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ditka
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans Saints
</P>
<P>
   Age: 59.
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: Aliquippa, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   College: Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching record: 119-84.
</P>
<P>
   Career highlights: Won a Super Bowl with the Dallas Cowboys as a
player (1972) and assistant coach (1977) and as head coach of the
Chicago Bears (1985). ... Became first tight end inducted into Pro
Football Hall of Fame on July 30, 1988. ... Was NFL Rookie of the
Year with the Cowboys in 1961 and played in five Pro Bowls. ...
Named NFL Coach of the Year with Bears in 1985 and 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
