u s BC-FBN-GIANTS-COLLINS-NY     10-09 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-COLLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS WILL GIVE GIANTS THE RISK FOR THE REWARD
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sit with Kerry Collins, whether it's in a quiet moment inside
the Giants' locker room or at a restaurant having dinner, and
something somewhere on Collins will be moving.
</P>
<P>
   His foot may go tap, tap, tapping a fidgety beat on the floor.
His hands may drum at the tabletop. Or, his eyes will be working
the room. They are almost imperceptible movements, small things
since his 6-foot-5-inch, 248-pound body will be at rest in his
chair, otherwise in complete repose.
</P>
<P>
   But there is always something going on. He is a man with places
to go, and eager to get there.
</P>
<P>
   That is a window into what Giants fans can expect Sunday when
Collins makes the first start of his Giants career against the
Arizona Cardinals. Collins may or may not make the Giants better,
but he isn't going to wait for the team's plodding offense to catch
up to him. He's eager to get somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not likely to be a debut laced with indecision.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Kerry, he drops back and the football is coming out of
the pocket right now,'' Giants Coach Jim Fassel said last week.
``You better be ready to make a play. He's got real good
anticipation and he'll just put it in there. He may not wait to see
if it's open, he's figuring somebody can make a big play.''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point:
</P>
<P>
   In relief of Kent Graham last week, Collins threw a pass deep
down the sideline to Amani Toomer. Toomer was covered, but Collins'
pass was to the receiver's outside shoulder, the one place Toomer
could catch it and no one else could. Toomer spun to the outside
and made the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best thing Kerry did in the game,'' Fassel said of
the 32-yard gain. ``He was covered, but he threw it anyway. Let
your best guys make plays. The Minnesota Vikings set a league
record doing that last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins has the arm strength, and the confidence, to force
passes into small openings and he makes extremely quick decisions
in the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   There is one problem.
</P>
<P>
   Throw into coverage and passes can also be intercepted. Collins
has 51 career touchdowns, but he also has 65 career interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Can Fassel, who likes his quarterbacks to play without mistakes,
handle the high-reward, high-risk style Collins has often
displayed?
</P>
<P>
   Or put another way, can the slumbering Giants' offense afford
not to accept the risk for the reward?
</P>
<P>
   If the average Collins game is two touchdown passes and two
interceptions, is that still a net gain for the punchless Giants?
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, after all, have a strong defense. They might be able
to overcome the turnovers. But the defense can't win every game if
the offense doesn't find a little spark.
</P>
<P>
   And Collins is a sparkplug. Indeed, he's an excitable young man.
</P>
<P>
   When Collins entered the Giants' huddle last week, the regulars
were surprised by his animation and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks really fast,'' tackle Scott Gragg said last week of
Collins. ``Kerry, how can I say this, well, he calls plays like
he's had a few cups of coffee. It's not a deer-in-the-headlights
look, he's very sure of what he's doing. But he's pretty worked
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins doesn't refute this scouting report on his huddle
habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am excited,'' he said. ``In the back of my head, I can still
hear Joe Paterno yelling at me: `Get them in and out of the huddle.
Play quick. It's a game of quickness.'''
</P>
<P>
   If he is high-strung in games, some of his teammates have also
observed what tight end Pete Mitchell termed ``a cool confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   He is someone who's been in the spotlight a long time.
</P>
<P>
   As a 6-foot-5-inch, 15-year-old starting quarterback in high
school, he played before crowds of 7,000 and larger before he
learned to drive a car. He was an All-America quarterback at Penn
State, leading them to an undefeated season as a senior and a Rose
Bowl victory in his last college game. Just days after his 24th
birthday, he was playing in the National Football Conference
championship game with the Carolina Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, still just 26, he will make his 50th start in a NFL
game.
</P>
<P>
   Too much too soon also led to a host of off-the-field problems.
And he is hardly a proven winner in the NFL. In a rag-tag season a
year ago, he was frequently reckless with the football, fumbling it
in the pocket and making foolhardy throws on the run.
</P>
<P>
   Even in his glory days with the Panthers, some of his teammates
and coaches said they worked around him _ the team carrying him,
not vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   But he is smart and his talent to play the position is
unquestioned.
</P>
<P>
   There was, for example, another pass in his relief role last
Sunday that exemplified what Collins can do that few at his post
can. He threw a deep square out, heaving the ball on a line from
the left hash mark all the way to the opposite sideline. The ball
arrived just as receiver Ike Hilliard was coming out of his break.
Hilliard grabbed it out of the air. First down.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dangerous pass, but an indefensible one if thrown
properly.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a pass the Giants didn't dare attempt in the days of
Dave Brown and Danny Kanell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the first time Kerry threw one of those in
practice,'' Giants cornerback Jason Sehorn, said. ``I thought, `You
mean we have to cover that now?'''
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter of timing and decisiveness and it takes a
quarterback with a certain conviction about his abilities, and
maybe someone just a bit antsy to get the ball down field. It takes
someone who is convinced he's got places to go. And he's not
waiting for you.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants find out Sunday just where Kerry Collins might take
them. This is what their $16.9 million gamble on Collins bought
last February.
</P>
<P>
   It does not figure to be a boring ride.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
