u a BC-NY-COMMUNITY-COURTS-N     10-09 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COMMUNITY-COURTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVERSING TREND, COURT SYSTEM MOVES BACK TO A BROOKLYN
NEIGHBORHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Teresa Cama, a lifelong resident of Red Hook,
Brooklyn, stood outside her home on Visitation Place and recalled
the days when the long-vacant brick building across the street was
a Roman Catholic elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   She graduated from the eighth grade at Visitation School a
half-century ago. Two of her children graduated from the school,
and another was in first grade when declining enrollment forced the
school to close in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   But as Mrs. Cama spoke of the building's ``heartbreaking'' fate,
she also looked forward to its transformation. The three-story
Tudor Gothic structure is becoming the city's second community
court _ part of an effort to bring the local justice system closer
to the people while helping to improve their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great,'' Mrs. Cama said as workers in the
building hammered, drilled and threaded electrical wiring through
unfinished floors and walls. The $5.4 million interior
reconstruction is to be completed, and the Red Hook Community
Justice Center up and running, by about year's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than being empty,'' Mrs. Cama continued. ``And it
will help keep the drug addicts out of the park and off the
streets.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's first community court opened in Manhattan six years
ago, and a third is planned for Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   When the work in Red Hook is completed, the site will include a
court that will handle cases that would normally be dealt with in
three separate courts in downtown Brooklyn: Criminal Court, Family
Court and Housing Court.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal cases will include low-level felonies like
possession of relatively small amounts of drugs, and misdemeanors
like minor assaults, shoplifting, fare beating and so-called
``quality of life'' offenses like prostitution, vandalism and
graffiti. Cases that would otherwise go to Family Court are to
include juvenile delinquency; those that would usually go to
Housing Court will include landlord-tenant disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The court is expected to hear about 10,000 cases a year
originating in Red Hook, Carroll Gardens, Cobble Hill, Park Slope
and Sunset Park, officials say. But the building will not only be a
courthouse. In reflecting a key goal of community court advocates _
to help offenders overcome problems that lead to their tangles with
the law _ the building will also house programs like drug-abuse and
domestic-violence counseling, job placement and health services.
</P>
<P>
   In a city where municipal tribunals like the defunct Magistrates
Courts used to be scattered across each borough, until local courts
were consolidated in the early 1960s, current moves toward
decentralizing the courts by opening community courts would seem to
be merely a swing of the pendulum. But not so, state court
officials and supporters of community courts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old Magistrates Courts were geographically based in the
community, but there wasn't an effort to understand the problems of
the communities,'' John Feinblatt, director of the Center for Court
Innovation, said of the defunct courts. The old system was replaced
by the current system of a Criminal Court and a Civil Court, with
more centralized branches in each borough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geography is only one part of the story _ philosophy is the
other part,'' Feinblatt said. He said the current community court
movement promotes courts that are not just away from downtown civic
centers, but that also emphasize social service and counseling
programs. His group, which helped plan the Red Hook center, is a
research and development unit of the state court system that was
established with the aid of the Fund for the City of New York,
which seeks to improve government functioning.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Lippman, the state's chief administrative judge, said,
``The whole idea of community courts is to make justice not some
far-away abstraction but something meaningful.'' He said that in
the current Criminal Court the volume of cases is so great that
``often the defendant walks out of the courtroom'' with no
punishment for the type of low-level offenses that will be dealt
with in the Red Hook court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here the message will be that crimes will result in
adjudications that benefit the community, whether it's cleaning up
a local park or a local dump,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lippman said court officials envisioned at least one community
court in each borough, though ``I don't see a return'' to the more
scattered system that characterized the old Magistrates Courts. He
said Red Hook was chosen for the city's second community court
because the area _ which for years was scarred by crime and
deterioration but is showing signs of revival _ was ``receptive to
the resources that a court can bring in.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone favors community courts. Critics say they unfairly
favor the neighborhoods lucky or influential enough to obtain them.
When the Manhattan court was being planned, Manhattan District
Attorney Robert Morgenthau was among those who held that the money
devoted to the community court should be used to improve conditions
in the borough's main Criminal Court at 100 Centre St. in lower
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He remains concerned that the resources that are used for the
community court in Manhattan can be better used at 100 Centre,'' a
spokeswoman for Morgenthau, Barbara Thompson, said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Brooklyn District Attorney Charles Hynes has
strongly supported the Red Hook court.
</P>
<P>
   While courts across the country have been consolidated in recent
decades to gain greater efficiency, advocates of community courts
believe centralization ``perhaps went too far, that the downtown
courthouses are inconvenient for most residents of an area,'' said
David Rottman, associate director of research at the National
Center for State Courts in Williamsburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   But for the people of Red Hook, there are other reasons for
supporting the community court.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they see the court,'' Evelyn Rivera, 35, said, ``people
around here will have more respect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
