</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-S.C.-GAMBLING-VOTE-ART-925(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMBLING FACES TWO BIG TESTS IN SOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add photo note.)  
 (ATTN: Ala., Ga.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCK HILL, S.C. _ It has been more than 50 years since any state
banned an existing form of gambling, but a drive around the border
roads of York County helps to explain why South Carolina is poised
to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   Video poker is everywhere. Its robotic musical signature drones
from gambling machines in virtually every gas station and
convenience store as mesmerized players feed in dollar after dollar
to play five-card stud and blackjack. Gaudy windowless parlors with
five machines to a room greet visitors who cross the state line
from North Carolina. The industry crept up on the state through a
series of back-door legal moves, but 34,000 of the machines have
now taken root across South Carolina, far more than in any other
state, and many people have had enough.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 2, voters will have a choice either to ban the machines
beginning next summer or regulate them more closely. The latest
newspaper poll shows that a sizable majority of likely voters _
more than 60 percent, in one poll _ want the machines permanently
unplugged.
</P>
<P>
   That vote, and another one on Tuesday in which Alabama will
decide whether to institute a state lottery, will be among the most
important tests in years of whether gambling's steady growth in the
Southern Bible Belt has finally reached its limit. Although the
lottery is more accepted and far less intrusive than video
gambling, several polls show that its popularity in Alabama has
dropped in recent months. The outcome of next week's lottery vote,
which once seemed certain to pass, is now considered a tossup.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very big symbolic votes coming up,'' said William
Thompson, a gambling industry expert and public administration
professor at the University of Nevada, Las Vegas. ``The last time a
state voted out gambling was in 1948, when Idaho banned slot
machines. It will be a very big victory for the anti-gambling side
if it's thrown out in South Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   Alabama's governor, Donald Siegelman, campaigned almost
exclusively on a promise to create a lottery, and is selling it as
the only way to create a pre-kindergarten program and a college
scholarship program similar to that in neighboring Georgia and
other states. Gov. Jim Hodges of South Carolina, who also ran on a
pro-lottery platform and accepted about $3 million from video poker
interests, now says he is opposed to video poker. His state's
lottery will be on the ballot in November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In both of the coming votes, gambling proponents have
encountered large and potent coalitions of religious groups, but
the size of the opposition in South Carolina has been particularly
remarkable. Virtually every denomination in the state _ including
Southern Baptists, Presbyterians and Jews _ has joined in
well-organized coalitions to get anti-poker voters registered and
to the polls. They have been joined by the South Carolina Chamber
of Commerce and most large businesses, which are worried about the
state's image, and most editorial pages. The state election
commission has reported a noticeable burst in voter registrations
in the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The social cost and the implications for our citizens were
already huge,'' said Paula Harper Bethea, chairwoman of the South
Carolina chamber. ``But we also think it has a negative economic
impact on the state, because it greatly affects our image. We're
struggling to get ahead in a lot of areas, and we have a good
quality of life, and we think we deserve better than video poker.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2,300-member chamber, the state's largest business
organization, is running television and radio advertisements
against the machines, while an anti-gambling group, Legacy
Alliance, is putting up billboards. Meanwhile, religious groups are
distributing yard signs and building grass-roots support. A recent
rally in Rock Hill, a hotbed of anti-poker sentiment, drew a crowd
of 3,500 to protest the effects of video gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents have an endless sheaf of stories about middle-class
parents who lost their life savings to a video poker addiction, or
poor families who spend their food money in the parlors. But they
have been careful not to make the vote a referendum on the merits
of gambling itself. The Rev. Steve Hogg, pastor of the First
Baptist Church of Rock Hill and a prominent leader of the
anti-poker forces, said many people in his coalition approved of
lotteries or horse racing, though he does not, and so they decided
to focus on the one issue that united them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't have put this coalition together if the lottery
was on the table, but we all agree that video poker is the most
destructive and addictive form of gambling there is,'' said Hogg, a
conservative Southern Baptist who wore a blue Vote No button on his
shirt pocket. ``I'm not one of those Christians who believes in
outlawing everything I think is sinful or immoral. I'm part of the
community, and we have to be pragmatic about what we consider to be
life-or-death issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the support for the machines has come from the state's
video poker industry, which has revenue of about $2.8 billion a
year and has raised about $2 million on the campaign to keep the
machines, more than twice as much as its opponents. Supporters say
the state will lose $200 million to $300 million in yearly tax
revenue if the machines are banned, and predict that 28,000 people
will lose their jobs. Many video parlors and gas stations are
plastered with fliers that cast the issue in terms of personal
freedom, saying that the next step is to ban the Internet or rock
music.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Since the poll was published by The State, in Columbia, and five
other newspapers last month, the pro-poker forces have intensified
their broadcast advertising and direct mailings, and are building a
get-out-the-vote effort among poker employees and players to rival
that of the churches. But many who have watched the issue say the
industry may have grown too large to stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's tightened up since the poll,'' said John
Cavanaugh, a political science professor at the University of South
Carolina. ``But there's still a strong anti-gambling feeling that's
catching hold in the state. Everyone sees the machines when they go
to the gas station, and many people know someone with an addiction
problem. The tide seems to be turning.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a considerable sentiment against the lottery in
Alabama, as well, again led by church groups, but the intensity of
the opposition is less than in South Carolina because of the nature
of the game. Many people consider the lottery less addictive and
less harmful than video poker, and are jealous of the
lottery-financed college scholarships offered to Georgia students.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this fails, there is no Plan B,'' said Rick Dent, a
spokesman for the Alabama Education Lottery Foundation, which is
running the pro-lottery campaign. ``This is our one chance to ever
have college scholarships, pre-K and computers in the schools. If
there were another way to pay for them, surely we would already
have them.''
</P>
<P>
   But lottery opponents have also repeated a frequent criticism of
the numbers game: Most tickets are purchased by poorer residents, a
large number of whom are black, while the scholarships tend to go
to middle-class white students. Church leaders said they were
particularly angered by a statement from Siegelman, the governor,
several weeks ago that opponents of the lottery should be ashamed
of themselves, and they said no other issue had brought different
denominations so closely together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply believe that government should not fund itself with
money from the people who can least afford it,'' said Michael
Anderson, executive director of the Mobile Baptist Association,
which represents about 100 churches.
</P>
<P>
   Siegelman later said he respected those who disagree with him on
religious or moral grounds, but pollsters say the intense
church-by-church mobilization has significantly eroded support for
the lottery. A poll conducted by three newspapers and published
this week showed that 51 percent of likely voters said they
supported the lottery, down from 61 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, every church in Alabama has a bus,'' said Eric
Johnston, a Birmingham lawyer who is treasurer of the largest
anti-lottery coalition. ``And on Tuesday, they're all heading for
the polls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
