<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Phloundering in NHL East Conference
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After going 15 consecutive quarters without a
touchdown, it's safe to say the Philadelphia Eagles had only one
small set of fans left in the city: the Flyers. The Eagles were the
only thing distracting Philly sports fans from the fact the Flyers
failed to score a goal in their first two games, despite
possessing, according to general manager Bobby Clarke, their most
talented roster in the last five years. The consecutive home
blankings predictably have Philly fans, not the reserved sort,
looking for scapegoats. Clarke no doubt realizes that his own
future rides with the success of this team and coach Roger Neilson.
Owner Ed Snider also has let it be known that the team's payroll is
way too high _ and a sudden mandate to lop off salaries usually
isn't conducive to building a Stanley Cup winner. The public's
cries to dump Neilson, Clarke said, ``is all the media's fault.''
Alluding to the fact that the Flyers also were shut out in their
final exhibition, Neilson said, ``That's three games in a row it's
happened. Three games without a goal. Nine periods without a goal.
Wasn't in the plan for the start of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   COMRADE BURE
</P>
<P>
   The story was a rehash of previous reports, but a Canadian
television network's report about a possible relationship between
Florida's Pavel Bure and alleged Russian organized crime boss Anzor
Kikalichvilli remains a concern for the league. Russian mobsters
have tried to extort money out of Russian NHL players in recent
years. NHL chief counsel Bill Daly said of Bure's alleged ties to
Kikalichvilli: ``It's a relationship we're concerned about and a
relationship we're monitoring.'' Bure's response: ``They can be
concerned, but there's nothing to be concerned about. It's all
stuff that's been written over and over and there's nothing to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   BRIEFLY . . .
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Daigle wanted so badly to leave Tampa Bay for New York
that he was willing to downsize his salary from $1 million to
$600,000. The Lightning wanted so badly to get rid of him that it
is picking up a majority of the salary while Daigle plays in the
Rangers' minor-league system.... Agent Kurt Overhardt on the
Devils' dealings with restricted free agent Brendan Morrison:
``They're not even treating him as a member of their family, unless
it's a dysfunctional family.''... Yes, that was former Atlanta
Knight (IHL) Stan Drulia scoring for Tampa Bay Thursday vs. the
Kings. It was his first NHL goal since 1992.... Carolina GM Jim
Rutherford reiterated that the team is not close to a deal with
Keith Primeau. In the meantime, Ron Francis is the new team
captain. ``I understand the club needs to try to put this situation
behind them and get on with the season,'' Francis said. ``Until
Keith's situation gets resolved, there's a big hole on this hockey
club. All of us notice that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
