<SLUG> BC-HKN-HOCKEY-FEATURE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pressure's on Rangers
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Neil Smith might be a native of Ontario, but his style
is pure Manhattan. And if the New York Rangers, a team of skating
dollar signs, should crash this season, the general manager's
office is going to look like the site of a subway derailment.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to tell where Smith is feeling more heat these
days, from around the league or from within his own city limits.
The Rangers continue to flounder at Penn Plaza, despite the
league's highest annual payroll at nearly $59 million, more than
triple the Thrashers'.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's summer shopping spree of six free agents, including Theo
Fleury, had netted two losses and a tie before winning their first
game of the season 3-1 at Carolina on Friday. No need to ask who
most of Smith's fellow NHL executives were pulling for last week
when Ottawa, which is ranked 23rd in payroll and is standing firm
in not renegotiating with holdout Alexei Yashin, visited Madison
Square Garden last week _ and won.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith doesn't seem to mind being perceived as the bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they're upset as much as they're maybe jealous
or envious, because they can't spend as much and they don't have
the revenue streams to do it,'' Smith said by telephone. ``This is
New York, and if they were in New York, they would be doing the
same thing. But they can also look at it this (way) . We've been in
the league for 74 years and we've only won four Stanley Cups, so
it's not like it's a sure-fire method.''
</P>
<P>
   A common league joke these days is that if NHL general managers
are colluding in holding down salaries, it's a 27-team collusion
with one maverick. But if the Rangers miss the playoffs for the
third year in a row and Smith is fired, he'll be going down having
spent somebody else's money, owner Cablevision's. The total value
of the deals given to Fleury, Valeri Kamensky, Sylvain Lefebvre,
Stephane Quintal, Kirk McLean and Tim Taylor was $67 million.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia owner Ed Snider, whose own team is struggling
despite the second-highest payroll, ripped the Rangers' spending
habits in Canada's National Post the other day. ``They are
continuing down a lane that everybody else in the league has
decided is a disaster,'' Snider said. ``So, obviously, they don't
care about the league. They say to hell with the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith initially wouldn't respond to Snider's comments, then
said, ``It doesn't surprise me. We're rivals.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that he doesn't think the team's 1999 payroll _
which includes a $15.5 million base-salary top line of Fleury,
Peter Nedved and Adam Graves _ creates an atmosphere atypical for
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always pressure here,'' Smith said. ``There's pressure
to find a cab in the morning. That's the way of life here. You get
used to it. We're not into slow rebuilding programs here. We're
into fast, like everything else here. When you're driving and you
see construction in your lane ahead, you don't slow down; you speed
up and cut in front of the car in the lane next to you. That's our
philosophy here.''
</P>
<P>
   Except the Rangers appear to be deep into a massive backup.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
