</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ITEMS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    History checks Salei's denial
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Anaheim's Ruslan Salei insists he wasn't trying to
injure Mike Modano when he crosschecked the off-balanced Dallas
center from behind and came close to paralyzing him. But Salei's
history screamed for something more than the 10-game suspension he
was handed. The defenseman was suspended two years ago for
head-butting and last year for ``slew-footing'' (taking down a
player with a leg-sweep from behind). Then there are the things he
wasn't even penalized for. Ask Thrashers center Mike Stapleton.
Last season, when he played for Phoenix, Stapleton nearly had his
left eye carved out by Salei's stick blade. As it was, he was
suffered a 28-stitch gash under the left eye and missed four games.
But no official saw the infraction and didn't penalize Salei. ``He
cut me down to the bone and damaged the tear duct,'' Stapleton
said. ``I don't know if he has respect for other players. I
understand he plays hard but there's a difference between playing
hard and (lacking) respect.... We're all kind of in like a
fraternity. This is our livelihood. The scary thing is, he could've
killed him.''
</P>
<P>
   FACEOFF: STEVE LUDZIK, TAMPA BAY COACH
</P>
<P>
   _ On his training ground in the IHL: ``I learned that talent is
not going to win it for you. You have to have chemistry. You have
to have guys who want to show up every night.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Comparing the IHL and AHL: ``I don't think there are too many
American League teams that would be able to compete. Look at teams
like Pittsburgh and you see a lot of International League players
playing on NHL teams that are doing very well.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On the trading of Alexander Daigle: ``It wasn't done for
personal reasons. It was just we couldn't get him to show that
passion that we thought we needed. We thought it was a bad example
to other players. It is very tough as an organization starting anew
like we are, when you say to guys, `We need passion.' That painted
(GM) Rick Dudley and myself in a corner.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On the team's playoff chances: ``If you say there's a
long-term plan, fans kind of get turned off. If your only
expectations are to play .500 hockey that would be, to me, like a
father saying to his son, `See if you can get 50 percent on this
exam and I'll be happy with that.' If you set your sights low,
you're going to be an underachieving team. I'd like my guys to
overachieve and push themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   DECADE LEADERS
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull, who scored goals in two of Dallas's first three
games, merely was extending his excellence in the 1990s. Hull
entered the season as the NHL's leading goal-scorer since Jan. 1,
1990. Note the absence of Wayne Gretzky, who had a league-high 702
assists in the decade. Here are the top 10 goal scorers, with
totals through Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   PlayerTeamGoals
</P>
<P>
   Brett HullDallas481
</P>
<P>
   Brendan ShanahanDetroit348
</P>
<P>
   Jaromir JagrPittsburgh345
</P>
<P>
   Theo FleuryColorado345
</P>
<P>
   Luc RobatailleLos Angeles344
</P>
<P>
   Steve YzermanDetroit336
</P>
<P>
   Joe SakicColorado334
</P>
<P>
   Pierre TurgeonSt. Louis331
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy RoenickPhoenix327
</P>
<P>
   Alexander MogilneyVancouver322
</P>
<P>
   DATELINE: LAS VEGAS
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Red Wings want to bring the Stanley Cup back to
Motown. The oddsmakers in the neon city believe they will. Detroit
is a 7-2 favorite to win the Cup, followed by defending champion
Dallas and Colorado at 5-1, and Philadelphia, New Jersey and Ottawa
at 8-1. The longest odds? Yep. The Thrashers are joined by Tampa
Bay at 300-1. Nashville and the New York Islanders are 150-1.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
