<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Star struck in NHL West Conference
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Not surprisingly, the check by Anaheim's Ruslan Salei
on Dallas Stars center Mike Modano last week caused a lot of
reaction around the league. The growing concern is that players _
upset league officials are taking insufficent action against
offenders _ will take their on-ice retribution to a new level.
Modano expressed concern that, ``Somewhere along the road, players
have lost respect for one another and the sport, and that is
unacceptable.... Hitting from behind and attempting to injure each
other does nothing for the game.'' But Anaheim coach Craig
Hartsburg, who played for the same Minnesota/Dallas organization as
Modano, defends Salei, saying, ``I'll go to my grave with it. I
don't think Rusty had any intention of any viciousness. It's just a
freak thing that happened.'' He couldn't convince Brett Hull,
Modano's teammate. Hull said of Salei, who is a native of Belarus:
``I'd like to see the guy sent away and have his passport taken
away. But we all know that's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   TRADE WINDS
</P>
<P>
   Word is that Rick Tocchet is not long for Phoenix. The
high-scoring winger is entering the final year of his contract and
Coyotes general manager Bobby Smith hasn't given any indication he
is interested in bringing Tocchet back. The player didn't help his
cause when he publicly questioned the team's commitment to winning
when it appeared it was more intent on slashing payroll. Owner
Richard Burke responded, ``Rick Tocchet is 80 percent of the
solution and 20 percent of the problem.'' Burke later apologized,
and Tocchet now says, ``It's water under the bridge. He said he was
sorry and we haven't talked about it since, so forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   BRIEFLY . . .
</P>
<P>
   Good move by Colorado to sign veteran David Reid, who came
cheaply (one year, $475,000). He scored twice for Dallas in last
year's conference finals when the Stars dumped the Avalanche.
``He's a depth guy and he's going to help these kids coming in,''
Avalanche GM Pierre Lacroix said. ``We saw that we needed someone
to grandfather these kids. All he wanted was to go for it another
time, to try to win it. He feels we have what it takes to reach his
objective.''... Wayne Gretzky says he has been contacted by ``five
or six'' teams _ including, presumably, Edmonton and Los Angeles _
about a position in the organization and that one unnamed team has
offered him 35 percent ownership. But he reiterated he will stay
out of hockey for at least one year before making a decision on his
future.... Edmonton president Glen Sather on Thrashers captain
Kelly Buchberger's departure: ``I admired Kelly for his
competitiveness, the work ethic he brought to the rink, his
fearless play. He loved it here but he was stuck in the system,
making Canadian dollars.... He's got a new three-year contract for
big dough. It's better for him.''
</P>
