<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1826 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-NY-BLACKS-BASEBALL-AR     10-09 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BLACKS-BASEBALL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL'S HALLOWED GROUNDS, BLACK YOUTHS WORSHIP BASKETBALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Two photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (bl) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Standing across the Harlem River from Yankee Stadium,
atop some of baseball's most hallowed ground, Michael Franklin, 13,
leaned against a black metal fence, largely unmoved by what others
were calling the magic of October baseball. He lives in Polo
Grounds Towers, an upper Manhattan housing project built on the
remains of the legendary home of the New York Giants, and later the
New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the Yankees,'' Michael said Thursday with a grin. ``But
basketball is my game.''
</P>
<P>
   In Brooklyn, on the blocks where once stood Ebbets Field, home
of the Brooklyn Dodgers, another housing project now dominates. The
only indication of its previous incarnation is a small granite
plaque under a fading ``Renting Office'' sign. There, on a day much
of the city was swept up with the fates of the Mets and Yankees in
the playoffs, Shawn Tyson, 23, said he had even less use for
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to watch like everyone else, but I don't catch it
anymore,'' said Tyson, who lives in the Ebbets Field Houses.
``Baseball is boring, it's too slow. Basketball has much more
action. I honestly can't see the appeal of the game at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Franklin and Shawn Tyson, who are black, were both
standing on ground steeped in baseball history _ ground where Bobby
Thomson hit his home run heard round the world and Jackie Robinson
broke baseball's color barrier. And they both gave voice to a
certain disconcerting truth about baseball. Among many American
blacks, it is a sport in decline.
</P>
<P>
   The decline is reflected in the shrinking number of blacks in
the major leagues and in the primacy of basketball as the sport of
choice among black youngsters in the inner city, and it is not
likely to be halted by the excitement and nostalgia surrounding the
first simultaneous World Series playoff appearances of the Mets and
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   One day last week, a group of black teen-agers at the Polo
Grounds Towers, asked to rank their favorite sports, spoke in what
amounted to a consensus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball, football, baseball and hockey,'' said Maurice
Burgess, 18, who acted as a spokesman for the group. ``And soccer?
You've got to interview some Australians about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, plenty of black residents at the two housing
projects, children and grandparents alike, have watched, and will
cheer for, the Mets and Yankees as they make their way through the
playoffs. Not all blacks have lost interest in baseball. But still,
black residents of the buildings express a certain sense of loss.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Giles, 81, a retired truck driver and ``devout Yankees
fan'' who lives at Polo Grounds Towers, said he vividly remembers
trips to the Polo Grounds and can recall where he was when Bobby
Thomson's home run won the pennant for the Giants in 1951. ``It was
a short home run,'' he said, eyes alight. ``But it was a home
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Giles acknowledges that things have changed. ``During my time,
no black man was allowed to play,'' he said. ``Then Jackie Robinson
did it, and all of a sudden there were so many blacks you couldn't
count them.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in next breath, he added, ``Now, there are so many
Latinos, you can't count them either.''
</P>
<P>
   Statistics bear him out. According to the Center for the Study
of Sport in Society at Northeastern University, the percentage of
blacks in the major leagues dropped to 15 percent in 1998, the
lowest number of the decade. In the same year, the percentage of
Hispanic players rose to 25 percent, a decade high.
</P>
<P>
   And the representation of blacks in baseball pales in comparison
to their numbers in football (nearly 70 percent) and basketball (80
percent). Also, nearly 90 percent of Little League programs
nationwide are located in mostly white suburban and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is concern about the number of blacks declining,
certainly,'' said Ricky Clemons, vice president for public
relations in baseball's National League. He said one major concern
was that ``a lot of inner-city high schools have eliminated
baseball. It's the first to go. It takes a lot of equipment and a
lot of space.''
</P>
<P>
   To counter this, Major League Baseball has supported Reviving
Baseball in the Inner Cities, an organization that aims to develop
fans and players in the hearts of the nation's larger cities. The
organization counts more than 30,000 participants in 50 cities.
</P>
<P>
   But developments at Ebbets Field Houses and the Polo Grounds
Towers illustrate baseball's urban decline. At Ebbets Field, an
adjacent playground was recently renovated to make more room for
basketball courts, eliminating a cement softball diamond. Baseball
players must now drag their equipment to diamonds in Prospect Park,
about a mile away, to play.
</P>
<P>
   At the Polo Grounds housing project, a central playground known
as the Willie Mays is the domain of basketball players, with
baseball shoved to the periphery; at nearby Holcombe-Rucker
Playground, a nicely groomed baseball diamond is used principally
for ``cookouts and such,'' Burgess said.
</P>
<P>
   Burgess pointed to his Yankees cap. ``This stands for New York,
New York, not New York Yankees,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the younger blacks interviewed said they enjoyed
basketball and football more because the games were faster, more
exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like that loose action,'' said Mike Kelly, 15, who lives at
the Polo Grounds Towers. ``It's swifter than people standing around
with bats.''
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of suggestions for improvements, mind you.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nine-inning game is too long,'' said Shawn Maynard, 19,
who lives in the Ebbets Field Houses. ``Maybe they should shorten
it to five innings.''
</P>
<P>
   His friend Leshawn Swea, 17, said baseball should consider
adding flashy sideshows, loud music during games or time limits.
``Or cheerleaders,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   If baseball has its passionate curators among black New Yorkers
who live on the grounds of the old ball parks, they are usually the
older residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to sneak over the fence here,'' said Clinton Collins,
71, of Ebbets Field Houses, who wore a New York Knicks cap. ``But
you could get a $2.50 box seat if you wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   He ticked off the names of players he had seen _ Pee Wee Reese,
Don Hoak, Jackie Robinson. Then, as if to make a point, he pulled
out a picture of his 13-year-old grandson, Farouk, dressed in a
football uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the love of baseball the older residents hold has been
embraced by some young blacks. The more talk about the prospect of
the Yankees or Mets, or both teams, in the World Series, the more
excitement bubbled up. Some youngsters could give a glowing review
of Derek Jeter's stylish play and Mike Piazza's clout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love watching baseball, especially when a player hits a home
run,'' said Rogelio Henry Jr., 13, an eighth-grader at Jackie
Robinson Middle School, behind his home in the Ebbets Field Houses.
``I'm living on history. Right here is history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
