u k BC-EDIT-U.N.-DUES-NYT &LR;      10-09 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-U.N.-DUES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.) 
</HEADLINE>
   EDITORIAL: AMERICA'S UNPAID U.N. DUES  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Oct. 10:
</P>
<P>
   American foreign policy reaps important benefits when the United
Nations sends peacekeepers to East Timor, relief workers to East
Africa, police and civil administrators to Kosovo or arms
inspectors to Iraq. But for years, Congress has prevented the
Clinton administration from paying the back dues America legally
owes the U.N. This fall, there is a good chance to end the long
stalemate, but only if House Republicans act responsibly.
</P>
<P>
   The administration and the Senate have agreed on a plan to make
up a large portion of the arrears, which now total about $1
billion. But the House version of the legislation is expected to be
saddled with unacceptable anti-abortion language that has nothing
to do with the U.N. dues issue. The language, promoted by Rep.
Christopher Smith, R-N.J., would prohibit U.S. assistance to groups
involved in lobbying foreign governments to liberalize their
abortion laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Smith provision is bad policy that would bar Washington from
giving any money to these groups for purposes unrelated to
abortion. It would also discourage efforts to reform extremely
harsh foreign abortion laws. If it appears in the final version of
the legislation, President Clinton is almost certain to veto it.
Smith should stop trying to attach this language. If he persists,
when it comes time to reconcile House and Senate versions, Speaker
Dennis Hastert must choose conferees who will eliminate the
abortion language. Unless the United States pays at least $300
million this year, it could lose voting privileges in the General
Assembly. Unless it pays a substantial portion of back dues, like
the $900 million the Senate has authorized, it risks losing moral
influence.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has withheld its dues to bring pressure for U.N.
financial reforms. But in recent years, the U.N. has reformed its
budget and staffing. Most of the U.N.'s costs are paid by other
countries and many of its purchases are made from American
companies. Refusing to pay now would seriously weaken the U.N.'s
ability to respond to future crises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 1631EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
