<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1834 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-TELECOMMUNICATIO     10-09 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TELECOMMUNICATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CONTROL OF THE ELECTRONIC HIGHWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Oct. 10:
</P>
<P>
   A bewildering series of mergers and regulatory actions in the
telecommunications industry in the past two weeks could ultimately
improve telephone service to consumers. But some of the mergers
designed to make local phone service better risk constraining what
viewers can see on their cable systems, threatening the diversity
of information that is central to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   A scorecard was needed to keep track of all the recent
maneuvers. Bell Atlantic, the largest local phone company, asked
the Federal Communications Commission for permission to enter
long-distance service, where it would take on AT&AMP;T, MCI Worldcom
and Sprint, thereby increasing competition. But then MCI Worldcom
and Sprint decided to merge, a move that would lessen competition.
Meanwhile, the commission approved the merger of SBC Communications
and Ameritech, two large regional Bell companies. It also approved
rules that will make it easier for AT&AMP;T, a huge cable operator, to
take over another cable company, Mediaone, putting about 60 percent
of American households within reach of AT&AMP;T's cable programs.
</P>
<P>
   Some hail these events as the dawn of technological change that
will throw every telecommunications company into competition with
every other, bringing consumers dramatically lower prices and fancy
new video, phone, wireless and Internet services. In this view,
there will be no such thing as a regional phone company or
long-distance company or cable company. Instead, full-service
companies will do it all. One company might provide all these
services over the phone lines. Another might use the cable line.
Others will deliver information by satellite or land-based
microwave. The optimists see five or six companies luring
customers.
</P>
<P>
   But others fear a world in which one or two companies take over,
concentrating control of the information that flows into a hundred
million households. That, critics fear, would squelch the variety
of news, information and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The commission may have fueled these fears by permitting too
many phone mergers. The 1996 Telecommunications Act invited AT&AMP;T
and others to go after local phone customers of the Baby Bells. So
far, that has not occurred and the commission is under intense
pressure from Congress to make it happen. The commission approved
the merger of Bell Atlantic and Nynex, two original Baby Bells,
because it extracted promises that Bell Atlantic would open up its
network to competitors. It approved the SBC-Ameritech merger
because the company agreed to offer local service in the
territories of the remaining Baby Bells. It would like to approve
AT&AMP;T's takeover of Mediaone because AT&AMP;T promises to provide local
phone service over cable lines _ the first important challenge to
the Baby Bells.
</P>
<P>
   If the commission has approved too many mergers, thus stifling
competition, the error means only that local phone rates will
remain too high for too long _ nothing disastrous. That is because
phone companies do not control the content of the calls and
Internet services that flow over their wires.
</P>
<P>
   The troubling issue concerns the rules the commission has issued
for mergers among companies that do control content, notably the
cable companies that decide what we see and hear. If the commission
allows AT&AMP;T to buy Mediaone, Consumers Union argues, one monster
cable company will threaten to dominate the purchase of video
programs _ indeed, a video programmer that fails to sell to AT&AMP;T
might be forced to close up shop.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, a cable channel carrying, say, sports or
Spanish-language programming might need to reach 20 percent of
cable subscribers to generate enough revenue to survive. If one
cable company expanded to 80 percent or more of the market, its
decision to reject the channel would leave it too few subscribers
to survive.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's rules for cable ownership are designed to
preserve diversity. They permit a cable company to serve at most 30
percent of the national market. That would allow at least three
cable companies to exist, each large enough to provide programmers
with enough viewers to survive. That way, no one cable company
could block programmers from finding an audience. But Consumers
Union says the commission's rules are full of loopholes and may not
prevent AT&AMP;T from growing large enough to dominate programmers.
</P>
<P>
   In reviewing mergers of companies that control information, the
commission cannot rely solely on traditional antitrust standards
that are used to protect consumers from paying too much for orange
juice or hair cuts. The commission needs to set a higher standard
even if that means blocking mergers that could pry open the local
phone market. A proper standard would insure that consumers end up
with many providers, not a couple of behemoths that can strangle
the information flow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 1632EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991009.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BROOKLYN-MUSEUM-2TAKE     10-09 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKLYN-MUSEUM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART MUSEUM TRUSTEES SAY CITY HALL PUSHED THEM TOO HARD
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The board of trustees of the Brooklyn Museum of Art
has long been a placid little backwater for the rich and powerful
of New York City. Once, years ago, there was a bit of a dust-up
over a decision to buy an Albert Bierstadt by selling a Winslow
Homer. Some trustees resigned in protest.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, board membership has consisted of tiresome meetings
about museum attendance and budget problems, spiced up with the
obligatory black-tie fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hasn't been particularly memorable,'' Henry Luce III said,
summing up his experience as a trustee.
</P>
<P>
   All that changed two weeks ago, the day the trustees were
summoned to the museum for a climactic meeting about whether to
proceed with a controversial exhibition of contemporary art.
Suddenly, trustees were plotting with ``Mission Impossible''
precision how to sneak into the museum without getting trapped by
reporters. Their wealthy friends, never before all that curious
about their board membership, now could not get enough museum
gossip at cocktail parties.
</P>
<P>
   And by the time they left the museum that evening, this group of
otherwise staid, work-it-out-over-Scotch lawyers and corporate
leaders had been transformed into angry champions of artworks that
most of them did not even particularly like or understand.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews last week, a dozen board members described a
transformation shaped by two pivotal events that day. The first was
a private, trustees-only tour of the ``Sensation'' exhibit. The
second was the trustees' visceral response to Michael Hess, the
city's corporation counsel, who attended the meeting to convey
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's distaste for the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was scary, really scary,'' a trustee, Susan Soros, the wife
of the financier George Soros, said of Hess. ``When he spoke, he
united the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of it had to do with Hess' message. He made it clear that
the only sure way the museum could overcome Giuliani's opposition
was by removing a Chris Ofili painting of the Virgin Mary adorned
with elephant dung and surrounded by cutouts from pornographic
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the trustees had just got their first look at the
exhibition, and while they found some of the works ``kooky,''
``banal'' and ``not very interesting,'' they were almost unanimous
in their admiration of the Ofili painting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Extraordinarily beautiful,'' said Sol Schreiber, a prominent
lawyer and former U.S. magistrate whose tastes lean toward the
tamer realm of glass art.
</P>
<P>
   The entrepreneur John A. Friede, a nephew of Walter H.
Annenberg, said he had got the impression from Giuliani's
descriptions of the Ofili painting that he was going to see animal
excrement smeared over the Virgin Mary. ``It was about as smeared
as a Vermeer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But more than the message, the trustees took offense at the way
it was delivered by Hess and Deputy Mayor Joseph Lhota. On the
whole, the trustees are people used to being courted and coddled
and recognized. In their view, Hess treated them as if he were
sternly lecturing a bunch of unruly teen-agers about proper table
manners. Hess said it was the way the trustees treated him that was
lacking.
</P>
<P>
   Some trustees said Hess called them ``arrogant'' _ an allegation
Hess firmly denies. Particularly galling, they said, was his
assertion that Giuliani could have them removed from the board.
``He can't do that to me, and there would be a terrible stink if he
tried,'' said Luce, who went on to describe Hess as ``a rude and
ugly man.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, several trustees said, a galvanizing moment that
solidified their view of Giuliani and his aides as barbarians at
the gate of artistic expression and dangerous threats to their own
sense of civic order.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shows no amenability to civilized discourse with anyone who
disagrees with him, so what do you do?'' said Richard W. Hulbert, a
retired managing partner of Cleary, Gottlieb, Steen &AMP; Hamilton, a
large Manhattan law firm. ``You've got Attila the Hun baying at you
from City Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Several trustees said they had walked into the boardroom unsure
of what the board would do. Events had transpired so quickly that
no one was sure of the overall sentiment. They had no clear idea
how many trustees might support a proposal _ floated and then
quickly withdrawn the day before by the board chairman, Robert S.
Rubin _ to remove the Ofili painting.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time Hess finished speaking, several trustees said,
there was no longer a doubt about the board's mood. The tense body
language, the fixed facial expressions, the sighs of disgust pretty
much said it all. With one dissenting vote _ from Lhota, the
mayor's representative on the board _ the trustees passed a
resolution authorizing the exhibition to go forward and Rubin to
take any legal action necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Hess said that he went to the meeting in peace and that, if
anything, some of the board members were rude to him. He
particularly recalled a man in a handlebar mustache snickering
during his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   As the voting proceeded, Floyd Abrams, the First Amendment
lawyer who had been retained by the museum the day before, kept a
nervous eye on the clock. At 4:56 p.m., the moment voting finished,
Abrams said, he quietly excused himself to call his office, which
then called one of his associates, who was standing by at federal
District Court in Brooklyn waiting for the signal to file a lawsuit
against Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Hess, who sat next to Abrams during the meeting, thought nothing
of the sudden departure. ``I thought he was going to the men's
room,'' Hess said.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, most of the trustees had been left in the
dark, too. They had not been told that a lawsuit had already been
drawn up, or that it was to be filed the moment they voted. Mrs.
Soros, returning home that night from a dinner honoring Richard C.
Holbrooke, the U.S. representative to the United Nations, turned on
the television and heard the news that the museum had filed suit.
She thought the reporter got the story wrong. ``I had no idea,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Abrams' tactical desire to catch the city by
surprise, the secrecy surrounding the lawsuit reflected the extent
and style of Rubin's influence over the museum. A shy man with a
terse, understated manner _ ``I don't like being in the
newspapers,'' he had told Hess _ Rubin is revered by the museum's
staff for his generosity in time and money. He donated more than $1
million last year.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Yale and the Harvard Graduate School of
Business, Rubin joined Lehman Brothers, the Wall Street investment
firm, in 1958, the same year he and his wife moved to Brooklyn.
Regarded on Wall Street as a brilliant banker, Rubin rose to the
presidency of Lehman Brothers, a position from which he surely
could have had his pick of museum boards. He picked the Brooklyn
Museum of Art, he said, out of a sense of duty to the place where
he and his wife raised four children. ``Brooklyn was good to us,
and I felt that's where I wanted to spend my time that was not
involved in business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such is Rubin's authority at the museum that he felt free to
meet with Hess and discuss possible concessions to Giuliani without
informing the board or the museum's director, Arnold Lehman.
Equally telling, after word of the negotiations leaked _ much to
the chagrin of Rubin _ neither Lehman nor the other board members
criticized Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody questions Bob's good faith,'' said Eugene J. Keilin,
chairman of the Municipal Assistance Corporation. ``He's worked too
hard and too long.''
</P>
<P>
   From the standpoint of demographics, Rubin and the board's 40 or
so trustees are worlds away from the audience the museum is hoping
to attract. Under Lehman, the museum has tried to attract a young,
hip, ethnically diverse audience with a taste for cutting-edge art.
Thus the ``Sensation'' exhibition and its advertisements warning
that viewing it may induce vomiting or shortness of breath.
</P>
<P>
   The museum board, on the other hand, is establishment all the
way, overwhelmingly white and not at all to be confused with
Generation X. A museum spokeswoman, Sally Williams, said three
trustees are members of minority groups. The trustees are a mixture
of major Wall Street players, corporate and civic leaders, or their
spouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very sensible people,'' Hulbert said. ``They're not
bomb throwers.''
</P>
<P>
   Many have roots in Brooklyn, in the arts or in both. Several
visited the museum as children, taking drawing lessons, going on
treasure hunts, or wondering what exactly was inside the mummies.
Others, like Seth S. Faison, a retired insurance executive, form a
kitchen cabinet of Brooklyn leaders who have cross-pollinated the
boards of the borough's major institutions, and who have made a
strategic decision to align Brooklyn's cultural institutions with
the avant-garde.
</P>
<P>
   It has little to do with artistic preferences _ Faison allowed
that many on the academy board preferred the Boston Pops over
Philip Glass _ and a lot to do with extracting Brooklyn's cultural
scene from the long, dominant shadow of Manhattan. So when a
trustee like Jack A. Josephson, an Egyptologist, says that being on
the Brooklyn Museum of Art board ``is not as socially acceptable''
as being on the board of the Museum of Modern Art or the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, he does not say this defensively. He
means it as a point of pride.
</P>
<P>
   Friede said: ``I have relatives on the board of the Met.
Brooklyn is a different kind of board. The Met is sort of like IBM.
While it's considered a great honor, most of what they do is write
checks.''
</P>
<P>
   But they are big checks, far bigger and more plentiful than
those written for the Brooklyn Museum of Art. And if the trustees
of the Brooklyn museum like to think they are in it to elevate art
and not their social status, some suspect that Giuliani felt
emboldened to move against them because he perceived a weakness.
``I'm sure that was in his mind _ `Oh, they're easy game,'''
Josephson said.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the trustees wanted to prove otherwise, to
serve notice that the Brooklyn Museum of Art is nobody's cultural
punching bag.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman had already been quietly trying to beef up the board,
recruiting not only Luce but also Mary Schmidt Campbell, a former
city cultural affairs commissioner who is dean of the Tisch School
of the Arts at New York University.
</P>
<P>
   With polls showing solid public support for the museum, and with
presidential candidates being asked for their opinions about the
museum, many of the trustees now exude a giddy confidence.
</P>
<P>
   They are certain, absolutely certain, they say, that they will
prevail in court. They argue, optimistically, that it will have
been a price well worth paying if one result of the controversy is
that the Brooklyn Museum of Art is branded into the consciousness
of New York City as a pretty cool place to hang out.
</P>
<P>
   But there are pessimists, too, trustees who hold a deep fear
that, win or lose, Giuliani will find a way to hurt the museum. Or
as Friede put it: ``Mommy is going to be mad. And next year is
Christmas. And next year Mommy is going to find a way to slip us a
lump of coal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
