<HEADLINE>
FORD AND AUTOWORKERS AVERT STRIKE WITH TENTATIVE AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Mo., Minn.)  (mk) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ After round-the-clock negotiations lasting
nearly 30 hours, the United Automobile Workers union reached a
tentative agreement Saturday with Ford Motor Co. on a new contract
for its 101,000 unionized workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The UAW has reached a tentative agreement with Ford on a new
contract covering hourly workers at Ford facilities in the United
States,'' the union and the company announced in a joint statement
at 1:30 Saturday afternoon. Both the union and the company refused
to discuss any details of the contract until they have had a chance
to discuss the contract with workers.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Ford contract is expected to have terms nearly
identical to those in contracts the union already reached with
other auto companies, it is expected to cover four years and call
for hefty raises.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's unionized workers would get annual raises of 3 percent on
top of increases that nearly compensate for inflation. In addition,
they would get a $1,350 signing bonus and sweetened pension
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Unionized workers were awaiting details of the contract, but
were pleased that a threatened strike at midnight Friday did not
materialize, despite negotiations that continued past the strike
deadline. Workers are expected to ratify the contract later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure a lot of people are relieved,'' said Rob Bellamy, a
trustee at Local 845 in Plymouth, Mich., where workers build
heaters, radiators and other auto parts for Ford. ``We haven't
heard any other information except that there is a tentative
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement Saturday ends the union's drive this fall to
negotiate new labor contracts covering the nation's 400,000
unionized autoworkers, whose contracts were due to expire Sept. 14
but were extended during the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 16, the union reached a deal with DaimlerChrysler Corp.
covering its 75,000 factory workers in the United States. On Sept.
28, the union reached a deal with General Motors Corp. covering its
143,200 blue-collar workers and 48,000 workers at Delphi Automotive
Systems, the auto parts unit that GM spun off to shareholders in
May. This week, the union told Ford it would end the current
contract at 11:59 p.m. on Friday, and would call a strike if no
agreement had been reached by then.
</P>
<P>
   With auto companies earning record profits, the union was able
to force them to share the wealth with blue-collar workers, who now
earn $50,000 to $100,000, depending on the amount of overtime they
work and the levels of corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the fattest contract in decades,'' said John Casesa,
an auto analyst at Merrill Lynch. ``The auto industry has been in
continuous restructuring since the early '70s, so this was a rare
opportunity to get a piece of meat.''
</P>
<P>
   The union had threatened to strike to show dissatisfaction with
Ford's plan to spin off its giant Visteon Automotive Systems unit
to shareholders. Nearly a quarter of Ford's unionized workers toil
in Visteon factories, and they feared that their jobs and pensions
would be less secure if Visteon were an independent company.
</P>
<P>
   As negotiations continued past the midnight Friday deadline,
thousands of workers at four Ford factories walked off the job,
causing Ford to lose about 13 1/2 hours of production. Workers
building Ford Explorers in St. Louis; pickup trucks and sedans in
Kansas City, Mo.; Ranger pickups in St. Paul, Minn., and Mercury
Cougars in Flat Rock, Mich., walked off their jobs at midshift.
However, the company said Saturday morning that workers at those
factories had reported to work Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Though neither the union nor the company released details
Saturday, Ford was expected to have promised wage and job
protection for its 23,500 Visteon workers in the event of a
spinoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there has been for six months now very intense
separation anxiety prevailing among the Visteon workers,'' said
Scott Merlis, a managing director and head of the automotive
practice at Wasserstein Perella Securities. The fact that the union
and the company overcame those fears without a strike, he said,
``really shows the strength of the historical, amicable
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it has been 23 years since there has been a strike at
Ford, which has basked in sunny labor relations as its rival,
General Motors, suffered 17 strikes in the last six years,
including one last year that cost it $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But after two weeks of bargaining resulted in a settlement here
at Ford's headquarters, local unions _ which had rushed to assemble
picket signs _ were able to put them away again, unused.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
