<SLUG> BC-NJ-COLGATE-REAL-710(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SCRAMBLE FOR OFFICE SPACE IN JERSEY CITY, MANHATTAN'S `WEST
BANK' 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hottest address for investment bankers today is the former
home of a toothpaste and detergent factory.
</P>
<P>
   It is not on Fifth Avenue, the Avenue of the Americas or Wall
Street, but across the Hudson River in Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. is about to close on the purchase of a
waterfront parcel for a million-square-foot office tower where
1,300 workers once churned out Colgate toothpaste, according to
real estate executives and Jersey City officials. And Goldman Sachs
&AMP; Co., the investment bank, is negotiating with Colgate-Palmolive
Co. to buy as many as four other parcels for what could be 3.9
million square feet of office space.
</P>
<P>
   Lord, Abbett &AMP; Co. will move its entire operations there from
the General Motors building. And, real estate brokers said,
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette is looking for space for its Internet
business at the 20-acre site, where Colgate's landmark 55-foot
octagonal clock still illuminates the Jersey City waterfront at
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the hottest address in town,'' said Leonard Boxer, a real
estate lawyer with Stroock &AMP; Stroock &AMP; Lavan who has many Wall
Street clients and a residential project at the Colgate site.
``Jersey City is benefiting from its proximity to where the action
is: New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Chase Manhattan Corp. announced that it would move
3,500 back-office jobs to Florida and Texas, while continuing to
expand in Manhattan. But most financial companies are looking
closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a repeat of the late 1970s or early '90s, when some
Manhattan companies fled a recession- and crime-racked city. Wall
Street is increasingly looking to what New Jersey developers like
to call the West Bank of Manhattan for back office space and,
occasionally, a new headquarters, because financial companies are
booming and large blocks of office space are virtually nonexistent
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Jersey City is less expensive and only minutes away by PATH
train or ferry. State and local governments there are willing to
provide enormous tax breaks and other incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these financial services firms are bursting at the
seams,'' said Richard B. Clark, president of Brookfield Financial
Properties, a major Manhattan landlord. ``They're moving
nonessential functions across the river so they can expand the
front office in Manhattan.''
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of losing large segments of the financial industry,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has provided $2 billion in tax breaks to 50
large corporations threatening to leave Manhattan. But his
administration has failed, urban planners say, to create back
office space in Brooklyn or Queens that may stem some of the
defections to Jersey City, where office rents are $10 to $30 a
square foot cheaper than in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In the last real estate boom, in the 1980s, Mayor Ed Koch
oversaw the development of office buildings in the Long Island City
section of Queens, as well as the Metrotech complex in downtown
Brooklyn, which serves as back office space for Chase Manhattan
Bank and other companies. But those projects have been full for
years.
</P>
<P>
   H. Claude Shostal, president of the Regional Plan Association, a
nongovernmental planning group, said the city should have provided
land and incentives to developers to build additional office space
on waterfront sites outside Manhattan, rather than giving corporate
giants like Time Warner, Bear Stearns and Morgan Stanley billions
in tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no economic development policy,'' Shostal said.
``They've thrown all the incentives at the big guys and they don't
have anything left for the development of back office space or the
small- and medium-sized firms that generate a lot of job growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy L. Levine, deputy mayor for economic development,
disagreed sharply with Shostal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Due to our success in retaining and attracting companies,
there is a shortage of space in Manhattan,'' Levine said. ``We are
trying to find, and in some cases have succeeded, in finding back
office space in Staten Island and College Point, Queens.''
</P>
<P>
   But developers say no Wall Street company would go to College
Point or Staten Island, the psychological equivalent of the other
side of the moon. It is the Colgate site that is suddenly in the
corporate searchlight.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the developers of other Jersey City office parks, Colgate
wants to sell the land rather than lease it. The company's Jersey
City factory closed in 1986 after more than a century of operation.
Colgate sought to turn the site into an office park, and in 1992, a
developer completed what is now called 101 Hudson Street, offices
for both Merrill Lynch and Lehman Brothers. But not much else
happened for years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hartz Mountain Industries is completing one office building
at 90 Hudson Street, which will be a home for Lord, Abbett and the
National Discount Brokers Group, and is starting a second on
another Colgate site.
</P>
<P>
   SJP Properties, one of the largest commercial developers in New
Jersey, recently bought the only remaining factory building at
Colgate and plans to transform it into modern office space, which
has attracted Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, as well as other
potential tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate executives on both sides of the river said Merrill
Lynch would soon complete the acquisition of another parcel for a
large office tower at Colgate. Merrill will almost certainly enjoy
a number of tax breaks, just as it has in Manhattan. Peter
Riguardi, the real estate broker representing Merrill Lynch,
declined to discuss the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jersey City affords large companies the ability to get large
blocks of office space at competitive prices,'' Riguardi said.
``The Colgate sites, in particular, provide them the ability to
control the development.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the developer Lester Fisher won approval from the
Jersey City planning board for a twin-towered complex with 650
apartments that would rise nearly 30 stories over a garage on the
Colgate property.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the prospect of Goldman Sachs' buying all the
remaining land at Colgate that has Jersey City buzzing. The
investment bank has doubled in size (to 3.5 million square feet)
and the number of employees (10,180) in lower Manhattan over the
last four years. Goldman anticipates it will need an additional 2
million square feet by 2004, which brought it to the Colgate site,
where it would own the land.
</P>
<P>
   New York City officials say that Goldman has talked to them
about a vacant lot at the north end of the World Financial Center,
or the office tower over a new trading complex for the New York
Stock Exchange, if and when it is built. But many brokers are
betting on Colgate, where, they said, Goldman is negotiating a
contract to buy two parcels and an option on two others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goldman Sachs is interested in tying up all the remaining
office sites on the river,'' said Joseph Barry, chairman of The
Applied Cos., a residential developer on the Jersey coastline.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the number of companies landing on the Jersey City
beachfront is mounting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the focus on the waterfront will become even more
intense over the next 18 months'' as the economy slows and
corporations become more interested in reducing costs, said Josh N.
Kurilofs, executive director of Cushman and Wakefield, a real
estate broker.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Insurance Services Office, an information
clearinghouse, announced that it would move its headquarters from
Manhattan to an office building under construction at Samuel J.
LeFrak's vast Newport complex on the water in Jersey City. LeFrak
is just finishing a separate building in Newport that will have
offices for PaineWebber, U.S. Trust and Cigna.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Murray, a spokesman for Colgate, declined to discuss any
pending deals. But, he added, ``If everything were to happen, it
would be the culmination of a dream we set out for that site 13
years ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
