<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-LOUIMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATEMENTS IN LOUIMA CASE BECOME ISSUE IN LATEST TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For two years, they have been hovering in the shadows of one of
the most heavily publicized cases of police brutality in New York
City: two police officers charged with lying about what they saw
when Abner Louima was tortured in a Brooklyn police station.
</P>
<P>
   As the case of the two officers, Rolando Aleman, 29, and
Francisco Rosario, 34, moves toward a trial early next year in
federal District Court in Brooklyn, prosecution and defense lawyers
are skirmishing over a crucial question: whether the prosecutors
are illegally using evidence that was supposed to be off limits.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are statements that Aleman and Rosario made to Police
Department investigators not long after Louima, a Haitian immigrant
who was arrested in a street brawl, was attacked in August 1997 by
officers of the 70th Precinct in Brooklyn. Two officers were
convicted and three were acquitted in connection with the actual
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Aleman and Rosario, although not members of the precinct,
happened to be in the Flatbush station house on another case when
Louima was tortured in a bathroom by a precinct officer, Justin A.
Volpe, who rammed a stick into Louima's rectum, causing severe
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The two officers were later questioned by Police Department
investigators about what they had seen. Under department
procedures, officers questioned under such circumstances are told
that any statements they make and any evidence derived from such
statements will not be used in any criminal prosecution against
them.
</P>
<P>
   The two officers were charged with lying to federal
investigators during interviews that were separate from their
sessions with the Police Department. The prosecutors say the
officers first falsely denied they were in the cell area of the
station when Volpe placed Louima in a cell after attacking him.
</P>
<P>
   In later interviews, the prosecutors say, Aleman and Rosario
admitted they had been in the cell area, but falsely said they saw
a different officer place Louima in the cell.
</P>
<P>
   Just what Aleman and Rosario told the Police Department
investigators was not revealed in court papers questioning whether
prosecutors used improper materials, and a defense lawyer in the
case declined to say on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But the defense's papers charge that the two officers'
statements to Police Department investigators might well have been
illegally used by federal investigators and prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers contended that it ``strains credulity'' that
the statements, or evidence stemming from them, were not
``transferred to the federal prosecutors.'' They asked that the
judge in the case, Eugene H. Nickerson, hold a hearing to determine
whether the evidence the prosecution plans to offer at the trial
has been tainted and should be excluded, which could weaken the
prosecution's case.
</P>
<P>
   But, in responding last week, the U.S. Attorney's office in
Brooklyn said that officials in the office responsible for
prosecuting Aleman and Rosario ``have not been exposed'' to the
statements made to police investigators. Certain members of the
office received copies of the interviews, the response said, but
those officials were not involved in investigating and prosecuting
the two officers, and the people who were involved were not given
or told of the statements.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say the two officers lied because they wanted to
avoid becoming witnesses against a fellow officer, a reticence that
law enforcement officials have called the blue wall of silence.
Cracks appeared in that wall when several other officers testified
for the prosecution in the earlier trial, which Volpe interrupted
to plead guilty.
</P>
<P>
   The jury went on to convict another officer, Charles Schwarz, of
helping Volpe, but acquitted three other defendants _ Sgt. Michael
Bellomo and Officers Thomas Bruder and Thomas Wiese _ of other
charges.
</P>
<P>
   The officers have denied they lied to federal investigators, and
on Friday a lawyer for Rosario, Richard W. Levitt, said, ``You can
be sure there's a powerful and credible defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The two officers, who were members of the Street Crimes Unit in
Brooklyn at the time Louima was attacked, are on restricted duty
pending the outcome of their case. If convicted of lying to federal
officials, they could be sentenced to up to five years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
