<SLUG> BC-EDUC-BLOCK-SCHEDULES-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS FIND PLUSES IN MARATHON-LENGTH CLASSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.C., Va., Wis.)  (lb) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTSDALE, N.Y. _ Deborah Valentino's seventh-grade English
class had just passed the 60-minute mark when she suddenly swung
open a classroom window, hoping the autumn air would act like a
cold washcloth on the faces of her 25 students.
</P>
<P>
   They had been heatedly deconstructing the character of Long John
Silver, the two-faced mutineer at the center of ``Treasure
Island,'' but there were still 20 minutes to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't put your head down!'' Ms. Valentino shouted at a
12-year-old boy who was fighting a sore throat, his cheek nestled
on his folded hands. ``We have a lot to do today.''
</P>
<P>
   In another era, Ms. Valentino's sixth-period class would have
ended after 40 minutes, but like hundreds of middle and high
schools across the United States _ more than one out of three, by
some estimates _ Woodlands Middle School rearranged its academic
day last year into a ``block schedule.'' Core courses like English,
math, science, social studies and foreign language now are held in
80-minute marathons, every other day, with no course being held two
days in a row.
</P>
<P>
   In their quest to remake schools in recent years, education
reformers in New York, Virginia and Colorado, among other states,
have repeatedly turned to the block schedule _ with the firm belief
that it gives teachers more time to probe topics in depth and gives
adolescents fewer opportunities to get in trouble while roaming
school halls.
</P>
<P>
   But tinkering with school culture, even a bell schedule, is
never easy, and the challenge of asking teachers and students alike
to sit still for 80 uninterrupted minutes was underscored
dramatically last week when teachers in Yonkers went on strike,
largely over the superintendent's introduction of block scheduling
at the beginning of the new school year.
</P>
<P>
   The Yonkers teachers, their planning books filled with lessons
that had never had to run more than 45 minutes, said that the
superintendent, Andre Hornsby, had confirmed his plans only days
before the start of school. When the strike was settled on
Wednesday, after a four-day walkout, the longtime schedule was
restored and the block schedule was put on hold for further study.
</P>
<P>
   To the teachers at Woodlands, in a separate district a few miles
north of Yonkers in Westchester County, the abruptness with which
the Yonkers superintendent had added block scheduling seems
inconceivable: Before such schedules were installed here, teachers,
parents and business leaders formed a committee that studied the
issue for two years. Once the plan was approved, the teachers had
an entire summer to rework their lessons, exploring ways to break
up their new-found time into what might in effect be several
classes, with lectures supplemented by extended group work, quiet
study and presentations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to change your teaching style,'' said Ms. Valentino,
who has worked at Woodlands for 23 years. ``I don't feel as
stressed out, feeling like I had to scrunch everything into 40
minutes. Things aren't left hanging.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the concept is still fairly new, preliminary studies in
North Carolina _ where nearly three-quarters of all high schools
have switched to block schedules since 1992 _ indicate that
students in the longer classes generally did as well, and often
better, on standardized tests when compared with their peers on
more traditional schedules.
</P>
<P>
   But tests are only one measure of an educational experiment's
promise: Other studies have suggested that students on block
schedules had fewer suspensions and were more likely to make the
honor roll, and that their teachers reported feeling more relaxed,
said Michael Rettig, an expert on block scheduling who is an
associate professor of education at James Madison University in
Harrisonburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that the block schedule, which first migrated
to U.S. school districts from Ontario and British Columbia in the
early '90s, has won universal acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   It should come as little surprise that there is at least one
anti-block-schedule Web site _ www.jefflindsay.com/Block.shtml,
which was created by a Wisconsin parent who contends that an
adolescent is too restless to be confined in a classroom so long.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Among the material listed on the site is a study of the British
Columbia experience by Gordon Gore, a retired physics teacher who
taught for two decades in a small city high school north of
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt the ideal period was 55 minutes to an hour,''
Gore said in a phone interview. ``Beyond that, my personal
experience is that you don't use the time efficiently. You wind up
filling the rest of the time with homework, which they should be
doing elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   At Woodlands, a school of 300, the new schedule has proved most
challenging to teachers of math and special education, who put a
premium on seeing their students, and reviewing material with them,
daily. A concept introduced on a Thursday might not be revisited
until Tuesday, if a Monday holiday intervenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My students need the consistency,'' said Mary Mekeel, who has
taught children with learning disabilities at Woodlands for 10
years. ``I'd take 80 minutes, every day.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Valentino, the English teacher, has embraced her new
hours, and it shows in her class, which is studying
``Frankenstein,'' ``Our Town'' and ``Treasure Island,'' among other
works this year.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday afternoon, she opened the class with a quiz, allowed
perhaps 20 minutes for students to finish a writing assignment
while she stood by to answer questions (``What's watered-down
rum?'' one boy asked), and then permitted them to read another
chapter of ``Treasure Island'' silently before engaging in a
half-hour dialogue. There was even time for Ms. Valentino to take
the discussion off on a tangent, albeit one relevant to literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of you use white-out like you're painting a fence,'' she
told her students at one point as they completed their assignments
at their one-piece, formica-and-metal desks. ``You're like
Huckleberry Finn.''
</P>
<P>
   That comment prompted a brief exchange over how Samuel Clemens
came to take the name Mark Twain _ from the periodic shout of the
riverboat captains seeking to mark the depth of the Mississippi
River. That, in turn, led back to the ship's setting on ``Treasure
Island.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the United States and Canada, there have been two main
branches of the block schedule. While, in general, neither
appreciably adds to or subtracts from the total minutes spent in
one class over the span of a year, the concentration of those
minutes is greater.
</P>
<P>
   In one variation, a course like mathematics meets for a double
period every day for an entire semester and then is replaced,
perhaps by science, for the second semester.
</P>
<P>
   But here in Hartsdale, administrators and teachers settled on
another plan, one that alternates a double period of math on one
day with a double period of science on the next, with the hope that
the material in both classes will seem fresh to students at the end
of the year, when standardized tests are taken.
</P>
<P>
   After Ms. Valentino's class ended at 2:05, having begun at
12:45, all of the students told a visitor they preferred their new
schedules, and not just because homework is no longer due every day
in every subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get to do as much before,'' said Erin Steiner, 12.
``They'd call attendance, you'd take a test and then you'd be
packing up to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Cho, 12, conceded, ``Sometimes, when I try to stay put, my
mind wanders and I forget to pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when the teacher makes jokes once in a while, it's not so
boring,'' he added. ``As long as there's a little fun in there,
it's OK with me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
