<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CELEBRITY-CANDIDATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: CAMPAIGNS OF THE RICH AND IRONIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVEN R. WEISMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  According to Jedediah Purdy, the earnest 24-year-old author of
the new book ``For Common Things,'' irony is the scourge of our era
_ a smirking, self-knowing stance that serves as a ``marker of
worldliness and maturity'' while sheltering us against the
betrayals and disappointments of politics. And to think that he
wrote that before Jesse Ventura, Warren Beatty and Donald Trump
toyed with the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Goofy presidential candidacies have long enlivened American
history, and many third-party candidates were prophets for
honorable causes. But this year the wonder is that so few
experienced people are running for the White House, even in the
mainstream. Each party has only two serious White House candidates
who have ever been elected to anything before _ Democrats Bill
Bradley and Al Gore and Republicans George W. Bush and John McCain
_ and all of them started at the top because they were famous or
had famous names.
</P>
<P>
   There have been many times when a business background was
regarded as a good qualification for the White House. Trump, after
all, is trying to re-create the ``Ross Perot spring'' of 1992, when
the combustible Texas billionaire was in first place in some
presidential polls. Republicans nominated Wendell Willkie in 1940,
and leaders of businesses and universities were often beseeched to
run for president when the system seemed most broken in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   But Trump is better known for his personality than anything he
actually built or accomplished. Today if there are leading figures
in the academic, business or scientific worlds who might qualify
for the presidency, they have little chance of becoming known
without a knack for exploiting the culture's obsession with
celebrities. Famous people fill a void that the writer George W.S.
Trow once called ``the context of no context.'' In his view,
Americans are so busy with work and family that it is easier for
them to relate to the turbulent world of celebrities than to
traditional leadership figures. Personalities like Trump or Beatty
may have useful ideas, and ideas in government often come from
outside the system, but it is their fame that draws attention.
</P>
<P>
   Ideas alone do not make for successful leadership, of course.
Candidates must connect with voters, and a dash of glamour does not
hurt. But one must also remember that Franklin Roosevelt, Abraham
Lincoln and other successful presidents who acted with eloquence,
courage and vision also brought superb skills of political
management, without which they would have failed. Like it or not,
these skills included the art of compromising, reversing course
when necessary, saying different things to different people and
deferring decisions _whether declaring war or signing the
Emancipation Proclamation _ until political circumstances
permitted. These skills are best acquired in mediating the demands
of the legislative and executive branches of government.
</P>
<P>
   The military would seem to be an exception to that rule, but not
really. Speaking of Gen. Dwight Eisenhower, Harry Truman predicted
that ``poor Ike'' would arrive at the White House and order
everyone around, only to find none of them doing what they were
told. But Eisenhower proved to be an effective and popular
president precisely because of the political skills he had acquired
in rising to the top in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Ventura is a case in point for the importance of extended
experience approximating the pressures of governing. His
attention-getting gifts as a wrestler served him well in an
insurgent gubernatorial campaign. But his vulgarities and clumsy
trashing of organized religion have revealed a self-destructive
tendency that it is better to know about before putting someone in
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Lippmann once derided FDR as having nothing particular to
recommend him for high office except that he really wanted to be
president. But at least he had run for office many times. The
coming year will be livelier if there are candidacies by Ventura,
Beatty, Trump, Cybill Shepherd, Oprah Winfrey or whomever. But in
the end, the voters usually choose to be governed rather than
entertained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 1657EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
