<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE METS' GOOFY TRADITION AT SHEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 2nd graf and second-to-last graf with Mets winning
Saturday.) 
 (jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the Mets at Shea Stadium in October, it's never
just baseball. It's been shoe polish and pine tar, a brawl at
second base, a box of scuffed balls. It was all those fans ripping
up chunks of grass in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   And now it's an ``inflammatory response'' to Mike Piazza's
sprained left thumb that benched their cleanup hitter and catcher
this weekend against the Arizona Diamondbacks. Still, the Mets won
Friday night, 9-2, and again Saturday, 4-3, on a 10th-inning home
run by none other than Piazza's replacement, Todd Pratt, to roar
into the National League Championship Series against the Atlanta
Braves
</P>
<P>
   ``It's known as gatekeeper's sprain,'' Piazza said.
</P>
<P>
   Such is life in October in the House That Truth Built _ the
awful truth that New York needed a NL team to replace the departure
of the Brooklyn Dodgers and the New York Giants after the 1957
season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets' tradition in October is being anywhere but Shea.
</P>
<P>
   In nearly 40 years since the Mets were organized, they have
qualified for the post-season only five times. But when the Mets
are at Shea in October, things happen. Goofy things that never seem
to happen anywhere else. Such as Piazza's inflammatory response. Or
the pitch in the fifth game of the 1969 World Series that Mets
leftfielder Cleon Jones claimed hit him on the foot.
</P>
<P>
   Umpire Lou DiMuro disagreed, but when the ball bounced into the
Mets' dugout, Gil Hodges inspected it, walked up to DiMuro and
showed him the black smudge on the ball from the shoe polish on
Jones' spikes.
</P>
<P>
   DiMuro waved Jones to first base, then Donn Clendenon hit a
two-run homer. When the Mets won, 5-3, they were World Series
champions and thousands of fans suddenly decided to study agronomy.
Thanks in part to the smudge of shoe polish on a baseball.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1973 NL Championship Series with the Cincinnati Reds,
Pete Rose objected to shortstop Buddy Harrelson's hard tag and soon
they were rolling in the dirt at second base.
</P>
<P>
   In the brawl that emptied both dugouts and both bullpens, Pedro
Borbon, a Reds' reliever, slugged Buzz Capra, a Mets' righthander.
Duffy Dyer, a Mets' catcher, then slugged Borbon who, in the
confusion, grabbed a cap he thought was his. When he realized it
was a Mets' cap, he chewed it apart with his teeth as he stormed to
the Reds' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   When Rose later trotted to left field, he was pelted with
garbage. So much so that Sparky Anderson, the Reds' manager, took
his team off the field and the umpires threatened a forfeit until
Yogi Berra (then the Mets' manager), Tom Seaver, Willie Mays and
Rusty Staub hurried to left field, pleaded with the fans and
restored the peace.
</P>
<P>
   Those Mets went on to upset the mighty Big Red Machine in that
NLCS before losing the World Series to the Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1986 NLCS with the Houston Astros, Mike Scott, once a
Met, struck out 14 in the 1-0 opener. When the Astros evened the
series at 2-2 with a 3-1 victory, he induced 14 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets believed that Scott's success was due more to
scuffing the ball than to skill. During that fourth game, Davey
Johnson, the Mets' manager, had the batboy collect foul balls and
any other discarded balls whenever Scott was pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Before the fifth game, the Mets displayed a box of the allegedly
scuffed balls to Chub Feeney, the NL president, but Feeney judged
Scott to be not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Mets are such big fans of Mike Scott that they save his
used baseballs,'' said Hal Lanier, the Astros manager, ``they ought
to bring `em over to our clubhouse so he can autograph `em.''
</P>
<P>
   To avert another confrontation with Scott in the seventh game,
the Mets had to win both that fifth game at Shea and a memorable
16-inning sixth game in the Astrodome. Which they did.
</P>
<P>
   Those Mets went on to win the World Series remembered for Mookie
Wilson's grounder that bounced through Red Sox first baseman Bill
Buckner's legs in the sixth game at Shea.
</P>
<P>
   In the third game of the 1988 NLCS that the Mets eventually lost
to the Los Angeles Dodgers in seven games, the Dodgers' reliever,
Jay Howell, was ejected for using pine tar to help grip the ball in
the raw chill as the Mets took a 2-1 series lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth game Dwight Gooden took a 4-2 lead into the ninth,
but Mike Scioscia hit a tying two-run homer, then Kirk Gibson hit a
homer in the 12th. The next day Gibson's homer triggered a 7-4
victory, the last post-season game at Shea until Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   But history shows that whenever something goofy happens at Shea
in October, the Mets win.
</P>
<P>
   They won the World Series with shoe polish, they won the
pine-tar game with Howell, they won after collecting the allegedly
scuffed baseballs, they won the NLCS with the Rose-Harrelson brawl.
</P>
<P>
   And now, they have moved into the NLCS despite Piazza nursing an
inflammatory response.
</P>
<P>
   What's next?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 1659EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
