<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1854 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-DBACKS-ART-N     10-09 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DBACKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRATT'S DRAMATICS SEND METS SOARING TO ATLANTA
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They have mastered the unexpected, become
practitioners of the surprise. Will the Mets ever do anything the
easy way again? And how much more fairy &UR;  &LR; tale can their season get?
</P>
<P>
   Todd Pratt, Mike Piazza's little-used backup who was playing
because the superstar's thumb was badly swollen, slugged a home run
with one out in the 10th inning to help the Mets continue to spin
their through-the-looking-glass tale with a 4-3 victory over
Arizona that propels them into the National League Championship
Series that begins Tuesday against _ oh, no _ Atlanta. The Mets
skipped onto the field as Pratt's ball sailed over the center-field
wall and then Shea Stadium erupted.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets tried everything from saying novenas to blowing smoke
on their bats in an attempt to pull their season together after
their recent encounters with the Braves and it worked. They are the
first Mets team to win a playoff series since 1986, when the Mets
won the World Series. Now, with the dreaded Braves on the horizon
yet again, the Mets can hope that the karma has turned in their
favor. Consider: The last wild card team to advance out of the
division series was the Florida Marlins in 1997. The Marlins won
the World Series with _ you can practically see the planets lining
up, can't you? _ Al Leiter pitching Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   Four outs away from a trip to the NLCS, Armando Benitez, the
fireballing closer who had not allowed a hit in his previous four
appearances, gave up a two-run double to Jay Bell that boosted
Arizona to a 3-2 lead. Then, Edgardo Alfonzo scored to tie the game
on a Roger Cedeno fly ball in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was assisted by Tony Womack, who had just moved from
shortstop to right field (a move he had made seven times during the
season), when he dropped a John Olerud fly ball. But after the Mets
loaded the bases against Arizona's spectacular closer Matt Mantei _
a process interrupted by third-base coach Cookie Rojas' furious
argument that a Darryl Hamilton shot had dropped fair rather than
foul in left field (it was barely foul on the replay) _ Rey Ordonez
struck out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   That set the stage for Pratt's heroics.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter, a player so hyperkinetic that he rarely stands still on
the mound, wove his second straight superb outing Saturday. He had
shut out Cincinnati in the game that won the wild card for the Mets
and Saturday held Arizona to three hits. But he left the game after
putting runners on first and second with two outs _ Womack reached
first when Alfonzo could not backhand a grounder that would have
ended the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter tipped his hat to the roaring crowd of 56,177 and watched
Benitez give up a rare hit to Bell to score the two runs that put
Arizona ahead. Only an outstanding throw from leftfielder Melvin
Mora on a Matt Williams shot into left field that got Bell at the
plate prevented worse damage and gave Alfonzo the opportunity to
tie the score and send the game to extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets wanted desperately to avoid a return to Arizona for
Game 5, where Randy Johnson awaited. But, for the first time in at
least three weeks, there was little pressure on the Mets and in the
upside-down world in which they have thrived for the last week,
that was not the best news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if you gave me a choice or anybody on on the team a
choice, we don't want to have to face Randy,'' Pratt said before
Saturday's game. ``The pressure is all on them. We are up. They
have to win. We don't have to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets have played their most inspired games during their
comeback from a seven-game losing streak when the situation seemed
most dire. When the pressure abated _ as it did in Game 2, when the
Mets had already beaten Johnson in Game 1 _ the Mets faltered,
scoring just one run off Todd Stottlemyre. Saturday, the Mets again
struggled early to generate runs against Brian Anderson, whom
Arizona manager Buck Showalter had chosen to start, rather than
bring Johnson back on short rest.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was 8-2 with a 4.57 ERA, but over his last four starts
of the regular season, Anderson had an ERA of 1.98. Part of the
reason for his success was his ability to limit home runs, a
problem that had plagued him earlier in his career. He tied for
most home runs allowed (38) in the National League last year and he
gave up 16 homers through 18 outings this season. But in his last
13 outings, Anderson gave up just two, a stretch of 641/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, though, after having just one base runner through the
first three innings, Alfonzo opened the fourth inning with a blast
to left field off a 2-2 pitch. It rose quickly and the crowd gasped
as Luis Gonzalez went back and then up on the wall to try to
retrieve the ball. Instead, it landed in the first row of seats for
a 1-0 lead. It was Alfonzo's third home run of the division series.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks were having no better luck against Leiter. He
had been superb in his two previous starts, beating Atlanta by
holding the Braves to two runs on five hits, and then pitching a
two-hit shutout of Cincinnati last Monday in the playoff game.
Leiter seems to thrive in spotlight games, and his teammates had
joked about trying to convince him that Game 4 was do or die. And
he did again Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of a handful of spectacular defensive plays,
including a sliding, shoetop catch by Hamilton of Bell's fly ball
in the fourth, Leiter took a no-hitter into the fifth inning. He
got Williams to fly out to Rickey Henderson to start the fifth. But
then he fell behind Greg Colbrunn, 3-1. Leiter had already walked
two batters, and he had to throw a strike here. He did, and with
that one pitch, which Colbrunn blasted over the left field wall and
Henderson's leap, Leiter had lost the no-hitter and the lead. It
was the first run Leiter had given up after working 17 consecutive
scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets regained the lead when Benny Agbayani, batting in the
cleanup spot for the second straight day in Piazza's absence,
stroked a double to the gap in right center that scored Henderson
with one out. But groundouts by Robin Ventura and Pratt ended the
inning with Olerud, who had earlier hit a single that he could not
stretch into a double, standing on third base. That set the stage
for the wild eighth inning, when the Diamondbacks took the lead,
then were tied by Alfonzo's run.
</P>
</TEXT>
