<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1859 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-HAWKS10-COX     10-09 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks' Mutombo a happy man
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. _ In troubled times, Dikembe Mutombo would go
home to Africa, to his family in Kinsasha, in the former Zaire (now
Congo) and the visit would be brief, maybe three days, and furtive.
Neither he nor his family nor the people of his country were
comfortable under the dictatorship of the late dictator Mobutu Sese
Seko.
</P>
<P>
   But these are increasingly better days.
</P>
<P>
   Last August when Mutombo went home to push harder for the
establishment of a new hospital in Kinsasha, he was in the company
of a TV crew from CBS' ``60 Minutes,'' by American doctors and
members of the U.S. government. He was so well received, the
emotional Mutombo said, that in recounting the story of his visit
tears spring to eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The welcoming I got this year I never had before when I went
home. The way the people welcome me, ministers, people from the
government, people in the street were crying just to see me. Crying
when they were shaking my hand. I wondered to myself, I never
thought I have such major impact on my country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``60 Minutes'' correspondent Ed Bradley will tell the story this
fall and Mutombo looks forward to that. ``Ed Bradley couldn't
believe what he saw _ that I'm going to build a hospital. I'm the
first person to bring this money together, to bring so much
medicine together.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his personal fund-raising campaign, Mutombo has learned
a hard lesson. ``I'm not raising really so much from individuals as
I thought I would. But there are corporations who want to help me.
Turner, Chevron, Mobil. Other companies that have business in
Africa. They want to be represented. By contributing to this
hospital they send the word to the rest of Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many ambitious projects, Mutombo's hospital for 250 beds
is actually getting less expensive to construct, simply because he
is building out, not up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought about building a high-rise hospital. But I been
doing a study and we find that when they build a high-rise in
Africa, including two in Kinsasha already, they have problems with
maintenance. Elevators don't work, things like that, so now we are
going to build on one level. There's no problem moving a patient
from one building to another and that cuts cost. The more you build
flat, the more you save. We have two architects. One says it will
cost no more than $30 million, the other says no more than $50
million. So I told both of them to do their feasibility study and
we'll see. We thought it would cost $55 million, but now we believe
it will be less.''
</P>
<P>
   So, things are going well for Mutombo's hospital and after one
week of training camp, things also are going well for Mutombo's
basketball. ``I am very comfortable with the new people around
me,'' he said. ``I have to contribute as much as I can to make the
club successful, but I know what I have to do: rebound, block
shots, crash the offensive boards. If I can accomplish those three
things, my team is going to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   These are not your father's Hawks. The game is decidedly
uptempo, wild, but fun to watch.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks are running and although Mutombo often dawdled in his
early years with the club, he is as eager as any rookie to get up
and down.
</P>
<P>
   In his recent autobiography, Larry Bird recounts the trials of
Robert Parish. When he first joined the Celtics under Bill Fitch,
Parish could not keep up. Soon, he was out in front on the break,
dunking, getting quick jump shots.
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo can see himself in that role. ``Things get better when
you have a big man who can run. For myself, I've never had any
complaints from any coach I've played for in my eight years that
the big fellow cannot get up and down the floor. I always give of
myself.'' But if they are tuned into a running game, don't think
the Hawks will cheat on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the aggressive style of defense Lenny (coach
Wilkins) wants us to play, it's still going to be hard for a team
to score 100 points against us,'' Mutombo said. ``If they do, we
will tell ourselves we didn't do our job. I don't care, if you have
a guy who can block a shot, a guy can box out, a guy who can
rebound, you will not give up a lot of points.''
</P>
<P>
   That's also true when players are happy.
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo says, ``Me? I'm a very happy man.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
