<P>
   TOBACCO-KY _ PAINT LICK, Ky. _ Baked by a summer-long drought,
some Kentucky tobacco fields will produce half their typical yield.
But the real heat, the farmers say, comes from a $206 billion
health settlement by Big Tobacco. Experts predict cigarette prices
will keep climbing and escalating excise taxes will further
diminish domestic demand. That means Kentucky farmers will need to
grow less tobacco. Their toil has made Kentucky the state most
economically reliant on tobacco and helped generate the country's
highest smoking rate. ``They see themselves under enormous attack
and there's a lot of pessimism,'' said Hampton Henton, director of
Kentucky's Farm Service Agency, which administers price-support
programs. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ALA-LOTTERY _ The showdown on whether Alabama will have a
lottery to compete with Georgia's comes Tuesday (Oct. 12). A look
at Gov. Don Saligenin's on-the-road campaigning for the lottery _
and the vigorous campaign mounted by Christian conservatives and
other gambling opponents. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ESCAPEE _ For 12 years ago, Georgia prison escapee Vianna Edith
Branham was a fugitive. But she didn't exactly keep a low profile,
bulking up as a bodybuilder and competing in national meets. She is
now back in prison, serving a life sentence for murder and armed
robbery. How did she manage to stay free for so long while keeping
such a high profile? (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
