<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ASTROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME ANXIOUS MOMENTS AS BRAVES OUST ASTROS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ By holding off a late Houston rally, the Atlanta
Braves moved on to the next round Saturday in the last game ever
played at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   After building a 7-0 lead in the sixth inning, then watching the
Astros fight back, the Braves advanced to the National League
Championship series against the Mets with an emotional 7-5 victory.
By winning the best-of-5 series, 3-1, the Braves advanced to face
New York in a best-of-7 series starting Tuesday night in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Houston refused to go quietly in the ninth inning. Stan Javier
opened by drawing a walk off the relief pitcher John Rocker, then a
wild pitch by Rocker moved Javier to second base. But Rocker got a
big strikeout against Jeff Bagwell, who finished just 2 for 13 in
another disappointing playoff series for him. Bagwell tried to
check his swing on the third strike, but the home plate umpire,
Dana DeMuth, ruled that Bagwell had swung.
</P>
<P>
   With his adrenaline rushing, Rocker, throwing extremely hard,
struck out Carl Everett, bringing the dangerous Ken Caminiti to the
plate with a chance to tie the score. But Caminiti was retired on a
deep fly to center field that was run down by Andruw Jones, and the
Braves, who led the major leagues with 103 regular-season
victories, began to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who will move into a new downtown stadium next year
after playing at the Astrodome since 1965, were eliminated in the
first round for the third consecutive year; they have never won a
postseason series. The Braves advanced to the NLCS for the eighth
time this decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros showed tremendous character in the eighth inning with
a four-run rally that cut Atlanta's lead to 7-5 and knocked John
Smoltz out of the game. Bagwell started the surge with a single,
then Smoltz hit Everett with a pitch. Caminiti, Houston's best
player in the series, cleared the bases with a three-run home run
to center field that brought the fans to their feet, hoping they
might witness a stunning comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta manager Bobby Cox had seen enough of Smoltz at that
point, and replaced him with Terry Mulholland. With nobody out, the
fans were still on their feet, looking for more runs. Chris Spiers
flied out to center field, but Tony Eusebio followed with a single.
That brought Tim Bogar, who had two hits, to the plate. Bogar
delivered again, this time crushing a line-drive double to the
left-center-field gap to score Eusebio all the way from first base.
Now the Astrodome was really rocking, with Houston bringing the
potential tying run to the plate and still only one out.
</P>
<P>
   Cox made another pitching change, turning to Kevin McGlinchy to
face Daryle Ward. McGlinchy got Ward on a ground ball to first
base, while Bogar went to third base. That brought up Craig Biggio,
who has struggled mightily in the postseason throughout his career.
Biggio had a dismal career.130 postseason average before this
series. Saturday, Biggio was 0 for 3 in his first three at-bats,
making him 2 for 17 in the series.
</P>
<P>
   But Cox took no chances, replacing McGlinchy with Rocker to face
Biggio. And Biggio continued to fail under pressure, as he struck
out swinging to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta threatened to rout Houston with a five-run sixth inning
to go ahead by 7-0. The Braves sent 10 batters to the plate, and
they whacked seven singles, chasing Shane Reynolds from the game
and also manhandling relief pitcher Chris Holt. Brian Jordan, the
offensive star of the series, opened the rally with a single,
followed by a single by Ryan Klesko. At that point, Astros manager
Larry Dierker replaced Reynolds with Holt, but that was like
throwing gasoline on a fire.
</P>
<P>
   Holt surrendered three consecutive hits and three runs. Jones
hit a single to left-center field that scored Jordan, and when left
fielder Spiers bobbled the ball in the outfield, Klesko moved to
third base and Jones moved up to second. Eddie Perez knocked in
both runners with a single that made the score 5-0, then Jose
Hernandez singled Perez to second base. Holt was relieved by Scott
Elarton, but Smoltz sacrificed the runners to second and third
base, and Gerald Williams singled to drive in Perez and Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves grabbed a 1-0 lead in the first inning on a sacrifice
fly by Chipper Jones. Williams had lined the first pitch of the
game into left field past a diving Spiers, and the ball rolled to
the wall for a double. Bret Boone moved Williams to third base with
a fly ball to right field, and Jones' fly ball scored Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz helped himself with his bat, as Atlanta added another run
in the third inning. Smoltz led off the third inning with a double
over the head of right fielder Javier, who was playing shallow.
After Williams sacrificed Smoltz to third base, Boone ripped a
single to left field that scored Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   Houston finally scored in the seventh inning on a leadoff home
run by Eusebio, but it seemed too little, too late. When the Astros
needed a timely hit this weekend, they rarely got one. Before the
eighth inning, Houston continued its pattern of wasting scoring
opportunities, leaving a combined five runners on base in the first
two innings while failing to score. In the first inning, the Astros
loaded the bases with two outs, but Spiers grounded out to second
base. In the second inning, Houston had runners on first and third
with two outs, but Javier grounded out to third base.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the Astros never recovered from Friday's crushing
12-inning loss in Game 3, in which they failed to score in the 10th
inning after loading the bases with nobody out. They will have all
winter to reflect on that loss, while the Braves will be looking
forward to the next series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
