<SLUG> BC-BOAT-COASTGUARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.)  
 COAST GUARD RESCUE ABILITY IS LAGGING 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the stormy early hours of Dec. 29, 1997, after an ill-fated
decision to abandon the protected waters of the Intracoastal
Waterway and head out to the open sea, the captain of the 34-foot
sailboat Morning Dew set a course for safe harbor in Charleston,
S.C. Neither he nor his three young crewmen would live to see the
coming new year.
</P>
<P>
   What happened that day has been the subject of intense scrutiny
and investigation. Last Tuesday, the National Transportation Safety
Board released a summary of its long-awaited report on the
incident. The board concluded that the 49-year-old skipper, Michael
Wayne Cornett _ whose crew included his two teen-age sons and a
nephew _ and personnel at U.S. Coast Guard Group Charleston played
contributing roles in the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Cornett was blamed for his ``failure to assess and respond to
the known risks of the journey that culminated in the vessel's
collision with the jetty at the entrance to Charleston Harbor.''
The Coast Guard was cited for ``substandard performance in
initiating a search-and-rescue response'' _ an SAR in Coast Guard
parlance _ ``to the accident.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Coast Guard, the report comes on the heels of recent
public pronouncements from two high-ranking officials regarding the
service and its overall SAR capability. In his State of the Coast
Guard address last May, Commandant James Loy admitted to ``very
real readiness shortfalls'' across the ranks and likened his troops
to a knife dulled from overuse.
</P>
<P>
   And in a speech at a marine trades show in August, Rear Admiral
Terry Cross said: ``Our distress communications system is
equivalent to what local police and fire departments were using in
the 1950s. I think most recreational boaters would be alarmed to
learn how fragile this weak link in our search-and-rescue system
really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulty communications were central to the Morning Dew case. At
2:17 a.m. on that December morning, the Coast Guard received a
distress call that was later confirmed, via computer enhancement,
to be a mayday from the stricken vessel. Unable to re-establish
contact, the Coast Guard ignored the call. Hours later, a
commercial vessel reported hearing voices in the water. But the
Coast Guard did not initiate a search until bodies washed ashore.
</P>
<P>
   In a phone interview last week, Cross suggested that, had
available technology been used, the catastrophe could have been
averted. ``The watch-stander did not have the ability to play back
and immediately enhance the transmission,'' he said. ``We think
that equipment should be part and parcel of all our ops centers. If
he'd heard the word mayday, it would've elicited a different
response.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross listed additional flaws with what is known as the National
Distress System. ``Theoretically, you should be able to make a call
via VHF radio anywhere along the continental coast within 20 miles
and this system would be able to hear you and initiate a response
from us,'' he said. ``The fact is there are numerous gaps,
including some places between New Jersey and Virginia and on the
Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``And very few of these stations have any kind of
direction-finding capability,'' he added. ``So even if we hear you,
if you can't in a calm, rational manner tell us where you are and
what your problem is, it's going to be very difficult to find
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard received some promising news when Congress
appropriated $16 million for fiscal year 2000 to begin upgrading
the distress system in what is expected to be a five-year project.
But Cross acknowledged that there are other problems within the
service that must be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   Due to budget and work-force streamlining, he said, today's
Coast Guard is the same size as it was in 1963, with roughly 35,000
active-duty members. But with drug and fisheries law enforcement,
search and rescue, and other responsibilities, the overall mission
has expanded. With fewer people standing longer watches, there has
been a marked increase in work-related injuries and accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average experience of our small-boat crew members, the
ones that primarily interact with the recreational boating public,
is 11.4 months,'' Cross said. ``That's not a lot in a boat crew,
the ones who go out and recover those folks who find themselves in
trouble. I'm not saying those people aren't technically qualified,
because they are. But that's not where we want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   In launching his own personal distress flare, Cross said: ``You
probably haven't heard Coast Guard officers come out and talk like
this in the past. I'm not overly concerned with where we are today,
but I am with the trend. And it absolutely needs to be turned
around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
