u s BC-SOC-SPAIN-RAYO-NYT &LR;      10-09 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SPAIN-RAYO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPANISH SOCCER TEAM EXCELS ON SHOESTRING BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN VINOCUR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ Life is fashioning one of its sweet parentheses
in Spain these days, bracketing out money, power and arrogance for
a long, dreamy moment.
</P>
<P>
   A soccer team from a throwback of a working-class neighborhood,
its president a woman, its budget a pittance, its goalkeeper an
American, has hiked to the top of the first division from its end
of the subway line. Rayo Vallecano, with no practice field, no gym,
no official Web site, subsists with an annual operating budget of
about a third of the $35 million it cost this summer for Real
Madrid, European soccer's eternal rich guy, to buy Nicolas Anelka
from Arsenal in the English Premier League.
</P>
<P>
   But there is Rayo, a corner grocery in the world of Big Soccer,
promoted from the under-leagues, ahead of Real, and tied in points
and won-lost record at the front of the Spanish Liga, more than a
month into the season.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Van de Velde holes out of the water hazard and actually
wins the British Open. The Toledo Mud Hens, up from Class AAA, take
the lead in the American League. And if fantasy digs in, and Rayo
keeps going and going over the next 33 league matches and actually
wins it all?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' said Kasey Keller, the American goalkeeper, looking
both delighted and lucid on a brilliant early autumn day. ``Nah.''
</P>
<P>
   Logic, in all its brutality, insists that Rayo will falter, and
that the symbols of profligacy and disdain, teams like Real, or FC
Barcelona, which shares the league's best record with Rayo, will
run over the little guy. Their deep rosters of millionaire
manpower, in the end, never surrender a point to sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moral of Rayo's experience, if you insist, is that money
is very important,'' said the team's spokesman, Fernando Lopez,
with a laugh, before moving quickly away from discussions about
what wealth cannot buy or what Rayo cannot win. In a league where
Barcelona's Nou Camp stadium holds 106,000, Rayo drew 6,000, 8,000
and then 12,000 to its Estadio Teresa Rivero in its first three
home games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's insufficient,'' Lopez said. ``The reality is that our
ambition stops with staying in the first division.'' But with
soccer embedded so deeply in Spain's national consciousness, Rayo's
success and Anelka's failure so far for Real _ the 21-year-old
Frenchman has collected no goals and hoots of derision since the
season began _ provide an antithesis too gaping not to create
comment about the meaning of all the money thrown into soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Clemente, a former national team coach, said last week
that Anelka's cost to Real Madrid ``looks to me like an insult to
society. In a modest country, with a lot of cultural, political and
social deficiencies, those millions could do a lot. I think Madrid
has enough social problems so that modest people are not asking
themselves, above all, if Anelka is going to score 25 goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``With those millions,'' Clemente said, ``you could take care of
everybody who's hungry in Madrid.''
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, some of the hungry actually lived in Vallecas,
the Madrid neighborhood where Rayo Vallecano _ the Vallecas
Thunderbolt _ has been at home for 75 years, climbing into the
First Division for seven of them, and then usually heading right
back down again. The neighborhood has a strong left-wing,
working-class character, and red brick apartment houses crowd to
the edge of its 19,500-seat stadium, so fans leaning on window
sills, as at Wrigley Field in Chicago, can look out and watch. In
stark contrast, Real's roots are steeped in a Fascist past; Real
Madrid was Franco's team.
</P>
<P>
   When Keller, the U.S. national team goalkeeper who came to Rayo
this year from Leicester City in England, was introduced as an
American to local supporters at a get-to-meet-the-players function,
they shouted, ``Viva Castro!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' said Keller, amused, ``it's a very interesting
place for an American to be. It's a socialist area, bordering on
communist. I feel I'm liked by the crowd. And I guess I'm about as
non-communist as you can be. I'm a guy who likes Steve Forbes'
flat-tax idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the armies of players, suits and p.r. men at Real
Madrid, Rayo's operations are very, very small beer indeed. Lopez
says the club has 15 employees, including three groundskeepers. Its
fans, he said, had become accustomed over the years to splitting
their affections, backing Real or Atletico, Madrid's second
super-rich team, regardless of their swank, as beloved Rayo
scuffled in the lower depths.
</P>
<P>
   While FC Barcelona has 100,000 socios (supporters' club-paying
members with season ticket rights), and Real 60,000, Rayo has
5,700. The biggest advertising sign on the stadium walls is for a
mattress company, and the souvenir shop has a handwritten poster
taped to its display window offering cut-rate prices on club
jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Rayo's payroll is essentially provided by the company of Jose
Maria Ruiz Mateos, a businessman cleared two years ago of
falsifying documents while he was head of the Rumasa conglomerate,
expropriated in 1983 by the then-Socialist government. Ruiz Mateos'
wife, Teresa Rivero, after whom the little Vallecas stadium was
renamed, was made the club's president five years ago, and she has
become its main cheerleader.
</P>
<P>
   What Rayo has done this year, after winning promotion from the
second division, is to play extremely well, with the kind of
generousness known mostly to poverty. Its victories have included
two against international heavyweights, Atletico and Celta Vigo,
and it dominated Zaragoza before missing a penalty kick for its
first loss, 1-0, last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of all of Rayo's affecting modesty, Luis Cembranos
has emerged as a rising star who could be a national team
selection.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Anelka, Keller said, Real might have got itself a
Mike Tyson type, with ``an entourage standing around shouting, `You
the champ, you the man!' and cutting him off from any kind of
reality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
