<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1868 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NY-REZONING-REAL-925(     10-09 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REZONING-REAL-925(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW YORK'S FLOWER DISTRICT, A CROP OF HIGH-RISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seven years ago, Manuel Castedo moved his
architectural practice into a 24-story loft building at 307 Seventh
Ave., near 27th Street, that was filled with furriers.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, he has been watching the fur flee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the first office tenant in this building,'' Castedo
recalled. Now there are telecommunications and computer companies
and other architects. Only a half dozen furriers remain.
</P>
<P>
   Change is engulfing the old fur, fashion, flower and flea market
districts along Seventh Avenue and Avenue of the Americas in the
West 20s. Castedo himself is contributing to the trend as the
architect of a project at 291 Seventh Ave., a block from his
office, a loft building that is being turned into nine
floor-through apartments by Houlihan-Parnes Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   And that is one of the smaller undertakings.
</P>
<P>
   In an area that has seen little new building since the Fashion
Institute of Technology completed its Seventh Avenue megastructure
in 1976, 2,100 housing units in seven projects, ranging from 10 to
37 stories and representing an investment of over $600 million, are
under construction or planned to begin within six months.
</P>
<P>
   Spurring the transition are rezonings along Seventh Avenue and
Avenue of the Americas that permit residential development in what
used to be manufacturing districts.
</P>
<P>
   Developers like to say that they are expanding the boundaries of
Chelsea northward, transforming unsightly parking lots into needed
homes and amenities. But to those who live or work in the
neighborhood, it feels more as if the high-rise, high-rent contours
of mid-Manhattan are being extended south, threatening daylight,
small businesses and lower-income residents.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond dispute is that another urban frontier, resistant to
change even in the robust market of the 1980s, is at last being
breached.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were these parking-lot sites lying fallow on the avenues
and there's clearly a great residential demand,'' said Joseph Rose,
the chairman of the City Planning Commission. ``The zoning changes
to permit residential development on those avenue sites made sense.
And now, after a long wait, it is under way.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Rose said the commission would guard the side
streets where so much small industry still exists. ``The commission
has been on record as vehemently opposing any zoning variances for
the mid-blocks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that ``one could engage in an interesting debate''
on whether tall towers suited the area, Rose said their setbacks
were meant to bring light and air to the mid-blocks.
</P>
<P>
   What the planning chairman envisions is a mixed-use neighborhood
in which apartment buildings, stores and light industry coexist.
</P>
<P>
   Some local leaders are not nearly as sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Christine Quinn said she fears that ``we've now
taken 23rd Street and, in our minds, decided that's where midtown
begins, which means that it's OK to have really large buildings and
it's not a place for small, family industries'' like sewing-machine
shops, printers, mannequin makers, furriers and flower dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will businesses be forced out but residents will see
housing costs soar beyond their reach, said Kevin Finnegan,
co-chairman of the land-use and zoning committee of Community Board
5 in mid-Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that what's under development is going to have
significant impacts on nearby neighborhoods,'' he said. ``Already
in Chelsea, if you're not in a rent-stabilized apartment, you know
you're going to have to move when the lease is up. This is going to
accelerate the same pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Housing costs are on the rise in the area from 22nd to 28th
streets, Seventh Avenue to Avenue of the Americas. According to the
Corcoran Group, average sales prices to date this year were
$282,000 for one-bedroom apartments, up 101 percent since 1996, and
$525,000 for two-bedroom units, up 119 percent. The median rents
were $1,650 for studios, up 34 percent since 1996; $2,800 for
one-bedroom units, up 70 percent, and $3,650 for two-bedroom units,
up 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Given the demand, Rockrose Development Corp. has repeatedly
raised prices at Chelsea Mercantile, an enormous loft building on
Seventh Avenue, between 24th and 25th streets, that it is
converting into a 354-unit condominium. The architect is Avinash
Malhotra, with public spaces designed by Gruzen Samton.
</P>
<P>
   Penthouse C, a 2,246-square-foot, three-bedroom duplex with a
commanding a view, was offered in May for $1.56 million. In June,
it was priced at $1.88 million; in July, $2.05 million. Today, the
price is $2.15 million.
</P>
<P>
   And Rockrose is having no trouble finding buyers. Last month,
with the building still under construction, 205 units were under
contract, said Kevin Singleton, vice president and general manager
of Rockrose.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground floor, Whole Foods Market Inc. of Austin, Texas,
plans to open a 40,000-square-foot Fresh Fields Whole Foods Market
next summer. The company calls itself the ``largest purveyor of
natural foods in the world'' but does not have a New York City
outlet. (It is not connected with Whole Foods of SoHo, 117 Prince
St., or Whole Foods-Uptown, 2421 Broadway, at 89th Street.)
</P>
<P>
   ``As we're developing a mini-neighborhood, this use is ground
zero,'' Singleton said. Rockrose is poised to do for lower Seventh
Avenue what it has already done in the West Village: transform the
area with a mix of new and renovated buildings, condominiums and
rental units, some of them subsidized for lower-income tenants.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It came on the scene last year by winning a sealed bid for what
is now Chelsea Mercantile, a U-shaped structure built in four
phases from 1906 to 1914. Long ago, the building housed National
Cloak and Suit Co. and more recently the federal Department of
Veterans Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Rockrose also owns the lots between Chelsea Mercantile and the
Fashion Institute of Technology, where it plans a 356-unit
``80-20'' rental project, designed by Costas Kondylis &AMP; Associates.
Thomas Elghanayan, the president of Rockrose, said the project was
made possible by the rezoning of a large swath of Chelsea earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially two buildings on an L-shaped parcel, the project
will face the avenue with a bay-fronted structure of 10 stories,
rising to 17 stories. An 11-story wing on 26th Street could be used
as a dormitory, Elghanayan said. Rockrose will seek tax-exempt bond
financing for one or both parts of the project, which would oblige
it to set aside 20 percent of the units for lower-income tenants,
with 80 percent at market rates.
</P>
<P>
   Rockrose does not think small and Elghanayan allowed that he is
pursuing other projects nearby. ``I can't disclose what,'' he said,
``but we're interested.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fashion Institute of Technology is similarly circumspect
about its future. But Jacqueline Venable, the vice president for
institutional advancement, said there is a master plan, within the
existing boundaries of the campus, ``to renovate, modernize and
expand our facilities to respond to the growth in our student body
and the changes in the industries we serve.''
</P>
<P>
   FIT will offer weekend courses in decorating and refinishing
next year. ``I want to serve the people who want to live around
here,'' said Elaine Stone, the acting dean for continuing
education, ``and make them feel that this is a community.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Stone began teaching at FIT 22 years ago _ in a Quonset
hut _ furriers still filled numerous buildings along Seventh
Avenue. No longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a lot of consolidation in the fur industry,'' said
Vincent Terranova, executive vice president of Bernstein Real
Estate. ``They are not occupying as much space as they used to.''
The company, which owns and manages lofts in the fur district and
elsewhere, was founded by Sidney J. Bernstein, now 95, whose father
was a furrier. The industry has not entirely vanished, however. For
example, 150 West 30th St. is still ``100 percent fur,'' Terranova
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The side streets are really remaining the same,'' Ms. Stone
said. ``I think it will stay a mixed neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is a different place from what it was in the early
1970s when a self-described ``neophyte broker'' named Harry
Macklowe of Wolf &AMP; Macklowe began selling property to a menswear
executive, Leonard Adell.
</P>
<P>
   Adell had an office at Avenue of the Americas and 31st Street.
Where others saw a streetscape that had been badly stunted by
decades under the Sixth Avenue el, Adell saw solid infrastructure,
good transportation and high visibility.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 1970s, Adell painstakingly assembled small
parcels along Avenue of the Americas into three sites, including
the Coogan Building at 26th Street, which was built in 1875 as the
Racquet Court Club but had long been used as loft space.
</P>
<P>
   ``This recent wave of activity is testimony that he was right,''
said Leonard's son, Matthew Adell, who is president of Adell Corp.
``We were alone in our vision for many, many years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Adells failed in their efforts to obtain a rezoning in the
late '70s and early '80s. Then, in 1989, the Coogan was designated
a landmark as ``one of the oldest surviving club buildings in
Manhattan.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, the Board of Estimate overturned the
designation. And a rezoning of Avenue of the Americas was enacted
in 1995. But the real estate market was not yet ready, Matthew
Adell said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, in partnership with Steven Witkoff, president
of the Witkoff Group, the younger Adell bought the three sites
assembled by his father. The parcels will be developed in phases,
as the market warrants, Adell said. The working title of the
project is ``Center Six.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Construction is to begin early next year of the first ``Center
Six'' building, between 26th and 27th streets: a $120 million tower
with 387 rental apartments. Because it will be conventionally
financed, Adell said, all the units will be market rate, probably
ranging from $1,700 to $4,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a mid-block plaza to the east of the building,
which generated a 20 percent zoning bonus. The faceted facade steps
up from a four-story commercial base to a 37-story turret.
Kondylis, the architect, said that the turret would serve as an
``urban signal,'' akin to the campaniles and domes of Europe, and
that the rounded corners echoed older buildings in the area.
</P>
<P>
   But the tower is also replacing the Coogan Building, which Quinn
and others would like to save.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Raab, the chairwoman of the landmarks commission, said
her predecessors ``did absolutely the right thing in designating
the building'' but that the ``political process reversed the
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you refight those battles?'' she asked. ``We decided not to
do that. The political process has spoken and there is no reason to
believe the politics would be any different'' _ especially since
the city subsequently rezoned the site to encourage the kind of
development Adell envisions.
</P>
<P>
   Landmarks and planning officials had more influence on the
design of the Caroline, a 440-unit, ``80-20'' rental building on
Avenue of the Americas, between 22nd and 23rd streets, in the
Ladies' Mile Historic District. Fraydun Manocherian, who leads a
partnership known as Whitehall Properties in the development of the
site, said he hoped construction might begin in a month or two.
</P>
<P>
   True to its setting in the historic shopping district, the
building will have a lot of retail space _ almost 100,000 square
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Richard Cook &AMP; Associates and Kondylis to complement
the old dry-goods stores nearby, the Caroline will rise 10 stories
on the avenue, doubling in height along 23rd Street. ``It's
completely counterintuitive to the standard statement as to how
Manhattan blocks develop,'' Cook said, ``but this was a very
careful insertion into the urban fabric.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's such a critical site in terms of the character of the
area that it deserved a building that paid attention to its obvious
context,'' said Rose, the planning chairman. And Ms. Raab believes
that ``the materials and the design took a historic motif and
turned it into 21st-century language.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn is unpersuaded. ``Sometimes in land use,'' she said, ``we
lull ourselves into thinking that what we've made better is in fact
good.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Manocherian said the result of the long
negotiations was a ``very unique building.'' Having bought the site
in 1984, he has been waiting almost as long as the Adells to begin
development.
</P>
<P>
   It is a couple of newcomers to the area, Albanese Development
Corp. and Arbor National Commercial Mortgage, who have become the
first to build on Avenue of the Americas under the new zoning.
</P>
<P>
   Their 30-story tower at 750 Ave. of the Americas, between 24th
and 25th streets, will have 300 studio, one-bedroom and two-bedroom
apartments, plus 15,000 square feet of retail space. It is an
``80-20'' project and is scheduled to open next May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we broke ground there was nothing going on'' in the way
of new construction, said Christopher Albanese, executive vice
president of Albanese Development. ``We're very excited that other
residential projects will follow us.''
</P>
<P>
   Macklowe, who returned to the area a few years ago with a
condominium conversion called the Chelsea Atelier, at Seventh
Avenue and 24th Street, sees the neighborhood taking form. ``This
is a logical, sequential development from Houston Street straight
up Sixth Avenue,'' he said. ``You're going to have a concentration,
which I think will really be beneficial in creating what they refer
to as a critical mass.''
</P>
<P>
   The Macklowe Organization is planning a 31-story tower at 777
Ave. of the Americas, between 26th and 27th streets. There are to
be 291 rental apartments in this $80 million project, which will
take advantage of a zoning bonus that rewards the construction of
lower-income housing elsewhere in the community board district.
Schuman Lichtenstein Claman Efron are the architects of the
Albanese and Macklowe towers.
</P>
<P>
   With the construction of these projects, Alan Boss' Annex
Antiques Fair and Flea Market Inc. has lost two parking lots on
which it conducts its well-attended weekend markets.
</P>
<P>
   Boss expects to operate for the foreseeable future in the lot on
the west side of the avenue, between 24th and 25th streets; in the
lot to the west and paralleling the avenue, between 25th and 26th
streets and in the lot on the east side, between 25th and 26th
streets. Ultimately, he might consolidate the market elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Boss is less certain than the developers that luxury housing is
the salvation of an area he has known for 23 years. ``What happens
when the cycle goes down?'' he asked. ``People can't pay $2,500 for
a one-bedroom if they don't have a job.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also sounds resigned to the construction going on around
him. ``I always knew it would be developed,'' Boss said. ``After
all, it's New York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
