<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1876 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-MIAMI-FLORIDASTAT     10-09 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MIAMI-FLORIDASTATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO WARRICK, BUT FLORIDA STATE STILL DEFEATS MIAMI 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Heisman Trophy candidate Peter Warrick,
freshly suspended for grand theft, asked his Florida State
teammates before Saturday's game against Miami to focus on the
Hurricanes, not on his problems.
</P>
<P>
   They took his advice, especially the team's wide receivers, and
came away with an emotionally charged 31-21 victory before 80,976,
the third-largest crowd in Doak Campbell Stadium history.
</P>
<P>
   The victory allowed 6-0 FSU (ranked No. 1 by The Associated
Press and No. 5 in The New York Times computer rankings) to move
significantly closer to the school's first unbeaten season under
coach Bobby Bowden. The Seminoles have a record 12 straight
Associated Press top four finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Chris Weinke's 332 yards passing featured
completions to 11 receivers, including seven filling the spots
vacated by Warrick and his accused fellow offender Laveranues
Coles, who was dropped from the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys have been crying the whole year about not getting
enough playing time,'' senior wide receiver Ron Dugans said at a
Friday night meeting of the team's receivers. ``Well, this is
gutcheck time. You're getting your chance.''
</P>
<P>
   What replacing Warrick and Coles boiled down to, according to
flanker Germaine Stringer, is spelling two fast receivers with two
just as fast. Stringer caught one touchdown pass and Dugans led the
parade with five catches for 80 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this tells FSU fans and the world,'' Stringer said in a
jubilant FSU locker room, ``is that we have more than one or two
guys who can catch the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick watched the game on the sideline, wearing a garnet
T-shirt and jeans and waving a white towel throughout, as
Saturday's renewal of one of FSU's most intense rivalries kept most
people in suspense until halfway through the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This reminded me of those old FSU-Miami games about 10 years
ago,'' Bowden said. ``This was a shootout of quarterbacks, and
Weinke won. But boy, was it tight!''
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Kenny Kelly threw for 370 yards, which included three
touchdowns and one interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have won this game,'' Kelly said. ``We were in
position to win, if we could have made a few more plays.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Weinke, he said afterward: ``I really don't want to talk
about Peter at all, because that's over and done with. This
football team showed up today, and we won.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, there was the usual bluster that this rivalry
generates. Miami's players trotted en masse to a giant FSU logo at
midfield. Sensing some encroachment to their home field, the
Seminoles also rushed to midfield, and coaches had to restrain both
sides from making contact.
</P>
<P>
   The game was just as spirited, and the first half ended tied at
21-21. The Seminoles took a 24-21 lead with seven minutes 59
seconds left in the third quarter on Sebastian Janikowski's 38-yard
field goal. Travis Minor's 2-yard touchdown run with 9:55 left in
the game gave FSU a 31-21 lead and a little breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, the Hurricanes were not out of it. But FSU's defense
continued its dramatically improved second-half play, allowing
Miami just eight first downs in seven second-half series.
</P>
<P>
   The first half definitely favored those who were partial to
offensive football. The teams combined for 78 plays and a whopping
529 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles opened the game's scoring in their second series,
and it came like a lightning bolt _ a 48-yard pass from Weinke to
the wide open Stringer.
</P>
<P>
   The teams then traded touchdowns until the game reached 14-14.
</P>
<P>
   Miami went 80 yards to score on split end Reggie Wayne's
eight-yard catch from Kelly. Then the Seminoles countered by going
65 yards in 13 plays, with running back Jeff Chaney's 3-yard run
ending it.
</P>
<P>
   One play later, Kelly found Santana Moss free at midfield, and
the speedy flanker outmaneuvered both rover Derrick Gibson and
cornerback Reggie Durden to complete a dazzling 80-yard play.
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied at 14-14, there was still 4:03 left in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   FSU was on the verge of scoring again late in the quarter, but
Miami cornerback Al Blades wrestled the ball out of fullback Dan
Kendra's hands at the Seminoles' 11.
</P>
<P>
   Miami seized that opportunity to put together its best drive of
the game and take its only lead. The drive lasted 13 plays and
covered 89 yards, with Moss slipping behind several Seminoles in
the left corner of the end zone for the 14-yard payoff.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes' lead lasted less than four minutes. Weinke
completed four passes for 64 yards on Florida State's next drive,
including an 18-yarder for the first touchdown for tight end Ryan
Sprague and a 21-21 tie.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, FSU had a little too much of everything for Miami _
Weinke, receiving talent and defense.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said afterward that he had found himself pleading for a
misdemeanor in Warrick's case, although he is not used to pleading
for misdemeanors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't want to lose the talent,'' Bowden said. ``It's
funny how things work out, but our guys came together today and
played a gutty game in a critical situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
