<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 MORRIS PASHMAN, 87, CHAMPION OF FREE SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Justice Morris Pashman of the New Jersey Supreme Court,
whose opinions touched on areas from freedom of the press to the
rights of the mentally handicapped, died on Oct. 3 at a hospital in
New York City. He was 87 and lived in Clifton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Pashman served in the state judiciary for 23 years, 10 of them
as a member of the state's highest court. He resigned in 1982 when
he turned 70, the age of mandatory retirement.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, Pashman drew notice when he dissented from a majority
decision to send M.A. Farber, a New York Times reporter, to prison
for refusing to release his sources for articles concerning Dr.
Mario Jascalevich, a physician on trial on murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Pashman was deeply concerned about the First Amendment
in the case,'' said Eugene Scheiman, a lawyer who defended Farber
and The Times. ``When Farber was about to be imprisoned, we asked
the New Jersey Supreme Court for an emergency stay. It was on a
weekend. Judge Pashman came in wearing his golf clothes and granted
the stay.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, when the full New Jersey Supreme Court upheld a
lower court and ordered the state to proceed with imprisoning
Farber and fining The New York Times Co. $100,000 plus $5,000 a day
until they complied with a court order to release the files, only
Pashman dissented.
</P>
<P>
   The following September, when the state Supreme Court reaffirmed
the action of the lower court, Pashman again dissented; he was
joined by Justice Alan Handler.
</P>
<P>
   When Jascalevich was acquitted, Farber was released after 40
days of incarceration. In 1982, Gov. Brendan Byrne of New Jersey
pardoned both Farber and The New York Times on their convictions
for criminal contempt and returned $101,000 in fines to The Times.
</P>
<P>
   Pashman was known for his defense of the rights of the underdog,
and he affirmed the equal citizenship rights of the mentally
retarded.
</P>
<P>
   Pashman was born on Sept. 27, 1912, in Passaic, N.J., and
received his law degree from Rutgers Law School. He was elected
mayor of Passaic in 1951 and served until 1955. In 1959, he was
appointed to the bench in Passaic County by Gov. Robert Meyner.
</P>
<P>
   Pashman is survived by a daughter, Linda Blair-McCrohan of
Clifton; a son, Louis Pashman of Upper Saddle River, N.J.; four
grandsons, and three great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, Pashman decided in favor of the Passaic County Bar
Association in a suit against the County Freeholders claiming that
lawyers had been put at a disadvantage by poor conditions at the
courthouse. As a result of Pashman's decision, a new courthouse was
built within four years. Chiseled into the wall of the building is
a quotation from his opinion: ``A lawyer's obligation is perpetual;
he needs no motivation beyond his sense of duty and his pride.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
