</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-NUERNBERG-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYER FOR FC NUERNBERG IS SUSPENDED FOR DOPING 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALAN MAIMON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a hot week last May when FC Nuernberg was preparing for
the game that would determine if it remained in German soccer's
first division. The team needed at least a tie against SC Freiburg
in the season finale that Saturday to avoid finishing third-to-last
in the league, grounds for automatic relegation to the second
division.
</P>
<P>
   According to Nuernberg midfielder Thomas Ziemer, he and his
teammates sought an extra edge for the game. When the team's
nutritionist, Helmut Brand, suggested they try an organic substance
called Tribulus terrestris, all but two agreed. Only Ziemer, 30,
was tested for drugs after the game, however. The results of the
test showed he had anabolic steroids in his system. Last week, the
German Soccer Federation, known as the DFB, suspended Ziemer for
nine months, the longest suspension of any kind handed down to a
player by German soccer's governing body.
</P>
<P>
   With the suspension of Ziemer, the first given to a German
soccer player found to have taken a performance-enhancing
substance, the DFB joined other European sports federations that
have increased their vigilance against doping. The Italian Athletic
Federation will soon consider a possible four-year suspension for
the marathon runner Giuliano Battocletti, who also tested positive
for steroids.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first real doping case in German soccer,'' said
Rainer Koch, the disciplinary committee chairman. ``We had to act
in order to preserve the credibility of the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   The role played by Brand, the nutritionist nicknamed Miraculix
by Ziemer and his Nuernberg teammates, remains unclear. A German
biochemical institute testified that the Tribulus terrestris
administered by Brand could not alone have resulted in Ziemer's
testosterone count.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is only speculation that Brand had something to do with
this case,'' Koch said. ``The fact is that players are still
responsible for their own negligent actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ziemer's suspension has resulted in debate in the international
soccer community about how doping should be monitored and punished.
A doping study published last week by the International Olympic
Committee indicated that soccer returned the lowest number of
positive tests of all sports.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these good marks, the International Soccer Federation,
known as FIFA, decided on Wednesday in Belgium to adopt random
out-of-competition doping controls during next year's European
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these measures, FIFA shows its commitment to fight
against the scourge of doping,'' FIFA president's, Sepp Blatter,
said.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions leveled against a player who tests positive remain
undefined. The DFB has no set rules determining how long a player
should be suspended for doping. While Koch's verdict is viewed by
many as harsh, it fell short of the mandatory two-year suspension
endorsed by the sport ministers of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had opted for that long of a suspension, we would have
certainly faced legal problems,'' Koch said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension of Ziemer comes at a time when doping has
received renewed legal attention in Germany. In September, the
Berlin State Prosecution Office indicted the two men most
responsible for the systematic doping of athletes in eastern
Germany. Manfred Ewald, former president of the country's sports
federation, and Manfred Hoeppner, who was the head doctor in the
sports medicine service, are accused of ``aiding and abetting the
bodily harm'' of 142 female athletes, most of them minors.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments of Ewald and Hoeppner are based on the
systematic nationwide doping of athletes. Representatives of FC
Nuernberg believe a distinction should be made between willful and
systematic doping and what happened to Ziemer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a player can be punished so severely for taking an illegal
substance without his knowledge, his life will be very
restricted,'' said Wilfried DeBuhr, managing director of FC
Nuernberg. ``Even dinner in a restaurant becomes problematic if the
food isn't prepared right before his eyes.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
