<DOCNO> NYT19991009.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-SEWANEE-NYT &LR;      10-09 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEWANEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1899 SEWANEE TEAM HAD COLLEGE FOOTBALL'S GREATEST ROAD TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: The South)  (mk) 
 By DAVID PASCHALL   
 Chattanooga (Tenn.) Times-Free Press   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be impossible today, and one would think it would have
been impossible 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the University of the South football team did it.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the likes of Notre Dame, Michigan, Alabama, Oklahoma
and Florida State ruled the college football world, the team better
known as Sewanee remarkably navigated the toughest road schedule
the sport has ever known.
</P>
<P>
   In a span of six days in 1899, Sewanee knocked off Texas, Texas
A&AMP;M, Tulane, Louisiana State and Ole Miss. Five of the 21 Tigers
were law students and four were medical students. The average age
was just over 21, the average weight 169 pounds. Along with the
players, coach Billy Suter, manager Luke Lea and the trainer, Cal
Burrows, made the 2,500-mile, 77-hour train trip that resulted in
five shutouts and the respect of a nation.
</P>
<P>
   Sewanee paid tribute to the 1899 team on Saturday, sandwiching a
pregame tailgate party and a postgame celebration around a game
against Division III rival DePauw.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there are some who would swear to the contrary, I did
not see the 1899 Sewanee football team play in person,'' Penn State
coach Joe Paterno said recently. ``One can't help but marvel,
however, when reviewing the accomplishments of that splendid
undefeated squad.''
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of Tuesday, Nov. 7, a century ago, Suter, Lea,
Burrows and the Tiger players caught a train out of Cowan, Tenn.,
and traveled through Memphis toward Texas. The train arrived
Wednesday evening in Austin, where the Tigers topped the Longhorns,
12-0, the following day before a crowd estimated at 2,000. The
captain, Henry ``Diddy'' Seibels, a halfback, scored two touchdowns
(worth five points apiece in those days) for the winners.
</P>
<P>
   Sewanee then traveled to Houston and dumped Texas A&AMP;M, 10-0,
before roughly 600 fans a day later. Fullback Ormand Simkins and
quarterback Warbler Wilson scored touchdowns for the Tigers, as
both extra-point attempts failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A&AMP;M went down in honorable defeat before the mighty Sewanee
team in what proved to be one of the fiercest and most brilliant
contests ever seen on the Southern gridiron,'' reported Texas A&AMP;M's
campus newspaper, The Battalion, in a burst of hyperbole. ``They
are unmistakably the champions of the South this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 350 miles separated Houston from New Orleans, but that
didn't faze the Tigers. They pummeled Tulane, 23-0, on Saturday
night. Halfback Rex Kilpatrick scored twice in a game eventually
called for darkness.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Sewanee rested.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Tigers ventured to Baton Rouge and demolished
Louisiana State, 34-0, before another throng of 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after a trip back to Memphis, Sewanee completed its
stamina test with a 12-0 defeat of Ole Miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the most amazing thing about this trip is how these
guys lasted,'' said Larry Dagenhart, a former Sewanee sports
information director. ``Football once a week is rough, but these
guys played five games in six days. And let's face it, there wasn't
a whole lot of expertise in athletic training back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Locating grandchildren or great-grandchildren with any knowledge
of the 1899 Tigers was next to impossible for Dagenhart, but one
person who kept abreast of that team is the retired Birmingham
journalist Wendell Givens. Seven years ago, Givens wrote
``Ninety-Nine Iron,'' a book about Sewanee's momentous week and
indelible team.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started my research, I wanted to know why on earth they
would play five games in six days,'' Givens said. ``Luke Lea was
the key figure. He was the student manager of that team and was
also kind of an athletic director without the actual title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sewanee and Vanderbilt were the big rivals at that time, but
they didn't play in 1899 because they couldn't agree on gate
receipts. Lea didn't want to be an ordinary student manager, so he
started setting up a trip. Sewanee had played at Texas in 1898 and
had beaten them, so I think Lea went from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went to the administration for approval to play two or
three games, but then he decided why not add more on the way back
home. The administration didn't worry about playing five games in
six days They just wanted to make sure they could pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, they approved the trip.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1899 Sewanee team had a tremendous advantage, Givens
suggests, in that the Tigers were able to practice all summer. Back
then, Sewanee students took the winters off due to harsh conditions
on Sewanee Mountain, more commonly known as Monteagle, and instead
went to school through the summer months.
</P>
<P>
   Sewanee finished 12-0 in 1899, outscoring its opponents by
322-10. Only Auburn, which faced the Tigers two weeks after their
successful train trip, could put points on the purple-clad defense
when the two met Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   Following its undefeated season, Sewanee posted winning records
from 1900 through 1918 and eventually joined the Southeastern
Conference in 1932. It didn't take long _ as evidenced by 37
consecutive SEC defeats _ for Tiger officials to realize their
athletic programs could not keep pace with growing powers like
Alabama, Auburn, Georgia, Louisiana State and Tennessee, so Sewanee
withdrew from the league in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Sewanee had additional undefeated seasons in the smaller College
Athletic Conference in 1958 and 1963 before entering the Division
III ranks in 1972. But there's no argument as to the greatest team
in Sewanee history.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Bowl Championship Series had been in effect in 1899,
there seems little doubt Sewanee would have played in the title
game,'' Paterno said.
</P>
<P>
   (David Paschall is a sportswriter for the Chattanooga, Tenn.,
Times-Free Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
