<HEADER>
A1888 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-DEMOCRATS-CAMPAIGN-BO     10-09 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-CAMPAIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE, BRADLEY TRADE JABS WHILE COURTING IOWA VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES _ On a warm autumnal day as the dry leaves crunched
underfoot, Al Gore and Bill Bradley took their campaigns to the
neighborhoods of this capital city, exchanging jabs over their
commitment to elevate politics to a higher plane.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president stood at the dead end of East 40th Court and
challenged Bradley, the former New Jersey senator, to a series of
weekly debates on issues ranging from farm policy to health care.
Bradley rebuffed Gore, accusing him of lashing out for lack of
confidence in himself.
</P>
<P>
   The two Democratic candidates for president came here for the
annual Jefferson-Jackson dinner, the state party's major
fund-raiser. It was the first time they had appeared in the same
room during the campaign, and it came as Gore is trying to
rehabilitate his candidacy and increase pressure on Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   In a low-key, but pointed response to the recent slings and
arrows from the Gore campaign, Bradley said Saturday that a
candidate who is not confident ``resorts to darts.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Bradley walked away from the Democratic Party when he
resigned from the Senate in 1996 at a time when working people
needed him most. As Newt Gingrich and the Republicans took over the
Congress, Gore said, Bradley left others to fight for the minimum
wage, abortion rights, and support of farmers.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour's walk knocking on doors in the Beaverdale section
and asking people for their support, Bradley said he did not
believe voters would hold his resignation from the Senate or his
declaration that ``politics is broken'' against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can talk about the future in a way that's compelling
enough. I also have always been a Democrat since I first cast my
vote in 1964,'' Bradley said. ``I am simply not going to get into
dealing with the darts that are being thrown.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he is concerned that his unwillingness to respond to
specific charges by Gore would hurt him, Bradley said he was not,
and would continue to be himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the American people want to have a positive vision of
the future, and to the extent that someone is confident in their
own vision of the future, they don't need to resort to the darts,''
he said. ``There's been an awful lot of partisanship and
negativism, and I think people really want to have a politics
that's more positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bradley is resisting Gore's calls to debate, he said
the two-man race is good for both candidates. ``I think competition
is what America is all about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But while Bradley was suggesting that Gore's attacks on his
record were a sign of old, negative politics, Gore was saying the
opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not use this campaign as a way to elevate the election
process to make it worthy of our democracy?'' Gore asked, pressing
for debates. ``The best way to elevate campaigns is to have
debates, and to focus on what's really significant and important.
</P>
<P>
   ``And is it fair to debate the impact of Reaganomics on America
at a time when the Republican majority in the Congress is trying to
go back to Reaganomics? Sure it is,'' he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said again, as he has the last couple of weeks, that
Bradley left the Senate at a time when he was needed after Gingrich
and the Republicans took over the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of us was called upon to fight against it with everything
we had, or not,'' Gore said. ``And he did not. That, again, ought
to be discussed and dealt with in the context of debate.''
</P>
<P>
   When told that Bradley had described him as ``timid,'' Gore
reached for his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ooh, a dart,'' he exclaimed, pulling an imaginary dart from
his green cotton shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I didn't walk away from the fight when Newt Gingrich
took over the Congress,'' Gore said. ``I didn't walk away from the
fight when Reaganomics was put up for a vote on the floor. I didn't
walk away from the fight when farmers needed farm credit, when
farmers needed loan-deficiency payments for conservation
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bradley walked through Beaverdale, he encountered people of
every stripe, including his own fans, Gore supporters, and
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Lyn Lienhard, a Democrat and a former social worker, had nothing
but kind words for Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's electable and he's solid, sincere, common-sense,
down to earth, personable,'' he said. ``It's like you're meeting a
friend rather than a politician.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Jongewaard was up on a ladder, caulking the windows on his
Tudor home, when Bradley walked up. After chatting for a couple of
minutes and wishing Bradley well, Jongewaard told reporters, ``I'm
a committed Gore supporter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't back somebody I didn't think could beat any
Republican,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
