<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JUDGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RAPS GOP OVER HOLDUP ON MINORITY JUDGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Wrapping up a trip that often had the air of a
farewell tour, President Clinton on Saturday shared fond memories
with Hispanic leaders and blasted Senate Republicans for a
``shameless'' refusal to confirm minority judges.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before thousands of Hispanics, Clinton blamed
partisanship for the refusal to back his judicial nominees, and did
not suggest the opposition was based on race.
</P>
<P>
   But he pointedly mentioned only minority judges whose
appointments were rejected or are languishing ``somewhere in the
dark recesses of the calendar of the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's rejection of African-American Judge Ronnie White, a
Missouri judge nominated to the federal bench, ``was wrong. It's
the kind of thing that's going on up there that ought to stop,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate's treatment of Judge White and its failure to vote
on the outstanding Hispanic nominees that are pending creates a
real doubt about their ability and their willingness to perform
their constitutional duties to advise and consent,'' Clinton told
the gathering of the US Hispanic Leadership Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The president's three-day swing through New York, Canada, and
Chicago brought him back to his roots of support as a first-time
presidential candidate in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In tones that often sounded as though he was preparing to pass
the torch to the next president, Clinton spoke passionately about
his commitment to gay rights, labor struggles, and the issues
facing America's fastest-growing minority group, Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than lay out a future political agenda, Clinton recounted
what he saw as his legislative and policy successes in office,
including the booming national economy and such initiatives as the
Family and Medical Leave Act.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke freely about his support for issues that often
brought him controversy during his presidency, including the
``awful battle which I waged and didn't win'' to allow gays to
serve openly in the military.
</P>
<P>
   In reflective tones, the president recalled his fights to create
unity among Americans, and tied them to the greater issue of
ethnic, racial, and religious strife domestically and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worried about social division,'' Clinton told a group of gay
rights activists in New York Friday. ``And every campaign, it
seemed to me, was yet another example of how we could sort of carve
up the electorate and make one group resent another, and hope that
your group was a larger group of resenters than the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Hispanic Conference Saturday, Clinton spoke
emotionally about the human division that has led to overseas
conflicts that he has dealt with as president.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look around this old world Sunday, the biggest problem
I have faced as your president in my responsibilities around the
world is dealing with the racial and the ethnic and the religious
and the tribal conflicts where people occupy the same land and
cannot get along, where they continue to believe what is different
about them is more important than their common humanity, where they
fear people who are different from them and get to the point where
they look down on them and in some places, God forbid, they think
it's OK to kill them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem is the oldest problem of the human heart:
the fear and hatred of people who are different,'' Clinton said,
drawing loud applause from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   The president barely mentioned his wife or his vice president in
his addresses. But the president's remarks are sure to reflect on
First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is expected to run for the
US Senate in New York, and on Vice President Al Gore, seeking the
Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   As a lame-duck president, Clinton can openly woo such voting
blocs as Latinos, gays, and labor unions with less concern for the
political consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Still, these groups are expected to make a difference in the
coming elections. Hispanics make up only 5 percent of the voting
population, but they are heavily respresented in delegate-rich
states, including Illinois, Florida, Texas, California, and New
York _ where Mrs. Clinton and Gore both face tough challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic strategists believe the Hispanic vote is their best
chance to regain control of the House of Representatives. And both
Democrats and Republicans agree that neither party has a lock on
the Latino vote.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Clinton's Hispanic nominees _ California judges Richard
Paez and Marsha Berzon _ have been waiting 3 1/2 years and 18
months, respectively, for a full Senate vote on their nominations.
``I think the treatment of Richard Paez and Marsha Berzon is
shameless,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and Capitol Hill have long fought over the
alleged politicization of judicial and diplomatic nominees, with
Democrats complaining that the Republican Senate has held up the
confirmation of qualified nominees for political reasons that have
nothing to do with the candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
