<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YELTSIN-ILLNESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN CHECKS INTO HOSPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris N. Yeltsin checked into the hospital
Saturday with what the Kremlin described as a case of the flu, but
press reports here are suggesting that his illness may be more
serious.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the president's illness as minor, Kremlin spokesman
Dmitry Yakushkin said Yeltsin did not feel well on Friday and had
agreed Saturday to be hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's unexpected hospitalization follows by just a day the
Kremlin announcement that the 68-year-old president _ who has only
rarely appeared in public over the past two weeks _ was overworked
and needed a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult for him to work long, taking into account
the age of Boris Yeltsin and other factors,'' said Yakushkin, in
televised comments on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Moscow's media, citing anonymous Kremlin sources,
have been reporting that Yeltsin is seriously ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``In whose hands is Russia's nuclear suitcase?'' read a headline
in Saturday's edition of the influential daily newspaper Segodnya.
The newspaper reported that Yeltsin has not been in the Kremlin for
four days and that he was preparing to have heart surgery in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will know in the next few days whether or not this is
true,'' the newspaper reported, adding that Yeltsin was also
considering resigning and turning power over to his prime minister
and anointed successor, Vladimir Putin. The Kremlin has denied the
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I understand the president is in very bad shape,''
said Andrei Piontkovsky, a Moscow-based political analyst. ``The
events of the last few days _ the media reports, Yakushkin's
announcement _ were designed to prepare the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's hospitalization occurs as Russia is embroiled in war
in the breakaway republic of Chechnya. With Yeltsin absent from the
political scene over the past several weeks, Putin has been taking
an increasingly high public profile, specifically regarding
Chechnya and other matters usually reserved for the president.
</P>
<P>
   State-controlled media have been trying to boost the prime
minister's standing, making much of a recent rise in his
popularity. Putin was shown repeatedly Saturday during a televised
soccer game he attended between Russia and Ukraine. At one point,
the camera focused on the prime minister for nearly two minutes as
he cheered Russia's national team.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has had health problems for years, including heart
trouble that led to multiple bypass surgery in 1996 and recurring
bouts of pneumonia and respiratory infections.
</P>
<P>
   He has also suffered from back pain and a recurring ulcer in the
past year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
