</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-WEEKEND-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 10/09/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ROCK HILL, S.C. -- Oct. 9, 1999 -- S.C.-GAMBLING-VOTE,
10-9 -- A strip of gaming parlors in Rock Hill. Video poker is
everywhere in the state of South Carolina. Some 34,000 of the
machines have now taken root across South Carolina, far more than
in any other state, and many people have had enough. South
Carolinians will vote Nov. 2 on whether to ban video poker
machines. The latest newspaper poll shows that a sizable majority
of likely voters, more than 60 percent in one poll, want the
machines permanently unplugged. (Donna Bise/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) RHINELANDER, Wis. -- Oct. 9, 1999 -- WIS-BURGLARY, 10-9
-- Detective Jim Wood, of the Oneida County Sheriff's Department,
outside a cabin that has been broken into many times. In the
deepest, most tranquil lands of Wisconsin, where people could
retreat for a few days and forget about urban woes, burglars have
been clearing out vacation homes with the efficiency of a moving
company. In some recent cases, burglars have cleaned out cabins so
thoroughly that they even pulled up the carpet and took the
toothbrushes and deodorant. (Mike Roemer/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MILWAUKEE -- Oct. 9, 1999 -- WIS-WELFARE-2, 10-9 --
Loretta Triplett, 48, who has battled depression for 35 years and
works part time as a clerk at Wisconsin Electric, hit Wisconsin's
welfare deadline. Arguing she could gain new clerical skills, Y-W
Works, a private agency in Milwaukee that handles her welfare case,
asked the state for another six months of benefits for Ms.
Triplett. The state gave her three. Wisconsin's tough work rules
have swept more than 57,000 families from the welfare rolls, but
the state is now grappling with the ultimate symbol of the new
welfare age: time limits. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Oct. 9, 1999 -- BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-7, 10-9
-- The New York Mets' Todd Pratt celebrates after connecting off
Arizona Diamonbacks reliever Matt Mantei with a drive to
straightaway center for the game winning home run on Saturday, as
the the Mets beat Arizona 4-3 to win their first-round series three
games to one. The Mets will now take on the Atlanta Braves in the
National League Championship Series in Atlanta on Tuesday. (G. Paul
Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Oct. 9, 1999 -- SUB-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-6,
10-9 -- The New York Mets' Todd Pratt, signed as a minor league
free agent after being out of baseball in 1996, celebrates after
hitting a game winning home run in the 10th inning, as the Mets
beat Arizona 4-3 to win their first-round series three games to
one. The Mets will now take on the Atlanta Braves in the National
League Championship Series in Atlanta on Tuesday. (G. Paul
Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Oct. 9, 1999 -- BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-5, 10-9
-- The New York Mets' Todd Pratt, replacing injured catcher Mike
Piazza for the second straight day, homers in the 10th inning
Saturday as the Mets beat Arizona 4-3 to win their first-round
series three games to one. The Mets will now take on the Atlanta
Braves in the National League Championship Series in Atlanta on
Tuesday. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Oct. 9, 1999 -- BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-4, 10-9
-- The New York Mets backup catcher Todd Pratt, shows home plate
umpire Jerry Davis that he tagged Arizona Diamondback Matt Williams
out at the plate in the top of the eighth inning. Pratt, signed as
a minor league free agent after being out of baseball in 1996, hit
the game winning home run in the 10th inning, as the Mets beat
Arizona 4-3 to win their first-round series three games to one. (G.
Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MILWAUKEE -- Oct. 9, 1999 -- WIS-WELFARE-2, 10-9 -- Robin
Edwards, a 38-year-old mother of six, at Y-W Works, a private
agency in Milwaukee that handles her welfare case, listens to a
social workers' lesson on talking to employers. Wisconsin is now
grappling with the ultimate symbol of the new welfare age: time
limits. Virtually everyone on welfare in the state is required to
join a work program, and there are two-year limits on those jobs.
This month, for the first time, a handful of Wisconsin families,
including Ms. Edwards, have hit the deadline. (Nicole Bengiveno/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Oct. 9, 1999 -- BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-3, 10-9
-- Al Leiter of the New York Mets pitching against the Arizona
Diamonbacks in the third inning of play on Saturday, during Game 4
of the National League Division Playoffs at Shea Stadium. The Mets
lead the series 2-1. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MILWAUKEE -- Oct. 9, 1999 -- WIS-WELFARE-1, 10-9 -- Robin
Edwards, a 38-year-old mother of six who works as a janitor at a
Milwaukee parochial school in exchange for a monthly welfare check
of $673, hit Wisconsin's welfare deadline, but got an extension.
This month, for the first time, a handful of Wisconsin families
have hit the deadline. As a result, they could lose their checks
not for refusing to work for their aid, but simply for staying in
the program too long. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Oct. 9, 1999 -- BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-2, 10-9
-- Arizona Diamonbacks pitcher Brian Anderson on the mound against
the New York Mets in the first inning of play on Saturday, during
Game 4 of the National League Division Playoffs at Shea Stadium.
The Mets lead the series 2-1. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Oct. 9, 1999 -- BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-1, 10-9
-- The New York Mets' Rey Ordonez completing a double play in the
second inning of play, as Greg Colbrun of the Arizona Diamonbacks
slides into second during Game 4 of the National League Division
Playoffs at Shea Stadium on Saturday. The Mets lead the series 2-1.
(G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
