<HEADER>
A1902 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-RICH-NYT &LR;      10-09 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-RICH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 LEE RICHARDSON, 73, AN ACTOR NOTED FOR HIS ENGLISH ACCENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lee Richardson, an actor whose career spanned more
than four decades of stage, film and television work, died on Oct.
2 at his home in Manhattan. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cardiac arrest after complications from a
perforated ulcer, said his daughter, Rachel Richardson Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 40 years, Richardson was a fixture on the New York
stage and in regional repertory roles. He appeared in so many roles
requiring an English accent that he was widely assumed to be
British.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, who was born in Chicago, read the works of
Shakespeare and Noel Coward as a soldier in the Army Air Corps
during World War II. After his discharge from the Army, he briefly
took prelaw courses at Loyola University before moving to the
Goodman Theater School in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   One of his early New York performances was off-Broadway in the
Circle in the Square production of Tennessee Williams' ``Summer and
Smoke'' with Geraldine Page. He was 24 at the time and caught the
attention of the artist Al Hirschfeld, who eventually depicted him
in four drawings.
</P>
<P>
   By 1954, Richardson was appearing regularly on the television
drama anthologies ``Playhouse 90'' and ``Studio One,'' tallying
more than 250 appearances. He also performed with George C. Scott
in the 1962 production of ``The Merchant of Venice'' in Central
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he became a founding member of the Guthrie Theater in
Minneapolis, where he worked with Jessica Tandy, Hume Cronyn, Zoe
Caldwell, Douglas Campbell and Rita Gam.
</P>
<P>
   After four years with the American Shakespeare Theater in
Stratford, Conn., he returned to Broadway in productions of ``Find
Your Way Home,'' ``The Texas Trilogy'' and ``Father's Day.'' He was
nominated for a Tony Award in 1973 for his performance in ``Vivat!
Vivat Regina!''
</P>
<P>
   He was a favorite of the director Sidney Lumet, who cast him in
the films ``Prince of the City,'' ``Daniel,'' ``Q &AMP; A'' and ``A
Stranger Among Us.'' He also appeared in John Huston's ``Prizzi's
Honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson performed voice-overs for more than 100 commercials.
</P>
<P>
   His wife of 35 years, Elaine Rower Richardson, died in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his daughter, of Manhattan, he is survived by a
son, Jonathan, of the Bronx, and a sister, Dolores Levine of
Anaheim, Calif. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 1919EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991009.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1904 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-DBACKS-METS10-COX     10-09 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-METS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Diamondbacks can't get glove on Mets
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the improbabilities compounding by the inning,
all of Shea Stadium came to a halt for an instant late Saturday
afternoon, allowing Steve Finley the opportunity to check his glove
out there some 410 feet from home plate.
</P>
<P>
   He found it empty. Next came bedlam.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Pratt, thrust into the void left by injured superstar Mike
Piazza, won the National League Division Series for the New York
Mets, his one-out homer off Arizona relief ace Matt Mantei in the
10th inning clearing by the wall by an estimated four feet in dead
center for a 4-3 win.
</P>
<P>
   Having now taken seven of their last eight games, the Mets renew
what has become a nasty little relationship with the Atlanta Braves
in next week's NLCS. The Braves left New York on Sept. 30 having
taken five of six from the Mets and taunting them for a season run
amok.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a good effort to stop us,'' said Mets
manager Bobby Valentine, still dripping from a champagne shampoo.
``The team that we're playing is going to be playing against some
ghosts, because they said we were dead. I don't know if they've
ever played people who have come back from the grave before.''
</P>
<P>
   Before it was over, Valentine had coached third base for an
ejected Cookie Rojas. Arizona had twice erased New York leads, the
second on Jay Bell's two-run double in the eighth that gave the
Diamondbacks a 3-2 advantage. Arizona MVP candidate Matt Williams
missed the last three innings, pulled in a pitching change. New
York managed to put eight men on base in the last three innings on
just two hits.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps Pratt's heroic swing fit an unlikely day. Having gone
0-for-6 subbing for Piazza, who sat out a second game with a sore
left thumb, Pratt determined to take a full cut at the first good
fastball he saw, instead of choking down, as he customarily does
against pitchers who reach the mid-90 mph.
</P>
<P>
   After watching a wasted curveball, Mantei's next pitch was where
Pratt likes it, a little up and out in the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost the ball and kind of paused,'' said Pratt, who nearly
came to a stop between first and second while Finley leaped vainly
at the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw me stop and I thought he had the ball until he put his
head down. I didn't see the umpire but as soon as I saw him put his
head down, I knew we won the game right then.''
</P>
<P>
   That ended a remarkable Arizona season in which the Diamondbacks
make the biggest turnaround in baseball history, improving by 35
victories in one year. Then after taking seven of nine from New
York in the regular season, it ended on one pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``My vocabulary's not that good,'' said manager Buck Showalter.
``It's just a tough situation. You win 100 games and then,
suddenly, you're a spectator.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
