A1905 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DINOSAURS-VS-SUBURBIA     10-09 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINOSAURS-VS-SUBURBIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWNS COLUMN: CAN FOOTSTEPS FLATTEN A SHOWROOM? 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLAUVELT, N.Y. _ Movie idea: We see a steaming jungle. It is the
Lower Jurassic period, in an area that will one day become the
Hudson River Palisades. To the east, the Atlantic coast is just
forming, but Manhattan's sparkling armature is still 195 million
years distant.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the sound of footsteps. A coelophysis, a dinosaur that
resembles an ostrich, plashes through the fronds. See how its
three-toed feet imprint the boggy ground. Now fast-forward to the
present. The bog has hardened into sandstone, and the prints left
by coelophysis (pronounced seel-o-FY-sis), looking like an odd
leaf, or Donald Duck's feet, are embossed in the rock. Some high
school students poking around in the woods discover the prints, and
they are cut out of the rock and hauled off to the State Museum in
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   But wait. Now there are more people poking around in the
underbrush where the footprints were found. Will a coelophysis, a
prehistoric revenant, suddenly jump out and bite them? What a silly
idea. These are the New York City suburbs, after all. The people
just want to stop another developer from moving into their area,
and they will seize any straw, whether an endangered species, a
historic event or the legacy of a passing dinosaur, in their
battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if there are more footprints there or not,''
said Elayn Armaniaco, whose house on Greenbush Road is up the hill
from the site. ``Dinosaurs are exciting, and to have this link to
our history here is exciting, and it ought to be preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   The 17-acre lot where coelophysis once trod is now owned by
Palisades Volkswagen-Audi-Volvo, which wants to put a new
dealership on the land, with the entrance on state Route 303. But
the rear parking lot of the dealership, while 40 feet below
Greenbush Road, would come within 100 or so feet of Greenbush
horizontally. With the rumble and hiss of Route 303 already in
their ears, members of the Greenbush Road Coalition, which Ms.
Armaniaco heads, have seized on coelophysis as a weapon in a
lawsuit seeking to overturn a zoning permit granted to the car
dealer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hired a lawyer, and he charged us to pursue any piece of
any information anywhere that we could present,'' Ms. Armaniaco
said. ``We found out about the dinosaur tracks, which is
significant, but what is more significant is that we have a letter
from the state paleontologist who says that these were the only
dinosaur remains in the state of New York, and that is huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Enlisting natural history to undo the work of the zoning board
is hardly unique in the suburbs these days, and examples abound in
the town of Orangetown, of which Blauvelt is a part.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, residents persuaded the Town Board to revoke
a permit for an industrial park on Route 303, citing the importance
of trees to the ecosystem. The developer sued and won an $8 million
judgment, which the town is still paying.
</P>
<P>
   Residents also objected to the new IBM training center in
Palisades, south of here, on the grounds that the project would
disturb a pair of bald eagles. And then there was something about
an endangered species raised in the effort to block a developer who
has acquired 50 acres on Clausland Mountain, overlooking the
Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's called the Eastern wood rat,'' said Thom Kleiner,
the Orangetown town supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenbush Road Coalition does not like the suggestion that
coelophysis is only a three-toed stalking horse for its campaign.
But when the politicians seem powerless against property owners who
want to develop their land, coalition members say, people must
seize any slender reed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unusual for someone to say, `Well, I've got to fight
and this is the only weapon I could grab,' '' said Danforth W.
Toan, vice president of the Historical Society of Rockland County.
</P>
<P>
   But to Donald Brenner, a lawyer who represents the auto dealer,
the story of coelophysis is like the 10th sequel to a horror movie
he has to watch over and over. ``We're dealing with an ostrich type
of dinosaur that could travel 50 miles per hour,'' he said. ``So
there are going to be tracks everywhere. Does that mean we just
stop everything?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
