A1924 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE10-     10-09 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bobby Labonte has Gibbs up front
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ Joe Gibbs knows all about Super Bowl trophies,
but getting close to NASCAR hardware is another story.
</P>
<P>
   After eight years of Winston Cup racing, the former coach of the
Washington Redskins finally has a title contender in Bobby Labonte.
The No. 18 Pontiac driver is the pole sitter in today's UAW-GM 500
at Lowe's Motor Speedwaynear Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte is second in the Winston Cup points standings with six
races left in the season. Rookie sensation Tony Stewart, who also
drives for Gibbs, is fourth in points.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Joe Gibbs Racing) has been working since (1992) trying to get
in a position where we could make a run for a championship,'' Gibbs
said. ``We were expecting to turn the corner with Bobby at some
point. In the past, we have been a team with Bobby that could win
races, but we weren't the team that could step to the next level
and be consistent every week to run for a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is finally the year where we did that. Bobby has
been good almost every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte has won four races, which is tied for third-best on the
circuit, and has posted 18 top-five finishes. He was eighth at
Martinsville, Va., last weekend to move ahead of Mark Martin in the
point standings. Labonte trails leader Dale Jarrett by 251 points.
</P>
<P>
   When discussing the points race, Labonte is optimistic but
realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could put it that way (that we are running out
time), but we might have run out of time six weeks ago, too''
Labonte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a deal where with every race that goes by, mathematically
it gets harder (to catch Jarrett). I'm not really worried about
that because I'm glad where we are. We're lucky we are in second,
because as many times as I have messed up, it could have been a lot
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, 35, has brought acclaim to Joe Gibbs Racing, which in
turn has given stablity to the low-key driver. Labonte has been in
Winston Cup racing for eight seasons, including the last five for
Gibbs. Labonte finished a career-best sixth in the point standings
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's Motor Speedway seems to bring out the best in Labonte.
With Wednesday night's effort, he has won the pole position for all
three races this season at the 1.5-mile oval. He nearly captured
the Coca-Cola 600 last May, but was edged out by Jeff Burton. His
first Winston Cup victory was at the '95 Coca-Cola 600, and he has
been worse than sixth at the Concord, N.C., track only once in the
past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte will be driving the same race car he won with at
Michigan and finished runner-up with at The Brickyard in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we come to Charlotte everybody is pumped up,'' Labonte
said. ``For whatever reason, when we come here we know we have a
better shot than maybe we do at other places.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
