<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST: SHAQ WILL WIN MVP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA _ Jerry West doesn't fancy himself much of a
prognosticator.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers executive won't guess how many games his team should
win this season. Won't even say how long it might take for the
Lakers to gel under new coach Phil Jackson. But when it comes to
Shaquille O'Neal, West speaks with the boldness of a professional
handicapper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to make a prediction regarding him,'' West said
Saturday. ``I think he's going to be the most valuable player in
the league this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The MVP trophy has eluded O'Neal in his seven pro seasons
despite his perpetual rank among league leaders in scoring and
rebounding. And West makes this prediction even as Jackson projects
a scoring decline for O'Neal, who must function as more of a passer
in the triangle offense.
</P>
<P>
   But then, that might be what O'Neal needs to become an MVP _ a
requirement to broaden his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaquille O'Neal is going to touch the ball a lot, but he's
going to be asked to do some other things with regard to passing
the ball, a little bit different kind of a movement,'' West said.
``I see a tremendous enthusiasm on his part. I mean, he's as happy
as I've seen him since he's been here in Los Angeles. And I have to
believe an awful lot of that is he believes in what this coach is
trying to do. And more importantly, he feels that this system will
allow him to reach his goal, and that's to win a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who already has a scoring title on his resume (1994-95),
said he is willing to score less, pass and rebound more and push up
his blocked-shots average. But as for the MVP title?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more focused on the team this year, I'm not really worried
about individual accolades,'' he said. ``I know if I do my thing,
my name will always be up there in the running. I never knew how
they (reporters) pick that . . . but I'm not going to be going city
to city kissing people's (butts) trying to get some votes. . . . As
long as my team does well, then I'll be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson likes Jordan: Jackson praised his current starting five
_ O'Neal, A.C. Green, Glen Rice (alternating with Rick Fox), Kobe
Bryant and Derek Fisher _ for its effective play in Friday night's
fullcourt scrimmage, the first of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   He was also pleased with the play of his rookie/free-agent team,
particularly 6-10 forward Gerald Jordan. The rookie team led by
Jordan and first-round pick Devean George outplayed the Lakers'
veteran second unit, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers will play in front of the public and media for the
first time tonight, in a 7 p.m. scrimmage at UC Santa Barbara's
Thunderdome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
