<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ WEIGHS IN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA _ The Big Man is practicing free throws, and he
makes the art for which he's so notorious look so simple as he
makes one after another.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never misses during these workouts,'' says Chris Bodaken,
long-time video coordinator of the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour morning practice of the Lakers has ended, but The
Big Man continues his free throw accuracy under the watchful
guidance of one of the team's new assistant coaches, Tex Winter.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Big Man, draped in perspiration, an imposing
physical specimen at over 7 feet and over 300 pounds, shambles
regally to the sidelines for a few moments of relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much weight have you lost?'' I ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm about the same as I was last year,'' replies Shaquille
O'Neal, meaning the Lakers' center still is in the 340 vicinity.
``But I'm in much better shape. I've worked out hard all summer,
lifting weights, running, gearing myself up for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't in good shape at the start of last season, but there
was that lockout and it threw everybody off. It seemed like we
always were going to start in 30 days. November came, 30 days.
December came, 30 days. January came, 30 days. We didn't start
until February, and by then I wasn't in the shape I should have
been. But that won't be the case this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning his seventh season in the NBA, Shaquille O'Neal finds
himself under wide-spread scrutiny because he's a $15 million a
year superstar attraction who's never played on a world
championship team and never played for a coach as demanding as his
new one, Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damned right I have a burning desire to win an NBA title,'' he
says. ``What else to I have left to prove? I have shown I can
score, rebound, block shots. Sure, it's been frustrating. I want to
win as badly as anyone, but it just hasn't happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Can Shaquille O'Neal dramatically change his game at this late
juncture in his career? Can he forgo offense and concentrate on
defense? Can he and Kobe Bryant co-exist? Will he dutifully follow
Jackson's instructions?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do what Phil Jackson wants me to do,'' says O'Neal, who
hasn't always done what previous coaches wanted. ``I call him
Father Phil because he reminds me so much of my father, who is a no
nonsense type of guy who demands you do what he says. Father Phil
has the resume with six world titles. How do you argue with him?''
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that Phil Jackson is in total command of the
Lakers, right down to even closing off to the media all but the
final 15 minutes of these innocuous training camp sessions at the
UCSB gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no arguing between coaches and players as I've seen in
the past,'' says O'Neal, who himself had words with Del Harris last
season. ``I like what I see here so far. I like the triangle
offense. It gives you a lot of options, and gives me the
opportunity to show off my passing skills. I'm a good passer, you
know.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt in my mind that we're going to be a major
force this season, and that Kobe Bryant and I can bring home a
title to L.A. I'm really looking forward to this season playing
with a new coach in a great new arena. It's going to be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you willing to commit to playing more defense?'' I wonder.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Man nods his head gently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, I can play defense as well as any center,'' he says.
``If I tried to, I could block as many shots as Dikembe Mutombo and
Alonzo Mourning. It's just that I don't want to get in foul
trouble. You gotta understand, they (the officials) will call me
for anything. I get hammered routinely, and they'll let it go. Guys
constantly flop against me, but I still get stuck with the foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a double standard I've had to live with, and it makes me
a little more restrained on defense. But no center dominates me at
the defensive end. If Father Phil wants me to pick it up
defensively, I certainly will. But it might come with a
price---foul trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   I ask Shaquille O'Neal why he never mastered the sky hook
perfected by Kareem Abdul-Jabbar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I did a long time ago when I was a kid,'' he relates.
``But the sky hook was old-fashioned, and I'm from the hip-hop age.
It's just something that my generation never related to. So I
stopped using it. I once saw Danny Manning do a jump hook, and I
liked that. I use that sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big Man is in an expansive mood, and why not?
</P>
<P>
   He might not be wearing any championship rings, but his annual
income dwarfs even Kevin Brown's from his earnings as an athlete, a
rap singer and movie actor.
</P>
<P>
   As if he needs to concern himself about securing his financial
future, O'Neal reveals he's doing just that---or perhaps
endangering it---by giving serious consideration to going into the
restaurant business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting to that age where I have to start thinking
corporate,'' he says. ``My people are looking to buy 10 Taco Bells
down in Houston and also some IHOPs (International House Of
Pancakes).''
</P>
<P>
   You can be sure that Phil Jackson is keeping his fingers crossed
that this particular O'Neal venture falls through, since the last
thing Jackson wants is more culinary venues available to O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, it has been an irritant for O'Neal not having won an
NBA title, but it's doubtful he's had any sleepless nights over
such a vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you were in Little League and your team lost, you'd cry
because you knew you might not have another chance to win a title
again,'' says O'Neal. ``And it was the same in high school and in
college. But in the pros, you don't cry because you know there will
always be another season when you'll be given an opportunity to win
the title. You just have to keep trying hard. And, believe me, I'll
be trying extra hard to win a title this season. . .''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
