r s BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT     10-09 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THIS BISON EXTINCT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Detroit Pistons signed Brian Williams, for better or
worse, for seven seasons and enough loot to purchase seven percent
of an NFL franchise, they probably didn't realize their man in the
middle would end up in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   They also didn't think he was on the cusp of changing his name
to something that stirred visions of a lunch destination with
alternative meat welcome to Bison Dele, now take a number.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is the same rascal who without compensation
kissed an NBA official. So the Pistons must be more angry than
stunned that Dele would rather do business in Beirut than play
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Well, a thousand times no.
</P>
<P>
   According to a source much closer to the Pistons than Lebanon,
Dele has become the most unpopular teammate on the Detroit scene
since the Pinto had a falling out with the Mustang and the LTD.
</P>
<P>
   What bugged his cronies the most was Dele's commitment to
mediocrity. This approach didn't exactly thrill his bosses, who now
view his ambivalence toward hoops as future salary-cap relief. With
Dele, the Pistons didn't seem prepared for a deep playoff run,
anyway. With cap room and creative thinking, they may be able to
re-sign their hero, Grant Hill, by hiring more help with that
spending cash.
</P>
<P>
   Just what is the former Magic-Nugget-Clipper-Bull up to in
Beirut? Well, we don't know what he weighs, but have been told Dele
owns a company in that land of paradise. According to legend, Dele
does have a pilot's license and if he shows less inertia at Middle
East business than on a low post in the NBA, he could be the only
human to play with and own Air Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   But despite giving the Pistons far less than they bargained for,
we have to salute someone who's honest enough with himself to
forfeit $36 million in future salary ... someone with the chops to
irritate ex-Clipper coach Bill Fitch by taking helicopter trips
during free time on the road ... someone who jumps out of planes
when they're not on fire ... someone who treated a friend from the
team's support staff to impromptu Vegas excursions.
</P>
<P>
   Someone who took time out from celebrating his role in the
Bulls' fifth NBA championship to phone Clipper equipment manager
Pete Serrano.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must have been 3 or 4 a.m on the night they won the
championship,'' Serrano said. ``It sounded like he was almost in
tears. He kept saying, `I got a ring, Pete. What an unbelievable
feeling this is.'''
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect Bison Dele to act as unencumbered by
conventional thinking as former teammate Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Dele, it should be pointed out, isn't acting.
</P>
<P>
   sub UF5 A Ming's ransom
</P>
<P>
   While Dele continues to elude captivity, another internationally
known center who remains at large is 19-year-old Yao Ming.
</P>
<P>
   Ming, who checks in at 7-foot-6 and an egg roll or two about 280
pounds, first stirred the imagination of American basketball
addicts at the 1998 Nike Camp. But his NBA dream continues to tread
water while he performs for the Shanghai Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bay Area-based agent Bill Duffy, Ming shouldn't be
expected in the NBA Draft until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the most unbelievable, exhausting, circuitous
dealing I'll ever have,'' said Duffy, a graduate of Damien High in
La Verne, whose client list includes Clippers center Michael
Olowokandi.
</P>
<P>
   Ming attempted to circumvent the red-tape required to leave
China several months ago by agreeing to be represented by a
U.S.-based agency that wasn't registered with the NBA. The deal was
voided, and Duffy worked his way back into the action.
</P>
<P>
   The delay, he said, is extended because several Shanghai
big-timers including the mayor have to issue their blessing. His
current team also could block the move unless it's given a piece of
Ming's NBA action.
</P>
<P>
   How good is this kid?
</P>
<P>
   Duffy, whose subjective view is salved a bit by his pedigree as
a former player (Santa Clara), believes Ming like Olowokandi could
be the No.1 pick in whatever NBA Draft he is eligible for.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the worst,'' Duffy said, ``he's Rik Smits.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll put our money on Duffy, who convinced the Toronto Raptors
to reward Michael Stewart (1.5 points and 2.4 rebounds per game)
with a six-year, $24 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations When Shaquille O'Neal reported to the
Lakers' training camp at 340 pounds, local wiseguys thought he'd
prepared for Phil ``Zen Master P'' Jackson's triangle offense by
studying wedges of pizza. Not to worry; the Diesel reportedly is
dragging around 340 pounds of muscle. But if he doesn't tuck in
that elbow, or stop jerking the release, or start thinking of St.
Louis (Arch, baby!), that 340 could be his free-throw percentage.
... Draft 2000 sleeper: Introducing 7-0 Mamadou N'diaye of Auburn,
an active, springy, shoot-last center from Senegal, who according
to witnesses was the best college prospect at Pete Newell's famed
Big Man Camp. ... A snoop who's taking in the Charlotte camp says
the skills of rookie point guard Baron Davis seem to translating
quite nicely to the NBA. ... A source close to new Indiana Pacers
backup center Zan Tabak said the Clippers' initial interest in the
7-0 Croatian was almost sabotaged when they weren't allowed to pay
for his flight from Europe to L.A. But after finding out Tabak had
auditioned in Indiana, the Clips were permitted to spring for that
half-continent hop. ... Sworn-to-be-future-ex-Clipper Maurice
Taylor, perhaps the league's foremost fan of Comedy Central's
``South Park,'' gives the movie version 3{ stars out of a possible
5. ``They had two hours to work with,'' Taylor explained, ``but
only killed Kenny once.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
