</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PENNSTATE-IOWA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NITTANY LIONS SWEAT SOME, BUT STILL WIN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IOWA CITY _ Penn State looked hot and bothered. Hot because its
game here against Iowa was played in 70-degree weather, nothing
like the cool breeze it had left back on its Eastern campus.
Bothered because the Nittany Lions kept slipping early and because
Iowa kept bouncing back, making them sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State led by only 7-0 for the game's first 29 minutes 51
seconds. And then in the second half the Nittany Lions rode their
crew of banging running backs and their rigid defense to a 31-7
victory before 66,398 fans at Kinnick Stadium. Penn State, ranked
third by The New York Times and second by The Associated Press,
improved to 6-0 overall and 2-0 in the Big Ten. Iowa fell to 1-4
and 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa lost, 49-3, at Michigan State last week. Penn State had
enjoyed two weeks off since its last game. Well maybe ``enjoyed''
is not the right word, according to James Boyd, a Penn State
safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we practiced really hard during that time,'' Boyd said.
``Guys had a lot of cuts and bumps and bruises coming into this
game. And then we went out there today and it felt like a heat
wave. Our guys were suffering. It took some time to get used to the
heat, but that's no excuse for the way we started.''
</P>
<P>
   They started slowly. Iowa, though, was excited, leaping for an
upset that would make their season. Penn State took advantage of
that emotion. On its second possession, with 7:32 left in the first
quarter, it ran a reverse to receiver Eddie Drummond, who hopped,
skipped and then sped past all 11 overpursuing Hawkeyes for a
68-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were chasing us a lot,'' said Joe Paterno, the Penn State
coach, explaining the call and the play. ``They were emotional.
They were really flying after everything.''
</P>
<P>
   But Iowa continued to take chances on defense and play inspired
football. Twice in the half it intercepted Penn State passes, both
times ending drives deep inside Iowa territory. Finally the
Hawkeyes gave in, with only nine seconds left before halftime, when
Penn State quarterback Rashard Casey kept the ball and kept his
balance, darting into the end zone on a 6-yard scramble to give the
Nittany Lions a 14-0 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty pleased with the effort,'' said Kirk Ferentz, the
Iowa coach. ``But I'm not happy with the loss. We showed that we
can play pretty well with a good football team. We were still in it
in the fourth quarter, so hopefully this will be a learning
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa scored on a 40-yard pass from Randy Reiners to fullback Rob
Thein with 9:31 left in the third quarter, making the score 14-7.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the game was decided by Penn State's ability to run
the ball passionately and by a fourth-and-goal Iowa play that
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Eric McCoo led Penn State with 130 rushing yards, but five of
his teammates gained at least 20 rushing yards each. Penn State's
fierce foursome of backs _ McCoo, Aaron Harris, Omar Easy and Larry
Johnson _ differ in size and speed, but all run hard. So does
another backup, tailback Kenny Watson, not to mention the other big
fullbacks. This group helped Penn State account for 341 rushing
yards and 19 rushing first downs. The Nittany Lions ran the ball 51
times, averaging 6.7 yards a carry.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa managed only 48 rushing yards and three rushing first
downs.
</P>
<P>
   McCoo nearly matched the Hawkeyes' total on one play. With 4:36
left in the third quarter, he burst free for a 47-yard touchdown
run to make it 21-7. Iowa was finished on the first play of the
fourth quarter when it could not convert a fourth-and-goal from the
Penn State 2. Reiners tried a keeper run outside and then turned
inside. Linebacker Brandon Short was waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play meant a lot,'' Short said. ``It showed the defense
we can still make the big play when needed.''
</P>
<P>
   With 10:05 left Penn State added another rushing touchdown, its
fourth, on a 10-yard run by Harris, and it scored a field goal six
minutes later. Once it was over it looked easy, but Paterno said it
had not been.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't commit a turnover and when you don't get turnovers
it can be tough,'' Paterno said. ``We ran well. All of our backs
are strong and they all block well. We've been fortunate. We've had
groups of great backs before, but this group doesn't have that
great one yet. Our line and especially our tackles are doing the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   When a team rushes for 300-plus yards, it ought to get 60
points, some of the Nittany Lions said. They can try next Saturday
when Ohio State (unranked by The Times; No. 21 A.P.) visits them.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Penn State players remained hot. Others were cool _
they are confident this team will run over all comers.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
