<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1937 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-INDIANS-REDSOX-NY     10-09 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX WIN, BUT IT RAISES QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Now the real fun starts at Fenway, the guessing games
and praying of the faithful for the healing of the hurting players.
Will Pedro Martinez be back from his injury, and if so will he
pitch Game 4 on Sunday instead of waiting for a possible Game 5 on
Monday in Cleveland?
</P>
<P>
   As the fans and players filed out into the streets of old Back
Bay Saturday night, after a 9-3 Red Sox victory over the Indians,
there were many other questions. Will Nomar Garciaparra's injured
wrist recover enough to allow him to swing the bat and play
shortstop? Can the Red Sox win two more from a Cleveland team that
still seems far superior? When should Martinez and Garciaparra
return? And even, what time will Game 4 begin?
</P>
<P>
   Because of television considerations, Game 4 on Sunday was to be
played either in the afternoon or the evening. The starting time
would be determined at the conclusion of the Yankees game at Texas
later Saturday night. A Yankee victory to end the series would mean
a night game in Boston. A Rangers victory to prolong the series
would mean a day game in Boston. Either way, some of the customers
would have time to attend church and meditate over Saturday's
heroics that cut Cleveland's lead to two games to one in the
best-of-5 first round of the American League playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox won it with a six-run explosion in the seventh inning,
which included a three-run home run by designated hitter Brian
Daubach and a two-run double by third baseman John Valentin, who
had also hit a solo home run in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The teams took turns leading, and the Indians tied it at 3-3 in
the top of the seventh on a throwing error by Valentin, whose
throwing error was a major factor in Cleveland's victory in Game 1.
This set up his redemption under the bright lights of this quirky
old edifice.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the seventh, Cleveland reliever Jaret Wright
was replaced by Ricardo Rincon after Wright began the inning by
walking Lou Merloni and hitting Jason Varitek. After retiring the
next two batters, Rincon walked Jose Offerman to bring up Valentin
with the bases loaded and two out.
</P>
<P>
   On a 3-2 pitch, Valentin ripped a ground-rule double to left,
scoring two runs and giving the Sox a 5-3 lead. Daubach, the next
batter, accidentally hit the home plate umpire, Tim Welke, in the
head, when he lost his bat while swinging and missing. On the next
pitch, Daubach kept the bat and hit a three-run homer to make it
8-3.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's Boston starter was Pedro Martinez's older brother,
Ramon Martinez, who joined the roster in September after
rehabilitation from shoulder surgery. Merloni took the place of
Garciaparra at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra was hit with a pitch on the right wrist a week
before the season ended. Although he missed the final games, he
started in Game 1 of this series in Cleveland, hitting a home run
on his first trip to the plate and a double on his second. But he
went 0 for 3 in Game 2 and skipped a workout Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't start,'' manager Jimy Williams said before Saturday's
game. When someone asked if Garciaparra would be available to
pinch-hit, Williams responded: ``If he can't start, then he can't
pinch-hit.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second serious injury to the Red Sox in this series.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, Pedro Martinez left after four innings with muscle
pain in his back. Martinez, who led the American League with 23
victories, is considered the probable winner of the Cy Young award
as best pitcher in the league. His recovery and return is
uncertain. Under his normal rotation, his next scheduled start
would be on Monday in Cleveland, if Game 5 is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra won the league batting title with a .357 average and
is a candidate for the league's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez and Garciaparra are the two best players on a
flawed team that reached the playoffs as the wild card. To some Sox
supporters, the injuries will add another page to the bitter lore
of the franchise. The team has not won a World Series since 1918,
and it came into Saturday's game having lost 18 of its previous 19
postseason games. Although some New England fans are tired of
discussing the legend, it is often said here that the team suffers
under a curse against the franchise for selling Babe Ruth to the
Yankees before the 1920 season.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez got off to a good start, allowing one run in the
fourth inning and setting down the side in order in the fifth. In
the bottom of the fifth, the Indians' starter Dave Burba, could not
continue because of tightness in the underside of his right
forearm. Burba had given up only one hit but appeared to be in some
distress on the mound in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Burba was replaced by Wright, who was greeted by a line drive
off his shin hit by Troy O'Leary. Although O'Leary was thrown out
by third baseman Travis Fryman, the liner was a sign of things to
come. The Red Sox took a 2-1 lead on three hits and a sacrifice
fly. Darren Lewis knocked in the first run with a single, and Trot
Nixon got the next one with the sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez began to struggle in the sixth, giving up a leadoff
double to Roberto Alomar, who scored on a fielder's choice when the
Red Sox could not make a tough double play on Harold Baines'
grounder to first.
</P>
<P>
   Leading off the bottom of the sixth, Valentin hit a 2-0 pitch
off Wright over the center-field fence to give the Red Sox a 3-2
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians manufactured an unearned run to tie it in the top of
the seventh, as Kenny Lofton singled, took second on a ground out,
stole third, and scored on the throwing error by Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   And then it was time for the Red Sox to bat, and put the game
out of reach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
