<SLUG> BC-FBC-MICH-MICHST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BATTLE OF UNBEATENS, SPARTANS PULL A STUNNER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOHN U. BACON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EAST LANSING, Mich. _ The rivalry between Michigan and Michigan
State usually produces a lot of trash talking, unimaginative
football and, 23 of the previous 29 years, a Michigan victory. But
the intrastate rivals broke with all three traditions Saturday in a
thrilling 34-31 Michigan State triumph.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1961, the two teams entered the contest
undefeated. And for the first time since 1995, the Spartans won,
thanks to a defense that held Michigan's running attack to 42 yards
on 21 carries, and to the offensive combination of quarterback
Billy Burke and split end Plaxico Burress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt more confidence in my team today than I ever have,''
said Spartans coach Nick Saban, whose team improved to 6-0 and 3-0
in the Big Ten. ``This is the best feeling I've ever had. This is
the happiest I've ever seen the players, the happiest I've ever
seen our fans. I know how much this game means to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans derailed Michigan, now 5-1 and 2-1 in the
conference, by scoring three touchdowns on three consecutive
second-half possessions to build a 34-17 fourth-quarter lead. Burke
completed 21 of 36 passes for a school record 400 yards, and
Burress, who buried the Wolverines with a school record 255 yards
receiving, caught 10 of the passes.
</P>
<P>
   On defense the Spartans held Michigan's running game to just two
yards on 19 carries in the third quarter, forcing the Wolverines to
pass.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan coach Lloyd Carr said last week that if the Spartans
``keep doing what they're doing, they'll be one of the great
defenses of all time. There isn't any question, this is the best
wide receiving corps we've seen. I can say clear cut it's the best
Michigan State team since 1987, and that was a great football team.
They've got a lot of weapons, and no weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr's analysis seemed vindicated on all counts Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In each of Michigan's games this season, Carr has played senior
quarterback Tom Brady in the first quarter and sophomore Drew
Henson in the second. Like a basketball coach with two shooting
guards, Carr then has the luxury of playing whoever has the hottest
hand that day.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, that initially seemed to be Henson, the summertime
Yankee farmhand, who connected on 6 of 9 first-half passes. But he
gained no net yards throwing in the second half, suffering an
interception and two sacks.
</P>
<P>
   With Michigan down by 27-10 with 2 minutes 56 seconds remaining
in the third quarter, Carr turned to Brady, who led the Wolverines
to three consecutive touchdowns. The third, which capped a 96-yard
drive fueled by pinpoint, 8-for-8 passing, brought the Wolverines
to within 34-31, with 2:47 left in the game. Michigan's poorly
executed onside kick, however, gave the Spartans the ball back for
good.
</P>
<P>
   It would be difficult to imagine a sweeter victory for the
Spartans. The Wolverines actively resisted the Spartans' admission
to the Big Ten in 1953, and vowed to refuse the newly created Paul
Bunyan trophy for state supremacy if they beat their younger
brothers that year. They didn't, losing by 14-6, but Michigan State
never forgot the slight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notre Dame and Ohio State were rivalries, but Michigan State
was a war, almost a civil war, a real hatred,'' said 1992 Michigan
captain Chris Hutchinson. ``We out and out didn't like each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   But both schools have recently made a conscious effort at
civility. ``First of all, give credit to Michigan State,'' Carr
said after the game. ``They are an outstanding football team, a
well-coached, physical team, and that was evident in their play
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones that you win, you know that you've done something.
And the ones that you lose, it's miserable. You put so much into
this game, it's always a difficult loss _ and yet, you have to put
it behind you.''
</P>
<P>
   Saban was equally diplomatic. ``I think Michigan has the
firepower to beat anyone in this league,'' he said. ``They can
still win the Big Ten championship. I still believe it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
