<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE HEADQUARTERS' EXIT DOESN'T ALWAYS DOOM A COMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY and SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Southwestern Bell Corp. rooted its
headquarters in St. Louis for 113 years. Then, one day in 1992, the
company issued a news release.
</P>
<P>
   So long, St. Louis. Howdy, San Antonio _ ``the gateway to
Mexico'' as Southwestern Bell called its new home. And just like
that, its executive connections to St. Louis were no longer in
service.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing has happened in Omaha, Neb., and Wichita,
Minneapolis and San Francisco: A major corporate citizen gets
hitched to another community.
</P>
<P>
   Now it appears to be happening in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement last week of a pending buyout of Sprint Corp.
by MCI WorldCom threatens to rob the area of something every
Chamber of Commerce covets _ a headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Cities tend to share the same initial reactions to news that a
headquarters could be lost: anger; helplessness; a sense of
betrayal; panic. How could you take those high executive salaries
elsewhere? Who will sit on our community boards? What benefactors
will fund our symphony?
</P>
<P>
   If other cities offer a lesson, it's that the consequences are
not so awful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we wish Southwestern Bell were back,'' said Russ
Signorino, a labor analyst and consultant for the United Way of
Greater St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in trying to make up for that loss in civic involvement,
lots of times you can find new opportunities and new players that
you didn't know existed. You can make it up with medium and small
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis lost not only Southwestern Bell _ now known as SBC
Communications Inc. _ but also in 1997 bid adieu to McDonnell
Douglas Corp. headquarters in a merger with Seattle-based Boeing
Corp., although St. Louis has kept most of the 23,000 manufacturing
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Together the departures cost St. Louis more than 1,500 executive
and managerial jobs. Still, the region has gained 84,000 jobs since
1994 and moved up the national ranks of cities with Fortune 500
headquarters, from eighth place to fifth.
</P>
<P>
   And civic endeavors are finding new caretakers. Support for pro
sports has come from Columbia _ home to E. Stanley Kroenke,
minority owner of the Rams football franchise, and to Bill and
Nancy Laurie, who put up $400 million to acquire the St. Louis
Blues hockey club.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the exit of a big corporate player can have lasting
effects. Without a well-known chief executive officer leading the
cheers, charitable giving may suffer, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   A series of mergers and headquarters shutdowns flattened
fund-raising for Wichita's United Way of the Plains in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The charity clearinghouse received more than $308,000 from Pizza
Hut and its employees in 1993, but only $101,000 in 1997 after
Pizza Hut's base shifted to Texas. Thorn America and its workers
gave more than $114,000 in 1997; its donations disappeared this
year following a headquarters move. Community lifeline
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area, few institutions chip in on civic
projects as much as Sprint does.
</P>
<P>
   Its $9 million contribution for the Union Station refurbishment
was the third-largest. It donated $4 million to the Royals
Succession Plan Fund. And when the Kansas City Zoo needed a new
attraction, the company backed the Sprint IMAX Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The company opened a call center to kick-start the 18th and Vine
restoration project. Friday is not just Friday here: At the
Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art, it's Sprint Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Only Hallmark tops the $2.75 million that Sprint and its
employees donated to the Heart of America United Way agencies last
year. Of the nearly $7 million the Sprint Foundation gave away in
1998, roughly $5 million went to area organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint officials have said they intend to remain a large
employer here and continue their corporate citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   People who study the effect of America's increasingly transient
companies note that hand-wringing won't change the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have control over this anyway,'' said Auburn
University researcher Danny Lam. ``You might as well be
optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, Internorth Inc. was a corporate citizen
without peer in Omaha. It had adopted Central High School and
helped redeveloped Omaha's inner city and downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Then a series of mergers swallowed the homegrown natural gas
company. It changed its name to Enron Corp. and, in 1986, moved its
headquarters to Houston. Most of Enron's 2,200 jobs and its top
executives left.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was very much a feeling of panic,'' said Vicki Krecek, a
vice president of the Greater Omaha Chamber of Commerce. ``This
made it clear that you cannot count on even the most loyal
corporate citizen to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Civic leaders say that most everything _ the arts, charities,
downtown retail _ would be healthier had Enron stayed. Yet the void
has largely been filled.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Joslyn Art Museum. Its three most important
collections in 1986 were all on loan from Enron. Upon moving, Enron
donated one to the museum and sold it another. The museum couldn't
afford, and so lost, the third.
</P>
<P>
   Enron also followed through on a fund-raising campaign that
delivered an additional $2 million to the museum. While it
continues to give gifts, they are smaller.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's forced us to go out to other people in the community who
used to say, `You've got Enron; why do you need my support?' &UR; ''
said Audrey Kauders, museum deputy director. ``It has been a net
loss, but it's not the end of the world.'' Filling the voids
</P>
<P>
   Some places can weather corporate departures almost without
notice, especially in the 1990s economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years San Francisco has lost the headquarters of
Pacific Telesis Group, Bank of America, Wells Fargo, TransAmerica
and AirTouch Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for every Class A company moving out, 10 smaller ones are
moving in,'' said Michael Sigala of the city's economic development
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, closings of military bases and large manufacturing
plants gave some cities chances to spread their economic risks
among smaller replacement businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Experts point to the redevelopment of the steel-plant district
in Pittsburgh, the rebirth of Baltimore's industrial waterfront and
the mix of small manufacturers in the mammoth plant that Chase
Brass Co. left behind in Waterbury, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Lam said he suspected that even with the Sprint merger, many
jobs would stay put.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a technical staff that is very happy in Kansas,
you would be very foolish to tell them to move,'' Lam said. ``They
probably have family there, their network of child care, schools,
you name it. You could have a lot of them quitting on you if you
tried to force them to move.''
</P>
<P>
   A symphony or a museum that depends heavily on a few corporate
sponsors, he said, is vulnerable to the fortunes of those few
firms. One big corporation, Lam said, ``shouldn't be a magnet for
solutions for all of a community's problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In losing the headquarters of Honeywell Inc., Minneapolis is
concerned about also losing an inner-city neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Honeywell's executives have worked in a campus in
the Phillips district, one of the city's poorest neighborhoods. The
company has pumped millions of dollars into developing housing
there.
</P>
<P>
   Honeywell's headquarters and 800 administrative jobs will move
to New Jersey pending regulatory approval of a merger with
AlliedSignal Inc. But the company has pledged to keep 7,500 jobs in
Minneapolis and to support the Phillips neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The parent company of Southwestern Bell says it, too, strives to
be a good civic partner in places far beyond its San Antonio
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty simple, profound ideal,'' said SBC spokesman
Kevin Belgrade. ``We live in the communities we serve. We work in
those communities, and we want our workers to be happy whether
they're in St. Louis or San Antonio.''
</P>
<P>
   SBC _ which still employs thousands in St. Louis _ recently made
a sizable donation to the St. Louis Zoo's $55 million capital
improvements campaign. What cannot be known is what SBC would have
meant to St. Louis had it stayed. That potential, instead, is all
San Antonio's.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, only six months after Southwestern Bell announced the
move, the company joined a group of San Antonio investors that paid
$75 million to keep the Spurs basketball team in town. SBC
donations also have helped keep the San Antonio Symphony afloat and
will provide new lecture halls and a high-tech library for a small
college.
</P>
<P>
   Said Mario Hernandez, president of the city's economic
development group: ``The brainpower a community gains by having a
major headquarters, that's priceless.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
