<HEADER>
A1960 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FISHER-PUMPKIN-KAN &LR;      10-09 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-PUMPKIN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI TOWN ONE OF MANY MARKING A DAY FOR PUMPED UP PUMPKINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REPUBLIC, Mo. _ Last Saturday, Dan Westfall's pride and joy sat
for hours smack dab in the middle of North Main Avenue and West
Grant Street here _ the hub of this Greene County community.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic was blocked off for a fall celebration, one of many that
animate small-town Missouri in the fall. Thus North Main was
essentially a sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   What Westfall had wrought was a crowd magnet. Thousands circled
it slowly, eyed it, pointed at it, took photographs and videos and
touched it, murmuring.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a pumpkin. Albeit it a big one. It took nine men to
load Westfall's pumpkin onto his pickup. Once in Republic at the
Pumpkin Daze Festival, it took a forklift to place it on a feed
scale.
</P>
<P>
   The pumpkin weighed in at 647 pounds, easily a Missouri record.
The old record _ set in 1997 _ was 503 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Westfall just grinned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here in 1992 with a pumpkin that weighed 72 pounds,''
he said. ``Finished dead last. But I made up my mind. I was going
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be easy. All up and down North Main, 300-pounders
were common. A few rested on sturdy tables. Others were in the
backs of pickups. The big guys rested on carpet-covered pallets,
necessities for the forklift.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing what was on North Main to ordinary pumpkins was like
equating giants to Lilliputians, redwoods to redbuds, or whales to
minnows. Here was the Great Atlantic variety of Cucurbita Maxima.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was similar at 16 other places in the United States
and five in Canada last Saturday for the Great Pumpkin
Commonwealth's annual ``weigh-off.''
</P>
<P>
   The North American winner _ meaning the biggest in the world _
was Gerry Checkon of Spangler, Pa., with a 1,131-pound pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   The rival World Pumpkin Confederation also had its weigh-off
last weekend. Bill Bobier of Windsor, N.Y., had a 986-pounder.
</P>
<P>
   Westfall's entry seemed, well, spare.
</P>
<P>
   A matter of latitude, explained Leon Medlin, a grower and
weigh-in official.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're down here between the 37th and 38th parallels,'' Medlin
said. ``For really big pumpkins, you'd better be up around the 42nd
and 43rd parallels _ the northeast and southern Canada. There they
get warm days and more hours of sunlight. But the key there is
their cool nights. Pumpkins love cool nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Medlin said bigger Missouri pumpkins would come with better
seeds and by educating growers in the subtle pumpkin arts.
</P>
<P>
   Although pumpkins have been cultivated for 10,000 years, giant
pumpkins are a relatively recent phenomenon. An Ontario farmer
named William Warnock stunned the 1900 Paris World's Fair by
entering a 400-pound pumpkin. In 1903 he grew a 403-pounder.
</P>
<P>
   That record held until 1976, when a Pennsylvania pumpkin hit 451
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   At roughly the same time, dairy farmer Howard Dill was
hybridizing pumpkin seeds on his Nova Scotia farm. To giant-pumpkin
growers, the name Howard Dill is akin to that of Microsoft's Bill
Gates in the computer world.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, propelled by Dill's seeds, pumpkin weights went
into the stratosphere. By the mid-1990s the first of what the
pumpkin-obsessed call ``kilo-pounders''_ which can grow 35 pounds a
day _ had been authenticated in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play for keeps in the Northeast,'' said Westfall, who
lives just north of Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes growers try a little skulduggery to add pounds to
their pumpkins. In past years there have been charges that growers
slathered auto body filler into cracks in the sides of pumpkins or
injected silicon gel or water into them.
</P>
<P>
   Westfall's seeds came from Dill _ $10 got three of the little
rascals measuring roughly an inch by a half-inch. Getting three
gold doubloons couldn't have been more exciting, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Westfall, a warehouse worker, started them in individual pots
and then transferred them to his 25- by 50-foot patch.
</P>
<P>
   When the best vine sprouted, he pollinated it with an artist's
brush. He filled soda bottles with water, froze them and put them
near the blossom to keep it cool. He built sunscreens. He used
insulation, Plexiglas, even bed sheets for various enclosures. He
fertilized continuously. His wife, Wanda, helped throughout,
especially making sure that watering occurred precisely at 5 a.m.,
1 p.m. and 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Ackerman, a grower from Marshfield, said he knew one grower
who became so fixated that he set up banks of lights around his
patch in an attempt to replicate the longer daylight hours of
southern Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he got was a $400 light bill,'' said Ackerman. ``But
that's how this stuff gets to you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Great Pumpkin Commonwealth offered a $15,000 prize for this
year's champion. In Republic, Westfall received $300. Figuring the
cost of his seeds, fertilizer, water, supplies, and more, he said,
he had laid out close to $100. But that doesn't even start to count
the labor and time he and Wanda put in.
</P>
<P>
   For Westfall, the payoff is down the road _ specifically the 200
or so seeds inside the pumpkin's 8-inch-thick walls. He's already
making plans for the 2000 growing season.
</P>
<P>
   As for his pumpkin's immediate fate, Westfall said he would put
it on display at a local business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, around Halloween, I'll take it home and carve it into a
jack-o'-lantern,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like you're supposed to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
