<SLUG> BC-RAC-GOLDCUP-BEHRENS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLD CUP A BATTLE FOR THE AGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Behrens, the leading handicap horse in training,
meets Lemon Drop Kid, the leading 3-year-old in training, in
Sunday's $1 million Jockey Club Gold Cup at Belmont Park, the
advantage for both Horse of the Year and 3-year-old male honors
will be at stake.
</P>
<P>
   The Grade I, 1 1/4-mile contest is doubly important for Lemon
Drop Kid, winner of the Belmont Stakes and Travers at Saratoga Aug.
28, his last outing. Not only is the talented son of Kingmambo
chasing Behrens for the most important Eclipse Award, but also he
is chasing the now-retired Charismatic, winner of the Kentucky
Derby and Preakness, for the sophomore title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behrens is the top horse,'' said Hall of Famer Scotty
Schulhofer, who trains Lemon Drop Kid. ``He's an excellent horse,
and he's done well. I'm not confident that I can beat him, but I'd
like to try. Lemon Drop Kid is a very competitive horse. He likes
to run, and, if we get a good, fast track, he'll prove he's a good
horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the weather may not cooperate with Schulhofer, as
there is rain in the forecast. It's not that Lemon Drop Kid can't
stand up in the mud, but he hasn't won in it, with two seconds and
a third in three tries. Also, Vision and Verse, a 3-year-old who
was second to Lemon Drop Kid in the Belmont and Travers, hates mud;
his trainer, Bill Mott, said Vision and Verse will be scratched if
the track is off.
</P>
<P>
   ``To beat Behrens would be a feather in Lemon Drop Kid's hat,''
said Schulhofer. ``To me, he's already done enough to win best
3-year-old. But if he beats Behrens, that will help a lot. He's
coming to the race as good as a horse can. He's much more mature.
He's grown up and filled out. He's a man now. He's got his mind on
what he's doing, and he's much more aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned about Behrens. He looks good. Whoever beats
him in the Gold Cup will be the winner. Hopefully, it will be Lemon
Drop Kid. Lemon Drop Kid is one hell of a good horse. He's got a
lot of talent and a lot of sense to go with it. It would be great
if he could be Horse of the Year. If he can beat Behrens, and win
the Breeders' Cup, then he could do it. He'd have a big edge on it.
When you come against older horses, and a horse like Behrens,
you're going into unknown territory. Lemon Drop Kid is going to
have to move up to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Behrens, a 5-year-old son of Pleasant Colony, has been first or
second in all seven starts this year (7-4-3-0). He captured the
Gulfstream Park Handicap, the Oaklawn Handicap, the Massachusetts
Handicap at Suffolk Downs, and the Suburban at Belmont, in
succession. His win streak was stopped only when the now-retired
Victory Gallop beat him by a nose following a furious stretch drive
in the Whitney at Saratoga Aug. 1, the last time he raced.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing awesome,'' said Jim Bond, who trains Behrens.
``He's been up at Saratoga training well, and, hopefully, he's
ready. He's telling me we've done right by him, and he's done
everything right by us. I'm not going to holler at him because he
got beat a whisker in his last race. He's a great horse, and has
overcome everything, including his trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behrens has been very consistent all year, and I want to be
the last one left standing in the winner's circle. I would like to
win Horse of the Year with Behrens, but he has to earn it.
</P>
<P>
   ``By winning the Belmont and Travers, Lemon Drop Kid proved that
he is a top 3-year-old, a very nice horse. We can't take him
lightly, but he's going to have to run an A+ race to beat us. He
can't just run an A race, he's got to be A+ to beat an older horse
like Behrens. I think he is the horse to beat in the Gold Cup, but
it's a tough thing for a 3-year-old to beat an older horse at this
level. We'll see if Behrens is up for the task of holding him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behrens just makes you look good. He's always been a good
horse, now he's a great horse. Hopefully, after the Gold Cup and
Breeders' Cup, everybody will be talking the same way about him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
