<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-WESTERN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACIFIC IS DEEP IN TALENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's time again for the annual division previews, and this year
we're going to work our way East instead of West. For starters, all
_ and we do mean all _ of the behemoths are in the Western
Conference. Right now, the top eight teams in the West would be
favored to win a series against any team in the East. Is it too
late for the Board of Governors to revamp the playoff system and
get rid of the mandatory Eastern finalist?
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Division houses three legit championship contenders
in the Lakers, Trail Blazers, and Suns. It houses America's Team,
the Sacramento Kings, who this season are must-see TV. It houses
the hapless Clippers, who, to no one's surprise, will remain ever
thus, Chris Ford's wizardry notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are easily the most intriguing, thanks to the arrival
of Phil Jackson, now working for another set of Jerrys (West and
Buss). There's also the quixotic journey of Shaquille O'Neal to win
a meaningful game and the Lakers' internal makeup, which last year
was roughly the same as plutonium.
</P>
<P>
   Portland, meanwhile, has added Scottie Pippen to an already
obscene arsenal, losing no starters in a six-for-one transaction
with Houston. The Trail Blazers have what the Lakers don't: a power
forward and a point guard. They also have the best team plane.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns have brought Penny Hardaway west in a true heist (Danny
Manning and Pat Garrity) from the donation-minded Magic and will
put points on the board, maybe even more than they allow. Their
games with Sacramento could actually produce a combined 200 points!
</P>
<P>
   Here's a team-by-team preview of the potent Pacific with teams
listed in predicted order of finish.
</P>
<P>
   PORTLAND TRAIL BLAZERS &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 35-15, first. Lost to San Antonio in conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Scottie Pippen, Steve Smith, Detlef
Schrempf, Joe Kleine.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: Isaiah Rider, Jim Jackson, Walt Williams,
Kelvin Cato, Stacey Augmon, assorted flotsam.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``And The Money Kept Rolling In (And Out).''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: Wow. Wait till Pippen takes his first ride on the
team plane and the flight attendant asks him how he likes his Ruth
Chris steak prepared. The Blazers have mind-boggling depth, talent
everywhere, with the one possible weakness being creaky Arvydas
Sabonis and backup Kleine. Mike Dunleavy can throw out a
Pippen-Brian Grant-Sabonis-Damon Stoudamire-Smith starting five and
still have Rasheed Wallace, Schrempf, Greg Anthony, and Jermaine
O'Neal available. With Pippen, Schrempf, and Sabonis, this has a
chance to be a highlight-film passing team. Wanna get picky? OK,
they could use another shooting guard, but Pippen could play there
in a pinch. The time is clearly now and Portland has loaded up
big-time.
</P>
<P>
   PHOENIX SUNS &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 27-23, tied for third. Lost to Portland in the
first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Penny Hardaway, Rodney Rogers, Shawn Marion,
Corie Blount, Oliver Miller.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: Danny Manning, Pat Garrity, Chris Morris.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``We'll Sing In The Sunshine.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: How would you like to be the guy back on defense
when Hardaway and Jason Kidd come down the floor? How do you defend
them in the halfcourt? The Suns could be an offensive colossus,
especially with the new rules. They have scoring up front with
Cliff Robinson, Tom Gugliotta, and the newly signed Rogers to go
along with their powerhouse backcourt. But will they be able to
stop anyone? Last season, opponents shot 45 percent against the
Suns, the sixth-worst defense in the league. Phoenix may get some
help there from the underrated Blount, but the rest of the group is
going to have to step up defensively, even though the Suns have the
capability to win most shootouts. This will be a fun team to watch,
even with Luc Longley in the middle. And rookie Marion should
prosper in their high-r.p.m. tempo.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES LAKERS &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 31-19, second. Lost to San Antonio in second
round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: A.C. Green, Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: Derek Harper, Sean Rooks, J.R. Reid.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``Dog and Butterfly.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: Well, we're all going to see how much Phil misses
No. 23, aren't we? Actually, the ever-shrewd Jackson walked into
the ideal setting: a talented team with a superstar unable to win
and plenty of talent around him. Sound familiar? ``I've won
everywhere I've been except college, the pros, and the Pacific
Division,'' says Shaq. It's true. This is his fourth year in Los
Angeles and the Lakers still haven't won a division title with him
there, let alone anything else. For that to change, Jackson is
going to have to get these guys to like each other and play
defense, no easy tasks. It also wouldn't hurt Shaq to start
rebounding and try to be civil with Kobe Bryant (and vice versa).
Jackson has enviable offensive might in O'Neal, Bryant, and Glen
Rice, but the team is still too iffy at point guard (Derek Fisher)
and power forward (Green, Robert Horry) and got no decent offseason
help to be given a free ride at this point.
</P>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO KINGS &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 27-23, tied for third. Lost to Utah in first
round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Nick Anderson, Tony Delk, Ty Corbin, Bill
Wennington, Darrick Martin.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: Tariq Abdul-Wahad, Vernon Maxwell.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``Ye Rambling Boys of Pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: This team was one well-defended pick-and-roll
away from eliminating Utah in the first round last year. It grew up
a lot, picked up fans along the way (including NBC, which didn't
even know where Sacramento was), and now has a chance to build on
this. The Kings added backcourt depth to help Jason Williams and a
couple of veterans, Corbin and Wennington, to help up front and in
the locker room. More important, they added a decent shooting guard
in Anderson, part of the Magic razing. The Kings were the only team
in the NBA to average 100 points last season and barely made that.
They also were one of two teams to allow more than 100 per game, so
we have a little work to do on the defensive end. (Do we sense a
trend here?) The Kings are now on everyone's screen. The days of
the automatic W at Arco Arena are over.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDEN STATE WARRIORS &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 21-29, sixth. Did not make playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Mookie Blaylock, Tim Legler.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: Bimbo Coles, Duane Ferrell, Tony Delk, Muggsy
Bogues.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``Easy People.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: Could this be a mirage? Well, maybe. But the
Warriors were actually in the playoff hunt last season until the
final week. The downside? Their most reliable, dependable player
was Terry Cummings, who turns 39 in March. Still, the Warriors
appear to have improved with the addition of the streaky but savvy
Blaylock. Golden State was desperate to get a point guard, and
Mookie was available. He comes and goes on offense, but if he still
has the defensive passion, that's a huge benefit. P.J. Carlesimo
also needs Antawn Jamison to continue his upward path; he came on
strong last year with increased playing time. But the center
position will be a problem now that Erick Dampier is out for a
while. Former No. 1 pick Adonal Foyle has done basically nothing in
two seasons; we expected far more from a Colgate man.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE SUPERSONICS &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 25-25, fifth. Did not make playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Horace Grant, Brent Barry, Chuck Person,
Greg Foster, Ruben Patterson, Lazaro Borrel, Vernon Maxwell.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: Olden Polynice, Detlef Schrempf, Hersey
Hawkins, Dale Ellis, Billy Owens, Corey Maggette, Cheri Hanson.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``Long, Long Time.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: Only one player, Gary Payton, remains from the
Seattle team that made it to the Finals in 1996. Schrempf and
Hawkins are the latest vets to go as GM Wally Walker tries to
rebuild and contend at the same time. That's hard to do. He did
re-sign Vin Baker, who is promising to be the Vin Baker of old. If
he is, that will help. If he isn't, we're talking freefall. But
even beyond Payton and Baker, there's not much here here, Cuban
defector Borrell notwithstanding. Grant is going to have to play
center, which, out West, means he'll have to contend with Shaq,
Hakeem, David, Arvydas, and others who know how to play the middle.
He's also about 300 years old and has a lot of miles on the tires.
Patterson could end up starting at small forward for lack of anyone
else, and Barry is the starting shooting guard _ and he can't
shoot! Even Hanson, the upbeat, irrepressible media relations
czarina, bolted for Milwaukee. It all adds up to a depressing year.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES CLIPPERS &QC; 
(FR) Last season: 9-41, seventh place. Did not make playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key additions: Lamar Odom, Derrick Anderson, Eric Murdock.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Key losses: Lorenzen Wright, Lamond Murray, Rodney Rogers,
Pooh Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Team song: ``Dying In The Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: Plus ca change . . . Over the summer, the
Clippers actually did two things that real NBA franchises do: They
signed their own free agent (Eric Piatkowski) and managed to sign
and trade two others (Wright, Murray) just before they left town.
Anderson, who thinks he's better than he really is, is what they
have to show for Murray. A couple of draft picks from Atlanta were
deemed sufficient compensation for Wright. (At least they kept him
from going to the Lakers.) But Rogers still left without
compensation and now their best player, Maurice Taylor, is poised
to do likewise next summer. Until he does, however, Ford can field
a front line of Odom, Taylor, and Michael Olowokandi, which is
passable. The backcourt is, well, Anderson and the point guard du
jour. It could be Murdock. It could be Anderson. It apparently
won't be Sherman Douglas, who manned the position last year. The
one noticeable upgrade is that they won't be playing in that
horrible Sports Arena anymore. They now share the dazzling downtown
Staples Center with the Lakers, which is as close as they'll get to
the real NBA this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
