<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONVENE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVES IN KC TAKE AIM AT BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Three conservative presidential candidates
speaking Saturday in Kansas City ripped Republican front-runner
George W. Bush as ``Clinton lite,'' a mushy-mouthed, unprincipled
leader destined to lead the GOP to defeat next year.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan, Gary Bauer and Steve Forbes took turns swinging at
Bush and tossing applause-generating rhetoric at a convention of
conservative Republicans known as the National Federation of
Republican Assemblies.
</P>
<P>
   The convention was at the Music Hall in Municipal Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Texas governor, did not attend the gathering. Assembly
officials said they felt snubbed because Bush was in Missouri on
Saturday for a Springfield fund-raiser for U.S. Rep. Roy Blunt, yet
did not come to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know quite how we win the White House back for the
Republican Party when on every major issue he's in agreement with
the likely Democratic nominee,'' Bauer, formerly of the Family
Research Council, said of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Texan, Forbes said, comes across ``as someone who is
embarrassed by the basic principles of this party, which can be
summed up in the words `more freedom, less government.' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Bush did not return telephone calls Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was an obvious target because of comments he made last week
criticizing GOP conservatives. He upbraided the Republican-led
Congress for a plan he said would have balanced the budget on the
backs of the poor. And he scolded the party for what he saw as
pessimism about America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often, on social issues, my party has painted an image of
America slouching toward Gomorrah,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The convention crowd roared at many of the anti-Bush comments
and appeared eager to hear him taken to task.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday afternoon, officials at the gathering announced
the results of a straw poll conducted while the candidates spoke to
a crowd estimated at 500. Anyone who paid $25 to attend the
afternoon rally could participate.
</P>
<P>
   The vote showed the lack of enthusiasm for Bush. Forbes won with
380 votes, or 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the field were 172 votes for Buchanan, 149 for
former Ambassador Alan Keyes, 86 for Bauer, 35 for Bush, three each
for Sen. John McCain of Arizona and former Transportation Secretary
Elizabeth Dole, and one for former Vice President Dan Quayle, who
recently dropped out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Today the convention will conduct its main order of business,
which is to endorse a GOP candidate for president. Convention rules
require that two-thirds of the delegates agree on a candidate
before an official preference is issued. The straw poll taken
Saturday is not binding.
</P>
<P>
   Formed in 1996, the assembly is a grass-roots group of GOP
activists who pride themselves on being ``Ronald Reagan
Republicans.'' One catalyst for their formation was 1996 Republican
presidential nominee Bob Dole's disdain for the party platform,
which was decidedly conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the group opposes abortion and says the
family is the cornerstone of society and that all human rights are
granted by God, not government.
</P>
<P>
   The assembly claims 8,700 dues-paying members in 43 states.
Among its members are David Miller, the Eudora insurance agent who
was defeated by Bill Graves in the 1998 Republican primary for
Kansas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Ashcroft was the only congressional member from Kansas
or Missouri to show up Saturday, but he said he was not an assembly
member.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the science of good politics is unity and to work
with people and to try to bring them together,'' Ashcroft said in
an interview. He is in a re-election battle next year with Missouri
Gov. Mel Carnahan, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Also speaking Saturday were Kansas Board of Education member
Steve Abrams of Arkansas City, who led the fight to de-emphasize
evolution in state teaching standards, and Gary Aldrich, a former
FBI agent who wrote a book that alleged White House corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Although the event Saturday attracted three major presidential
contenders, as well as the long-shot Keyes, the gathering attracted
little national media attention. Even the candidates downplayed the
significance of today's endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to win to keep going,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Convention organizers said Forbes had poured the most money into
winning the endorsement. He is seeking to establish himself as the
top alternative if Bush stumbles in the early 2000 primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who was the first to speak, set the tone by emphasizing
themes that were repeated by the other candidates. In emphasizing
his anti-abortion credentials, Forbes said he would appoint federal
judges who believed the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will choose a running mate who also believes in the sanctity
of life,'' Forbes said to sustained applause.
</P>
<P>
   He said parents should have their pick of schools for their
children and that federal education money should be returned only
to states that offer school choice.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes advocated more money for the U.S. military.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pursuit of happiness means we have to be safe and secure in
the world,'' he said. ``That means we must stop hollowing out the
military of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes received his biggest applause for his trademark call for
a flat-tax system that would ``drive a stake'' through the heart of
the current tax code.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who may bolt the GOP for the Reform Party, drew
perhaps the loudest ovation of the afternoon when he suggested that
President Clinton was unfit to command the military.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who once worked for Reagan, skipped a morning news
conference and declined to meet with reporters after his 20-minute
speech. But in his address he again hinted that he was close to
leaving the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where we're headed right now,'' he said in
closing. ``But I do know that some months from now and some years
from now we'll be fighting for the same cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you hear we are engaged on another front, we are in
battle,'' Buchanan said. ``Don't wait for orders from headquarters.
Mount up and ride at the sound of the guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer called Bush the pessimist in the race. ``He is running as
a Bush Republican, and I am proudly running as a Reagan
Republican,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes advocated elimination of the income tax with revenue
replaced by sales taxes, tariffs and duties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
