<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-EATON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EATON'S ACTIONS SPEAK LOUDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Football players change. They grow. They mature.
They flame out. They fade away.
</P>
<P>
   What they seldom do is reinvent themselves. Madonna has
reinvented herself. Several times. Garth Brooks is trying it now.
Jesse Ventura did it.
</P>
<P>
   But football players? Nah.
</P>
<P>
   As the Sage of the Meadowlands, Bill Parcells, has always
maintained, ``You are what you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why what Chad Eaton has done in a two-year span is
amazing.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, you know Chad Eaton. No. 90. Starting defensive tackle
for the Patriots. Outspoken. Wild and crazy. Dyed his hair, put
tattoos on his body the way women put on lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   This is a guy who as a member of the Patriots practice squad was
so out of touch with his team that he came to work Monday morning
not even knowing whether his team had won or lost the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him about the doings of Mulder and Scully on ``The
X-Files,'' however, and Eaton could cite you chapter and verse
about what had happened the night before.
</P>
<P>
   But that was another lifetime ago.
</P>
<P>
   Before he went through the emotional trauma of seeing his mother
Nancy lose an eight-month battle to liver cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Before he and his wife Tina celebrated the birth of their son
David Chad.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was plucked off the Patriots' practice squad in
November 1996 by Parcells and defensive coordinator Bill Belichick
and learned that life in the NFL was more than practicing football
Monday through Friday, with Tuesdays off as well as most of your
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   That Chad Eaton is a distant relation to the one you will see
Sunday afternoon when the 4-0 Patriots face the 2-2 Chiefs at
Arrowhead Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, he's still media-friendly, which is how he got his first 15
minutes of fame a couple of years ago. You can hear him on the
radio each week on WEEI's ``Dennis and Callahan.'' Look around the
Patriot locker room during any given media session and Eaton will
be giving a state of Patriot Nation assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of it went to his head,'' said his friend and former
college teammate at Washington State, Drew Bledsoe, with a smile
and a laugh when asked to describe the difference in the
6-foot-5-inch, 300-pound Eaton. ``He used to be a a nice guy. Now
he's a media whore.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Bledsoe got a little more serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a dominant player in college and it took him a while to
get adjusted in the NFL,'' said Bledsoe. ``He's come on in the last
two years, and I expect him to prove to be a force.''
</P>
<P>
   Eaton doesn't disagree with the assessment or the prediction.
The tattoos are gone, the hair is back to a more natural sandy
blond, and conversations around the locker room with Eaton reveal
what he is: a funny, outgoing professional football player who is
serious about his job, without being overly serious about himself.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him about the switch, about the toning down of his outer
self and he shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to switch gears,'' he said. ``What I was doing wasn't
working for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Eaton wasn't sure what he wanted or who he was.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up a small-town kid in Washington and went on to a
small-town atmosphere in Pullman, Wash., the outpost in college
football known as Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even then, he recognized reality when he saw it. Like the
time a bungee cord was set up from the top of a crane just off
campus.
</P>
<P>
   Was it Eaton who chose to dive through the air?
</P>
<P>
   No, it was Bledsoe, the thrill-seeking quarterback, who made the
jump _ a fact unbeknown at the time to Cougars coach Mike Price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there with him,'' said Eaton with a laugh. ``I said,
`Oh, no, there goes our season, we're going to be 0-11.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That Eaton was even part of a team amazed him. He grew up with a
noninterest in sports that still exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the grunge scene around Seattle,'' he said. ``I hated
sports.''
</P>
<P>
   But a friend mentioned Eaton to his father, who then talked to a
friend who was a football coach at Puyallup High School.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, Eaton liked football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked the physical part,'' he said. ``I liked being part of
a team. I felt like a warrior. I pictured myself as a knight.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years of high school football and three more of college
turned him into an NFL prospect, although the first steps were
uneven at best.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals made him a seventh-round draft choice in 1995, but
he was released in training camp. He was signed by the Jets, cut 13
days later, and signed with the Cleveland Browns. He was on the
practice squad until the final two games of the regular season. He
was not activated for either of those last two games.
</P>
<P>
   He was hurt, angry, and ultimately . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I was bored,'' he said. ``What I did was practice football.''
</P>
<P>
   After Belichick rejoined Parcells with the Patriots in 1996,
Eaton took his practice squad routine to New England.
</P>
<P>
   But again football was not the first priority. His mother was
dying and Eaton couldn't do a thing about it. Eaton had to refocus.
Football became an escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't have football, I would have gone out of my mind,''
said Eaton, who was finally activated by the Patriots in December
1996, playing in each of the last four regular-season games and
three playoff games, including the Super Bowl loss to the Green Bay
Packers.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Eaton has emerged as a different player, a different
person. But he's still having fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never absorbed it as a business,'' he said. ``I try to
take out the business part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the business has gotten better. Once buried in the depths of
the practice squad, Eaton is now in the middle of a three-year $1.5
million contract. Not the megabucks of the NFL elite, but hardly
chump change.
</P>
<P>
   And while football occupies his days, he has a plan beyond he
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get into broadcasting when this is over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His brashness is toned down, though not to the point where he is
as reclusive as some teammates, who regard media interviews with
the same anticipation as root canal work. But he is no longer
someone the media turn to for outlandish statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was irritating,'' said Eaton, when asked about the
perception. ``I felt I needed to prove myself as a football player,
not just someone who was outspoken or wild.''
</P>
<P>
   His persona has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know him that well,'' said tackle Bruce Armstrong.
``But sure he's changed from a couple of years ago. The hair and
the tattoos, all of that's gone. But he's got a family now, right?
That changes you. It matures you.''
</P>
<P>
   Support also has come from the coaching staff, particularly head
coach Pete Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be comfortable as a second-string player,'' Carroll told
him. ``Don't accept that role. You've got a chance to make
something of yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a starter, however, has raised the bar of expectation.
Eaton concedes he has not played as well this season as he did a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The success I had last year isn't there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he also knows things are different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are coming to the line of scrimmage now and pointing me
out,'' he said. ``Now I know I have to do more things. But I feel I
have some kind of credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   He's got that. But he's also still changing, still in the
process of reinventing and redefining Chad Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still figuring what works for me,'' he said. ``So far it
seems to have worked, so I'm sticking with that recipe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
