<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-COLON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS ALREADY HAVE ACE IN PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even with a night's rest to put Game 1 in perspective, Cleveland
general manager John Hart could hardly contain his excitement. His
speech picked up speed Thursday afternoon as he praised the
previous night's starter, Bartolo Colon. Hart talked about the
impressive development of the 24-year-old staff ace over the last
two seasons. He carried on about Colon's competitive spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the man-in-charge described the righthander's
performance as dominant. ``We've been on the other end,'' said
Hart. ``We've been 0 for 8 in first games of the postseasons that
we've been in, too. I think the best thing that we took out of last
night was the fact that we were able to take a young man that we'd
been grooming to be a guy that could go out in a big game.''
</P>
<P>
   That big game is Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Red Sox' 9-3 win Saturday, Colon will come back on
three days' rest and start Game 4 at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be the first time I'm pitching with three days
rest. My arm feels good. I'm going to try to do everything,'' Colon
said through the Indians interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have the same approach and try and throw the kind
of game I always pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland GM said there's never been a question about
Colon's makeup as a stopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power arm. Great kid. Hard worker. He's emerging as that
guy,'' Hart said Thursday. ``To actually see him go out in a big
game with a tough matchup and pitch the way he did, that's good for
this franchise and it bodes well for years to come. We've got a
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   With Colon's commanding performance and the injury to Boston ace
Pedro Martinez both occurring in Game 1, the teams switched places.
Suddenly, the Indians knew the pleasure of having a dominant
pitcher win a series opener.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Cleveland's 3-2 win Wednesday, the dominance of
Colon and his 100-mile-per-hour fastball seemed almost too good to
believe for the Indians. The boost of confidence and burst of
momentum he provided his mates was immeasurable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bartolo has always pitched great against Pedro, but we
haven't always given him a lot of run support,'' said Cleveland
second baseman Roberto Alomar. ``We have to realize that Bartolo is
younger and he's still learning. I think Bartolo did a great job.
It's always nice to win the first game.''
</P>
<P>
   The youngster's education may not be finished, but the Indians'
search for a pitcher capable of controlling the outcome of key
games appears to have ended. While the injury to Martinez took some
of the attention away from the 11-strikeout effort of his Dominican
countryman, nothing was lost on the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``From Bartolo's point of view, I think he woke up  &UR; today &LR;  and
felt he pitched a pretty good game,'' Jim Thome said Thursday. ``He
didn't necessarily beat Pedro, but he beat the Red Sox. That was
huge for us. It seems like when Bartolo faces Pedro, he brings his
game to another level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
