<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1973 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-JOHNSON     10-09 1757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-JOHNSONQUINN?-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUINN, JOHNSON PUSH TO MAKE SWEET 15 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There have been opportunities to make things easier on
themselves, but then again, they are so accustomed to the toughest
of roads that nothing fazes them anymore. Both Kevin Johnson and
Fran Quinn have learned to grind away in the gut-wrenching
occupation of touring golf professional, and the fact that the
calendar has turned to October means they are running out of
chances.
</P>
<P>
   That's the bad news.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is, they don't need many chances. They need one
more tournament, which conveniently enough is all that remains to
the 1999 Nike Tour schedule. The Tour Championship will be held in
two weeks, after which the top 15 players on the money list
automatically receive PGA Tour cards for 2000. Johnson currently
ranks 12th, with $114,167. Quinn is 16th, with $101,498.
</P>
<P>
   An opportunity to strengthen their positions was wasted this
weekend as both Johnson (78-67) and Quinn (77-70) missed the cut in
New Mexico. When the money list is updated Sunday, both could slip
down, but it won't change the focus of the moment, which is to play
well at the Tour Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I said I wasn't thinking about the
situation,'' said Quinn, the former Mass. Open champion from
Northborough, ``but it comes down to this: If you play well, it
will take care of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Quinn, Johnson has a victory on the Nike Tour this season.
Like Quinn, what he really wants is that PGA Tour card, something
that has eluded him since he turned pro nine years ago. The
32-year-old from Pembroke would like nothing more than to dance
around that most brutal of all challenges _ Qualifying School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to panic,'' said Johnson, who was as high as
fifth on the money list in April, after his victory at the South
Carolina Classic, which was followed by four top 10s in the next 10
events. But since August, Johnson has missed four cuts and been
outside the top 20 in six other events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been playing that good,'' he said. ``Actually, I
haven't been playing that badly, I'm just not scoring. I had it
going real well (at the Oregon Classic late in September) and was
just a few shots off the lead through three rounds. But I played
badly on the last nine, made two doubles, and fell from second or
third to 21st.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a tumble is crucial on the Nike Tour, since the fall-off in
pay is substantial. But looking at the money list and trying to
figure out what you need to do can drive you crazy, said Quinn. You
start to pay attention not only to your game, but to what those
behind you on the money list are doing, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not playing well, those are the breaks,'' said
Quinn, who has slumped since his victory in early August, missing
six cuts and finishing in the top 10 just once. He's at the end of
a 13-week stretch in which he has played 12 times. Though his wife,
Lori, and 14-month-old son, Owen, travel with him, the life is
tough, and this off week couldn't come at a better time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll work with Shawn Hester (an assistant pro at Charles River
CC and one of Quinn's closest friends), do a little bit of
maintenance, and take a break,'' he said. ``I am tired, but I keep
reminding myself that I'll have a lot of time off until January.''
</P>
<P>
   With only 50 players in the field for a $400,000 purse, the Nike
Tour Championship affords plenty of chance for players from outside
the top 15 to jump up. It also gives those inside the magic number
the opportunity to secure their status. So both Johnson and Quinn
have plenty riding on the event.
</P>
<P>
   Though Johnson appears to be losing ground, he refuses to treat
this year as a negative. After all, he wasn't fully exempt at the
start of the season and had to do some Monday qualifiers just to
get into a few events. It led to a third-place finish at the second
event of the season, then his victory six weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm close, and if anyone had told me at the beginning of the
year that I would be in this position, I would have taken it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Happier days
</P>
<P>
   Competitive golf returned to a more civil environment _ thank
goodness _ with the Dunhill Cup, which concludes Sunday at St.
Andrews. The competition features golfers playing for their
countries (16 three-man teams), but without the flag-waving and
histrionics. The first day, for instance, saw Craig Parry bail out
Australia, which was in danger of getting stunned by Japan. Down by
two shots to the unheralded Tsuyoshi Yoneyama, who was safely on in
regulation at the par-4 closing hole, Parry needed a birdie to
perhaps force a playoff. From about 45 yards, Parry did even
better: He chipped through the Valley of Sin and ran his shot up
the slope and into the hole for an eagle to earn a victory and give
Australia a 2-1 win. Parry deserved to celebrate, though his
reaction was far more sporting. He shook Yoneyama's hand and said,
``I'm sorry.'' . . . In Spain's opening victory over France, there
unfolded a scenario that had to be a nightmare revisited for
European followers. Ahead by two shots playing the 17th, Jose Maria
Olazabal made a triple-bogey in his match with Jean Van de Velde.
(Collapse? 17th-hole drama? Sound familiar?) As he did at
Brookline, however, Olazabal made birdie at the 18th; but unlike
The Country Club, where he had blown a 4-up lead on Justin Leonard,
that closing birdie got him into a playoff and the two-time Masters
champion converted a 10-foot birdie putt at No. 1 to edge the
Frenchman . . . Speaking of Van de Velde, he earned a flock of
admirers for the way he handled himself after the British Open at
Carnoustie, and he's sure to win over even more after he spoke out
against European Ryder Cup captain Mark James. Said Van de Velde,
who qualified for the team but played in only one match: ``Everyone
has been focusing on the Americans' bad behavior, but to me the
result had nothing to do with that. We lost because we asked too
much of most of the guys and because we didn't put enough trust in
three.'' . . . The American contingent at the Dunhill Cup _ Mark
O'Meara, Tom Lehman, and Payne Stewart _ had police escorts on
course, for fear they would be targeted by hecklers in the wake of
the Ryder Cup. But there were no incidents, and the police had to
concern themselves only with watching great golf. No surprise to
those who understand Scottish golf fans . . . It wasn't the best of
weeks for Lehman. The airline lost his luggage on the trip over,
then he missed the opening ceremonies because he overslept. On
Friday, Lehman was shocked by Emanuele Canonica, as Italy upset the
United States, and to make matters worse, the American had to be
asked back to the 18th green to tap in for his par. Apparently
thinking the match was over when Canonica tapped in for his par,
Lehman had left the green, forgetting that in medal match play,
nothing can be conceded. Though it was a moot point, Lehman was
penalized one shot for the slip-up . . . Quick, which of the
following names does not fit? O'Meara, Olazabal, Colin Montgomerie,
Ernie Els, Nick Price, Sergio Garcia, Carlos Franco, Craig Parry,
Paul Lawrie, Retief Goosen, Padraig Harrington, and Notah Begay.
Obviously, it is a cast of world-class golfers, most of whom have
proven themselves for years, and others (Garcia, Lawrie,
Harrington) who have only recently stepped upon the international
stage with noteworthy play. Then there is Begay. Why? Sure, he won
a PGA Tour event this year, the Reno-Tahoe Open, and has a solid
money-list ranking (59th), but the key to his inclusion is the fact
he is in the IMG stable. Guess who runs the World Match Play?
That's right, IMG. It's a shameless move to include Begay in the
field, particularly at the expense of, say, Darren Clarke. When Lee
Westwood asked out of the event, it would have been a natural move
to replace him with Clarke, but instead Begay got picked . . .
Things must be interesting with the ABC golf team in the aftermath
of Peter Alliss's stinging criticism of certain Americans and his
TV colleague, Curtis Strange. Regarding the Ryder Cup controversy,
Alliss was quoted in the London Telegraph as saying Americans are
``bad winners; their exuberance seems to be less gracious than our
exuberance and I have no idea why.'' When the Ryder Cup resumes at
the Belfry in 2001, the American captain, it has been rumored,
could be Strange. ``(He's) a Jekyll and Hyde,'' Alliss is quoted as
saying. ``I know him very well. We've worked together on ABC and
he's a real redneck at times; very stubborn and vitriolic when the
mood takes him.'' All this from an event that was intended to
foster goodwill and spirited competition.
</P>
<P>
   Out by a neck
</P>
<P>
   Pat Bates, who grew up in Manchester, learned to play golf at
Essex County Club, and went on to win the Mass. Open, is recovering
from surgery to repair a ruptured disk in his neck and just
recently started hitting balls again. His Nike Tour season lasted
just five events before he injured his neck in the simplest of
fashions _ giving his 1 1/2-year-old son a ride. ``He was on my
shoulders and I bent over fast,'' said Bates. ``It was a serious
blowout.'' The surgery went fine, said Bates, but things were rough
right afterward. He will not even attempt to go to Qualifying
School; instead, he will accept a full medical exemption and play
the Nike Tour again in 2000. There were bright notes to being on
the disabled list, said Bates, noting that he and wife Kristine
(daughter of Doug Tewell) welcomed daughter Kendall to the family
six months ago. There has been plenty of time to spend with the new
baby and older brother Spencer . . . You may have missed this
morsel from the Senior PGA Tour's stop in Clemmons, N.C., a week
ago. Fred Gibson, a 52-year-old former club pro who had but six top
10 finishes in 63 events, became the 11th first-time winner on the
Tour this year. A surprise? You could say that, given the fact that
Gibson earned a mere $704 in his PGA Tour career, that from a low
finish at the 1980 Kemper Open . . . Surely you can relate to Cindy
McCurdy. In the final round of the New Albany (Ohio) Classic last
Sunday, the LPGA Tour veteran took a 14 _ that's fourteen _ on the
par-5 13th by hitting four balls into the lake fronting the green.
Her back-side 50, in a round of 85, left her last among those who
made the cut. She had started the tournament 70-71 before a weekend
of 77-85.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
