<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX HOLD OFF INDIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Already down two games to the Cleveland Indians and winter one
loss away, the Red Sox Saturday spotted the Tribe their last
healthy superstar, shortstop Nomar Garciaparra, who sat out because
of his sore right wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Wait till next millennium?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly. With Garciaparra's stand-in, Lou Merloni, jump-starting
two rallies and John Valentin alternating between committing
another ghastly error and delivering big hits (tie-breaking home
run in the sixth inning, tie-breaking two-run double in the
seventh), the Sox extended summer for at least another day with a
9-3 swatting of Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Brian Daubach, who had promised there was still a little
magic left in the Belleville Basher, followed Valentin's
bases-loaded double with a three-run home run to make the seventh a
five-run inning, Boston's biggest in the postseason since scoring
six for Luis Tiant against the Big Red Machine in Game 1 of the
1975 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who trail the best-of-five-game series, 2-1, will send
Kent Mercker to the mound against Indians ace Bartolo Colon in Game
4 in Fenway Park. If the Yankees beat Texas Saturday night to close
out their Division Series, the Sox game will be played at 8 p.m. If
the Rangers are still alive, the Sox and Indians will play at 1.
</P>
<P>
   A scenario unfolded at Fenway Saturday that was all too familiar
to Sox fans: A starting pitcher, spinning a shutout, is forced to
leave after four innings because of an injury. But unlike Game 1,
when the victim was Boston ace Pedro Martinez, this time it was
Indians righthander Dave Burba, who set down the first nine Sox
batters, allowed only a bloop single by Butch Huskey in the fourth,
but departed after the inning with a 1-0 lead because of what was
announced as tightness in the underside of his right forearm.
</P>
<P>
   A Fenway Park gathering that already was taking a more animated
interest in this game than do the usual postseason assemblages of
pampered and privileged ticket-holders let out a bloodthirsty roar
at the sight of the new Indians pitcher: Jaret Wright, the
23-year-old with a hothead's mien and villain's reputation because
of a beanball-induced brawl in April.
</P>
<P>
   With a singsong ``Jaaa-rrrettt'' resonating through the stands,
Wright gave the revenge-seekers the satisfaction they were seeking
by allowing the Red Sox to seize a 2-1 lead in his first inning of
work.
</P>
<P>
   Merloni got things going by punching a ground ball through the
right side for a one-out single. Catcher Jason Varitek, hitless in
his first nine at-bats in the series and playing with a bad right
hand about which he has said nothing, lined a double off the
Monster, Merloni stopping at third.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Lewis, another member of the wounded wrist club, fought
back from an 0-and-2 count to 3-and-2, then lifted a soft line
drive just over the head of second baseman Robbie Alomar, scoring
Merloni with the tying run. Rookie Trot Nixon followed with a fly
to right field deep enough to score Varitek with the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in 23 innings that the Sox had scored more
than a run.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez, as calm as Pedro the Younger is passionate, had
given up a run in the top of the fourth on singles by Jim Thome and
Harold Baines and a sacrifice fly by David Justice. He left to a
standing ovation in the sixth that would have been sweeter had he
been able to hold onto the lead. But the Indians first pushed
across the tying run on a double by Alomar, an infield out, a walk,
and a fielder's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who struck out six and allowed just five hits while
throwing 96 pitches, was saluted as much for his gallantry and
grace as he was for his excellence.
</P>
<P>
   The game then turned into a question of who would prevail:
Johnny Val the slugger or his evil twin, Johnny Val the slinger.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin, who was hitless in his first 10 postseason at-bats but
had driven center fielder Kenny Lofton to the track in the fourth,
came up in the sixth and launched one that even Lofton couldn't
retrieve, a 409-foot home run into the triangle to give the Sox a
3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Indians' next at-bat, in an uncanny imitation of his
disastrous misplay in Game 1 _ same Sox pitcher on the mound (Derek
Lowe), same Indians batter (Manny Ramirez) _ Valentin bounced
another throw to first in the dirt, allowing Lofton to score the
tying run. Lofton had singled, taken second on an infield out, and
stolen third without drawing a throw. After a walk to Alomar, he
scored on the error by Valentin, who fielded a Ramirez grounder and
inexplicably threw on the run when he had enough time to have taken
a seat on a Jordan's sofa.
</P>
<P>
   But this was clearly a night when Wright's stuff was wrong for
the Indians. He walked Merloni to open the Sox seventh and hit
Varitek in the arm with his next pitch. Indians manager Mike
Hargrove then went to lefthander Ricardo Rincon, who induced Darren
Lewis to bunt into a force play, then struck out Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Out of danger? Hardly. Jose Offerman drew a walk, loading the
bases for Valentin, who scorched a liner just inside the third-base
line. The ball was headed for the corner before being touched by a
fan, but two runs scored on the ground-rule double. Then Daubach,
one pitch after clocking plate umpire Tim Welke in the head with
his backswing, cleared the bases with a blast over the camera well
in center.
</P>
<P>
   The Belleville Basher, benched for the second straight start,
had entered the game in the sixth as a pinch hitter for DH Butch
Huskey and had whiffed for the fourth straight time in this series.
</P>
<P>
   A walk to Mike Stanley, a single by Troy O'Leary, and another
hit by Merloni made it 9-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox were alive to play another day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
