<SLUG> BC-IOWA-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE QUESTIONS BRADLEY'S PARTY LOYALTY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES _ Vice President Al Gore drew his sharpest contrasts
yet with former Sen. Bill Bradley Saturday, casting his rival for
the Democratic presidential nomination as one who went along with
the Reagan budget cuts and fled Washington after Newt Gingrich and
the Republicans took over the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bradley cast Gore as a captive of the
establishment and the entrenched powers of the party and the vice
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates were campaigning here Saturday and both spoke
Saturday night before 3,000 people at a state Democratic Party
dinner. In Iowa, which will hold the campaign's first caucus, now
scheduled Jan. 31., Gore is ahead in polls. But Rob Tully, the
chairman of the Iowa Democratic party, said the race was fluid and
very competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon, during a campaign walk through neighborhood
streets, Gore portrayed Bradley as a disloyal Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The 1981 budget vote, Gore said, was ``the single most defining
vote for the Democrats in the last 20 years,'' and the
determination to counter Gingrich was second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of us was called upon to fight against it with everything
we had or not, and he did not,'' Gore said of Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his attempt to pressure Bradley into engaging him,
the vice president also said he wanted to debate Bradley once a
week, up from his earlier call for debates once every two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates so far plan another joint appearance at a
town-hall meeting in New Hampshire on Oct. 27, and a debate on Jan.
8 in Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   Gore sidestepped mentioning Bradley by name Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's intention all day was clear _ to appeal to the core
of loyal Democrats who will vote in caucuses and primaries and to
raise doubts about Bradley's perseverance and reliability in the
face of difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic base is a crucial segment that Gore needs to nail
down as Bradley's support swells, particularly among independents.
</P>
<P>
   To try to interest that base in his campaign, Gore has taken to
telling his audiences, as he did Saturday, that the next president
could appoint three or four new justices to the Supreme Court and
that if a Republican is president, any new justices would be vetted
by religious conservatives like Jerry Falwell, Pat Robertson and
Ralph Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Gore portrayed himself as an unswerving Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't walk away from the fight when Newt Gingrich took over
the Congress,'' Gore said. ``I didn't walk away from the fight when
Reaganomics was put up for a vote on the floor. I didn't walk away
from the fight when farmers needed farm credit, when farmers needed
loan deficiency payments and conservation programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley did not directly respond to Gore's comments, but he
portrayed Gore as the establishment candidate and a captive of vice
presidential trappings, which he has been trying to escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that we are up against an entrenched
power.'' Bradley said. ``When a candidate has the president of the
United States standing by his side, loyally, as he has stood by his
side, and he has the Democratic National Committee, most of the
large Democratic fund-raisers, arrives in Air Force II, and is
ahead by 15 points nationally, well, that's entrenched power. All I
have is the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley did not run for re-election to a fourth term in the
Senate in 1996. He did vote for the Reagan budget cuts but he
simultaneously supported tax cuts, saying that if that combination
of proposals had passed, the nation could have avoided the ensuing
budget deficits.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was already vice president when Gingrich became speaker of
the House in 1995 and had little choice but to stay as he and
Clinton headed into a re-election campaign in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that the Reagan budget had raised child poverty, hurt
public education and limited access to health care. ``I voted
against it,'' said Gore, who served in the Senate with Bradley. ``I
fought against it. Some felt that in order to survive politically,
they should vote for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The attacks on Bradley's loyalty to the party come as Gore is
trying to energize his campaign and show that he is ready and able
to fight for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore remains somewhat cautious. In a kind of minuet with the
media, he hesitated to criticize Bradley until he was egged on by
reporters. But his campaign also uncharacteristically gave
reporters the opportunity to do so, staging a rare ``media
availability'' with Gore a few hours before Saturday night's joint
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The timing virtually guaranteed that the main topic would be
Bradley. Conducted on a leafy suburban street here, where Gore was
backed by a throng of cheering children, the session with reporters
lasted only a few minutes, and Gore largely joshed his way through
it.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what kind of Democrat would vote for the Reagan budget and
leave the Congress after Gingrich took over, Gore initially said,
``I see some hungry quotation marks eager to be filled with a
pungent quotation.'' He then added, ``I don't know. Maybe the kind
that would announce he was considering running as an independent
against President Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley never made such an announcement. In November 1995, he
said he had ``not ruled out'' an independent candidacy although he
said he was not laying the groundwork for a ``formal third-party
challenge to the two-party system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
