<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-JETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS MAY CLIMB OUT OF TAILSPIN YET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those of you who thought Rick Mirer was a stiff, well, you
may not be right about that one. Mirer is beginning to ``get it,''
in the words of Bill Parcells, and the Jets coach is beginning to
think he can pull a rabbit out of a hat and make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep advising everyone not to make too many evaluations
until about the 10th week, because then the pressure is on and the
schedule is pretty clear for everyone,'' said Parcells. ``To be
judgmental at this point, you know, one thing happens to the wrong
team, and all of a sudden the whole thing has changed. If we could
just play well this month . . . then starting the second half you
might have a chance to get into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells is on the money. He realizes that at some point New
England, Buffalo, and Miami all will have their little problems to
contend with. He's already had his. What he has to do is get Mirer
to be consistent, get Wayne Chrebet back on the field (maybe as
early as next Monday night), and move on through the season with a
different group of players than the ones he started with. This week
he placed linebacker Chad Cascadden and cornerback Otis Smith on
the injured reserve list, joining Vinny Testaverde and Leon
Johnson. He did that for a reason, not wanting to linger with
players who may not be in the picture.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when he made the moves, he got a call from Marty
Schottenheimer, the former Chiefs coach who is now an ESPN
commentator, who told Parcells that he understood completely what
he was doing and how Parcells was going to approach the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has in no way, shape, or form given up on the season.
He seems to sense that he can pull this off.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two games, Parcells has taken over the play-calling
duties from offensive coordinator Charlie Weis. He wanted to create
a new balance on offense between the run and the pass. After all,
he doesn't want Mirer throwing as much as Drew Bledsoe used to and
as much as Testaverde threw it last year in New York. He wants his
offensive line to control the line of scrimmage and he wants Curtis
Martin to finally step up and be a star.
</P>
<P>
   With a play schedule in hand on the sidelines, Parcells has run
66 run plays and 59 pass plays the past two games. In the first two
games, the Jets ran it 42 times and threw it 64 times. Monday
night, Parcells will be up against his old friend Tom Coughlin, who
coincidentally took over the Jaguars' play-calling this year
because he lost Chris Palmer to the Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has always liked Mirer (there's no need to revisit the
Mirer-Bledsoe story of 1993), and he acquired Mirer believing he
could flourish if something happened to Testaverde. A few weeks ago
in this space, Mirer's former offensive coordinator at Seattle,
Larry Kennan, said Mirer eventually would win the admiration of
Parcells and his teammates because ``he's a born leader and a guy
who can throw the ball down the field more effectively than he's
shown.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett Favre echoed that feeling about Mirer last week, saying,
``I think he has the potential to be a great quarterback. That's
why he was drafted early. I don't think that was a mistake. As you
can tell, no one has been able to turn Seattle around in the last
10-15 years, so it wasn't Rick's fault out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said, ``I'm trying to learn about the player. I saw
improvement in his downfield throws from the second to the fourth
game, a change in his demeanor. It's a very difficult thing to
know. It took me half the season to know Vinny Testaverde.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirer is feeling more comfortable with the Jets' scheme and is
starting to understand what Parcells wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to teach the team how I think we have to play to be
successful so that everybody gains an understanding of that,'' said
Parcells. ``I'm putting more emphasis on how I think this team has
to behave to play to be successful _ under the current
circumstances we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells is again doing a masterful job in motivating certain
players. He's not using the ``she'' tactics as he did to Terry
Glenn and Vincent Brisby at one time, but he has expressed
dissatisfaction with 32-year-old free agent tight end Eric Green.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells signed Green to a four-year, $7.5 million deal last
winter after Kyle Brady went to Jacksonville as a restricted free
agent. But he has been a dud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping he'd be the player we were competing against the
past couple of years, but it hasn't gone the way I expected,'' said
Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Green has had a pinched nerve, but Parcells is obviously trying
to tell him, in his own unique way: Get with the program.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells will have Jason Ferguson back at nose tackle this week,
Chrebet soon should give Mirer another target, and Keyshawn Johnson
is buying into Parcells's thinking hook, line, and sinker.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no clear-cut team out there,'' said Johnson. ``We're
right in the middle of this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Green in Brown's future
</P>
<P>
   Troy Brown has a great outlook on his NFL career: ``You have to
play harder than the next guy. This is your paycheck. You have a
family to feed. I'll get motivated to feed my son.'' Brown won't
have to worry about food next year, when he becomes a free agent .
. . On the subject of money, the Patriots certainly have the
prerogative to make Lawyer Milloy a franchise player and pay him
the average salary of the top five safeties in the league, which
would be in the $2.5 million range. But if the Patriots want to
avoid the first ``franchise'' tag in their history, they'll
probably have to meet Milloy's asking price of $4.5 million-$5
million . . . To gear up for the free agent season, Shawn Jefferson
has fired his agent, Phil Williams, and signed on with Gary
Uberstine, who also represents Chad Eaton, Steve Israel, Willie
McGinest, and Pete Carroll . . . By the way, if the Patriots
continue to succeed, will Bob Kraft tear up Carroll's contract and
give him a new one, much like the 49ers did with Steve Mariucci
last year? If Carroll wins the division and gets into the playoffs,
he would be underpaid at $1 million . . . Could you imagine the
town of Foxborough letting the Patriots leave town over an access
road? . . . There'll be more money coming to the Patriots in the
form of a $23.3 million slice of the Houston expansion
franchise-fee pie. The Patriots got a similar slice when Cleveland
came into the league. The only team not getting a piece was the St.
Louis Rams, who forfeited their share as part of the relocation
deal from Los Angeles. It's still amazing that LA doesn't have a
stake in the nation's most popular sport . . . Old friend Lovett
Purnell got a tryout with the Jets last week, but Parcells didn't
bite . . . The NFL will realign in 2002 into eight divisions of
four teams each. Which AFC team will have to switch to the NFC when
Houston enters the AFC? The consensus seems to be Seattle, but you
can expect a few battles before anything is etched in stone.
Currently, the popular alignment would look like this: AFC East _
Patriots, Jets, Dolphins, Bills; AFC Central _ Steelers, Bengals,
Browns, Ravens; AFC West _ Chargers, Broncos, Chiefs, Raiders; AFC
South _ Houston, Jaguars, Titans, Colts; NFC East _ Giants,
Redskins, Cowboys, Eagles; NFC Central _ Vikings, Packers, Lions,
Bears; NFC West _ 49ers, Rams, Seahawks, Cardinals; NFC South _
Buccaneers, Falcons, Saints, Panthers . . . This reporter wrote
before the season that going with Brian Griese over Bubby Brister
at quarterback might disrupt the chemistry of the Broncos. How did
Mike Shanahan not see this coming? Now Brister is back as the
starter with the Broncos 0-4 and with Terrell Davis out for the
season . . . Brady keeps a picture of Parcells in his locker in
Jacksonville. The Tuna wasn't one of his personal favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Giant opportunity for Collins
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Collins finally will get the chance to prove why he's the
Giants' best bet as a starter. He is a pure passer, something the
Giants haven't had since Phil Simms. Coach Jim Fassel is looking
for something to jump-start a very stagnant offense . . . Steve
Young will miss Sunday's game with post-concussion syndrome, and
Buffalo's Rob Johnson hasn't been activated the past two weeks
after suffering headaches following a concussion he suffered
against Philadelphia. Johnson sees limited playing time as Doug
Flutie's backup but has had concussions the past two seasons, which
is not a good sign . . . Eagles coach Andy Reid will start Doug
Pederson at quarterback over Donovan McNabb Sunday vs. Dallas
because McNabb is still not picking up blitzes as he should. Reid,
a former quarterbacks coach with Green Bay, believes McNabb needs
to look at blitzes from the sideline to see how they develop and
how he can deal with them. Palmer made a similar comment about Tim
Couch, that his young quarterback might have to watch from the
sideline at some point . . . When a Kansas City reporter told
Chiefs owner Lamar Hunt, ``Thanks a million,'' for his returning
his call on the Houston expansion story, Hunt retorted, ``No,
thanks to $700 million.'' . . . The Patriots were one of the teams
who considered bringing Errict Rhett into the fold last winter. He
is now a bargain in Baltimore after re-signing for the $400,000
veteran minimum, with incentives. He's overtaken Priest Holmes as
the Ravens' No. 1 back and has three consecutive 100-yard games . .
. Nothing new in Washington. The Redskins' defense is among the
worst in the league, so Norv Turner is trying to tinker with it.
Two years ago, he made current Patriots secondary coach Ron Lynn
the scapegoat by firing him as defensive coordinator. Now he's
bringing in 72-year-old Bill Arnsparger to assist defensive
coordinator Mike Nolan, who worked for Arnsparger at Louisiana
State. The Redskins are 3-1 but have allowed 29.5 points per game .
. . Bengals No. 1 pick Akili Smith will face the Browns' killer
``UFO'' defense in his first NFL start. The Browns sacked Bledsoe
four times last week, and they should do even better against a
worse offensive line and a rookie quarterback. The Browns basically
put all seven linemen and linebackers up, and when the ball is
snapped, some rush the QB and some drop back. Smith, incidentally,
believes that Palmer wanted to draft him over Couch as the No. 1
pick but was overruled by the Browns' upper management . . .
Whether it was psychology or not, Jimmy Johnson's harsh critique of
Dan Marino after last Monday's loss was unnecessary. There was no
respect shown to Marino, who doesn't deserve to be dressed down in
the media. Marino showed his class by not lashing back, as a lesser
man would have done . . . Favre, on facing the Bucs' Warren Sapp:
``I shouldn't say I'm looking forward to playing him. You know,
he's a hell of a player, but God, I get tired of him hitting me and
telling me about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
