<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-AUSSIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSSIES GET JUMP ON THEIR CHOICE EVENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What events are already sold out in Sydney? Anything the host
Aussies are likely to win gold medals in: swimming (at a $455 top),
rowing, cycling, field hockey. As usual, tickets for the opening
ceremonies (at a $1,382 top), track and field finals, and
basketball medal rounds are already oversubscribed. The Australian
public gets to buy more than half of the 9.6 million tickets. The
rest will be sold overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Delayed response
</P>
<P>
   International Olympic Committee president Juan Antonio Samaranch
says he'd be delighted to be grilled by a bunch of Yankee
congressmen _ anytime after Dec. 12. That's when the Lords of the
Rings are expected to approve the laundry list of reforms coming
out of the Salt Lake bidding scandal. ``I'm ready to go, but only
in the right moment,'' says Samaranch. ``I have to walk into the
House with the changes in my pocket.'' Those changes, which range
from the makeup of the membership (likely to include 15 active or
recent athletes) to age limits to host city selection, will be
rubber-stamped by the IOC 2000 commission at month's end, then
forwarded to the full IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Look for the IOC to switch its scheduled February executive
board meeting from Salt Lake City/Colorado Springs to an
un-American site. The reason: The Lords don't want to be questioned
by FBI agents about what they did or didn't know about ski trips
and scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Though the IOC has turned over to its ethics commission the
recent Atlanta report on its bidders' lavish gift-giving, odds are
that no members' heads will roll. The quid pro quo element that
marked Salt Lake's largesse is weaker (or subtler) in Atlanta's
case and many of the members involved have already been booted out.
</P>
<P>
   NHL making plans
</P>
<P>
   It's all but certain that the NHL will be back for the 2002
Winter Games in Salt Lake. The league and players have agreed on a
12-day shutdown and a 10-day Olympic tournament and resumption of
the World Cup in 2004. Formal deal should be struck by year's end .
. . Back on the Grand Prix skating circuit after a year's absence
is UCLA freshman Michelle Kwan, who'll be competing in both Skate
America and Skate Canada. Kwan, who's living in the dorms with a
randomly assigned roommate, has scheduled her classes from Monday
through Thursday so she can juggle both school and sport. And since
next year's world championships were pushed back a week when they
were moved from Brisbane to Nice, Kwan will be done with exams when
she goes overseas. The field for Skate America (in Colorado Springs
at month's end) includes Kwan, Sarah Hughes, and Russia's Yulia
Soldatova on the women's side, and Michael Weiss, Tim Goebel,
Russia's Alexei Yagudin, and Canada's Elvis Stojko on the men's . .
. Heavy medals in the field for the 30th ``Evening With Champions''
skating benefit Friday and Saturday at Harvard's Bright Center.
Besides 1992 Olympic runner-up (and newlywed) Paul Wylie, the
roster includes Russian world medalists Irina Slutskaya and
Soldatova plus former world pro dance champions Maia Usova-Evgeny
Platov, US titlists Danielle and Steve Hartsell (pairs) and Naomi
Lang-Peter Tchernyshev (dance), and 14-year-old wunderkind Naomi
Nari Nam. Call 617-493-8172 for ticket details . . . Bad luck
continues to dog US pair Laura Handy and Paul Binnebose. First,
they had to withdraw from their debut worlds with illness last
season. This month, Binnebose fell during a practice lift and
fractured his skull.
</P>
<P>
   Making do
</P>
<P>
   Modest expectations for the US gymnasts at this week's world
artistic championships in China, which is hosting for the first
time. None of the ``Magnificent Seven'' from Atlanta are competing
on the women's side; Dominique Moceanu is recovering from knee
surgery and Amy Chow didn't make the team. Vanessa Atler and
Kristen Maloney are the best medal hopes for the Americans, who
finished sixth last time and haven't had an individual make the
podium since Shannon Miller won in 1993. Blaine Wilson and the
eternal John Roethlisberger lead the men's team, which hasn't
produced a medal since 1979. The Romanian women and Chinese men,
who've won the last three global titles, are odds-on to repeat. The
Russians won the team and individual crowns at the recent rhythmic
world championships in Japan. Jessica Howard (32d) was the top US
finisher . . . No medals for the US at the recent world greco-roman
wrestling championships in Athens, but the Americans did qualify
for Olympic slots in two classes _ 213.75 pounds (Jason Klohs) and
286 pounds (Dremiel Byers, who beat Olympic runner-up Matt Ghaffari
to make the team) and just missed at 187.25 (Quincey Clark). As
expected, the Russians won the team title and superheavy behemoth
Alexander Karelin won his 12th straight global gold medal. Better
prospects for the Yanks at this weekend's freestyle championships
in Turkey. The squad, which placed third last year, has former
champs Terry Brands (127.75) and Les Gutches (187.25) plus
returning bronze medalists Cary Kolat (138.75) and Lincoln McIlravy
(152). If form holds, the US could qualify in six of the eight
Olympic classes . . . Great leap for the US men's volleyball team,
which knocked off the Cubans to win the regional title for the
first time since 1985. They'll compete in next month's World Cup in
Japan along with the US women, who placed second to Cuba. Top three
teams there make it to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Smooth sailing
</P>
<P>
   Encouraging showing by the US sailors, who won five medals in 11
events at the recent Olympic shakedown regatta in Sydney. Bob
Merrick of Portsmouth, R.I., took a silver with Paul Foerster in
the men's 470. With Tom Olsen of East Dennis and Eric Doyle winning
the recent Star world title, the Americans have qualified for the
Games in all but two classes (Finn and men's Mistral) and still
have final chances in both . . . Want a definition of domination?
All 10 finalists in the five categories at the recent world table
tennis championships in Holland were from China. It's the third
time the Chinese have managed that. The Americans, as usual, were
nowhere near the medals. Best effort came from Gao Junchang, who
reached the round of 32 in both singles and doubles . . . The
inaugural winter Goodwill Games, slated for Lake Placid next
February, will be compact (four days) and decidedly
made-for-Turner. No biathlon, no long track speedskating, nothing
longer than a sprint in cross-country skiing and only one Alpine
event (men's downhill). The program includes figure skating (pros
only), snowboarding, jumping, freestyle skiing, short track
speedskating, and the cement-and-ice trinity of bobsled, luge, and
skeleton . . . Olympic champion Justin Huish will be the sole
returnee on the US men's archery team in Sydney. Vic Wunderle, who
won the recent trials, and Shane Parker supplant Atlanta veterans
Butch Johnson and Rod White. Janet Dykman made the women's team
again, along with two-time Olympian Denise Parker (who missed
Atlanta) and 17-year-old Karen Scavotto of Enfield, Conn. Geena
Davis (yes, the actress), who finished a respectable 29th after
taking up the sport only two years ago (at 41), says she'll try
again. She did make it to Sydney, though, as a wild-card entrant
for the recent pre-Olympic event.
</P>
<P>
   Luge, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Got a buddy willing to ride feet first with you on a sled? The
US Luge people can use you for a few months. With Chris Thorpe and
Gordy Sheer sitting out the first half of the season and Chris
Niccum banned for doping, two of last year's top three men's
doubles teams are off the screen . . . No, the Lords of the Rings
won't be adding ``practical shooting'' to the Olympic program. Once
known as combat shooting, the ``run-and-gun'' version involves
firing at human-shaped targets with assault rifles,
semi-automatics, and shotguns from behind windows and doors. No
chance, says the IOC, which already has three gun-related sports
(shooting, modern pentathlon, biathlon) in the Games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
