<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1978 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-BRUTALIT     10-09 2154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-BRUTALITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SURE WAY TO POLICE BRUTALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Modano will make $6 million this season and has pay days,
if he wants them, that will last until April 2004 _ an additional
$32.5 million. So why was the slick Stars centerman talking with
such resignation last week, pondering a walkaway at age 29?
</P>
<P>
   For once, folks, this is not a league problem, not the owners'
fault, not the product of some miserly general manager. It's not
because an agent placed him in a bum deal. It's not even the last
possible scapegoat, the fans (see various recent Ryder Cup
stories). If he leaves, he won't be able to say the devil made him
do it.
</P>
<P>
   It is, quite simply, because of the way the game is played, and
for that players have only themselves to blame. They are the
problem. No one else.
</P>
<P>
   Modano, of course, is one of the lucky ones. He can afford to
hit the road, although the bet here is that he will play at least
through '04, perhaps with the current deal extended in the spring
of '02 or '03. That's just the way the negotiating game goes, which
has nothing at all to do right now with his contemplated early
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I things continue,'' Modano said last week while recovering
from a mild concussion, broken nose, and strained neck ligaments,
``I'm not going to play anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano was one of the Stars who last weekend were roughed up by
the overly aggressive Mighty Ducks (not an oxymoron). Ruslan Salei,
one of the game's nastier blue liners for his three-plus NHL
seasons, hit Modano from behind, spilling him awkwardly into the
boards. As he crash-landed headfirst on the ice, Modano's neck took
a frightening Exorcist-like twist, and one can only wonder what
might have happened if the slightest bit more torque had been been
exerted on his neck. The outcome could have been catastrophic, be
it life-threatening or paralyzing.
</P>
<P>
   There was another vicious hit in the same game, by Ducks
defenseman Pascal Trepanier, a battering elbow-first slam on Joe
Nieuwendyk. Oh, and just to make it real hockey, ex-Whaler whack
job Jim McKenzie entered a scrum flailing and kept swinging until
he broke Darryl Sydor's eye socket.
</P>
<P>
   I am not going to waste one word here blaming the officials. The
NHL's guys in stripes do, by far, the best job of policing in all
of professional sport. The fact that linesmen are paid, in part, to
break up fights is a sad statement about the sport and the men who
play it. Too many trees already have perished, used to carry the
written debate over why fighting should or shouldn't be tolerated
in today's hockey. No doubt someone in the days ahead will make the
point that vicious hits and violent play are the outcropping of
putting a cap on these fights. To which there is only this
response: Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   Look, if Player X goes out with the intent to injure Player Y,
there truly is nothing anyone can do about that. That's true of
every professional sport worldwide (hello, Jack Tatum), just as it
is on the playground, in the supermarket, on the highway, and
anywhere else evil creeps into our society. Hockey only increases
the odds for nitwits to take aim because it arms them with the
tools of the game, sticks and steel blades. Late-night convenient
stores have been terrorized with far less.
</P>
<P>
   What can hockey do to prevent it? That's the wrong question.
Folks looking to NHL headquarters for the fix are the same ones who
call Channel 7 looking for weatherman Harvey Leonard to answer for
the 18 inches of snow in the driveway. The league handed out
suspensions, took pay out of players' pockets, and can only hope
that the current punishment _ and the implied promise to increase
such penalties _ diminishes future crime. What else do you want,
handcuffs with official NHL logos?
</P>
<P>
   The frightening truth is that there is no fix. What, ask owners
not to sign guys like Salei and Trepanier? OK. But who makes up the
cull list? How are potential perpetrators identified? Impossible.
</P>
<P>
   How about this for a preposterous suggestion: Tell fans to stay
away until these goons are gone. Don't bet on that. In today's
society, there's a better chance that crowds would drop if the
threat of bodily harm were reduced. Who do you suppose is filling
the stands of auto racing tracks around the country? There are more
meatheads than motorheads out there, guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that puts a stop to intent-to-injure incidents is
the conscience that fills the helmet. The league can keep
ratcheting up the penalites, and perhaps eventually issue a
lifetime ban to someone (get Judge Judy a black-and-white striped
robe for that one), but even then there would be no guarantee of
eradication. A victim's paralysis or death also wouldn't stop it.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey is a dangerous game, made more so by the likes of Salei
and Trepanier. None of that is news. The game is unquestionably
more violent that it was 10 years ago, and there are many reasons
for that, such as lower skill level brought on by expansion, and
better equipment that leads to what is sometimes a false sense of
security. None of that is news, either.
</P>
<P>
   If Modano or another high-profile athlete quits to make a
statement, now that will be news. For now, he is only stating the
obvious, that it's a dangerous and sometimes ugly, frightening
world out there.
</P>
<P>
   For now, there is only one answer: Proceed at your own risk. And
just hope that the raving lunatic with the stick in his hand, his
emotions charged, tiny licks of flame dancing in his pupils, at
least has a thread of conscience holding him back.
</P>
<P>
   Economics lesson
</P>
<P>
   Byron Dafoe's agent, Ron Salcer, says the Bruins' unwillingness
to negotiate a more generous deal for his client _ more in line
with Dafoe's requested $12 million over three years _ is an outward
show of contempt by club management. ``The only conclusion I can
make,'' he said, ``is that the franchise is not concerned about
winning, and that they're not concerned about the players or the
public. That is their cynical attitude. I feel it shows contempt,
and as long as the fans keep showing up, it will last, I guess.
It's this attitude: `We don't pay it because we're the Boston
Bruins.' Well that just shows contempt _ to everyone.'' It shows
that Salcer truly understands the most basic black-and-gold
equation: The club's perennial healthy attendance keeps ticket
prices high and payroll suppressed. Will losing change that?
Absolutely not (witness: 1996-97). Now, if losing leads to empty
seats, then big money might be spent on players. But don't count on
that. Ticket prices would come down slightly at first, and if that
failed, the club's Buffalo-based ownership might consider selling
before making outlandish free-agent signings. And, remember, one
need only look at the ongoing train wreck that is the Rangers to
realize spending alone doesn't carry a guarantee . . . Loved this
one last week by Flyer chairman Ed Snider: ``It amazes me,'' he
told the Philadelphia Inquirer, ``that we can be so stupid as
owners, all of us _ me included.'' He was bemoaning the Flyers' $47
million-plus payroll, second in the league to the Rangers, who came
in just under $60 million. Snider &AMP; Co. have been among the
league's biggest overspenders, not to mention underperformers . . .
In case you missed it, ex-Bruin Dave Reid hooked on last week with
the Avalanche, who need veteran protection up front while Peter
Forsberg heals. Reid made $700,000 last year and won a Cup with
Dallas. Now 35, he took about a 30 percent pay cut to stay in the
game _ and perhaps win another Cup with the talented Avalanche.
Reid would have been a nice fit in the Hub, at about one-third the
price the Rangers paid to steal away defensive forward Tim Taylor.
Asked this summer about bringing Reid back, Boston management said
it wasn't interested, that younger players could do the job. That
was weeks before the horrifying, back-to-the-'60s 0-3-0 start . . .
Phoenix general manager Bobby Smith was none too pleased to read
this comment by St. Louis GM Larry Pleau: ``What I can't understand
is how a coach can get everyone to dive in front of an Al MacInnis
slapshot and then get fired.'' Pleau was referring to ex-Coyote
coach Jim Schoenfeld, given the gate after the Blues rubbed out the
Coyotes in Round 1 last spring . . . World renowned architect Frank
Gehry, born in Toronto in 1929, years ago designed a line of
laminated maple furniture, naming some of the pieces the ``Cross
Check Chair,'' the ``Hat Trick Chair,'' and the ``Power Play
Chair.'' Makes you wonder what Canada's answer to Frank Lloyd
Wright could do with the conventional penalty box bench, doesn't
it? Maybe the ``Trap Door Chair'' or perhaps the simple ``Electric
Chair.'' Gehry, who grew up in Timmins, Ontario, still plays pickup
hockey and is working on a new building at MIT. Downtown you can
spot his handiwork at the corner of Newbury Street and Mass. Ave. _
the renovated Tower Records building.
</P>
<P>
   The Richter scale
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens were quiet in the offseason, not adding much to
the payroll after deleting the likes of Mark Recchi and Vincent
Damphousse at the March trade deadline. They did pick up ex-Bruin
Barry Richter for short money, and he put up a large debit in the
opener _ a giveaway to Mats Sundin that was converted for a
shorthanded strike . . . No father-son act ever played net for the
same NHL club until John Grahame followed Ron Grahame in the
Bruins' cage last week (21-plus years between family appearances).
The other father-son acts, but with different clubs, included
Dennis and Pat Riggin (the latter an ex-Bruin) as well as Sam and
Pete Lopresti . . . The sight of Patrick Lalime starting in the
Ottawa net Thursday night against the Bruins served as yet one more
reminder how precarious a goalie's life can be. Lalime had a
fabulous season in '96-97, filling in for the injured Tom Barrasso
in Pittsburgh and rattling off the best start by a rookie netminder
in league history. He couldn't settle on a contract with the
Penguins the following season, though, and began a two-year odyssey
in the minors (IHL stops in Grand Rapids and Kansas City). His
obstinance took him out of the NHL market for two years, and he
might have been out longer if not for the Senators grabbing him in
a swap with the Ducks in June for ex-Bruin Ted Donato . . . Leafs
defenseman Dimitri Yushkevich, who made $1 million last year, ended
his holdout Friday, signing a three-year pact that will bring him a
shade under $2 million a year. Only a week earlier, the Leafs
handed Woonsocket's Bryan Berard a two-year pact for an average
$1.65 million a year . . . The Lightning swung a great deal over
the summer, picking up top goalie prospect Dan Cloutier from the
Rangers, and now have the luxury of not needing to press the kid
into action because veteran Daren Puppa is healthy after three
years of various back and groin ailments. It all turned around for
Puppa when the Bolts' new management hooked him up with the Detroit
Vipers (IHL) medical staff, leading to treatment for a previously
undetected hip injury . . . Tough start with the Rangers for
Taylor. He missed the first two weeks of training camp after an
appendectomy, then suffered a concussion and took eight stitches
above the right eye when Vancouver defenseman Ed Jovanovski lined
him up with a check and drove him to Palookaville . . . Look for
the Rangers soon to deal ex-Canadien Mathieu Schneider. He's making
around $3 million this year, and though he has a heavy shot from
the point, he became an expensive spare part when the Blueshirts
picked up Kevin Hatcher from the Penguins . . . He's a little too
soft to project for greatness, but ex-Leaf Fredrik Modin has the
kind of blistering slapper that could bring 40 goals or more.
Toronto dished him to Tampa in order to bring big block Cory Cross
(6-5, 220) to the Maple Leaf blue line. Good deal for both sides,
but Modin has that Stephane Richer kind of big-strike potential . .
. Can anyone out there remember so many Original Six clubs looking
so shabby? . . . The Red Wings have concluded that 23-year-old
Mathieu Dandenault is a defenseman. And that's final, you know,
until maybe there are a couple of injuries up front, enough
defensemen to go around (literally), or heck, if the offense could
use a booster shot . . . The Stars were the victims of no fewer
than five boarding penalites in their first two games _ more than
some teams endure over the course of 2-3 seasons . . . The Stars
committed nearly $20 million in the combined deals for Richard
Matvichuk (four years, $7.8 million) and Eddie Belfour (two years,
$11.5 million) . . . In Sweden, the Elite League's top scorer now
wears a yellow helmet into game action. ``Imagine the target you'd
be in the NHL, wearing that?'' said Sundin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
