<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS WILL BE ON RED ALERT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ There's Red Skelton, Red Auerbach, Red
Buttons. There's red meat, red blood, red eyes, and the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Glenn likes seeing red.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was an Ohio State player, and that color red can be
intimidating a little bit, especially when you see just all red,''
said Glenn. ``For me, I'm kind of used to red. As a matter of fact,
red is my favorite color.''
</P>
<P>
   What the 4-0 Patriots have to avoid is being red-faced with
embarrassment following Sunday's game at Arrowhead Stadium, where
rabid Chiefs fans dress in all red. Kansas City was humiliated by
the Patriots at Foxboro Stadium last season, 40-10.
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots could be granted one wish, it would be to score
early. They've been outscored, 37-3, in the first quarter, and that
Adam Vinatieri field goal came on their first possession of the
first game, Sept. 12 vs. the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Since then they've been the Comeback Kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a team you really don't want that,'' said Glenn, who caught
13 passes for 214 yards in a 19-7 win over Cleveland last Sunday.
``We would like to score all of our points in the first quarter if
we could. We don't want to rely on (coming back), but we know we
have that capability if that should happen to us again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots would love to be able to spring Glenn for a
double-figure number of catches again, but nobody, including Glenn,
is expecting that to happen. The Chiefs have two very tough corners
in James Hasty and Cris Dishman. Both play a bump-and-run style, so
Glenn is going to get hammered at the line of scrimmage, the way
Jason Sehorn hammered him two weeks ago in a 16-14 win over the
Giants. Glenn cried foul in that game, believing Sehorn was hitting
him past the 5-yard allowed area. If that should happen again,
Glenn will make it known to the officials.
</P>
<P>
   If Glenn and Shawn Jefferson are blanketed by the corners, it
could mean that tight end Ben Coates finally gets the ball more.
Coates was shut out last Sunday and has caught only 10 passes in
four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great to catch the ball,'' said Coates, ``but
whatever they give us, we have to take advantage of it, just like
we did with Cleveland.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Drew Bledsoe wants to make sure Coates feels like
he's a part of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to get into what Ben has meant to this team over
the years,'' said Bledsoe. ``If Ben didn't catch a ball (last
week), that's got to be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben is more of a role-type player right now,'' said Glenn.
``We haven't been using Ben as much as Ben would like us to use
him, but we really haven't had to. It's going to come down to a
couple of games where _ maybe even in this game _ Ben is going to
catch his balls, and touchdown balls, and he will be back to the
same old Ben Coates.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn is hoping the Patriots' running game starts to click to
take the pressure off Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's more to come,'' said Glenn of the running
game. ``(Ours) has been a little suspect the past couple of years.
We have been relying heavily on the pass. As for Terry Allen, I
don't know right now. We are just waiting for him to break that big
run, that big game, that 40-, 50-, 60-yard gain for a touchdown. It
would definitely open up the pass a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn understands that after his 13 catches last week, he's a
marked man. The Chiefs aren't likely to play it the way the Browns
did and give Glenn easy catches.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first 10 catches they were still up, 7-6, on us at
halftime, so why would they change anything?'' said coach Pete
Carroll. ``But on the 11th and 12th catches, that's when Terry did
hurt them.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn knows the Patriots must conquer the crowd _ and the noise
_ early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see on film that the crowd is a big factor,'' said
Glenn. ``We're 2-0 on the road, so I think our team responds pretty
well to crowds. This one might be worse than what we've faced
against New York and Cleveland, but winning this one would be very
satisfying considering what we're up against out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Red, all the time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
