<HEADER>
A1981 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-WOMEN-BO     10-09 1773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-WOMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN DEALT LOW BLOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERONA, N.Y. _ Women's boxing took two shots in the nose this
weekend when what it needs is a shot in the arm.
</P>
<P>
   A fledgling sport that is barely on the edge of respectability
thanks only to the talented but too-seldom-seen Lucia Ryker and
public relations whiz Christy Martin, women's professional
prizefighting got more publicity staging sideshows than it has
gotten for actual bouts, and that is not good for the sport's
long-term health.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Laila Ali, the 21-year-old daughter of Muhammad
Ali, made her professional boxing debut in a hail of flashbulbs at
the Turning Stone Casino here against an Indiana waitress who
fought as though she were still working in a barroom.
</P>
<P>
   The waitress, April Fowler, described her only professional loss
before she met Ali this way: ``I got knocked down and I stayed
down. I wasn't going to be getting any more (money) for getting
up.''
</P>
<P>
   The young Ali, who is trained by former WBU cruiserweight
champion Johnny McClain, had worked a year for this moment and at
least was trying to box in the classic sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``From Day 1 to Day 2, I learned there was a lot more to boxing
than I thought if you want to be good,'' Ali said. ``That's if you
want to learn how to box. It's hard to deal with sometimes if
you're in the ring sparring with some woman just going wild,
swinging wild. That's not boxing; that's fighting. Anybody can just
go fight. What does that have to do with boxing?''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, which is why the women's sport has evolved so slowly
and still meets with more skepticism than acceptance among fans and
promoters. For every skillful fighter like Ryker, there are 100
women like Fowler. Out of shape and unskilled, they fight with
their head down, arms windmilling, looking like a barroom brawler
after a long night tapping a keg.
</P>
<P>
   For women's boxing to ever approach acceptance, it must lose
that sideshow flavor and develop real fighters. Ali at least is
trying to do that, but there are so few like her that it's a
struggle to find worthy opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really wanted to bother with this,'' said veteran
promoter Mike Acri of the Ali fight. ``I don't really like women
boxing and I didn't anticipate this coming along, but her lawyer is
a friend of mine and her father was the greatest in boxing history,
so I said I'd help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wondered at first if this was just a kid using the name for
two or three fights or someone who wanted to make it in boxing. I
didn't know how dedicated she was until I talked to her trainers
and watched her. Now I feel there's something to it. She's
obviously an athlete. She takes it seriously. She has the right
attitude, and that's all you can ask from a young fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is so much more difficult than developing a male
boxer. At least with them you know what you can do. You can find
opponents and check records and know something about the styles and
bring them along as they improve. With Laila, finding opponents is
almost impossible. There were only about 18 girls in her weight
class (168 pounds), and there's no way of tracing the backgrounds
of these girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, the skills, training, and experience of female fighters
have been minimal, and a conflict has evolved between those who
truly would like to help bring the sport along and promoters who
are willing to exploit the situation for a fast buck.
</P>
<P>
   A case of the latter came Saturday &UR;  &LR; night in Seattle, where
promoter Bob Jarvis made the first (and hopefully last) match
between a man and a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a freak show,'' wrote Seattle Times sports columnist
Steve Kelly, and who could argue?
</P>
<P>
   Always alert for a train wreck to cover, the media jumped all
over it. Sports Illustrated, which pays short shrift to real boxers
most of the time, arranged a photo shoot of Margaret McGregor and
her male opponent, Loi Chow. The magazine paid Chow to fly in early
from Vancouver and did the same for Hy Peskin, a veteran sports
photographer from San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same magazine that didn't send a staff reporter to
the Mike Tyson-Buster Douglas fight in Tokyo a few years back
because SI felt it was going to be a circus act. So what's man vs.
woman, high art?
</P>
<P>
   Asked about that, Jarvis said, ``I go by the precept that most
women probably don't want to fight guys but Margaret wants to and,
hey, it's a free country.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally, McGregor was to have fought a kid named Hector
Morales, who would have been making his pro debut against a
36-year-old woman. Wisely he thought better of it and pulled out,
saying, ``My friends, you know, were kidding me about being a woman
beater, but then I started thinking if I lose, I jeopardize my
whole career. If I lost to a woman, what man is ever going to fight
me again? But for her, it's a different story. A big, big story.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but who wants to really read it? Or write it?
</P>
<P>
   Not Rick Kulis, who runs the International Female Boxers
Association and has been that end of the sport's biggest promoter.
Kulis realizes there is a danger in fight cards like this
weekend's, a danger of further marginalizing a wing of boxing still
in its infancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he's planning to write a book,'' said trainer Vern
Miller of Chow, who took on McGregor for $1,500 plus his photo fee
from SI, the $150 he charged the London Daily Mirror for his
picture, and the financial demands he made to appear on syndicated
TV interview shows. ``I'm pretty sure he's planning to use this
publicity for something.''
</P>
<P>
   The bigger question is, what is women's boxing going to use it
for? And what does it say about the people who cover sports and the
people who watch it that a week ago two veteran professional
prizefighters put on a boxing war at the Icenter in Salem, N.H., a
classic 10-round battle that was a test of skill and will finally
won with 20 seconds to go by a bloody Lowell junior lightweight
named Micky Ward and only 1,801 people came to watch while Friday
night at the Turning Stone Casino 2,500 came out to see Laila Ali
fight a waitress?
</P>
<P>
   Worse, even more came to Seattle's Mercer Arena to watch a
36-year-old woman, who claims to have once bitten the legs off her
sister's Barbie doll, ``box'' a 34-year-old part-time jockey with
an 0-2 record. In that crowd were representatives of Sports
Illustrated, the New York Times, the London Times, the London
Mirror, and the Canadian Broadcasting Co., while representatives of
the ``Tonight'' show called to say they might want McGregor to be a
guest.
</P>
<P>
   If women truly want to box (and Lord knows why they would, and
that's not sexist, so don't bother writing, because anyone with an
ounce of sense wonders the same thing about men if they know
anything about the hardships of such a career choice), this is not
the way to push their sport.
</P>
<P>
   Ryker was recently dropped by promoter Bob Arum not because she
lost a fight, because she never has; he dropped her because he
believes he has a better shot at making money promoting a Playboy
model named Mia St. John.
</P>
<P>
   On some of the photos in Playboy, St. John is wearing boxing
gloves and nothing else. Those pictures are the sum total of what
she brings to a boxing ring.
</P>
<P>
   Look at that magazine and this weekend's festivities, and you
can ask yourself one thing. Can you spell the word
E-X-P-L-O-I-T-E-D?
</P>
<P>
   Then again, why should women fighters be treated any differently
than most of the men have been for generations?
</P>
<P>
   Short jabs
</P>
<P>
   Word is, the chief rival of International Boxing Federation
junior middleweight champion Fernando Vargas, World Boxing
Association junior middleweight champion David Reid, is looking to
opt out of HBO's stable when his contract is up and jump to cable
rival Showtime. One reason? The apparent reluctance of his
promoter, America Presents, to follow through on a promise to end
that contract with a unification fight with Vargas. These days, all
Dan Goossen wants to talk about is a Reid-Oscar De La Hoya fight,
playing down any chance of a Reid-Vargas showdown next year . . .
Jay Larkin, Showtime's programming chief, has contingency plans set
for the Oct. 23 telecast of the Mike Tyson-Orlin Norris bout. That
is the night of the first World Series game and Larkin does not
intend to compete, even with Tyson. ``The first pitch is 8:10 p.m.
Eastern time and we don't go on with Mike until 11 p.m. or 11:30
p.m.,'' Larkin said. ``We have the undercard and then we can tap
dance until the game is over if we have to. When it is, we'll walk
Tyson in and try to catch the viewers. We'll do print ads and PR
work and on-air marketing to make the connection with sports fans
between the end of the game and the start of Mike's fight. We know
you could have a 4 1/2-hour baseball game, but realistically we
think it will work out.'' Originally, Showtime planned the fight
for Oct. 2, but Tyson's unwillingness to agree on an opponent and
other delays he imposed caused the problem . . . Once Roy Jones
made it official that he wasn't fighting Nov. 6 on HBO's ``Boxing
After Dark,'' the cable giant thought it had replaced him with
stablemate Smoke Gainer against World Boxing Council junior
lightweight champion Floyd Mayweather, one of HBO's rising young
stars. Enter Don King. Exit Floyd Mayweather. Mayweather's
promoter, Bob Arum, thought they'd agreed in principle to a
multifight deal with HBO that would have extended Mayweather's
contract for another 3 1/2 years while allowing him to remain a
pay-per-view free agent. But the papers were never signed and word
Friday was that King had convinced Mayweather he was being
underpaid. Mayweather refused to sign the deal or accept a Gainer
fight, leading his father, Floyd Sr., to rip him in a local paper
in Grand Rapids, Mich., while HBO was left scrambling to find a new
fight, possibly in New York, on that date . . . It appears Jones
will be in the first HBO fight of 2000 if he appears as scheduled
on Jan. 4, although it may not be against mandatory challenger
Graciano Rocchigiani . . . Anyone who watched the sad beating
once-great Julio Cesar Chavez took from journeyman Willie Wise last
weekend saw a perfect argument for mandatory retirement from the
ring. A bloody and battered Chavez looked like an old man getting
mugged by street punks as Wise battered him around for 10 rounds to
easily win a decision and derail Chavez's hopes of one last title
shot. ``I'm very surprised at how poorly I performed,'' Chavez
said. How come? No one else who's been paying attention was.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
