<SLUG> BC-FBC-BC-TEMPLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC NOT WISE TO OWLS IN FIRST LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ This was a loss that was four victories in the
making.
</P>
<P>
   After Boston College bumbled, stumbled, and fumbled its way to a
4-0 record against teams that had a collective 4-14 record, things
finally caught up to the Eagles in Saturday's 24-14 Big East loss
at Temple before a Veterans Stadium crowd of 15,067.
</P>
<P>
   It is now 45 years since the Eagles won their first five games
of a season, as they couldn't handle the lowly Owls (1-5, 1-1). And
the Eagles (4-1, 1-1) lost to Temple at The Vet for the second time
in three years. The Owls handed BC a 28-21 loss in the debut of
Eagles coach Tom O'Brien Sept. 6, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   BC's offense was outgained for the second game in a row _ this
time, 429 yards to 328 _ after showing signs of slippage in a 33-22
victory last week over Northeastern, which was throttled Saturday
by UMass, 77-0. After taking a 14-0 lead in the second quarter, BC
allowed Temple to score 24 unanswered points. Meanwhile, the
offense squandered three red zone opportunities when John Matich
missed a 35-yard field goal in the first quarter, backup
quarterback Brian St. Pierre threw an interception in the end zone
in the second quarter, and Cedric Washington fumbled at the Temple
19 as the Eagles were driving for a fourth-quarter score that would
have tied the game at 21.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, junior quarterback Tim Hasselbeck emerged
from BC's locker room after the game with his right (throwing) arm
in a sling. Hasselbeck suffered a slight separation in the first
quarter, but played the remainder of the game and completed 14 of
22 passes for 146 yards. His 4-yard pass to fullback Ryan Burch
lifted BC to a 14-0 lead with 14:55 to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give Temple a lot of credit, they hung in there
today,'' said O'Brien. ``As the game progressed, they got better,
and I think it's safe to say we got worse. We're not a very good
football team right now.''
</P>
<P>
   With backup quarterback Devin Scott at the helm, the Owls
rallied to three scoring drives that netted 197 yards of offense.
BC's first three series of the second half resulted in
three-and-outs that netted a grand total of minus-8 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance in the first half to put 'em away _ not
totally put 'em away _ but to get going,'' said O'Brien. ``All that
did was that it brought them back to life and we came out and
didn't meet their challenge in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   On Temple's first possession, Ralph Parent blocked a punt and
Jonathan Ordway recovered at the Temple 6. Three plays later,
freshman William Green crashed in from 2 yards out for a 7-0 Eagles
lead with 11:58 remaining. After Matich's 35-yard attempt missed
right, George White's second interception of the game set up a
four-play, 64-yard drive that ended with Hasselbeck's 4-yard toss
to Burch.
</P>
<P>
   Then Scott, who had suffered a rib-cage injury in last week's
55-24 loss at Pittsburgh, came on the scene, completing 17 of 23
passes for 169 yards. Temple, which had been largely ineffective
with starter Mac Devito (13 for 24, 104 yards) at the helm, seemed
to gain new life when Scott entered. Temple threatened from the BC
28 with 17 seconds remaining before halftime (aided by a
roughing-the-kicker penalty).
</P>
<P>
   On Scott's first play, he lofted a 27-yard pass to Greg
Muckerson (seven catches, 81 yards) which set up a 1-yard plunge
two plays later by Marcus Godfrey that cut BC's lead to 14-7. In
the second half, Scott completed 11 of his next 12 passes to rally
Temple to a pair of scores, hitting a diving Carlos Johnson (seven
catches, 87 yards) with a 9-yard pass that tied it at 14.
</P>
<P>
   Scott then put the Owls ahead to stay, 21-14, when he capped a
10-play, 73-yard drive with a 4-yard toss to fullback Jason McKie.
After Washington fumbled at the Temple 19, thwarting BC's only
legitimate scoring threat of the second half, Cap Poklemba
converted a 31-yard field goal _ which bounced off the right
upright _ to give Temple a 10-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a total surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I said last week, if I was at Temple, I'd be looking at the
people they've played and looking at the people we were playing,''
O'Brien said. ``They've been getting better the last two weeks
playing tough teams, and we've slipped in the last week or two, and
I think it has to do with the way we played and what we did a week
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The seeds of this setback were sown long before Saturday. This
was just the inevitable result.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
