<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-ALOMAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALOMAR IN THE FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He has been the missing link for a ballclub that didn't know it
needed one. It wasn't like the Indians were a busted chain, not
after winning five straight division titles and reaching the World
Series twice.
</P>
<P>
   But Robbie Alomar made Cleveland even greater this season. Going
into Saturday's Game 3, Sandy's kid brother was looking like the
man most likely to get his mates another date with the Yankees in
the American League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous case that should be made for Robbie as
the MVP of the league this year,'' said manager Mike Hargrove.
``There are so many ways that he can help your team win. With his
glove. With his speed. With his bat. With his knowledge of the game
on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians signed the 31-year-old Alomar for $32 million over
four years after he bailed out of Baltimore as a free agent. They
knew they were getting both performance and pedigree _ a 10-time
All-Star, career .300 switch-hitter, and a seven-time Gold Glove
second baseman, who'd picked up two Series rings in Toronto. What
they didn't realize was that they were also getting the invisible
glue that has bound them even more firmly together.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks team all the time,'' said Cleveland general manager
John Hart, who says that Alomar is the best free agent the
franchise has ever signed. ``He started talking team the first day
he walked into our locker room in Winter Haven. Robbie will sit at
a little corner locker and talk when it's time. He'll go out to
dinner. All the old stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The old, low-key, subtle stuff. There was no need for Alomar to
impose his personality on a team that already knew how to get to
October. Besides, his catcher/sibling Sandy was already wearing the
unofficial captain's ``C'' on his chest protector.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a real quiet guy, but I like to help my people,'' said
Robbie. ``All the players here are like my family. We are here to
help each other out.''
</P>
<P>
   Alomar had a stunning regular season, becoming the first player
in club history to hit 20 homers, score 100 runs, knock in 100
runs, and steal 30 bases. He also hit .323. He went until June 9
without an error and made only three in his final 92 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you watch Robbie perform on a daily basis, you don't
truly realize that special talent he has,'' said Hargrove. ``He has
the ability to go out and play the game like nobody else I've ever
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially in October. Before this year, Alomar had batted .333
with 29 RBIs in 50 postseason games. In the first two games, Alomar
had five of the Indians' 14 hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a money player,'' testified Sandy. ``Just a great
postseason player.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the whole point of the kid brother's coming to Ohio in
the first place. It wasn't for a family reunion. ``The goal for our
family is to play in the postseason,'' said Sandy. ``This is the
whole enchilada right here. Playing in the postseason together and
trying to win the whole thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
