r a BC-PLAYBOY-PARK-2ndTAKE-     10-09 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAYBOY-PARK-2ndTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY STEVE CARNEY 
</HEADLINE>
 
LOS ANGELES: be a good neighbor.'' 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We're trying to fashion some reasonable restrictions,'' said
Councilman Mike Feuer, who's taken up the cause for residents, who
he said ``felt their proximity to the Playboy Mansion was causing
real disruption to the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Playboy Mansion presents its own situation,'' Feuer said,
as it attracts not only the partygoers' cars, but the commercial
vehicles of caterers and other employees.
</P>
<P>
   Feuer suggested imposing the restrictions after he received the
latest petition from neighborhood residents last week, but fellow
council members were turned off. However, the council's
Transportation Committee will review the matter Oct. 19 in hopes of
coming up with a compromise. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Whenever she's gone there for fund-raisers, Goldberg said she
simply parked and walked to the Playboy Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   She said she opposes street-parking restrictions in
neighborhoods where homes have driveways and garages available. She
said such rules make sense in places like Venice Beach, however,
where residents must battle to find street parking near their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I'm saying, No, I don't care about noise,'' she
sy8 {UU$.Z+ RK$,+..YKHZ$UY+$[KW$ZR.IZY]HH($.X;eSs%G|X7
nYZ-,K- &QC; M9::j$( The Playboy Mansion itself is a few twists and
turns away
from Beverly Glen, on Charing Cross Road. In the surrounding
neighborhood, long circular drives arc through expansive, manicured
lawns. At least one Mercedes or Lincoln sits in each one. But on
many of the streets fronting those estates, no parking is allowed
whatsoever _ those residents already have their highly desirable
parking restrictions. So the valets from the Playboy Mansion end up
queuing the cars on Beverly Glen, residents say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the party's on Mapleton (Drive), park on Mapleton for
heaven's sake,'' said one neighbor on Beverly Glen, who asked that
his name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   Hefner bought the mansion in 1971, and moved there full-time in
1975, Farley said. Since then, its very name has conjured images of
Playmates cavorting on the grounds with celebrities and stars, the
adventures of the glitterati titillating mortal men.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way these people -- the jet-setters -- live.
That's Hollywood,'' said City Councilman Nate Holden, who also
opposes the parking restrictions. ``At the same time, the people
who live in the neighborhood want their peace and quiet. That's
fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) to single out one property -- that's not the way
preferential parking works,'' said Holden, who said he would
investigate the situation personally, by attending a function at
the mansion Friday. ``If the place has become a nuisance, there's
another way of going at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Weinberger said representatives at the Playboy Mansion
are always helpful when she calls with concerns, such as if their
driveway is blocked. But the couple said they wish they didn't have
to worry about such things in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's made it sort of an unpleasant place to live, but we're
devoted to the neighborhood,'' Howard Weinberger said. ``We want to
preserve what's left of it.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
