<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAYBOY-PARK-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARKING AT PLAYBOY PARTIES IRKS NEIGHBORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY STEVE CARNEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The story has all the makings of the ultimate L.A.
battle: rich people upset about their privacy, politicians taking
unpredictable sides, sexy all-night parties and ... parking.
</P>
<P>
   Along Beverly Glen Boulevard, the residents of the large,
stately homes once owned by Ronald Reagan and Jane Wyman, Juliet
Prowse and Barbara Stanwyck are upset with their hedonistic
neighbor - Hugh Hefner and his Playboy Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   For two years, residents have petitioned City Hall to expand
parking restrictions, in hopes of stemming the crush of cars that
line their street every time Hefner throws one of his extravagant
parties.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council deferred the latest request last week for
special parking restrictions on weekends, during prime party hours,
but promised the 14 residents who signed the petition it would keep
looking for a solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we can hardly get out of our driveway,'' said Pamela
Weinberger, 83, who has lived with her husband, Howard, in their
house on Beverly Glen Boulevard since 1958. They say the greatest
nuisance is the valet parkers themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come roaring down the hill and screech their brakes and
stop and then roar off,'' said Howard Weinberger, also 83, a
retired physician.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they lay patches,'' Pamela Weinberger said. ``If we're
sitting here all we hear is squealing, squealing.''
</P>
<P>
   The upscale neighborhood dispute has created strange bedfellows,
to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilwoman Jackie Goldberg, a staunch women's-rights
advocate, opposed the parking restrictions, which she called
exclusionary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had nothing to do with Hugh Hefner. Please don't say I'm
fighting for Hugh Hefner. That's probably the last thing I would
do,'' she said. ``If it's a use I adore or a use I abhor, it
doesn't make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect it's mostly they don't like people they don't know
parking in their neighborhood,'' Goldberg said.``I'm sorry, that's
not a choice you get. You don't own that street.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The problem is that for Hugh Hefner, having a party can mean
about 700 for a summertime fashion show. The average attendance is
about 500 for the half-dozen or so charitable events held every
year inside the mansion's high walls and towering hedges, said Bill
Farley, director of communications for Playboy Enterprises
International Inc.
</P>
<P>
   He said the mansion has room on the grounds to park about 25
cars, for the small, more regular weekend gatherings. For larger
events, they ask guests to park at UCLA or a nearby Robinsons-May
store and they provide shuttles to the mansion, but many attendees
still hand over their keys to valet attendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not considerate and it gets crowded and it's not safe
for children,'' said Bijan Raphael, 50, who has lived on Beverly
Glen for nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not very pleasant. It's just a bad situation,'' said
Raphael, a self-employed entrepreneur who said the problem seemed
to escalate about two years ago. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Parking on Beverly Glen is restricted to cars with permits from
8 a.m. to 6 p.m. on weekdays. Residents hope to extend that to the
weekends, allow only two-hour parking weekend nights and ban
overnight parking on Saturdays and Sundays. The rules would affect
Beverly Glen only between Charing Cross Road and Comstock Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the restrictions go up, we'll live with them,'' Farley
said. ``We want to be a good neighbor.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
