u s BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     10-09 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHICH WILL IT BE: SUDDEN FAME OR SUDDEN CALAMITY?
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The managers made the moves they make in their sleep
without losing a Z. When they had a one-run lead to protect, they
made the standard late-inning defensive switch. Except Bobby
Valentine's saved the game, while Buck Showalter's cost him the
season.
</P>
<P>
   On a tense October afternoon that conjured quixotic Shea Stadium
memories of championships past, here was a clear demonstration of
the arbitrary nature, the fragile polarity, between moving on as a
baseball genius and going home to a mournful hug.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine's guy, Melvin Mora, cut down a huge eighth-inning run
from left field. In the bottom of the inning, Showalter's man, Tony
Womack, dropped a crucial fly ball in right.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, we were reminded that the blue-collar appeal of the
sport has always been the ability of some anonymous soul to step
off the bench and into postseason lore. And its cruelty is the
sudden calamity an unsuspecting outfielder can innocently drift
under.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens,'' Showalter said of Womack's blunder that
redirected the game into extra innings, where Todd Pratt was the
last line in a storybook ending. ``A lot of guys wouldn't have got
to that ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, meanwhile, basked in the glow of the 4-3 victory over
Arizona that sends the Mets back for yet another Atlanta joust,
like a battered boxer who just won't stay down. ``You get a lead
and you put in your best defensive outfielder,'' he said. ``Mora is
in there like a reliever, to save the game, and that's what he
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, stand-in for the star, proceeded to hit the game-winning
home run in the 10th inning. John Franco of New York City earned
his first postseason victory in relief. Al Leiter pitched a gem and
was treated by Sandy Koufax to a postgame chat. The day and series
came up roses for Valentine, who bested fellow chess master
Showalter and now moves on, plotting revenge against one of his
least favorite humans, Bobby Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, practically doubled over by now from all his recent
last laughs, could take from Saturday a few more strokes of
brilliance to bewilder the panel of peers he fantasized about this
week in a national magazine. He could begin with Mora, who was
inserted in left for Rickey Henderson as Leiter tried to nurse his
way through the eighth inning with a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter got two outs, walked Turner Ward and watched with
everyone else in disbelief as Edgardo Alfonzo botched Womack's
one-hopper near second. Armando Benitez came on to yield Jay Bell's
two-run double and Matt Williams' hard single through the hole
between third and short.
</P>
<P>
   Mora is 27 years old, a career minor leaguer who appeared in 66
games for the Mets this season. He plays infield and outfield, and
Valentine wanted him on the postseason roster _ at infielder Luis
Lopez's expense _ precisely because he could play both.
</P>
<P>
   Mora said his best positions are left field and center. People
who have watched him out there would not have been surprised that
he charged Williams' hit, straightened up and fired a true
two-hopper to Pratt, nipping the sliding Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew how big that run was for them,'' he said. ``But my arm
is strong. I threw a couple of guys out at home this year in
Triple-A.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine wasn't surprised that his roster move and defensive
switch worked out. He was just, as usual, grateful for the chance
to say he told us so. ``I have said a couple of times that Mora is
our best defensive outfielder, and people have snickered at me,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   So the Mets came up in the home eighth, needing a run, with
Gregg Olson relieving Brian Anderson for the Diamondbacks. He
walked Alfonzo leading off, and then John Olerud lifted a high
drive to deep right.
</P>
<P>
   Womack, the shortstop for seven innings, had moved to the
outfield to replace Bernard Gilkey. There was no reason at that
point to raise an eyebrow, because Gilkey is not Roberto Clemente
and the speedy Womack had played right field for most of the
season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony, I think, is one of the top two or three right-fielders
in the league,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   True or false, there was one element to the move that ultimately
invited a second-guess, besides that it turned out bad. The
outfield was drenched in sun while the ball was emerging from the
shadows. Darryl Hamilton, the Mets' center fielder, said the Shea
outfield in the afternoon sun is always an adventure. Roger Cedeno,
sent to right field for Benny Agbayani, had told Hamilton he was
praying Leiter would throw ground balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger said, `I don't want the ball hit to me,''' Hamilton
said. ``You can't catch what you can't see.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Womack's predicament as he failed to pick up Olerud's
drive and stumbled back in a sun field he had not been in all day.
He seemed to locate the ball on the warning track. Up went the
glove. The ball never went in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just dropped it,'' he said. ``I wish I could get it back,
but I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets pushed across the tying run. The game continued for
Pratt to settle. Soon champagne was being sprayed all over the home
team's clubhouse, Showalter ducking as he somberly made his
congratulatory rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, a few feet away, was hugging the co-owner, Fred
Wilpon, shouting: ``Ain't it great, with John getting the win?
Ain't it beautiful?''
</P>
<P>
   All a matter of which side you're on, and which standard
defensive switch worked out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
