<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBE FORESAW WINTER COMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA _ To all Kobe Bryant's amazing attributes, you can
add prescience.
</P>
<P>
   In February Bryant telephoned Tex Winter in Chicago to pick his
brain about the Bulls' famed triangle offense. Winter couldn't have
been more surprised if Ed McMahon had been on the other end of the
line.
</P>
<P>
   It was months before the Lakers would begin wooing Winter's
cohort in NBA championships, Phil Jackson, and years since Winter
suspected the league's young stars had stopped caring about any
offense that didn't start and end with a one-on-one move.
</P>
<P>
   As with the startling love match of tennis stars Steffi Graf and
Andre Agassi, there were signs, looking back, that pointed to
Jackson and the Lakers someday hooking up. But Bryant swears he
didn't pick up on any of them.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, he can't say what _ aside from simple curiosity _
compelled him to call Winter, who is now a member of the Lakers
coaching staff, teaching every player the triangle offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freaky, isn't it?'' Bryant said after a recent practice. ``I
called him just because I was interested in how the offense works.
Why? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   It's less of a mystery to longtime Lakers assistant coach Bill
Bertka, who is on the other end of Bryant's knock when the 6-foot-7
guard comes searching for videotapes of great players, past and
present, to wile away idle hours on the road.
</P>
<P>
   If you think Bryant's 21st birthday in August is going to alter
his nightly routine dramatically, think again. It turns out the
player who skipped college is a serious student of basketball. His
approach couldn't be more academic if he were a doctoral candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe's unique in his pursuit of learning about the game,''
Bertka said. ``It's not unusual for him to come to my room and
request Pete Maravich tapes to see how he played. That's why the
story of him calling Tex is interesting. It wasn't just lip
service.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, recalling the conversation, said: ``I was just asking
him pretty general questions. I let him run off with it and I just
sat back and listened.''
</P>
<P>
   It warmed Winter to realize the future of the NBA was interested
in an offense that's a blast from the past. It can be traced all
the way back to Sam Barry's coaching days at USC in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It impressed me that he really thirsted for knowledge,'' said
Winter, who lettered at USC in 1947. ``He really wanted to know
about the game. He was particularly interested in knowing how
Michael fit into the triangle.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan disdained the triple-post offense at first,
viewing it as too egalitarian for his talents. That was before the
offense helped carry the Bulls to the first of their six NBA
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant has Jordan's number, but he won't need to ring him for an
endorsement. Bryant knows that which Jordan had to learn; namely,
he can get his points and win titles, too, with an offense that
amplifies, rather than isolates, his athleticism.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant was a believer even before he hung up with Winter. Last
season he privately lamented the limitations of the Lakers'
offense, which consisted of dumping the ball inside to center
Shaquille O'Neal and making like a potted plant.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant had studied enough videotape over the years to know there
was a better way for so much talent to bloom. If that made him
selfish in the eyes of his teammates, let's hope they had that
blurred vision checked over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Winter is not a witch doctor and the triangle offense is not an
elixir. It's only as good as the fundamentals of the least-sound
player on the floor. So the chest-pass drills Jordan and Scottie
Pippen did without complaint better be performed with gusto by
Bryant and O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about the triangle offense and what it's going to
do for the Lakers,'' Winter said. ``In the final analysis, it's not
the triangle that's going to be the key to the team's success but
how well the guys can execute the skills (on which it's based).''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant likened learning the new offense to learning Italian when
he was a child. At first, he was tentative. He made mistakes. There
were awkward moments and embarrassing gaffes and lots and lots of
repetitive drills that seemed too specific to be of any general
help. Then one day something clicked and those strings of sentences
that had been indecipherable suddenly made sense.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, if the Lakers don't see instant results from the
labor, they mustn't despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll come,'' Bryant said. ``We've just got to be patient with
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bryant says something's going to happen, believe him. He's
not Magic; the Lakers' next great guard is mystic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' Bryant said, ``when I first came to L.A., I told
my father (Joe) I'd be playing for Phil and Tex someday.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused and shook his head in wonderment. ``It's kind of
freaky how things have played out.''
</P>
<P>
   You could say it's flat-out fateful. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
