<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2223 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-PRATT-NYT &LR;      10-09 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PRATT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: AN UNDERSTUDY TAKES A TURN ON CENTER STAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the fourth inning, the Mets had a runner at second
base and two out. Todd Pratt grounded out. In the sixth inning, the
Mets had runners at second and third and two out. Todd Pratt
grounded out. In the eighth inning, the Mets had runners at first
and third and one out. Todd Pratt grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could easily have been the goat today,'' Pratt said.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Hamilton, his teammate, dismissed that thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the playoffs,'' Hamilton said, ``you have to forget about
it. All you need is the big hit. He may get a lot of opportunities,
but you have to forget about the ones you didn't get through and
concentrate on what's at hand. The fact that he forgot about those
at-bats and came through with the big hit is unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, the Mets' catcher Saturday for the second consecutive
game in place of Mike Piazza and his ailing left thumb, produced
the big hit all right, the one that sent the Mets soaring to
Atlanta for the National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the 10th inning, Pratt crushed a pitch from Matt
Mantei over the center-field fence, over the glove on the right
hand of a leaping Steve Finley. The home run gave the wild-card
Mets a 4-3 victory over the Arizona Diamondbacks and placed them
one step away from a possible World Series meeting with the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm not Mike Piazza, obviously,'' Pratt said on the
Shea Stadium field in the minutes after the game, ``but for one
swing I was.''
</P>
<P>
   But after Pratt had a moment to reflect on what he had done and
who he was, he became insufferably modest, refusing to take credit
for having done anything more than having given ``my team a chance
to go to the NLCS.''
</P>
<P>
   If not for Piazza's inflamed and swollen thumb, Pratt would have
played about the same amount of time in this postseason as he did
with Philadelphia in 1993, when he appeared in one game and batted
once (he struck out) in the league series and played not at all in
the World Series. But he played in two of the four division series
games here, distinguishing himself with a good at-bat Friday night
that produced an important walk and with the home run and a pivotal
play at the plate Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   His diving tag of Jay Bell on a throw from Melvin Mora in the
eighth inning kept the Diamondbacks only one run ahead. His home
run put the Mets one run ahead for posterity.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, whose three home runs during the regular season came in
the space of six games and 16 at-bats in April when Piazza was
injured, did not forget how to hit one, fortunately for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   In his first at-bat against the hard-throwing Mantei, Arizona's
No. 1 reliever, Pratt said he had choked up on the bat, an approach
he adopts against pitchers who throw fastballs in the high 90-mph
range. But when he went to the plate with one out in the 10th, he
held the bat at the end, gripping the knob with his left hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw me the first pitch, a curveball, that wasn't even
close,'' he related. ``I just said if it's a fastball anywhere I
can touch it, I'm swinging. I said I need to get out in front of
this one, and he actually threw it to where my favorite pitch is, a
little up and out over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   As Pratt began running, he watched Finley, the remarkably
talented center fielder, go back to the wall and leap. ``I've seen
him make that catch a million times,'' Pratt said. ``When he came
down, I thought he still had the ball. Then I saw him put his head
down. I almost started crying right there.''
</P>
<P>
   For an instant, Finley thought he had caught the ball. It hit
the top of his glove, and when he came down and looked in his
glove, he thought the ball would be there. It wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me a second to realize the game was over,'' he said
disconsolately. ``It was a long walk back to the clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   In that instant, Pratt became Bobby Thomson, Bill Mazeroski,
Bucky Dent, Joe Carter. No, the home run won't rank with those hit
by that foursome, but it will become part of Mets' lore. Last year
Pratt almost became part of the Mets' past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a very testing year for me,'' said Pratt, who
opened the season in the minor leagues and was returned there twice
more. ``Every time I got sent down I didn't deserve it. It was very
heartbreaking last year.''
</P>
<P>
   It was so frustrating that Pratt said he nearly quit, once when
he didn't make the team in spring training, the second time around
mid-season when he was demoted again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right then,'' he said of the second instance, ``was the first
time I cried after being talked to by a manager. I stayed here
three days, once again contemplating asking for my release and
saying forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   But an injury quickly opened a spot for Pratt and he was
restored to the roster. Given all that he went through, he was
asked Saturday, why wouldn't he take credit loud and long for what
he had just done.
</P>
<P>
   Listing other players without whose performances the Mets could
not have won the game, Pratt said: ``It is very easy for a player
to get very high emotionally on himself and talk himself up. I'm
just not that kind of player. I'm arrogant, but I'm arrogant inside
because I know I can play this game.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
