<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNABOUT FAIR PLAY FOR VALENTIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hero, goat, hero.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if John Valentin couldn't decide whether he wanted to
be Bill Russell or Bill Buckner. Bob Cousy or Bob Stanley. Jim
Lonborg or Jim Burton.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox were on life support, playing without their two best
players and ready to go into that long, cold, ``what-if?'' winter
that's imprisoned every Sox team since World War I. And Valentin _
the only member of the Red Sox who played with Mo Vaughn, Roger
Clemens, and Wade Boggs _ was being measured for a bust in the
Boston Baseball Hall of Shame.
</P>
<P>
   Bad throws. No hits. It couldn't get much worse. The fans at
home were booing him, questioning his desire, and blaming him for
another quick playoff exit.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin was feeling it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel (lousy),'' he said after his throwing error cost the
Red Sox the first game of their playoff joust with Cleveland.
``It's my fault.''
</P>
<P>
   It kept getting worse. Valentin went 0 for 4 in the Game 2
humiliation and hit into a double play. There were whispers
(actually there were shouts on sports talk radio) that the Sox
should have gone with rookie Wilton Veras instead of the
high-priced veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been busy,'' said Valentin. ``You get ground balls, you
try to make the plays. It's part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's 9-3 Red Sox win was knotted at 2-2 when
Valentin walked to the plate in the sixth inning wearing an
0-for-10 doughnut. The number on his back (13) seemed appropriate.
Then, at 6:13 EST, he turned on a pitch by Jaret Wright (Cleveland
manager Mike Hargrove should be slaughtered back home for staying
so long with the head-case righthander) and launched it onto the
black tarp that covers the triangle of Fenway's center-field
bleachers. The Red Sox led, 3-2. The crowd loved him again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the boos) is part of the game,'' he said. ``No one likes
it, but the fans are very emotional. When you mess up, they let you
know. It was a 2-2 game when I hit the home run so obviously I was
pretty happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The adulation and happiness lasted less than a half hour. Back
in the infield for the seventh, Valentin committed another hideous
throwing error. With two on and two out, he came in and gloved a
Manny Ramirez grounder on the trap hop, took several steps, then
inexplicably threw to first while he was still running. His throw
was in the dirt. It was the same kind of throw that cost the Sox
Game 1. First baseman Mike Stanley, who'll never be mistaken for
Vic Power or George Scott, attempted to backhand Valentin's one-hop
toss and it clanged off Stanley's glove as Kenny Lofton crossed the
plate with the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I underthrew it,'' he said. ``I always throw on the run in
that situation. Of course, I felt bad. I think my teammates
understood how I felt and they pretty much left me alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play this game, you try to be at an even keel. You
try not to go through that roller coaster after you make a mistake.
You don't try to atone. That's just the way it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The silly error might have broken a lesser man, but Valentin has
been doing this a long time. So when he came to the plate in the
bottom of the same inning with the bases loaded and two out _ game
still tied, 3-3 _ he knew this was a chance for redemption.
</P>
<P>
   To their credit, the Fenway legions stood and applauded when the
beleaguered veteran walked to the plate. It was as if Valentin had
earned a line of credit through his years of good deeds in the
community. Fans were giving him a break, even though he'd just
blown the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot to concentrate on when I'm up there,'' he said.
``So I not really noticing if they're booing me or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The applause mounted as Cleveland lefthander Ricardo Rincon ran
the count to 3-and-2. Valentin fouled off the first 3-2 pitch, then
cracked a ground-rule double to left, giving the Sox a 5-3 lead and
setting the stage for Brian Daubach's game-breaking, three-run
homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was basically trying to tell myself to get a pitch that was
up in the zone,'' said Valentin. ``On the previous pitch, he threw
a pitch that was inside,'' it might have been ball four, ``and I
hit it foul. I wanted to get something a little higher and hit it
hard. He ended up throwing me a strike, a fastball, and I hit it
down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he never worried about becoming Buckner Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in that stuff. I believe in destiny. If the
Red Sox are destined to win the World Series, they're destined to
win. If not, they're not. We won tonight and I had a big part of
it. But I've got to have a short memory because I've got to be here
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   A short memory is handy if you play for the Red Sox. Or if you
watch them. When it comes to Boston baseball in October, too many
of us have long memories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
