</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPREWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS WANT TO KNOW WHY SPREWELL WAS MISSING LAST WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Latrell Sprewell could use a good icebreaker
to cut the tension bound to fill the room when the Knicks' coach,
Jeff Van Gundy, and general manager, Scott Layden, meet with him on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   They will want to know why Sprewell went days without contacting
the team and missed all of training camp, which broke up at the
College of Charleston Saturday without him. Sprewell was in
Westchester County, where he arrived Friday after what people close
to him say was a three- to four-day cross-country road trip from
Oakland, Calif., to his hometown of Milwaukee to the New York area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what has happened,'' Van Gundy said Saturday.
``After we speak, everyone will have a better understanding. There
haven't been any whys given to me. I'm just going to take the
meeting and listen, say what I have to say, and hopefully we'll be
able to move on and move forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not wondering about anything. I'm just waiting more than
wondering. I'm waiting to hear what he has to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Sprewell says that he had a personal matter to take care
of, or that he needed to clear his head after his trial in a civil
suit in California, or that he needed to get his affairs in order
before the season, the team would be hard-pressed to lift its
disciplinary action against him _ fining him for missed practices _
because he failed to communicate his plans with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, he was missing. From Wednesday afternoon until Friday
afternoon, the team had no contact with Sprewell or his agent,
Robert Gist. Still, the only person the Knicks had talked to was
Gist, who on Friday afternoon finally returned one of numerous
messages left for him by Layden. Gist helped arrange the meeting on
Sunday that will include Layden, Van Gundy and Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   No one had spoken directly to Sprewell yet, not even his closet
friends on the team. All anyone knew was that he checked into the
hotel that he lived in last year on Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen or heard from him, but he'll be in New York
when we get there,'' Marcus Camby said. ``We're really looking
forward to having him back. It's about time.''
</P>
<P>
   His absence from the team could be costly. After Sprewell was
excused from practice on Monday and Tuesday because of the civil
suit, the team began to fine him for each unexcused practice. While
Sprewell was apparently traveling the highways of America, he was
racking up fines that could amount to $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone already knows what's expected,'' Van Gundy said.
``It's not like he didn't know he was supposed to come to training
camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the player who had done so much image repair last year
_ following his return to the league after he was suspended for
choking Golden State coach P.J. Carlesimo in December 1997 _ was
being seen as unprofessional and insubordinate. It's uncertain how
much good will Sprewell undermined with his behavior last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably defer that question until I get more
information,'' Layden said. ``But these matters don't help you.''
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the team has to think carefully about its
desire to sign Sprewell to a contract extension _ which could be as
high as $70 million _ before the season begins.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Sprewell's image, the team was hurt. Over the six-day
camp, the Knicks had nine practice sessions without one of its
biggest stars. It was difficult enough without the injured Patrick
Ewing, but Sprewell's absence left a large hole in the team's
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, there's no doubt,'' Van Gundy said. ``Obviously
there's enough time, but you're not going to be as good as if you
have the whole time for the schedule we're facing to start the
year. It's definitely not what we would have liked considering
injuries and Latrell's absence.''
</P>
<P>
   What was behind the disappearance? That's what the Knicks intend
to find out in Sunday's meeting. Was his lack of communication
unavoidable? Or does he have a lack of commitment to the team?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the only one who can answer that question,'' Ewing said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
