<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2229 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-HOLBROOK-AZR &LR;      10-09 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND EVER THE TWAIN SHALL MEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - Hal Holbrook's por trayal of writer Mark Twain is so
believable that a Twain scholar once mistakenly published a paper
using the actor's photograph instead of the writer's.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was embarrassing for the scholar, says an editor with the
Mark Twain Project at the University of Califor nia at Berkeley,
but understandable. As Mark Twain`s reincarnation, Hol brook stands
head and shoulders above all comers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most guys who do this are not concerned with authenticity,''
says Robert Hirst, a general editor with the project whose
unfathomable mis sion is to publish all of Twain's writings.
``They're taking advantage of Mark Twain's appeal. They don't
hesitate to do things which are not genuinely what Mark Twain
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrook, on the other hand, does not simply impersonate the
19th-cen tury sage. He becomes him.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1954 when Holbrook first became Twain, or Samuel L. Clem
ens, with his original one-man show at Lock Haven State Teachers
Col lege in Pennsylvania. When he pres ents Mark Twain Tonight on
Oct. 16 at Arizona State University's Gam mage Auditorium, he will
be ap proaching his 2,000th performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's around 19-hundred-some thing,'' the actor says from his
office in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   After 45 years of portraying the great American humorist,
Holbrook must certainly be weary of the role.
</P>
<P>
   Not at all, he says. Constantly revising and rewriting his
material, which he gleans himself from the volumes that Twain
produced, Hol brook keeps his monologue fresh, year after year. In
fact, he's actually enjoying the work now more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twain's material seems to be more pertinent and on the nose
than ever before,'' Holbrook says, inspired that a man dead for a
century could have such insights into contemporary soci ety. ``So
much going on in the world today taps into what Twain was saying.''
</P>
<P>
   The author talks of the quest for power and greed, of the
corruption of politicians, the idiosyncrasies of the human race.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrook reads off one bon mot that sounds decidedly 20th
century:
</P>
<P>
   ``(We must) get rich. Dishonestly if we can, honestly if we
must.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrook, possibly the leading Twain authority outside academia,
cobbles his material from all of Twain's writings: the letters
(Twain was an inveterate correspondent), his essays, his
autobiographical material and his famous fiction _ The Adventures
of Tom Sawyer, The Adventures of Huckleberry Finn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a quote from here, a quote from there . . . I move them
around like chess pieces,'' Holbrook says. ``Sometimes, they have a
life of their own.''
</P>
<P>
   New material surfaces all the time. A Nevada archivist recently
discovered an 1868 newspaper account of one of that state's first
public hangings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see that stiff, straight corpse hanging there yet,'' the
newspaper reporter wrote, according to a Sep tember 1999 Associated
Press article, ``with its black pillow-cased head turned rigidly to
one side, and the purple streaks creeping through the hands and
driving the fleshy hue of life before them. Ugh!''
</P>
<P>
   The reporter: Samuel Langhorne Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrook is not surprised that one more historic nugget has
turned up, well aware that Twain writings are a seemingly
bottomless trove of litera ture.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much material,'' he says, material that supplies a
diligent actor with a lifetime of scripts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way this thing feeds you and drains you, you're submerged
_ you involve yourself from A to Z. It becomes an obsession.''
</P>
<P>
   For Holbrook, Mark Twain is a magnificent obsession. At age 74,
he's finding fewer film and TV roles for men his age. But he's
grown into the Twain persona. And with Hol brook as his own writer,
director and star, Mark Twain Tonight has be come a portable
career, his bread and butter.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, the venerable actor, who has won five Emmy awards (and
has an additional seven Emmy nomina tions), a Tony, an Obie
(off-Broad way) and a Peabody award, has more on his plate than
bread and butter. He is currently filming a movie in Portland,
Ore., that co-stars Cuba Gooding Jr. and Robert De Niro.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1952, it is the story of the first Black man to break
into the ex clusive club of Navy divers. Hol brook plays a
commandant in the diving school who is determined to keep the man
out. DeNiro, Holbrook says, plays a ``tough-drill-sergeant type''
trying to flunk him.
</P>
<P>
   Gooding plays the man, Carl Breash ear, who often visits the
movie set.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrook's stature in Hollywood is unquestionable. But don't
look for his name to appear alongside Warren Beatty's and Cybill
Shepherd's on some presidential ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, no,'' he snorts, calling the current spate of actors and
other celebrities considering a run for high office ``a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Holbrook doesn't have opinions about the state of
modern American society. Sounding rather crusty, he launches into a
polemic worthy of his alter ego.
</P>
<P>
   On politics: ``We're living in a world so corrupted. . . .
Presidents run the country by the polls. . . . What are we
electing, a man or a mouse?''
</P>
<P>
   On Hollywood: ``Too much sex, pornography and foul language. . .
. If our behavior is based on animals, where are we headed?''
</P>
<P>
   On someday returning to series television: ``You have to make a
living. I happen to be an actor. But this field is dealing in stuff
I don't like. It's a problem for me.''
</P>
<P>
   On society in general: `'We have totally failed in our
responsibility not only to our children but to our country. We
deserve to be swacked good.''
</P>
<P>
   You can almost picture him in a white suit and fluffy white
coif, knuckling a fat cigar. Where does the writer end and the
actor begin?
</P>
<P>
   Just don't call him cynical. Can't abide the word. Euphemism for
speaking the truth.
</P>
<P>
   And don't start in on the contro versy over Tom Sawyer or Huckle
berry Finn. Told that a school in Mesa recently banned a
performance of Tom Sawyer the play, Holbrook allows that Twain is
often dogged by censorship, usually regarding the tale of Huck
Finn, a vagabond boy beaten by a racist father before he runs away
and befriends escaped slave Jim.
</P>
<P>
   Huckleberry Finn ``is about racism,'' Holbrook says. ``You'd
have to be some kind of moron to believe it's racist.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrook is not always in a pique about the state of the world.
His own five children, including two stepchildren by actress Dixie
Carter, his third wife, have turned out well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of them,'' he says, although he takes little credit
for their successes.
</P>
<P>
   He sees them _ and his one grandchild _ often.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrook and Carter likewise in tersect as often as possible,
between his Twain performances, stage and film roles that keep him
on the road half of the year, and her double duty in two new TV
series, Family Law and Ladies Man.
</P>
<P>
   Carter is kept hopping by the two roles, he says, but ``you want
to make a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Twain, of course, had some thing to say about making a
living:
</P>
<P>
   ```Work consists of whatever a body is obliged to do. Play
consists of whatever a body is not obliged to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping the Holbrooks have time for both. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
