<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTHRIDGE-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE'S ARNOLD OUT 3-4 WEEKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MISSOULA, Mont. _ This was the dreaded worst-case scenario for
the Cal State Northridge football team.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Montana beat CSUN by three touchdowns, but the
Matadors lost top receiver Aaron Arnold in the fourth quarter when
Arnold separated his right shoulder on a 20-yard completion at the
Grizzlies' 2.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold, a senior who entered the game leading Division I-AA in
receptions per game, is expected to be out three to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's worse, this loss or losing him,'' CSUN
interim head coach Jeff Kearin said of Arnold, the school's
all-time leader in receptions, receiving yards and receiving
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   After the Matadors' 48-27 loss, Arnold walked off the
Washington-Grizzly Stadium field with his right arm in a sling.
Statistically, he had his worst game of the season, with four
catches for 75 yards and one touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Amerson and Terrence Jones, who are second and third,
respectively, on the team in receptions, combined for nine catches
and 96 yards Saturday. Neither scored a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got three `favorite' receivers,'' CSUN quarterback Marcus
Brady said. ``I've got 100 percent confidence in Drew and I've got
100 percent confidence in Terrence.''
</P>
<P>
   Slip-sliding away: Most of the game was played under a constant
rain, which made the footing precarious. Brady slipped a few times
and so did CSUN tailback Jaumal Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the rain played much of an issue,'' Kearin said.
</P>
<P>
   But Montana head coach Mick Dennehy, who said the Matadors are
the most athletic team in the Big Sky Conference, didn't complain
about the slick grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Mother Nature,'' Dennehy said. ``I love her to death.
At least I can't be accused of watering down the field.''
</P>
<P>
   No revenge: CSUN lost for the third time in four games all-time
against Montana, but until Saturday the series had been close, with
the Matadors outscoring the Matadors 71-70 in those meetings.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN beat Montana 21-7 last year, holding the Grizzlies to their
lowest point total in 78 games. But Montana had to play backup
quarterback Sean Davis, who was 17 of 33 for 172 yards in his only
start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year's game was not a factor going into this year's
game,'' Dennehy said. ``We didn't go down with a magnum, we went
down with a popgun.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark it down: Joe Gilliam, a freshman receiver, scored his first
touchdown as a Matador early in the fourth quarter. Gilliam's
11-yard score was the highlight of his three-catch, 27-yard day.
</P>
<P>
   Gilliam entered the game with just four catches in two games.
</P>
<P>
   Making the call: Scott Himelstein, a Chaminade High graduate,
made his debut as the play-by-play announcer for KCSN, the
Matadors' flagship station. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 2258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991009.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-LIGHTNING-     10-09 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-LIGHTNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRODEUR DOESN ' T GET MUCH WORK AS DEVILS SHUT DOWN LIGHTNING, 1-0
 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ After allowing seven goals two nights
ago in their home opener, the Devils tightened up on defense
Saturday night and all they needed offensively was a goal by Brian
Rolston for a 1-0 victory over the Tampa Bay Lightning.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur faced only 14 shots to earn his first shutout of
the season and the 37th of his career. It came against a Tampa Bay
team that showed little coordination on attack, especially in the
first two periods, when the Devils took 28 of their 32 shots in the
game before a crowd of 13,982.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, now 2-1-0, were dominant in the first two periods,
limiting the visitors to just seven shots.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur's most crucial moments came in the second half of the
third period, first during a penalty to Vadim Sharifijinavov midway
through the period, and then during a double-minor to Krzysztof
Oliwa for roughing.
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning's best scoring chance came with just three minutes
left in the game and Tampa Bay on the power play. Chris Gratton hit
a hard shot from the blue line that handcuffed Brodeur, but he
recovered quickly to knock aside the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   None of the shots seemed to cause any concern for Brodeur, who
escaped suspension by the league for a blatant slash on
Pittsburgh's Matthew Barnaby on Thursday night in the 7-5 loss to
the Penguins in the home opener.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur said there was no justification for a suspension because
his slash behind Barnaby's knees was not intended to injure and
Barnaby came back and played just minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get chills when you do something bad and I didn't feel any
of that,'' Brodeur said of the first period incident against
Barnaby that resulted in the first ejection of his career. ``It was
more of a check-swing than anything. There was no intention to
injure there.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur is one of the critics of the league's new rule that
allows players to make contact with the goaltenders. He said
goaltenders must take action to protect themselves and he took his
first such action in the season opener in Atlanta when he was
assessed a double-minor for roughing Chris Ferraro of the Thrashers
late in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, the Devils had plenty of opportunities for a
goal in the first 40 minutes against the Lightning, but their only
score was 7 minutes 6 seconds into the middle period, when Rolston
leaped on a rebound from a shot by Petr Sykora and beat Dan
Cloutier from his left.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second goal in as many games for Rolston, who was
moved onto the team's premier line two nights ago as the left wing
with Jason Arnott his center and Sykora his right wing.
</P>
<P>
   Rolston was a key player on the team's checking line the last
two seasons, but he is one of two or three players on the Devils
who have a chance to reach the 30-goal plateau, something no one on
the Devils has accomplished since 1994. His goal Friday night was
the only one the Devils needed for their first victory at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 2302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
