<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2234 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-REHM-AZR &LR;      10-09 1619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REHM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING `VOICE' TO HER PAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 By BARBARA YOST 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  PHOENIX - As her befuddled driver
raced through the streets of Balti more, radio talk show host Diane
Rehm feared she would be late for her first book signing. The
driver was lost.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I was going crazy!'' Rehm says by telephone in that familiar
lilting voice tinged with just the touch of a quaver.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, she did arrive at the Bibelot bookstore half an hour
late, only to be greeted by an overwhelming assembly of 300 patient
fans clutch ing copies of her new autobiography, Finding My Voice.
Despite her cha grin at having kept the crowd waiting, her spirits
were instantly lifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you it was exciting,'' she says from yet another
stop on her current book tour, this time in Ann Arbor, Mich. ``This
is the fun part of it. . . . You get a chance to get out there and
meet the people listening to the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite a heady experience for the little Arab-American girl from
Wash ington, D.C., child of immigrants from Turkey who physically
abused their two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Rehm prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, she began volunteering at a Washington public radio
station and six years later took over the talk show she was helping
to produce. She now commands the broadcast booth of the Diane Rehm
Show, which went into national syndication in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The story Rehm tells in Finding My Voice is one of her troubled
child hood, a first marriage that ended when she was 21, a second
marriage to her beloved John ``Scoop'' Rehm, the birth of their two
children, voice problems that periodically banish her from the air
and, finally, content ment with who she was and what she has
become.
</P>
<P>
   She tells it all in a frank memoir that has alienated her from
members of her extended family, but that will satisfy her legions
of listeners.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 12, Rehm will appear at Changing Hands Bookstore at 6428
S. McClintock Drive, in Tempe, at 11 a.m., and then at Borders
Books &AMP; Music, 2402 E. Camelback Road, in Phoenix, at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in Baltimore, her followers will make the pilgrimage to
see a guru most have only heard, worship ing at the altar of a talk
show host known for her on-air decorum when others fire canons at
guests and listeners alike.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Rehm might still be the good little girl trying to
escape Mother's wrath by being on her best behavior. But that
leaves the air waves with one less loudmouth to feed, and it has
earned Rehm acclaim and a place in 60 U.S. radio markets.
</P>
<P>
   If Rehm prides herself on the roster of celebrities she has
interviewed on her show _ Henry Kissinger, Carl Sagan, Gen. Colin
Powell, Hillary Clinton, Lauren Bacall, Maya Ange lou _ she is just
as delighted with the people who have recently inter viewed her.
</P>
<P>
   Early in September, she was the guest at the National Press Club
for an onstage interview by Nightline host Ted Koppel.
</P>
<P>
   Linton Weeks of the Washington Post profiled her and her book in
August, causing tremors in the Aed family as many of her relatives
learned for the first time she was spilling the family beans.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 21, her 63rd birthday, she was the guest of honor at a
Washing ton, D.C., gala celebrating her two decades on the air.
</P>
<P>
   But, no doubt surprising to many of her listeners, Rehm's life
has not been as easy as it might seem. Revealing that truth and a
desire to step down from her pedestal moti vated her to write her
book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a huge sense of relief,'' she says, ``a huge sense of
having told the truth about what my life was . . . changing
people's perception of who I was and where I came from.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehm came from darkness. Her parents immigrated to the United
States in 1929, after her father, Wadie Aed, persuaded her mother,
Eugenie Zouekie, to break her en gagement to a man she loved and
move to America, leaving her family behind.
</P>
<P>
   Did that sacrifice leave the young woman embittered and abusive?
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows?'' is the only answer Rehm can offer, still baffled
by her mother's behavior after years of counseling that has allowed
her to move past the memories.
</P>
<P>
   It was Eugenie whose temper would flare at a moment's notice. As
children, Rehm and her sister, Geor gette, tried their best to
avoid confrontation that would trigger an outburst. Though Rehm
does re count happy times, devastating inci dents still haunt her,
the times when she displeased Eugenie and suffered the cruel
repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the congressman.
</P>
<P>
   A beautiful child, strikingly blond in an Arab family
characterized by dark good looks, little Diane at tracted the
attention of a prominent congressman who promised to make her a
movie star. It seemed the American dream. The dream died when,
instead of sending her on her way to Hollywood, the man hustled her
into his hotel room and molested her.
</P>
<P>
   Rehm confessed to her parents, who were outraged. Because that
was a time when accusing a respected member of Congress of such un
speakable crimes was unheard of, her abuser was never punished.
Still disturbed by the event, Rehm will not even say whether he's
still alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so scary for me,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   At 16, she learned her mother was dying of cirrhosis of the
liver, be lieved to be the result of an old bout with malaria. Two
years later, Rehm became engaged to George Hamaty, an acquaintance
from Arab social circles who was eight years her senior. They
planned to marry in January of 1956, but moved up the date four
months as her mother's condition deteriorated, fearing she would
not live until the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   And then Mother was gone, dying the next New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching the hospital too late, Rehm agonized at having no
chance to say goodbye. Guilt over her mother's death dogged her for
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was my fault,'' she says. ``I thought if I had
only been a better child, if I had done more, she would not have
died.''
</P>
<P>
   In November that year, her father died of a heart attack. Rehm
strug gled to get past her grief, to be a good wife in a
traditional Christian Orthodox home. But a chasm was growing
between the man who ex pected his wife to be subservient and a
young woman who wanted more.
</P>
<P>
   Divorce in the Arab community was unthinkable, but by 1959, Rehm
was on her own, feeling an unfamiliar and heady sense of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   While working at the Department of State, she met boisterous
young lawyer John Rehm, born in Paris to American parents. As they
began to date, John introduced her to art, to music, to fine
cuisine. They were married in December 1959.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a sometimes rocky union, Rehm reveals, hitting a
particular bump in the road when she began working at WAMU. Still,
she charac terizes John Rehm as ``wonderful, a very loving man,''
and dedicated Finding My Voice to her ``lover, teacher, and,
finally, best friend.''
</P>
<P>
   The book's title has many layers of meaning. Its most obvious is
a reference to the battle Rehm has waged over the past few years
with a vocal-cord disorder called spasmodic dysphonia, which
periodically leaves her voice with a marked quiver and spells of
dysfunction that require injections of medication.
</P>
<P>
   After suffering for years with voice problems, which went
undiagnosed except for explanations ranging from stress to improper
breathing, she was correctly diagnosed just after decid ing to
write her book, a task she had long avoided.
</P>
<P>
   Literary agent Ron Goldfarb had been nagging her for years to
tell her story. Her medical problems conven iently supplied not
only the title of her book, but its final chapters as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I ever would have written the book if I hadn't
been pushed,'' Rehm says. ``I kept saying I didn't have anything to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   But as her 20th on-air anniversary approached, she decided
``maybe the time has come.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the frankness of her story might surprise some readers,
Rehm felt obligated to share even the most painful moments of her
childhood as well as those in her current marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I started writing, I couldn't write the book and not tell
the whole story,'' she says. ``That wouldn't have been an honest
book.''
</P>
<P>
   To prepare her relatives for the laundry she was about to air,
she broached the secret of her mother's abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brushed me off,'' she says, until the Post story became
her pre-publication Laundromat, anger ing and possibly alienating
many family members.
</P>
<P>
   For some time, Rehm's sister denied the abuse. Though she
finally ac knowledged the reality of their child hood, she asked to
be left out of the book. Rehm compromised with only brief
references to Georgette.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was John Rehm. How would he react to the candor
with which his wife discusses the flaws in their 40-year marriage?
</P>
<P>
   Before submitting her manuscript, Diane asked him to read it,
promis ing, ``If there is one word you don't want in the book, I'll
take it out.''
</P>
<P>
   He changed nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Now on a whirlwind book tour that has her out of town several
days, then back in town for non-stop local events, Rehm is pleased
with Finding My Voice and the warm receptions she has had.
</P>
<P>
   She believes she has rescued many fellow sufferers of spasmodic
dys phonia from their despair. Her hus band and children have
expressed pride in her accomplishments. And through therapy, she is
silencing the demons of her past.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps she now deserves that spot on a pedestal for her
inspiring story. Rehm has found not only her voice but her purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want people to get from the book,'' she says, ``is that
whatever challenges you face, if you keep putting one foot in front
of the other, you can get through it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
