<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN DUPES THE DOPES AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - Among news junkies, the most dangerously addictive nar
cotic is something we call the ``exclu sive.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you want to get a reporter hooked, to alter his view of
reality, just promise him a story no one else has. I've seen it
happen lots of times, perhaps because the most successful
``exclusive'' dealer in the country operates right here in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   His name is U.S. Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's running for president, the senator has been
peddling his mind-altering material to dopes all over the nation.
The lastest media type to get strung out on a McCain ``exclusive''
is television's Jane Pau ley. &QL; 
`Candid interview'
</P>
<P>
   Tonight (Oct. 10) on Dateline NBC, in what the network describes
as ``a remarkably candid interview,`` Mc Cain and his wife, Cindy,
speak with Pauley about Cindy McCain's for mer addiction to
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The couple are coming forward now, according to an Associated
Press report, ``rather than wait for (Mc Cain's) political
opponents to bring it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? It worked five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, after a string of health problems, Cindy
McCain got hooked on the painkillers Percoset and Vicodin. She not
only had different doctors writing prescrip tions, but she stole
pills from the American Voluntary Medical Team, a charitable group
she headed.
</P>
<P>
   An employee fired from the team filed a lawsuit claiming Cindy
had ordered him to conceal ``improper acts.'' He tipped off the
Drug Enforcement Administration, which began an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, when the McCains knew the story was about to go public,
the senator rounded up a few friendly reporters and offered them an
``ex clusive'' interview with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   One of the writers described the discussion in NBC-like terms as
``a candid, and often difficult, inter view.'' &QL; 
Facts downplayed
</P>
<P>
   The part about stealing from the medical team, which cared for
sick people in Third World countries, wasn't mentioned until the
16th paragraph, and was described as Cindy having ``dipped into
supplies.''
</P>
<P>
   Initial articles also didn't report the interviews were granted
only after the McCains had worked out a deal with the U.S.
Attorney's Office that kept Cindy from being prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter from The Republic tried to ask Cindy McCain
about what actually happened, her attorney answered, ``She has no
comment. You're not going to talk to Cindy. You're not going to
talk to me. You're not going to talk to anybody associated with us.
Have you got the message?''
</P>
<P>
   Then he hung up.
</P>
<P>
   In their interview with Dateline, the senator says of his wife's
problem, ``To this day, I feel partially respon sible . . . and
maybe I was wrapped up too much in Washington and my ambitions to
pay as much attention as I should have.''
</P>
<P>
   He began paying attention after Cindy's problem started
interfering with those ambitions, however.
</P>
<P>
   And now he's paying attention again, but not because his
opponents may try to use her troubles against him.
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Any Republican presidential candi date who dared to criticize a
woman who, five years ago, bravely over came a potentially deadly
addiction would be committing political sui cide.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one person in America who could use Cindy's
addiction for his own benefit, and that's McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Already he's confessed indiscretions in his first marriage and
mistakes in the ``Keating Five'' scandals. Mc Cain says he's
learned from these crises and is a better man for it. And, once he
brings up these problems, no one else can use them against him.
</P>
<P>
   With his latest ``exclusive,'' McCain gets to play the
sympathetic hus band. In this age of the political confession, when
every negative from the past can be turned into a positive, Cindy
is a gold mine.
</P>
<P>
   A husband hellbent on shoving his way to the front of the
presidential line has no problem shoving his wife to the back,
behind Betty Ford and Kitty Dukakis. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-99 2309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
