<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIME-RING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIME RING WITNESSES BEING KILLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - One by one, potential witnesses against a Phoenix area
crime syndicate have been shot down, derailing years of undercover
work and squelching an indictment against the suspected
ringleaders.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least four men are dead, including a key witness who survived
one hit attempt only to be gunned down again after he moved out of
state.
</P>
<P>
   According to court records, the homicide victims all were
associates of Luis A. and Felipe ``Porky'' Cisneros, both of whom
have served prison time.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the killings were committed before the Cisneros
brothers were to stand trial last year on 14 felony charges
involving fraudulent schemes, possession of stolen prop erty and
operating a chop shop.
</P>
<P>
   The latest killing too place three weeks ago. The victim was a
Cisne ros associate who was being pressed to cooperate with police
and prose cutors. Damien Shawn Semus, 20, of Queen Creek, was found
in an east Mesa wash with bullet wounds in his face and chest.
</P>
<P>
   Luis and Felipe Cisneros, 29 and 25 respectively, are not
charged in con nection with the homicides or with any other crime.
</P>
<P>
   Amber Bullock, Semus' mother, said he was under pressure from
authori ties to turn against the Cisneros brothers. Her stepson,
Shawn R. Bullock, 22, was murdered under similar circumstances 14
months ear lier. Both young men were drug dealers with criminal
records.
</P>
<P>
   Weeping as she spoke, Amber Bull ock blamed the Department of
Pub lic Safety and Attorney General's Office for failing to protect
her sons. She noted that the Cisneroses were not jailed even after
a metham phetamine lab and stolen vehicles were found at their auto
body shop during a raid in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't understand why the hell they're walking
around,'' she said. ``Did you see all the stuff they (DPS) got from
them? Isn't that enough to put them somewhere?
</P>
<P>
   ``If they (prosecutors and police) can't take care of it, I'll
take care of it. . . . I only have one son left, and I don't
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Cisneros said, ``This is crazy already. Anything that
happens, we get blamed for it.''
</P>
<P>
   He then referred inquiries to attor ney Alan Simpson, who
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors refused to talk about the slayings, related
investigations, or whether they failed to protect in formers and
prospective witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   DPS officials warned that publicity about the case might
endanger law-enforcement officers and others. They also expressed
fear that any prospective witnesses who remain might become too
terrified to speak with authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The Cisneroses were indicted with several other suspects in
1997. Most police reports and court documents in the case have been
sealed. How ever, available records describe a conspiracy involving
drug sales and falsified vehicle identification num bers. &QL; 
String of deaths begin in 1996
</P>
<P>
   The string of murders began while the Cisneroses were under
investiga tion in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In November of that year, authorities seized a stolen pickup
truck from Shawn Bullock. According to court records, the vehicle
was acquired through a Cisneros intermediary named Aaron ``Guerro''
Romero, 26, of Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock, who was on probation for theft at the time, spoke with
Romero about the stolen truck, then listened as Romero called
someone to discuss the problem. Bullock gave Romero a business card
listing the name and phone number of his ``case agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, Romero's bullet-rid dled corpse lay outside the
Cisne roses' Mesa auto body shop.
</P>
<P>
   According to a property forfeiture motion filed by the U.S.
Attorney's Office, Bullock told a government informer that ``Luis
Cisneros had Guerro killed, and that he also wanted to kill
Bullock.''
</P>
<P>
   The next homicide victim was listed by prosecutors as Axel
Samoyoa, the state's ``major civilian witness'' in the Cisneros
case.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 17, 1996, Samoyoa was wounded five times at a Phoenix
auto repair business, with bullets from the same gun that killed
Romero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surviving but fearful, Mr. Samoyoa was moved out of state,''
court records state. ``He had submitted to two days of a three-day
(interview with Cisneros defense lawyers). Hours before the
scheduled resump tion of the interview, Mr. Samoyoa was shot
numerous times in his car and killed.''
</P>
<P>
   An exhaustive search turned up no public record on anyone named
``Axel Samoyoa.'' DPS investigators said the name is a pseudonym,
but declined to provide other informa tion. &QL; 
Car found, butbody never shows up
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Bullock also was being urged by investigators to turn
against the Cisneros brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, days after Bullock received a government subpoena
to testify, his new Cadillac DeVille was found with the interior
spattered with brain matter.
</P>
<P>
   Outwardly, Bullock appeared to be a successful young
entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   He owned a luxury car and a $212,000 house in Val Vista Lakes, a
posh Gilbert community. Shortly before his death, he owned a
Harley-Davidson ``Fat Boy'' motorcycle and a 28-foot boat.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a life for someone who left Red Mountain High
School without a diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, Bullock made his money as an auto trader. But court
records say he and Semus, his stepbrother, were leaders in the
Cisneros organi zation.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 5, 1997, DPS investigators searched a Mesa pawnshop
owned by Bullock and Semus, as well as their homes and the
residences of two associates. Those raids netted weapons, cash,
narcotics ledgers, 3 pounds of methamphetamine, 24 ounces of
cocaine and 40 pounds of pot.
</P>
<P>
   Both men had been arrested before, and Bullock apparently hated
his stay behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   While serving nights in jail earlier during 1997, he wrote to
the court begging for probationary release and promising to clean
up his act. He claimed he had a scholarship to attend Mesa
Community College and was working 12 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleading with you to take a little time and see how far I
have really come,'' Bullock's letter to the judge says. ``Your
Honor, I will not even spit on the sidewalk wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Police say that on the night of July 21, 1998, Bullock told a
roommate he was going on an errand. A few hours later, his black
Caddy was found on East Atlanta Street, in south Phoenix, with the
passenger window missing and nothing inside except body fluids.
</P>
<P>
   DNA records confirmed the victim's identity, but coroners have
not issued a death certificate because they have no body. Family
members never held a memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   Homicide investigators aren't sure what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those situations where we don't have a
body,'' Phoenix police Detective Randy Chapman said. ``There's a
cloud of mystery around his lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   On the final day of 1998, the case was ruled a homicide. A
police report, which is otherwise heavily edited, lists this name
under ``suspect information'': Cisneros, Luis An thony. &QL; 
Case dismissed by prosecution
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks after Bullock's death, Assistant Attorney General
Warren Granville asked a Maricopa County Superior Court judge to
drop all criminal complaints against the Cis neroses because
charges ``can no longer be sustained in light of the murder of
three of the state's wit nesses.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the killings has been solved.
</P>
<P>
   Granville would not disclose infor mation about Samoyoa's
homicide, whether he was a protected witness, or whether other
homicide victims were under surveillance when they were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Search warrants and lab tests are sealed by court order. The
Depart ment of Public Safety refused to release its records. But
DPS investi gators and the U.S. Attorney's Office stressed that
none of the homicide victims was a protected witness.
</P>
<P>
   Federal, state and local authorities have repeatedly scrutinized
the Cis neros brothers, with limited success.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Department of Corrections, Luis was convicted
of manslaughter in the 1990 gunshot slaying of a Glendale man. He
served three years of a five-year sentence. Felipe served five
months in prison for a 1993 theft.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, however, the brothers benefited from police
errors, good lawyers and witness deaths.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, for example, Chandler police raided Luis Cisneros' home
and found a cache of weapons, including a semiautomatic rifle with
a 100-round magazine, and a .50-cal iber pistol with slugs the
diameter of a dime.
</P>
<P>
   Although officers had a search war rant, they pried open a
screen door before announcing themselves to the occupants. As a
result, a judge threw out all charges. &QL; 
The lawyer defends his clients
</P>
<P>
   That court victory was obtained by Simpson, Luis Cisneros'
defense law yer for years.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson also represented Shawn Bullock, the potential witness
against Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock's stepmother said she be lieves Simpson had a conflict
of interest. In an interview, Simpson insisted there was no
conflict because Shawn Bullock never agreed to testify against the
Cisneros brothers. If Bullock was being ``flipped'' by prosecutors,
Simpson added, ``they were certainly not doing it through me.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Simpson argued in court papers that the unsolved
murders should not be attributed to his clients: ``No inference
should be drawn that Luis Cisneros or Felipe Cisneros bears any
responsibility for these homicides.''
</P>
<P>
   Simpson said Romero was friends with the Cisneroses, so it's
``prepos terous'' to think they would take his life. Besides, he
said, Mesa police suspect the murder was committed by Carlos
Santillan, another man with a record for narcotics posses sion and
auto theft. Santillan was killed in a vehicle accident two years
ago. (Mesa police have not released records from the Romero
homicide.)
</P>
<P>
   Simpson said Samoyoa was purport edly a confidential informer
for federal agents in unrelated cases, which means others had
motives to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he noted that Bullock was involved with large-scale
drug traf ficking, which might explain his assassination by parties
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not view my client to be a danger,'' Simpson said of Luis
Cisne ros. ``He has a wonderful family.''
</P>
<P>
   Granville, the prosecutor, declined to comment on Simpson's
comments or any continuing investigations. &QL; 
More raids at auto shop, homes
</P>
<P>
   But court records suggest the saga is not over.
</P>
<P>
   On March 31, 1999, DPS investiga tors went after the Cisneros
brothers again. SWAT-style teams with search warrants raided their
Mesa auto shop, their homes and four other locations associated
with them.
</P>
<P>
   At the South Robson Street business, detectives found a ``huge''
metham phetamine lab, according to court records. They also seized
about $22,000 in cash, more than 20 allegedly stolen vehicles and
at least a dozen firearms, including a Tech 9 semiautomatic with 35
rounds in the magazine. In addition, they confis cated Bullock's
motorcycle and boat, which Luis Cisneros had obtained from him.
</P>
<P>
   That same day, investigators searched the Queen Creek home of
Damien Semus, who was awaiting trial on charges of aggravated as
sault, narcotics possession, arson and auto theft.
</P>
<P>
   Amber Bullock said DPS officers were pushing her son to testify
against the Cisneroses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said we should convince Damien to come in there and tell
everything, to spill his guts to them,'' she said. ``And we said,
`Do you think we're crazy? Let them kill him, too?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Amber Bullock does not believe either of her sons would have
cooperated with authorities. It didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a Mesa schoolgirl riding the bus home saw something
in a wash near Usery Mountain Recre ation Area. Maricopa County
sher iff's deputies searched the area and found the body of Semus.
</P>
<P>
   There are no suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The Cisneroses have not been charged in the March 31 raids.
</P>
<P>
   The government still has property seized under forfeiture
statutes, but the brothers are trying to regain it.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros attorney Simpson com plains in court motions that SWAT
officers ransacked private offices, took money from a child's piggy
bank and confiscated items that were lawfully obtained. Because
search warrants are sealed, he noted, the Cisneroses cannot even
find out why their stuff was taken.
</P>
<P>
   As for the meth lab, Simpson said in an interview that the DPS
raid took place before Luis and Felipe Cisne ros arrived at work
that morning, so someone else could be responsible. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
