u s BC-BBA-YANKS-STRAWBERRY-     10-09 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY PROVES HE IS A WEAPON 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas. _ There has been a calm demeanor about Darryl
Strawberry since he arrived in the Yankees clubhouse. Watch
Strawberry sneak into the showers to smoke a cigarette or dress
slowly and quietly near his corner locker or talk more honestly
about the Yankees than anyone other than David Cone. There are
never any moments in which Strawberry looks as if he is rushing.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what Strawberry does around the Yankees, he always
seems placid. Strawberry never acts like someone who is late for a
flight, never behaves like someone who wants to avoid attention,
never campaigns as someone who craves the endless attention. To
Strawberry, there are no reasons to be unnerved. Baseball is the
simple part for Straw, always has been and always will be.
</P>
<P>
   That is why he looked Saturday night like a carefree teen-ager _
not a sometimes troubled 37-year-old who has admitted his
addictions to drugs and alcohol _ after he had smashed Esteban
Loaiza's fastball in the first inning for a three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knew the ball would leave the Ballpark in Arlington.
Eventually, everyone would know that Strawberry's homer and Roger
Clemens' spotless pitching over seven innings were primary reasons
the Yankees humbled the Rangers, 3-0, and swept the division series
again.
</P>
<P>
   As the white ball transformed into the size of a Tic-Tac and
kept soaring toward left center field, Strawberry furiously chewed
gum and kept gazing at it. When the ball finally vanished over the
fence, Strawberry stopped chewing gum and left his mouth wide open,
almost in awe of his own achievement, before resuming his chewing,
putting his head down and running.
</P>
<P>
   Then Strawberry went back to being the calm designated hitter
and the Yankees went back to beating the Rangers for the ninth
straight time in the postseason. Expect Joe Torre to ride
Strawberry like a new Harley-Davidson in the League Championship
Series against the Indians or the Red Sox. Who would have figured
that Strawberry would be such a central figure in this latest
Yankee tale? Strawberry, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as my performance goes, I've been around this game a
long time,'' he said recently. ``I don't put pressure on myself to
perform. When I'm given the opportunity, I expect to perform. I've
done this before. It's really not a matter of worrying about
whether I can still do it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a humility about Strawberry when he discusses where he
has been and what he can do, but that humility does not totally
disguise the confidence, even cockiness, that he still has.
Strawberry created his own problems when he was arrested for
possessing three-tenths of a gram of cocaine and solicitation of a
prostitute in Tampa, Fla. last April, which he blamed on drinking
and on being depressed following chemotherapy treatments for colon
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry rejoined the Yankees when rosters expanded on Sept. 1
and spoke passionately about the errors that he had made. ``This
time around, when I looked in the mirror, I looked at the enemy,''
Strawberry said that day. ``It was me. It wasn't anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounded riveting, but Strawberry almost sabotaged his tenuous
career and placed himself in the tricky position of having to prove
himself all over again when he was recalled from Triple-A Columbus.
His fourth comeback with the Yankees since 1995 looked as if it
might end with Strawberry in front of a television set in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is a weapon, we'll incorporate it into the club,'' Torre
said at the time. ``We pretty much have to figure out if he is a
weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   About a week later, Strawberry showed that he was a weapon, and
the doubts about his status on the postseason roster were
eliminated. Now the defending World Series champions need
Strawberry, especially since Chili Davis' bat has been absent for
almost four months and since Paul O'Neill's rib injury might force
him to miss more games.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, who scored the first run in Game 1, had the homer
and a single Saturday night. Until Strawberry struggles, Davis
should not budge out of the dugout against right-handers. A player
with Strawberry's experience and abilities suddenly is a much more
precious commodity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became more valuable to the team,'' said Strawberry,
``whatever situation I'm in.''
</P>
<P>
   He is in a splendid situation again, zooming toward another
World Series ring and providing the sort of power and presence that
September call-ups rarely provide in October. But Strawberry's
situation is different and he is different, always has been and
always will be. Watch him cruise through another postseason with
the Yankees, looking calm. By now, Darryl knows there is no reason
to rush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
