<HEADER>
A2240 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-GANG-AZR &LR;      10-09 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GANG-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW WEAPON AGAINST  GANGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By JUDI VILLA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - For years, only gang rules really mattered on 13th Place
in Phoenix.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Residents needed permission just to cross the street. Once, two
women got lost on the street and were robbed. Another time, an
elderly man was left standing naked in broad daylight after members
of Eastside Los Cuatro Milpas stole his pants and laughed at him.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Phoenix police are impos ing their own controversial,
and some say unconstitutional, rules on this beleaguered central
city neigh borhood.
</P>
<P>
   They are slapping gang members with civil injunctions that ban
them from hanging out together in public and whistling to warn each
other when police are coming.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 8 and 9, detectives served notice to 14 Los Cuatro
Milpas members that they are about to be prohibited from
``standing, sitting, walking, driving, gathering or ap pearing
anywhere in public view'' with any other gang member.
</P>
<P>
   The injunction, which will take effect after a court hearing
Oct. 20, is a laundry list of rules that includes imposing curfews
on younger Milpas members and banning loud music.
</P>
<P>
   It forbids drinking and fighting in public, carrying all
weapons, block ing anyone's path and even being on the premises of
any abandoned building. Gang members also cannot ride a bike if
it's for the purpose of buying or selling drugs, and they can't use
or possess marking pens, razor blades or spray paint cans if they
intend to deface property.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix is the first city in Arizona to resort to civil
injunctions as a way to curb gang activity. But police in
California have been imposing them in gang-blighted areas since
about 1987. California courts have upheld injunctions in Los
Angeles and San Jose despite claims that they trample the civil
rights of gang members, mainly their right to peaceable as sembly.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights advocates, such as the Arizona Civil Liberties
Union, threaten to challenge Phoenix's in junction, and they say
the restric tions unfairly target minorities and have no socially
redeeming value.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Peter Klahr, a Phoenix attor ney, called such injunctions
unneces sary and overbearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are intimidating people, mad-dogging them,
threatening them, then by all means arrest them,'' Klahr said. ``If
somebody's merely gathering with their friends, leave them alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Miranda has lived near 13th Place for seven years. And he
has the scars to prove it. Two years ago, two men grabbed him as he
went into his house, threatened his life and de manded money. One
kicked Miran da's ankle so hard that it shattered.
</P>
<P>
   There's a steel plate in his ankle now and, even after three
surgeries, Mir anda still limps sometimes. When the humidity hits
35 percent, he's in pain. And, if the weather's wet enough, he
needs his cane.
</P>
<P>
   After the attack, Miranda installed a front gate, a security
door and bars on his windows. He bought a Ger man shepherd for
protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel much better because of the gates and security doors,''
Miranda said. ``I lock up the front fence, and I always try to have
company. . . . If I need something, it has to be before dark. When
it gets dark, I go inside and lock myself in.''
</P>
<P>
   Gang members warn that residents ``better be'' afraid of them,
espe cially if they disrespect them, mess with them or get in their
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything could happen,'' one Mil pas member said. ``It ain't
heads up like it used to be. We used to fist-fight. It's killing
now. People find a sharp, hard stick and they're gonna shank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix police moved into the neigh borhood, bordered by Seventh
and 16th streets, Buckeye Road and Interstate 10, last year after
hearing that dopers were paying drugs to Los Cuatro Milpas leaders
for protec tion.
</P>
<P>
   They found that gang members roughed up elderly residents for
their welfare checks. They robbed people, booby-trapped their drug
houses to slow down police and forced resi dents to keep out of
certain areas, police say.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who complained or called police was beaten, police say.
Gun shots were fired into the air as warnings. One man started
walking around the block to get to a market that was just across
the street, and he bought a gun. Gang leaders even stole from
members of their own gang.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys were getting away with it for a long time, and they
knew they were getting away with it,'' gang unit Detective Jeffrey
Nolder said. ``So, they kept doing more and being more open about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested four gang leaders at the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, police targeted an additional 20 gang members
for an intervention program designed to help them find a way out of
gangs and drugs. The program offered jobs, educational
opportunities, fi nancial aid, life skills and self-suffi ciency
training and tattoo removal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just throwing them in jail or slapping their wrists,
saying, `This is bad,' '' Nolder said. ``We're giving them
alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the targeted gang members snapped up the offers, and
half continued to have repeated run-ins with police.
</P>
<P>
   Since the March arrests, residents are starting to see more
children in the park. The ice-cream trucks come through near dusk.
People sit out front, even if it is just until dark. Thirteenth
Place is clean.
</P>
<P>
   But police say Los Cuatro Milpas gang members still have their
stran gle-hold on the area. Graffiti is prolific on walls and trash
cans, drug houses keep popping up, and gang members congregate with
guns strapped to their sides.
</P>
<P>
   Some gang members continue to commit burglaries, thefts and
armed robberies, police say. The activity indicates they are
jockeying for positions, police say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't do anything to prevent it, the next tier will step
up and assume the leadership positions we've taken out and again
gain control of this neighborhood,'' Sgt. Terrance Donegan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Police Department has found that injunctions are
a good way to disrupt and control gang activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a company,'' said Los Angeles police Officer Jason
Lee, a gang expert. ``If I start taking salesmen away, the company
is not going to do very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Violation of Phoenix's injunction is a Class 1 misdemeanor,
punishable by up to six months in jail and fines of $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to sap the strength that comes from a gang's numbers
and re-create the social order of the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can try and get a little more control of the streets,
and the gangs see that we're not going to tolerate this behavior
that has been going on, maybe they'll tread a little more
lightly,`` said Philip Haggerty, Phoe nix's chief assistant city
attorney. ``If they realize they've lost the cloak of
invulnerability they've been operat ing under because they're a
gang, then we've done something good.``
</P>
<P>
   But Carmen Hernandez figures there's really no way to stop the
gangs. At 6 p.m., she pulls her five children inside, and they
don't come out until morning. Sometimes, they see the gang members
driving down the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's not afraid of gangs?'' she asked. ``How many innocent
people have they killed? How many kids have they killed? How can
you not be afraid?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my kids to grow up like them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
