r a BC-SPECIES-ALIEN-AZR &LR;      10-09 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECIES-ALIEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ALIEN' THREAT TO WILDLIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By JOHN STANLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - Aliens are among us.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They colonize our deserts, infest our waterways, swarm in our
skies and prey upon helpless natives.
</P>
<P>
   No, we're not talking about winter visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The invasion of non-native animals and plants into Arizona
threatens the state's indigenous wildlife and costs the state
millions of dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona is one of the most biologi cally diverse places in
North Amer ica,'' said biologist Randy Babb of the state Game and
Fish Depart ment. ``And the impact non-native species are making on
it is horren dous.''
</P>
<P>
   The aliens crowd out natives, de crease biological diversity and
reduce wildlife habitats. They increase fire dangers in deserts and
flood damage along riparian areas, and they de crease forage
available for wildlife, including livestock.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, alien species cost taxpay ers an estimated $122
billion a year, according to the Department of Agriculture. Exact
figures are not available for Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the intruders would surprise you: the tumbleweed, the
wild burro, crayfish, house sparrows, pigeons, carp, Mediterranean
geckos and bull frogs.
</P>
<P>
   But two of the most damaging are a tree and an exotic grass,
according to officials: the tamarisk, or salt cedar, and red brome
grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tamarisk was introduced in the late 1800s as an ornamental
species, for wind breaks and an erosion stabilizer for stream
banks,'' said Gina Ramos, a natural-resource specialist at the
Bureau of Land Management. ``Now, a million acres of the South west
are infested with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rory Aikens, a spokesman for the Arizona Department of Game and
Fish, said salt cedar has largely replaced native willows,
cottonwoods and mesquite along many of Arizo na's rivers and lakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salt cedar is now the primary plant around edges of Lake
Powell,'' he said. ``It has replaced many of the native trees
having value as food and shelter for animals.'' &QL; 
Increases flood damage
</P>
<P>
   Russ Haughey, a wildlife biologist for Game and Fish, said the
salt cedar is to blame for the increased amount of flood damage
done to private property across the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It grows very densely. So, when a river spreads across the
flood plains, it doesn't drain out as quickly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Babb said red brome, an exotic grass introduced early this
century for cattle forage, is to blame for the intensity of several
Arizona wildfires, including the devastating 1995 ``Rio'' fire in
the McDowells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red brome is a real threat to the Southwest,'' he said. ``It
outcom petes native plants for moisture, food, sunlight and growing
space. It grows fast, dries out and creates an incredible fire
danger. Then, when fires damage native species, red brome is the
first to grow back.''
</P>
<P>
   Haughey said larger and more fre quent fires in the Sonoran
Desert in the past 50 years are believed to be due primarily to red
brome.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ramos, non-native plants are brought into the state
in a variety of ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone may bring in an illegal plant because of its pretty
flowers,'' she said. ``But when they throw it out, its seeds could
still be active. Also, animals can brings seeds into the state in
their hooves or fur. Or people buy hay in another state and bring
it into Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramos says the first step to control non-native species is to
get the cooperation of everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't do anything on BLM land if across the way is land
controlled by other agencies,'' she said. &QL; 
`Most wanted' species
</P>
<P>
   John Caravetta, associate director of the plant services
division of the Arizona Department of Agriculture, said there are
58 non-native species the department is particularly con cerned
about excluding from the state. Among those ``most wanted'' are the
Asian longhorned beetle, eucalyptus lerp psyllid, Japanese bee tle,
pink hibiscus mealybug and giant salvinia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Red imported fire ants have spread across the southern United
States since their introduction in the 1930s. Although the
aggressive, biting in sects are spotted in Arizona from time to
time, the state is not classified as infested, thanks largely to
the efforts of the state Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get a call about a colony, we go in and eradicate
it,'' said Lloyd Brown, a department spokes man.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Yuma's Cibola High School reported an infestation of
the im ported red fire ant. Brown said they found about 7,000
mounds at the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like a disaster area out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The department is working with city officials to eliminate the
ants.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the department eradicated several hundred colonies of
red ants at a former nursery in south Phoe nix.
</P>
<P>
   The department operates four in spection stations at four
Arizona ports of entry. They are in Yuma, Sanders, Ehrenberg and
San Simon.
</P>
<P>
   ``These serve as our first line of defense,'' Caravetta said,
``and we do intercept lots of pests at the ports of entry.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Gehlker, a spokesman for the Phoenix branch of the Sierra
Club, summed it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to heed the words of Aldo Leopold (an early
environmentalist and writer): `The first principle of intelligent
tinkering is to save all the pieces.' Too often species are brought
in for one purpose, but then unintended consequences make things
worse. We need to be careful about introducing non-native species
in a slapdash way because you never know what you might do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to remember,'' Brown said, ``none of these
things are evil in themselves. They're just out of place.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
