<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2250 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT     10-09 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY BLAST ENOUGH TO POWER CLEMENS OVER RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Roger Clemens had missed this more than
anything else in baseball, pitching in a postseason vortex, his
teammates depending on him, needing him. The scrutiny thrilled him.
</P>
<P>
   And Clemens responded Saturday night, capitalizing on the three
runs Darryl Strawberry gave him with a first-inning home run by
throwing seven shutout innings, as the Yankees completed a
three-game sweep of the Texas Rangers in an American League
division series with a 3-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees pitchers held the Rangers to one run in three games
for the second consecutive year; after batting .141 against the
Yankees last year, the Rangers batted .163 (14 for 92) in this
year's series.
</P>
<P>
   Starting next Wednesday night in New York, the Yankees will play
the winner of the series between the Cleveland Indians and the
Boston Red Sox, which Cleveland leads by 2-1, in the AL
Championship Series. It is unclear whether Paul O'Neill will
participate. The All-Star right fielder missed Saturday night's
game because of bruised ribs and may be out indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who allowed three hits, walked two and struck out two
before Mariano Rivera worked the final two innings, might have
aggravated a hamstring injury in his final inning.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Girardi, the Yankee catcher, had been prepared for Clemens
to go to the mound in an excited state, perhaps overthrowing,
trying too hard. If necessary, Girardi was ready to slow him down
as much as possible, go to the mound to remind him of how many outs
there were, remind him of the situation. Anything to calm him.
</P>
<P>
   For Girardi understood all the baggage that Clemens might have
carried to the mound with him.
</P>
<P>
   He had not been the winning pitcher in a postseason game since
Oct. 15, 1986 _ he had six starts in the interim, over the years _
and after the Yankees traded David Wells for Clemens before this
season, there was the expectation that Clemens had to be as
successful as Wells in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   And Clemens, raised in Katy, Tex., and an alumnus of the
University of Texas, was pitching in his home state. He acquired a
sideline pass to see the beginning of the Texas-Oklahoma football
game earlier in the day, and his mother Bess and other family
members were here, having made the 4 1-2 hour drive from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is his stage tonight,'' manager Joe Torre said of
Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens prepared himself thoroughly, using part of his bullpen
workouts to simulate game action and the Texas lineup; he would
imagine he was pitching to Juan Gonzalez, Rafael Palmeiro and
others, and Girardi called balls and strikes. Clemens was crisp.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the groundwork helped him more than what Strawberry
provided before Clemens threw a pitch. One out into the first
inning, Derek Jeter smashed a line drive that bounced off the top
of the left-field wall, ricocheted against the facing of the stands
and fell back onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   Beckoning for an umpire to call this a home run, Jeter rounded
second and ran into the Texas second baseman Mark McLemore, who was
moving into position for a relay. Jeter returned to second and
although he lost his protest for a home run, he was awarded third
on McLemore's interference.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams walked, but the Rangers pitcher Esteban Loaiza
whiffed Tino Martinez on three pitches, exploiting the typically
large strike zone being called by umpire John Hirschbeck.
Strawberry was next, and Texas catcher Ivan Rodriguez called for a
fastball, shifting his body behind the outside corner as he set his
glove for Loaiza.
</P>
<P>
   But Loaiza missed the target, his fastball drifting over the
plate. Strawberry pounced, his drive carrying high to left-center,
10 rows deep into the stands. Players burst over the front steps of
the Yankees' dugout, trading high fives, yelling, and Strawberry
circled the bases with a small grin that broadened when he reached
the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to dominate had been lifted off Clemens;
Strawberry's runs had given him a margin for error, had given him
room to relax and focus on Hirschbeck's wide strike zone. He stared
in for the signs from Girardi, his glove obscuring all parts of his
face other than his eyes, his arms tucked against his sides and his
upper back slightly hunched, the pitcher's fetal position. Clemens
was very comfortable in this place.
</P>
<P>
   He retired the Rangers on eight pitches in the first inning,
throwing his fastballs for strikes, striking out Mark McLemore with
a slider on the outside corner. Everything was working. Everything
was in order. Clemens was not rushing, he had tackled and pinned
his adrenaline, and there was no need for Girardi to calm him.
</P>
<P>
   Every time he fell behind in the count, Clemens simply
challenged hitters with his fastball; Strawberry's home run
afforded him this luxury. He threw first-pitch strikes to 9 of 10
hitters in one sequence, and all three of the Rangers' hits in the
first six innings were singles. Texas could not score.
</P>
<P>
   One out into the bottom of the fifth inning, Tom Goodwin smacked
a one-hopper off Clemens' right calf, and Clemens dropped to the
ground in pursuit of the ball and threw to first for the out.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly he found himself surrounded by concerned teammates and
Steve Donahue, the Yankees' trainer. Donahue asked how he was, and
towering over the trainer, Clemens smiled and appeared to lecture
Donahue good-naturedly. From his expression, it was easy to discern
what he was thinking: If you think I'm coming out of the game
because of that little bruise, you've got to be crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens maintained his shutout into the seventh, Bernie Williams
aiding him with two running catches on deep drives. After covering
first base with one out, Clemens came away wincing, limping
slightly; all year, he has been bothered by a strained hamstring,
once going on the disabled list, and he might have aggravated the
injury.
</P>
<P>
   But Clemens finished the inning, and for now he has put to rest
all the concerns and unfavorable comparisons, and met all the
expectations. It's October, Clemens pitched superbly, and the
Yankees are advancing in the playoffs.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
